WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.680
Preface and Introduction of Up From Slavery.

00:00:18.220 --> 00:00:21.540
Up From Slavery by Booker T. Washington.

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:23.860
Preface and Introduction.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:29.500
This volume is dedicated to my wife, Margaret James Washington,

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:32.880
and to my brother, John H. Washington,

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:36.540
whose patience, fidelity, and hard work

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:41.360
have gone far to make the work at Tuskegee successful.

00:00:42.260 --> 00:00:42.740
Preface.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:46.120
This volume is the outgrowth of a series of articles

00:00:46.120 --> 00:00:49.400
dealing with incidents in my life which

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:53.180
were published consecutively in the Outlook

00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:56.940
While they were appearing in that magazine,

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:01.740
I was constantly surprised at the number of requests which

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:04.780
came to me from all parts of the country,

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:07.940
asking that the articles be permanently

00:01:07.940 --> 00:01:09.920
preserved in book form.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:14.000
I am most grateful to the Outlook for permission

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.160
to gratify these requests.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:19.900
I have tried to tell a simple, straightforward story

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.700
with no attempt at embellishment.

00:01:22.700 --> 00:01:26.360
My regret is that what I have attempted to do

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:29.180
has been done so imperfectly.

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:31.720
The greater part of my time and strength

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:35.160
is required for the executive work connected

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:39.380
with the Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:44.900
and in securing the money necessary for the support

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:46.040
of the institution.

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:50.700
Much of what I have said has been written on board trains

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:54.040
or at hotels or railroad stations

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:56.780
while I have been waiting for trains

00:01:56.780 --> 00:02:00.520
or during the moments that I could spare

00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:03.360
from my work while at Tuskegee.

00:02:03.500 --> 00:02:06.900
Without the painstaking and generous assistance

00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:09.480
of Mr. Max Bennett Thrasher,

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.500
I could not have succeeded in any satisfactory degree.

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:14.900
Introduction.

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:18.600
The details of Mr. Washington's early life

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:21.980
as Flankley sat down in Up From Slavery

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:25.440
do not give quite a whole view of his education.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:29.620
He had the training that a colored youth received

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:34.020
at Hampton, which indeed the autobiography does explain,

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:38.300
but the reader does not get his intellectual pedigree

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:40.820
for Mr. Washington himself, perhaps,

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.720
does not as clearly understand it as another man might.

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:47.120
The truth is he had the training

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:50.920
during the most impressionable period of his life

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:52.940
that was very extraordinary,

00:02:53.460 --> 00:02:57.200
such a training as few men of his generation have had.

00:02:57.560 --> 00:02:59.500
To see its full meaning,

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.740
one must start in the Hawaiian Islands

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:04.980
half a century or more ago.

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:09.920
There, Samuel Armstrong, a youth of missionary parents,

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:13.260
earned enough money to pay his expenses

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:16.960
at an American college equipped with a small sum

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:20.920
and the earnestness that the undertaking implied.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:23.140
He came to Williams College

00:03:23.140 --> 00:03:26.660
when Dr. Mark Hopkins was president.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:31.560
Williams College had many good things for youth in that day,

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:33.240
as it has in this,

00:03:33.460 --> 00:03:36.700
but the greatest was the strong personality

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.060
of its famous president.

00:03:39.820 --> 00:03:43.400
Every student does not profit by a great teacher,

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:46.180
but perhaps no young man ever came

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:48.480
under the influence of Dr. Hopkins,

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:52.660
whose whole nature was so right for profit

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.560
by such an experience as young Armstrong.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.400
He lived in the family of President Hopkins

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:04.780
and thus had a training that was wholly out of the common,

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:08.160
and this training had much to do

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:11.680
with the development of his own strong character,

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:14.360
whose originality and force

00:04:14.360 --> 00:04:16.840
we are only beginning to appreciate.

00:04:17.540 --> 00:04:21.200
For this interesting view of Mr. Washington's education,

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:25.980
I am indebted to Robert C. Austin, Esquire,

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:29.320
Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Hampton Institute

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:32.660
and the intimate friend of General Armstrong

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:36.000
during the whole period of his educational work.

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:40.860
In turn, Samuel Armstrong, the founder of Hampton Institute

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.540
took up his work as a trainer of youth.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:45.900
He had very raw material,

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:48.320
and doubtless most of his pupils

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:51.500
failed to get the greatest lessons from him.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:55.720
But as he had been a particularly receptive pupil

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:56.900
of Dr. Hopkins,

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:00.520
so Booker Washington became a peculiarly

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:02.300
receptive pupil of his.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:05.520
To the formation of Mr. Washington's character,

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:09.400
then went the missionary CEO of New England.

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:13.260
Influenced by one of the strongest personalities

00:05:13.260 --> 00:05:15.200
in modern education,

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:19.260
and the wide reaching moral earnestness

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:21.420
of General Armstrong himself.

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:24.240
These inferences are easily recognizable

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:26.080
in Mr. Washington today

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:29.440
by men who knew Dr. Hopkins and General Armstrong.

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:32.900
I got the cue to Mr. Washington's character

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:36.180
from a very simple incident many years ago.

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.760
I had never seen him and knew little about him,

00:05:39.820 --> 00:05:42.620
except that he was the head of a school

00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:44.240
at Tuskegee, Alabama.

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:46.940
I had occasion to write to him

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:51.000
and I addressed him as the Reverend Booker T. Washington.

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:53.820
In his reply, there was no mention

00:05:53.820 --> 00:05:56.900
of my addressing him as a clergyman.

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.060
But when I had occasion to write to him again

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:02.920
and persistent in making him a preacher,

00:06:03.140 --> 00:06:05.960
his second letter brought a postscript.

00:06:05.960 --> 00:06:08.260
I have no claim to Reverend.

00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:10.640
I knew most of the colored men

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:13.100
who had at the time had become prominent

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:14.880
as leaders of their race,

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:16.920
but I had not then known one

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:20.160
who was neither a politician nor a preacher.

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:22.960
And I had not heard of the head

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:25.400
of an important colored school

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:27.140
who was not a preacher.

00:06:27.460 --> 00:06:31.660
A new kind of man surely if he looks upon his task

00:06:31.660 --> 00:06:35.420
as an economic one instead of a theoretical one.

00:06:35.420 --> 00:06:39.960
I wrote him an apology for mistaking him for a preacher.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:42.920
The first time that I went to Tuskegee,

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:45.320
I was asked to make an address

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:47.320
to the school on Sunday evening.

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:51.140
I sat upon the platform of the large chapel

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:54.080
and looked forth on a thousand colored faces.

00:06:54.240 --> 00:06:58.840
And the choir of a hundred or more behind me

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:01.360
sang a familiar religious melody

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:05.280
and the whole company joined in the chorus unction.

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:08.120
I was the only white man under the roof

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:12.220
and the scene and the songs made an impression on me

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:14.020
that I shall never forget.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:19.360
Mr. Washington arose and asked them to sing one after another

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:23.200
all the old melodies that I had heard all my life.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:28.140
But I had never before heard them sung by a thousand voices

00:07:28.140 --> 00:07:31.880
nor by the voices of educated Negroes.

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.200
I had associated them with the Negro of the past,

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:39.060
not with the Negro who was struggling upward.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:42.700
They brought to my mind the plantation, the cabin,

00:07:42.900 --> 00:07:46.100
the slave, not the freedom in quest of education.

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.160
But on the plantation and in the cabin,

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:51.500
they had never been sung

00:07:51.500 --> 00:07:54.460
as these thousand students sang them.

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:59.100
I saw again all the old plantations that I had ever seen.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:02.600
The whole history of the Negro ran through my mind

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:06.200
and the inexpressible pathos of his life

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:08.920
found expression in these songs

00:08:08.920 --> 00:08:11.680
as I had never before felt it.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:15.760
And the future, these were the ambitious use of the race

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:18.920
at work with an earnestness that put to shame

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:20.660
the conventional student life

00:08:20.660 --> 00:08:23.160
of most educational institutions.

00:08:23.720 --> 00:08:26.700
Another song rolled up along the rafters

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:28.460
and as soon as silence came,

00:08:28.660 --> 00:08:32.860
I found myself in front of this extraordinary mass of faces

00:08:32.860 --> 00:08:34.780
thinking not of them,

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:37.960
but of that long and unhappy chapter

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:39.640
in our country's history,

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:43.400
which followed the one great structural mistake

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:45.560
of the fathers of the republic.

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.060
Thinking of the one continuous great problem

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:52.580
that generations of statesmen had wrangled over

00:08:52.580 --> 00:08:55.220
and a million men fought about

00:08:55.220 --> 00:08:59.320
and that had so drafted the mass of angry men

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:03.840
in the southern states as to hold them back a hundred years

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:07.660
behind their fellows in every other part of the world,

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:09.320
in England, in Australia,

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:12.040
and in the northern and western states.

00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:14.940
I was thinking of this dark shadow

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:19.020
that had oppressed every large-minded statesman

00:09:19.020 --> 00:09:20.640
from Jefferson to Lincoln.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:24.740
These thousands young men and women about me

00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:26.260
were victims of it.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.560
I too was an innocent victim of it.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:34.020
The whole republic was a victim of that fundamental era

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:37.060
of importing Africa into America.

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:41.240
I held firmly to the first article of my faith

00:09:41.240 --> 00:09:43.900
that the republic must stand fast

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:46.700
by the principle of a fair ballot.

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:49.740
But I recalled the wretched mass

00:09:49.740 --> 00:09:52.140
that Reconstruction had made of it.

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:55.260
I recalled the low level of public life

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:57.320
in all the black states.

00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:01.500
Every effort of philanthropy seemed to have miscarried.

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:06.760
Every effort at connecting abuses seemed of doubtful value

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:11.620
and the race friction seemed to become severer.

00:10:11.900 --> 00:10:14.780
Here was the century-old problem

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:18.720
in all its pathos seated, singing before me.

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:21.180
Who were the more to be pitied,

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:24.480
these innocent victims of an ancient wrong

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:29.140
or I and men like me who had inherited the problem?

00:10:29.480 --> 00:10:33.300
I long ago thrown aside illusions and theories

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:37.540
and was willing to meet the faces face to face

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:41.880
and to do whatever in God's name a man might do

00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:45.380
towards saving the next generation from such a burden.

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:49.980
But I felt the weight of 20 well-nigh hopeless years

00:10:49.980 --> 00:10:53.180
of thought and reading and observation

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:55.960
for the old difficulties remained

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:58.040
and new ones had sprung up.

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:02.520
Then I saw clearly that the way out of a century of bundles

00:11:02.520 --> 00:11:05.800
had been made by this man who stood beside me

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:08.440
and was introducing me to his audience.

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:12.000
Before me was the material he had used.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.380
All about me was the indisputable evidence

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:19.080
that he had found the natural line of development.

00:11:19.460 --> 00:11:23.060
He had shown the way time and patience and encouragement

00:11:23.060 --> 00:11:25.160
and work would do the rest.

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:28.280
It was then more clearly than ever before

00:11:28.280 --> 00:11:31.040
that I understood the patriotic significance

00:11:31.040 --> 00:11:32.640
of Mr. Washington's work.

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:36.060
It is this conception and of him

00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:38.880
that I have ever since carried with me.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:43.400
It is on this that his claim to our gratitude rests.

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:46.200
To teach the Negro to read,

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:48.780
whether English or Greek or Hebrew,

00:11:49.140 --> 00:11:50.480
bitters no paslips.

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:52.380
To make the Negro work,

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:55.140
that is what his master did in one way

00:11:55.140 --> 00:11:56.900
and hunger has done in another.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:00.740
Yet both these left sultan life were defounded.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:04.020
But to teach the Negro to do skillful work

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:07.520
as men of all the races that have risen have worked,

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:11.600
responsible work, which is education and character.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:16.320
And most of all, when Negroes so teach Negroes to do this,

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:20.140
that they will teach others with a missionary zeal

00:12:20.140 --> 00:12:24.020
that puts all ordinary philanthropic efforts to shame.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:28.460
This is to change the whole economic basis of life

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:30.740
and the whole character of a people.

00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:33.260
The plan itself is not a new one.

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.660
It was worked out at Hampton Institute,

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:38.540
but it was done at Hampton by white men.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:43.960
The plan had in fact been many times theoretically laid down

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:47.200
by thoughtful students of sultan life.

00:12:47.740 --> 00:12:50.740
Handicrafts were taught in the days of slavery

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:53.900
on most well-managed plantations.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:58.360
But Tuskegee is, neptuness, a brand new chapter

00:12:58.360 --> 00:13:00.380
in the history of the Negro

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:03.840
and in the history of the naughtiest problem

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:05.240
we have ever faced.

00:13:05.680 --> 00:13:08.980
It not only makes a carpenter of a man,

00:13:09.240 --> 00:13:11.480
it makes a man of a carpenter.

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:15.580
In one sense, therefore, it is of greater value

00:13:15.580 --> 00:13:20.060
than any other institution for the training of men and women

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:23.340
that we have from Cambridge to Palo Alto.

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:27.440
It is almost the only one of which it may be said

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:30.360
that it points the way to a new epoch

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:33.540
in a large area of our national life.

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:37.840
To work out the plan on paper or at a distance,

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:39.220
that is one thing.

00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:43.740
For a white man to work it out, that too is an easy thing.

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:46.760
For a colored man to work it out in the South,

00:13:47.120 --> 00:13:49.060
where in its constructive period,

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:53.180
he was necessarily misunderstood by his own people

00:13:53.180 --> 00:13:54.920
as well as by the whites,

00:13:55.280 --> 00:13:58.980
and where he had to adjust it at every step

00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:01.120
to the strained race relations,

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:05.420
that is so very difficult and more difficult a thing

00:14:05.420 --> 00:14:08.380
that the man who did it put the country

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:10.940
under lasting obligations to him.

00:14:11.260 --> 00:14:15.060
It was not and is not a mere educational task.

00:14:15.620 --> 00:14:18.200
Anybody could teach boys trades

00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:20.780
and give them an elementary education.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:23.060
Such tasks have been done

00:14:23.060 --> 00:14:25.100
since the beginning of civilization,

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:27.660
but this task had to be done

00:14:27.660 --> 00:14:30.400
with the rawest of raw material,

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:34.580
done with the civilization of the dominant race,

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:40.040
and so as not to run across race lines and social lines

00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:42.820
that are the strongest forces in the community.

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:46.460
It had to be done for the benefit of the whole community.

00:14:46.680 --> 00:14:49.820
It had to be done, however, without local help

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:52.700
in the face of direct poverty done by begging

00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:56.820
and done in spite of the ignorance of one race

00:14:56.820 --> 00:14:59.100
and the prejudice of the other.

00:14:59.380 --> 00:15:01.980
No man living had a harder task

00:15:01.980 --> 00:15:06.200
and a task that called for more wisdom to do it right.

00:15:06.620 --> 00:15:09.820
The true measure of Mr. Washington's success

00:15:09.820 --> 00:15:14.420
is then not his teaching the pupils of Tuskegee,

00:15:14.620 --> 00:15:17.100
nor even gaining the support

00:15:17.100 --> 00:15:20.200
of philanthropic persons at a distance,

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:24.480
but this, that every Southern white man of character

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:29.300
and of wisdom has been one to cordial recognition

00:15:29.300 --> 00:15:31.220
of the value of the work.

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:36.660
Even men who held and still hold to the conviction

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:41.380
that a mere book education for the Southern blacks

00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:45.180
under present conditions is a positive evil.

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:49.140
This is a demonstration of the efficiency

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:52.620
of the Hampton Tuskegee idea that stands

00:15:52.620 --> 00:15:55.440
like the demonstration of the value

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:57.920
of democratic institutions themselves.

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:00.620
A demonstration made so clear

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:02.820
in spite of the greatest odds

00:16:02.820 --> 00:16:05.820
that it is no longer open to argument.

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:10.620
Consider the change that has come in 20 years

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:13.400
in the discussion of the Negro problem.

00:16:13.560 --> 00:16:15.500
Two of three decades ago,

00:16:15.500 --> 00:16:18.320
social philosophers, statisticians,

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:22.520
and well-meaning philanthropists were still talking

00:16:22.520 --> 00:16:27.020
and writing about the deportations of the Negroes

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:31.080
or about their settlement within some restricted area

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:34.760
or about their settling in all parts of the union

00:16:34.760 --> 00:16:39.860
or about their decline through the neglect of their children

00:16:39.860 --> 00:16:42.680
or about the rapid multiplication

00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:46.640
until they should expel the whites from the South

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:50.900
of every sort of nonsense under heaven.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:54.440
All this has given place to the simple plan

00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:59.320
of an indefinite extension among the neglected classes

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:04.220
of both races on the Hampton Tuskegee system of training.

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:08.180
The problem in one sense has disappeared.

00:17:08.180 --> 00:17:11.220
The future will have for the South

00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:14.880
swift of snow development of its masses

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:17.420
and of its soil in population

00:17:17.420 --> 00:17:22.600
to the swift of slow developments of this kind of training.

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:26.940
This change of view is a true measure

00:17:26.940 --> 00:17:28.740
of Mr. Washington's work.

00:17:29.260 --> 00:17:33.500
The literature of the Negro in America is colossal

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:37.480
from political oratory through abolitionism

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:40.940
to Uncle Tom's Cabin and Cotton is King,

00:17:41.240 --> 00:17:45.200
a vast mass of books which many men have read

00:17:45.200 --> 00:17:49.180
to the waste of good years and I among them.

00:17:49.740 --> 00:17:53.480
But the only books that I have read a second time

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:57.440
or ever care gain to read in the whole list,

00:17:57.820 --> 00:18:02.460
most of them by tiresome and unbalanced reformers,

00:18:02.860 --> 00:18:05.640
are Uncle Remus and Up from Slavery.

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:10.440
For these are the great literature of the subject.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:13.100
One has all the best of the past,

00:18:13.260 --> 00:18:16.440
the other foreshadows a better future

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:19.840
and the men who wrote them are the only men

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:23.820
who have written of the subject with that perfect frankness

00:18:23.820 --> 00:18:26.820
and perfect knowledge and perfect pose

00:18:26.820 --> 00:18:29.200
whose other name is genius.

00:18:30.120 --> 00:18:34.560
Mr. Washington has won a worldwide fame at an early age.

00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:39.380
His story of his own life already has the distinction

00:18:39.380 --> 00:18:42.760
of translation into more languages,

00:18:42.760 --> 00:18:46.040
I think than any other American book

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:51.480
and I suppose that he has as large a personal acquaintance

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:56.900
among men of influence as any private citizen now living.

00:18:58.180 --> 00:19:01.860
His only teaching at Tuskegee is unique.

00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:06.280
He lectures to his advanced students

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:09.160
on the art of right living,

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:13.620
not out of textbooks but straight out of life.

00:19:13.860 --> 00:19:16.920
Then he sends them into the country

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:18.560
to visit Negro families.

00:19:19.340 --> 00:19:22.840
Such a student will come back with a minute report

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:28.340
of the way in which the family that he has seen lives,

00:19:28.340 --> 00:19:30.820
what their earnings are,

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:34.520
what they do well and what they do ill

00:19:34.520 --> 00:19:39.360
and he will explain how they might live better.

00:19:40.800 --> 00:19:44.360
He constructs a definite plan for the betterment

00:19:44.360 --> 00:19:46.400
of that particular family

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:49.820
out of the resources that they have.

00:19:50.740 --> 00:19:53.140
Such a student, if he be bright,

00:19:53.460 --> 00:19:57.220
will profit more by an experience like this

00:19:57.220 --> 00:20:00.080
than he could profit by all the books

00:20:00.080 --> 00:20:05.780
on sociology and economics that ever were written.

00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:09.600
I talked with a boy at Tuskegee

00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:12.980
who had made such a study as this

00:20:12.980 --> 00:20:16.980
and I could not keep from contrasting his knowledge

00:20:16.980 --> 00:20:21.000
and enthusiasm with what I heard in a classroom

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.340
at a Negro university in one of the southern states,

00:20:25.340 --> 00:20:28.000
which is conducted on the idea

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.660
that a college course will save the soul.

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:35.740
Here, the class was reciting a lesson

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:39.660
from an abstruse textbook of economics,

00:20:41.120 --> 00:20:44.760
reciting it by rote with so obvious failure

00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:49.640
to assimilate it that the ways of labor was pitiful.

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:53.300
I asked Mr. Washington years ago

00:20:53.300 --> 00:20:57.400
what he regarded as the most important result of his work

00:20:57.400 --> 00:21:00.980
and he replied, I do not know which to put first,

00:21:01.260 --> 00:21:03.940
the effect of Tuskegee's work on the Negro

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:08.620
or the effect of the attitude of the white man to the Negro.

00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:13.780
The race divergence under the systems of miseducation

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:16.040
was fast getting wider.

00:21:16.320 --> 00:21:20.600
Under the influence of the Hampton Tuskegee idea,

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:25.480
the races are coming into a closer sympathy

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:29.420
and into an honorable and helpful relation.

00:21:30.500 --> 00:21:33.860
As the Negro becomes economically independent,

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:37.760
he becomes a responsible part of the southern life

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:40.820
and the whites so recognize him

00:21:40.820 --> 00:21:44.100
and this must be from the nature of things.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:48.140
There is nothing artificial about it.

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:52.720
It is development in a perfectly natural way

00:21:52.720 --> 00:21:57.020
and the southern whites not only so recognize it

00:21:57.020 --> 00:22:01.240
but they are imitating it in the teaching

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:04.700
of the neglected masses of their own race.

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:08.940
It has thus come about that the school

00:22:08.940 --> 00:22:14.100
was taking a more direct and helpful hold on life

00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:17.920
in the south than anywhere else in the country.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:22.240
Education is not a thing apart from life,

00:22:22.740 --> 00:22:25.360
not a system, nor a philosophy.

00:22:25.700 --> 00:22:29.500
It is a direct teaching how to live and how to work.

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:34.560
To say that Mr. Washington has won the gratitude

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:37.560
of all throughout southern white men

00:22:37.560 --> 00:22:40.180
is to say that he has worked

00:22:40.180 --> 00:22:43.200
with the highest practical wisdom

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:45.680
at a large constructive task

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:50.140
for no plan for the upbuilding of the freedom

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:54.500
could succeed that ran counter to southern opinion.

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:58.240
To win the support of southern opinion

00:22:58.240 --> 00:23:02.040
and to shape it was a necessary part of the task

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:04.660
and this he has so well succeeded

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:09.020
that the south has a sincere and high regard for him.

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:13.520
He once said to me that he recalled the day

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:17.700
and remembered it thankfully when he grew large enough

00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:23.100
to regard a southern white man as he regard a northern one.

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:28.380
It is well for our common country that the day is come

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:33.120
when he and his work are regarded as highly in the south

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:35.820
as in the other part of the union.

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:39.640
I think that no man of our generation

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:44.940
has a more noteworthy achievement to his credit than this

00:23:44.940 --> 00:23:49.620
and it is an achievement of moral earnestness

00:23:49.620 --> 00:23:51.960
of the strong character of a man

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:55.620
who has done a great rational service.

00:23:58.080 --> 00:24:01.480
Introduction by Walter H. Page.

00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:04.880
End of Preface and Introduction.

00:24:12.760 --> 00:24:14.160
Thank you.

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:49.180
I was born a slave on a plantation in Franklin County, Virginia.

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:55.880
I am not quite sure of the exact place or exact date of my birth, but at any rate,

00:24:56.180 --> 00:25:04.020
I suspect I must have been born somewhere and at some time. As nearly as I have been able to learn,

00:25:04.020 --> 00:25:14.240
I was born near a crossroads post office called Hales Fort, and the year was 1858 or 1859.

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:21.960
I do not know the month or the date. The earliest impression I can now recall are of the plantation

00:25:21.960 --> 00:25:29.200
and the slave quarters, the latter being the part of the plantation where the slaves had their

00:25:30.080 --> 00:25:37.280
My life had its beginning in the midst of the most miserable, desolate, and discouraging

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:43.120
surroundings. They were so, however, not because my owners were especially cruel,

00:25:43.220 --> 00:25:49.620
for they were not, as compared with many others. I was born in a typical log cabin

00:25:49.620 --> 00:25:57.560
about 14 by 16 feet square. In this cabin, I lived with my mother and a brother and sister

00:25:57.560 --> 00:26:04.980
till after the Civil War, when we were all declared free. Of my ancestry, I know almost nothing

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:11.960
in the slave quarters, and even later I heard whispered conversations among the colored people

00:26:11.960 --> 00:26:18.680
of the tortures which the slaves, including, no doubt, my ancestors on my mother's side,

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:26.200
suffered in the middle passage of the slave ships which being conveyed from Africa to America.

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:33.100
I have been unsuccessful in securing any information that would throw any accurate

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:39.660
light upon the history of my family beyond my mother. She, I remember, had a half-brother

00:26:39.660 --> 00:26:46.360
and a half-sister. In the days of slavery, not very much attention was given to family history

00:26:46.360 --> 00:26:53.380
and family records, that is, black family records. My mother, I suppose, attracted the

00:26:53.380 --> 00:27:01.720
attention of a purchaser who was afterward my owner and hers. Her addition to the slave family

00:27:01.720 --> 00:27:09.320
soon attracted about as much attention as the purchase of a new horse or cow. Of my father,

00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:16.580
I know even less than of my mother. I do not even know his name. I have heard reports to the

00:27:16.580 --> 00:27:24.180
fact that he was a white man who lived on one of the nearby plantations. Whoever he was, I never

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:31.620
heard of his taking the least interest in me or providing in any way for my rearing. But I do not

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:38.820
find a special fault with him. He was simply another unfortunate victim of the institution

00:27:38.820 --> 00:27:45.700
which the nation unhappily had and grafted upon it at that time. The cabin was not only

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:52.640
our living place but was also used as the kitchen for the plantation. My mother was

00:27:52.640 --> 00:28:00.400
the plantation cook. The cabin was without glass windows. It had only opening in the side which

00:28:00.400 --> 00:28:07.120
let in the light and also the cold chilly air of winter. There was a door to the cabin, that is

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:14.160
something that was called a door, but the uncertain hinges by which it was hung and the large cracks

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:21.180
in it to say nothing of the fact that it was too small made the room a very uncomfortable one.

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:29.220
In addition to these openings, there was in the lower right-hand corner of the room the cat hole,

00:28:29.460 --> 00:28:37.980
a contrivance which almost every mansion or cabin in Virginia possessed during the Antebellum period.

00:28:38.510 --> 00:28:45.780
The cat hole was a square opening about seven by eight inches provided for the purpose of

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:52.400
letting the cat pass in and out of the house at will during the night. In the case of our

00:28:52.400 --> 00:28:59.460
particular cabin, I could never understand the necessity for this convenience since there were

00:28:59.460 --> 00:29:05.840
at least a half-thousand other places in the cabin that would have accommodated the cats.

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:13.340
There was no wooden floor in our cabin, the naked earth being used as a floor. In the center of the

00:29:13.340 --> 00:29:20.220
earthen floor there was a large deep opening covered with boards which was used as a place

00:29:20.220 --> 00:29:27.540
in which to store sweet potatoes during the winter. An impression of this potato hole is very

00:29:27.540 --> 00:29:33.620
distinctly engraved upon my memory because I recall that during the process of putting the

00:29:33.620 --> 00:29:41.720
potatoes in or taking them out, I would often come into possession of one or two which I roasted and

00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:48.080
thoroughly enjoyed. There was no cooking stove on our plantation and all the cooking for the

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:55.800
whites and slaves my mother had to do over an open fireplace, mostly in pots and skillets,

00:29:55.920 --> 00:30:03.480
while the poorly built cabin caused us to suffer with cold in the winter. The heat from the open

00:30:03.480 --> 00:30:10.780
fireplace in summer was equally trying. The early years of my life which were spent in the little

00:30:10.780 --> 00:30:17.420
cabin were not very different from those of thousands of other slaves. My mother, of course,

00:30:17.580 --> 00:30:23.280
had little time in which to give attention to the training of her children during the day.

00:30:24.040 --> 00:30:31.260
She snatched a few moments for our care in the early morning before her work began and at night

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:38.680
after the day's work was done. One of my earliest recollections is that of my mother cooking a

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:45.680
chicken late at night and awakening her children for the purpose of feeding them. How or where

00:30:45.680 --> 00:30:53.280
she got it I do not know. I presume, however, it was procured from our owner's farm. Some people

00:30:53.280 --> 00:31:00.440
may call this theft. If such a thing were to happen now, I should condemn it as theft myself,

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:07.440
but taking place at the time it did, and for the reason that it did, no one could ever make

00:31:07.440 --> 00:31:14.560
the belief that my mother was guilty of thieving. She was simply a victim of the system of slavery.

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:22.280
I cannot remember having slept in a bed until after our family was declared free by the

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:29.340
Emancipation Proclamation. Three children, John, my old brother, Amanda, my sister, and myself,

00:31:29.340 --> 00:31:37.320
had a pallet on the dirt floor. Or, to be more correct, we slept in and on a bundle of filthy

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:44.660
rags laid upon the dirt floor. I was asked not long ago to tell something about the

00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:51.400
sports and pastimes that I engaged in during my youth. Until that question was asked,

00:31:51.620 --> 00:31:57.740
it had never occurred to me that there was no period of my life that was devoted to play.

00:31:57.740 --> 00:32:04.880
From the time that I can't remember anything, almost every day of my life had been occupied

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:12.200
in some kind of labor, though I think I would now be a more useful man if I had had time for sports.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:20.200
During the period that I spent in slavery, I was not large enough to be of much service. Still,

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:26.760
I was occupied most of the time in cleaning the yards, carrying water to the men in the fields,

00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:34.120
or going to the mill to which I used to take the corn once a week to be ground. The mill was about

00:32:34.120 --> 00:32:41.600
three miles from the plantation. This work I always dreaded. The heavy bag of corn would be

00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:48.860
thrown across the back of the horse, and the corn divided about evenly on each side. But,

00:32:48.960 --> 00:32:55.680
in some way, almost without exception on these trips, the corn would so shift as to become

00:32:55.680 --> 00:33:03.420
unbalanced and would fall off the horse, and often I would fall with it. As I was not strong

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:11.420
enough to reload the corn upon the horse, I would have to wait sometimes for many hours till a chance

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:18.900
passerby came along who would help me out of my trouble. The hours while waiting for someone were

00:33:18.900 --> 00:33:26.100
usually spent in crying. The time consumed in this way made me late in reaching the mill,

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:31.840
and by the time I got my corn ground and reached home, it would be far into the night.

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:40.560
The road was a lonely one and often led through dense forests. I was always frightened. The woods

00:33:40.560 --> 00:33:48.260
were said to be full of soldiers who had deserted from the army, and I had been told that the first

00:33:48.260 --> 00:33:56.680
thing a deserter did to a negro boy when he found him alone was to cut off his ears. Besides, when I

00:33:56.680 --> 00:34:04.800
was late in getting home, I knew I would always get a severe scolding or a frogging. I had no

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:12.740
schooling, whatever, while I was a slave, though I remember on several occasions I went as far as the

00:34:12.740 --> 00:34:20.020
schoolhouse door with one of my young mistresses to carry her books. The picture of several dozen

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:28.160
boys and girls in a schoolroom engaged in study made a deep impression upon me, and I had the

00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:35.460
feeling that to get into a schoolhouse and study in this way would be about the same as getting into

00:34:35.460 --> 00:34:43.220
paradise. So far as I can now recall, the first knowledge that I got, or the fact that we were

00:34:43.220 --> 00:34:50.580
slaves and that freedom of the slaves was being discussed, was early one morning before day when

00:34:50.580 --> 00:34:57.900
I was awakened by my mother kneeling over her children and fervently praying that Lincoln and

00:34:57.900 --> 00:35:05.960
his armies might be successful and that one day she and her children might be free. In this connection,

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:12.220
I have never been able to understand how the slaves throughout the South, completely ignorant

00:35:12.220 --> 00:35:20.380
as were the masses, so far as books or newspapers were concerned, were able to keep themselves so

00:35:20.380 --> 00:35:27.780
accurately and completely informed about the great national questions that were agitating the

00:35:27.780 --> 00:35:35.160
country. From a time that Garrison, Lovejoy and others began to agitate for freedom,

00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:41.000
the slaves throughout the South kept in close touch with the progress of the movement.

00:35:41.640 --> 00:35:48.500
Though I was a mere child during the preparation for the Civil War and during the war itself,

00:35:48.500 --> 00:35:55.200
I now recall the many late at night whispered discussions that I heard my mother and the other

00:35:55.200 --> 00:36:01.720
slaves on the plantation indulge in. These discussions showed that they understood the

00:36:01.720 --> 00:36:07.820
situation and that they kept themselves informed of events by what was termed the

00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:14.320
great fine telegraph. During the campaign, when Lincoln was first a candidate for the presidency,

00:36:14.320 --> 00:36:22.200
the slaves on our far-off plantation miles from any railroad or large city or daily newspapers

00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:29.380
knew what the issues involved were. When war was begun between the North and the South,

00:36:29.680 --> 00:36:36.040
every slave on our plantation felt and knew that though other issues were discussed,

00:36:36.320 --> 00:36:43.480
the primal one was that of slavery. Even the most ignorant members of my race on the remote

00:36:43.480 --> 00:36:49.880
plantations felt in their hearts with a certainty that admitted of no doubt that the freedom of the

00:36:49.880 --> 00:36:57.040
slaves would be the one great result of the war if the Northern armies conquered. Every success

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:04.420
of the Federal armies and every defeat of the Confederate forces was watched with the keenest

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:11.320
and most intense interest. Often the slaves got knowledge of the results of the great battles

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:18.980
before the white people received it. This news was usually gotten from the colored man who was

00:37:18.980 --> 00:37:25.940
sent to the post office for the mail. In our case, the post office was about three miles from the

00:37:25.940 --> 00:37:33.340
plantation and the mail came once or twice a week. The man who was sent to the office would linger

00:37:33.340 --> 00:37:39.320
about the place long enough to get the drift of the conversation from the group of white people

00:37:39.320 --> 00:37:46.280
who naturally congregated there after receiving their mail to discuss the latest

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:52.460
news. The mail carrier on his way back to our master's house would as naturally

00:37:52.460 --> 00:38:00.580
retell the news that he had secured among the slaves and in this way they often heard of

00:38:00.580 --> 00:38:06.480
important events before the white people at the big house as the master's house was called.

00:38:06.960 --> 00:38:13.900
I cannot remember a single instance during my childhood or early boyhood when our entire

00:38:13.900 --> 00:38:22.100
family sat down to the table together and God's blessing was asked and the family ate a meal in a

00:38:22.100 --> 00:38:29.860
civilized manner. On the plantation in Virginia and even later meals were gotten by the children

00:38:29.860 --> 00:38:36.720
very much as dumb animals get theirs. It was a piece of bread here and a scrap of meat there.

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:44.520
It was a cup of milk at one time and some potatoes at another. Sometimes a portion of

00:38:44.520 --> 00:38:51.560
our family would eat out of the skillet or pot while someone else would eat from a thin plate

00:38:51.560 --> 00:38:58.040
held on the knees and often using nothing but the hands with which to hold the food.

00:38:58.040 --> 00:39:05.000
When I had grown to sufficient size I was required to go to the big house at mealtimes

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:12.340
to fan the flies from the table by means of a large set of paper fans operated by a pulley.

00:39:12.940 --> 00:39:19.660
Naturally much of the conversation of the white people turned upon the subject of freedom and

00:39:20.340 --> 00:39:27.820
and I absorbed a good deal of it. I remember that at one time I saw two of my young

00:39:27.820 --> 00:39:35.700
mistresses and some lady visitors eating ginger cake in the yard. At that time those cakes seems

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:44.620
to me to be absolutely the most tempting and desirable things that I had ever seen and I then

00:39:44.620 --> 00:39:51.600
there resolved that if I ever got free the height of my ambition would be reached if I could get to

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:57.780
the point where I could secure and eat ginger cakes in a way that I saw those ladies doing.

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:05.220
Of course as the war was prolonged the white people in many cases often found it difficult

00:40:05.220 --> 00:40:13.260
to secure food for themselves. I think the slaves felt the deprivation less than the whites because

00:40:13.260 --> 00:40:20.400
the usual diet for slaves was cornbread and pork and these could be raised on the plantation.

00:40:20.860 --> 00:40:27.480
But coffee, tea, sugar, and other articles which the whites had been accustomed to use could not

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:34.960
be raised on the plantation and the conditions brought about by the war frequently made impossible

00:40:34.960 --> 00:40:42.400
to secure these things. The whites were often in great straits. Parched corn was used for coffee

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:49.940
and a kind of black molasses was used instead of sugar. Many times nothing was used to sweeten the

00:40:49.940 --> 00:40:56.460
so-called tea and coffee. The first pair of shoes that I recall wearing were wooden ones.

00:40:57.240 --> 00:41:02.680
Their rough leather on the top but the bottoms which were about an inch thick were of wood.

00:41:03.220 --> 00:41:09.560
When I walked they made a fearful noise and besides this they were very inconvenient since

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:17.200
there was no yielding to the natural pressure of the foot. In wearing them one presented an

00:41:17.200 --> 00:41:24.140
exceedingly awkward appearance. The most trying ordeal that I was forced to endure as a slave boy

00:41:24.140 --> 00:41:33.280
however was the wearing of a flax shirt. In the portion of Virginia where I lived it was common

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:40.040
to use flax as part of the clothing for the slaves. That part of the flax from which our

00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:46.980
clothing was made was largely from the refuse which of course was the cheapest and roughest part.

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:55.500
I can scarcely imagine any torture except perhaps the pulling of a tooth that is equal to that

00:41:55.500 --> 00:42:02.260
caused by putting on a new flax shirt for the first time. It is almost equal to the feeling

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:10.300
that one would experience if he had a dozen or more chestnut burns or a hundred small pinpoints

00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:18.080
in contact with his flesh. Even to this day I can recall accurately the tortures that I underwent

00:42:18.080 --> 00:42:26.520
when putting on one of these garments. The fact that my flesh was soft and tender added to the

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:34.520
choice. I had to wear the flax shirt or none and had it been left to me to choose I should have

00:42:34.520 --> 00:42:41.260
chosen to wear no covering. In connection with the flax shirt my brother John who is several

00:42:41.260 --> 00:42:48.260
years older than I am performed one of the most generous acts that I ever heard of one slave

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:54.900
relative doing for another. On several occasions when I was being forced to wear a new flax shirt

00:42:54.900 --> 00:43:03.040
he generously agreed to put it on in my stead and wear it for several days till it was broken in.

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:11.020
Until I had grown to be quite a youth this single garment was all that I wore. One may get the idea

00:43:11.020 --> 00:43:17.860
from what I have said that there was bitter feeling towards the white people on the part of my race

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:24.260
because of the fact that most of the white population was away fighting in a war which

00:43:24.260 --> 00:43:31.480
would result in keeping the negro in slavery if the south was successful. In the case of the slaves

00:43:31.480 --> 00:43:39.300
on our place it was not true and it was not true of any large portion of the slave population

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:46.240
in the south where the negro was treated with anything like decency. During the civil war one

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:53.860
of my young masters was killed and two were severely wounded. I recall the feeling of sorrow

00:43:53.860 --> 00:44:02.500
which existed among the slaves when they heard of the death of Mars Billy. It was no sham sorrow

00:44:02.500 --> 00:44:09.780
but real. Some of the slaves had nursed Mars Billy others had played with him when he was child.

00:44:10.400 --> 00:44:17.260
Mars Billy had begged for mercy in the case of others when the overseer or master was

00:44:17.260 --> 00:44:24.460
thrashing them. The sorrow in the slave quarters was only second to that in the big house when the

00:44:24.460 --> 00:44:31.560
two young masters were brought home wounded. The sympathy of the slaves was shown in many ways.

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:38.240
They were just as anxious to assist in the nursing as the family relatives of the wounded.

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:45.440
Some of the slaves would even beg for the privilege of sitting up at night to nurse their

00:44:45.440 --> 00:44:53.660
masters. This tenderness and sympathy on the part of those held in bondage was a result of their

00:44:53.660 --> 00:45:01.480
kindly and generous nature. In order to defend and protect the women and children who were left on

00:45:01.480 --> 00:45:09.100
the plantation when the white males went to war, the slave who was selected to sleep in the big

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:15.780
house during the absence of the males was considered to have the place of honor. Anyone

00:45:15.780 --> 00:45:22.620
attempting to harm young mistress or old mistress during the night would have had to cross the

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:29.920
dead body of the slave to do so. I do not know how many have noticed it but I think that it will be

00:45:29.920 --> 00:45:37.500
found to be true that there are few instances either in slavery or freedom in which a member

00:45:37.500 --> 00:45:47.480
of my race has been known to betray a specific trust. As a rule, not only did the members of my

00:45:47.480 --> 00:45:54.100
race entertain no fearing of bitterness against the whites before and during the war but there

00:45:54.100 --> 00:46:02.180
are many instances of Negroes tenderly caring for their former masters and mistresses who for some

00:46:02.180 --> 00:46:11.240
have become poor and dependent since the war. I know of instances where the former masters of

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:17.660
slaves have for years been supplied with money by their former slaves to keep them from suffering.

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:24.900
I have known of still other cases in which the former slaves have assisted in the education

00:46:24.900 --> 00:46:32.140
of the descendants of their former owners. I know of a case on a large plantation in the south

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:40.160
in which a young white man, the son of the former owner of the estate, has become so reduced in

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:49.260
purse and self-control by reason of drink that he is a pitiable creature. And yet, notwithstanding

00:46:49.260 --> 00:46:56.000
the poverty of the colored people themselves on this plantation, they have for years supplied

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:03.460
this young white man with the necessities of life. One sends him a little coffee or sugar,

00:47:04.460 --> 00:47:13.460
another a little meat and so on. Nothing that the colored people possess is too good for the son of

00:47:13.460 --> 00:47:21.160
Old Mass Tom, who will perhaps never be permitted to suffer while any remain on the place who kneel

00:47:21.160 --> 00:47:28.980
directly or indirectly of Old Mass Tom. I have said that there are few instances of members of

00:47:28.980 --> 00:47:36.200
my race betraying a specific trust. One of the best illustrations of this which I know of is

00:47:36.200 --> 00:47:44.280
a case of an ex-slave from Virginia whom I met not long ago in a little town in the state of Ohio.

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:52.800
I found that this man had made a contact with his master who two or three years previous to the

00:47:52.800 --> 00:47:59.780
Emancipation Proclamation to the fact that the slave was to be permitted to buy himself by

00:47:59.780 --> 00:48:08.120
so much per year for his body and while he was paying for himself, he was to be permitted to

00:48:08.120 --> 00:48:15.340
labor where and for whom he pleased. Finding that he could secure better wages in Ohio,

00:48:15.540 --> 00:48:22.480
he went there. When freedom came, he was still in debt to his master some $300.

00:48:23.840 --> 00:48:29.500
Notwithstanding that the Emancipation Proclamation freed him from any obligation

00:48:29.500 --> 00:48:36.620
to his master, this black man walked the greater portion of the distance back to where his old

00:48:36.620 --> 00:48:43.960
master lived in Virginia and placed the last dollar with interest in his hands. In talking

00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:50.100
to me about this, the man told me that he knew that he did not have to pay the debt but that he

00:48:50.100 --> 00:48:57.420
had given his word to the master and his word he had never broken. He felt that he could not

00:48:57.420 --> 00:49:03.600
enjoy his freedom till he had fulfilled his promise. From some things that I have said,

00:49:03.740 --> 00:49:10.860
one may get the idea that some of the slaves did not want freedom. This is not true. I have never

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:18.400
seen one who did not want to be free or one who would return to slavery. I pity from the bottom

00:49:18.400 --> 00:49:26.880
my heart any nation or body of people that is so unfortunate as to get entangled in the net of

00:49:26.880 --> 00:49:34.360
slavery. I have long since ceased to cherish any spirit of bitterness against the Southern

00:49:34.360 --> 00:49:42.740
white people on account of the enslavement of my race. No one section of that country was wholly

00:49:42.740 --> 00:49:50.520
responsible for its introduction and besides it was recognized and protected for years by the

00:49:50.520 --> 00:49:58.520
general government. Having once got its tentacles fastened on to the economic and social life of

00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:04.920
the republic, it was no easy matter for the country to relieve itself of the institution.

00:50:05.580 --> 00:50:12.480
Then when we rid ourselves of prejudice or racial feeling and look facts in the face,

00:50:12.480 --> 00:50:18.940
we must acknowledge that notwithstanding the cruelty and moral wrong of slavery,

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:27.080
the 10 million Negroes inhabiting this country who themselves or whose ancestors went through

00:50:27.080 --> 00:50:35.660
the school of American slavery are in a stronger and more hopeful condition materially, intellectually,

00:50:35.660 --> 00:50:45.680
morally, and religiously than is true of an equal number of black people in any other portion of

00:50:45.680 --> 00:50:52.660
the group. This is so to such an extent that Negroes in this country who themselves or whose

00:50:52.660 --> 00:51:00.280
forefathers went through the school of slavery are constantly returning to Africa as missionaries to

00:51:00.280 --> 00:51:07.960
enlighten those who remained in the fatherland. This I say not to justify slavery. On the other

00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:15.900
hand, I condemn it as an institution as we all know that in America it was established for selfish

00:51:15.900 --> 00:51:24.780
and financial reasons and not from a missionary motive, but call attention to a fact and to show

00:51:24.780 --> 00:51:34.560
how Providence so often uses men and institutions to accomplish a purpose. When persons ask me in

00:51:34.560 --> 00:51:41.480
these days how in the midst of what sometimes seemed hopelessly discouraging conditions I can

00:51:41.480 --> 00:51:48.440
have such faith in the future of my race in this country, I remind them of the wilderness through

00:51:48.440 --> 00:51:55.100
which and out of which a good Providence had already led us. Ever since I have been old enough

00:51:55.100 --> 00:52:01.560
to think for myself, I have entertained the idea that notwithstanding the cruel wrongs

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:07.840
inflicted upon us, the black man got nearly as much out of slavery as the white man did.

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:15.040
The hurtful inferences of the institution were not by any means confined to the Negro.

00:52:15.040 --> 00:52:22.980
This was fully illustrated by the life upon our own plantation. The whole machinery of slavery

00:52:22.980 --> 00:52:31.020
was so constructed as to cause labor as a rule to be looked upon as a batch of degradation of

00:52:31.020 --> 00:52:39.000
inferiority. Hence labor was something that both races on the slave plantations sought to escape.

00:52:39.480 --> 00:52:45.800
The slave system on our place in a large measure took the spirit of self-reliance

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:54.140
and self-help out of the white people. My old master had many boys and girls, but not one,

00:52:54.320 --> 00:53:02.100
so far as I know, ever mastered a single trade or special line of productive industries.

00:53:02.820 --> 00:53:10.660
The girls were not taught to cook, sew, or to take care of the house. All of this was left to the

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:17.940
slaves. The slaves, of course, had little personal interest in the life of the plantation, and their

00:53:17.940 --> 00:53:24.700
ignorance prevented them from learning how to do things in the most improved and thorough manner.

00:53:24.700 --> 00:53:32.260
As a result of the system, fences were out of repair, gates were hanging half off the hinges,

00:53:32.700 --> 00:53:38.720
doors creaked, window panes were out, plastering had fallen but was not replaced,

00:53:39.220 --> 00:53:45.740
weeds grew in the yard. As a rule, there was food for whites and blacks, but inside the house and

00:53:45.740 --> 00:53:53.420
on the dining room table, there was wanting that delicacy and refinement of both of touch and

00:53:53.420 --> 00:53:59.940
which can make a home the most convenient, comfortable, and attractive place in the world.

00:54:00.720 --> 00:54:08.480
Withal, there was a waste of food and outer materials which was sad. When freedom came,

00:54:08.680 --> 00:54:16.520
the slaves were almost as well fitted to begin life anew as the master, except in the matter of

00:54:16.520 --> 00:54:25.140
learning and ownership of property. The slave owner and his sons had mastered no special industry.

00:54:25.620 --> 00:54:33.120
They unconsciously had imbibed the feeling that manual labor was not the proper thing for them.

00:54:33.740 --> 00:54:40.820
On the other hand, the slaves in many cases had mastered some handicraft and none were ashamed

00:54:40.820 --> 00:54:47.160
and feel unwilling to labor. Finally, the war closed and the day of freedom came.

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:54.660
It was a momentous and eventful day to all upon our plantation. We had been expecting it.

00:54:55.020 --> 00:55:01.520
Freedom was in the air and had been for months. Disserting soldiers returning to their homes

00:55:01.520 --> 00:55:08.800
were to be seen every day. Others who had been discharged or whose regiments had been paroled

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:16.440
were constantly passing near our place. The grapevine telegraph was kept busy night and day.

00:55:17.080 --> 00:55:23.680
The news and mutterings of great events were swiftly carried from one plantation to another.

00:55:24.200 --> 00:55:31.980
In the fear of Yankee invasions, the silverware and other valuables were taken from the big house,

00:55:31.980 --> 00:55:40.720
buried in the woods and guarded by trusted slaves. Woe be to anyone who would have attempted to

00:55:40.720 --> 00:55:47.440
disturb the buried treasure. The slaves would give the Yankee soldiers food, drink, clothing,

00:55:47.740 --> 00:55:54.280
anything but that which had been specifically entrusted to their care and honor.

00:55:54.700 --> 00:56:00.800
As the great day drew nearer, there was more singing in the slave quarters than usual.

00:56:00.800 --> 00:56:09.860
It was bolder, had more ring, and lasted later into the night. Most of the verses of the plantation

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:17.780
songs had some reference to freedom. True, they had sung those same verses before, but they had

00:56:17.780 --> 00:56:25.500
been careful to explain that the freedom in these songs referred to the next world and had no

00:56:25.500 --> 00:56:32.680
connection with life in this world. Now they gradually threw off the mask and were not afraid

00:56:32.680 --> 00:56:39.280
to let it be known that the freedom in their songs mean freedom of the body in this world.

00:56:39.960 --> 00:56:46.260
The night before the eventful day, word was sent to the slave quarters to the effect that something

00:56:46.260 --> 00:56:53.320
unusual was going to take place at the big house the next morning. There was little, if any, sleep

00:56:53.320 --> 00:57:01.720
that night, all as excitement and expectancy. Early the next morning, word was sent to all the

00:57:01.720 --> 00:57:07.820
slaves, old and young, to gather at the house. In company with my mother, brother, and my sister,

00:57:07.920 --> 00:57:14.380
and a large number of other slaves, I went to the master's house. All of our master's family were

00:57:14.380 --> 00:57:21.840
either standing or seated on the veranda of the house, where they could see what was to take place

00:57:21.840 --> 00:57:29.860
and hear what was said. There was a feeling of deep interest or perhaps sadness on the faces,

00:57:29.860 --> 00:57:37.400
but not bitterness. As I now recall the impression they made upon me, they did not at the moment seem

00:57:37.400 --> 00:57:45.220
to be sad because of the loss of property, but rather because of parting with those whom they

00:57:45.220 --> 00:57:53.500
reared and who were in many ways very close to them. The most distinct thing that I now recall

00:57:53.500 --> 00:58:00.180
in connection with the scene was that some man who seemed to be a stranger, in brackets a United

00:58:00.180 --> 00:58:08.200
States officer, I presume, made a little speech and then read a rather long paper, the Emancipation

00:58:08.200 --> 00:58:14.840
Proclamation, I think. After the reading, we were told that we were all free and could go

00:58:14.840 --> 00:58:22.500
when and where we pleased. My mother, who was standing by my side, leaned over and kissed her

00:58:22.500 --> 00:58:29.580
children while tears of joy ran down her cheeks. She explained to us what it all meant, that this

00:58:29.580 --> 00:58:36.360
was the day for which she had been so long playing but fearing that she would never live to see.

00:58:36.360 --> 00:58:43.980
For some minutes there was great rejoicing and thanksgiving and wild scenes of ecstasy,

00:58:44.020 --> 00:58:50.980
but there was no feeling of bitterness. In fact, there was pity among the slaves for our former

00:58:50.980 --> 00:58:59.640
owners. The wild rejoicing on the part of the emancipated colored people lasted but for a brief

00:58:59.640 --> 00:59:06.260
period, for I noticed that by the time they returned to their cabins there was a change in

00:59:06.260 --> 00:59:13.680
their feelings. The great responsibility of being free or having charge of themselves or having to

00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:21.000
think and plan for themselves and their children seemed to take possession of them. It was very

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:28.460
much like suddenly turning a youth of 10 or 12 years out into the world to provide for himself.

00:59:29.160 --> 00:59:35.900
In a few hours, the great question with which the Anglo-Saxon race had been grappling for

00:59:35.900 --> 00:59:42.860
centuries had been thrown upon these people to be solved. These were the questions of a home,

00:59:43.200 --> 00:59:49.920
a living, the varying of children, education, citizenship, and the establishment and support

00:59:49.920 --> 00:59:58.080
of churches. Was it any wonder that within a few hours the wild rejoicing ceased and a feeling of

00:59:58.080 --> 01:00:04.840
gloom seemed to pervade the slave quarters? To some, it seemed that now that they were

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:11.740
in actual possession of it, freedom was a more serious thing than they had expected to find it.

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:20.340
Some of the slaves were 70 or 80 years old. Their best days were gone. They had no strength

01:00:20.340 --> 01:00:28.000
for which to earn a living in a strange place and among strange people, even if they have been sure

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:34.840
where to find a new place of abode. To this class, the problem seemed especially hard.

01:00:35.320 --> 01:00:42.640
Besides, deep down in their hearts, there was a strange and peculiar attachment to old masters

01:00:42.640 --> 01:00:49.100
and to old missus and to their children, which they found it hard to think of breaking off.

01:00:49.740 --> 01:00:57.060
Of these, they spent in some cases nearly half a century and it was no light thing to think of

01:00:58.100 --> 01:01:05.700
Gradually, one by one, stealthily at first, the older slaves began to wander from the slave

01:01:05.700 --> 01:01:24.460
quarters back to the big house to have a whispered conversation with their former owners as to the

01:01:51.380 --> 01:02:12.960
After the coming of freedom, there were two points upon which practically all the people on our place were agreed, and I found that this was generally true throughout the South, that they must change their names, and that they must leave the old plantation for at least a few days or weeks in order that they might really feel sure that they were free.

01:02:14.020 --> 01:02:29.280
In some way, a feeling got among the colored people that it was far from proper for them to bear the surnames of their former owners, and a great many of them took other surnames. This was one of the first signs of freedom.

01:02:29.280 --> 01:02:49.800
When they were slaves, a colored person was simply called John or Susan. There was seldom occasion for more than the use of the one name. If John or Susan belonged to a white man by the name of Hatcher, sometimes he was called John Hatcher, or as often, Hatcher's John.

01:02:49.800 --> 01:03:15.760
But there was a feeling that John Hatcher, or Hatcher's John, was not the proper title by which to denote a free man, and so in many cases John Hatcher was changed to John S. Lincoln, or John S. Sherman, the initial S standing for no name, it being simply a part of what the colored man proudly called his entitles.

01:03:15.760 --> 01:03:44.800
As I have stated, most of the colored people left the old plantation for a short while at least so as to be sure, it seemed, that they could leave and try their freedom on to see how it felt. After they had remained away for a while, many of the older slaves especially, returned to their old homes and made some kind of contract with their former owners by which they remained on the estate.

01:03:45.860 --> 01:04:15.120
My mother's husband, who was the stepfather of my brother John and myself, did not belong to the same owners as did my mother. In fact, he seldom came to our plantation. I remember seeing him there perhaps once a year, that being about Christmas time. In some way, during the war, by running away and following the Federal soldiers, it seems, he found his way into the new state of West Virginia.

01:04:15.120 --> 01:04:44.310
As soon as freedom was declared, he sent for my mother to come to Kanawha Valley in West Virginia. At that time, a journey from Virginia over the mountains to West Virginia was rather a tedious and in some cases a painful undertaking. What little clothing and few household goods we had were placed in a cart, but the children walked the greater portion of the distance, which was several hundred miles.

01:04:45.260 --> 01:05:02.760
I do not think that any of us had ever been very far from the plantation and the taking of a long journey into another state was quite an event. The parting from our former owners and the members of our own race on the plantation was a serious occasion.

01:05:02.760 --> 01:05:24.880
From the time of our parting until their death, we kept up a correspondence with the older members of the family, and in later years we have kept in touch with those who were the younger members. We were several weeks making the trip, and most of the time we slept in the open air and did our cooking over a log fire out of doors.

01:05:24.880 --> 01:05:51.620
One night I recall that we camped near an abandoned log cabin, and my mother decided to build a fire in that for cooking and afterward to make a pallet on the floor for our sleeping. Just as the fire had gotten well started, a large black snake fully a yard and a half long dropped down the chimney and ran out on the floor. Of course, we had once abandoned that cabin.

01:05:52.680 --> 01:06:12.100
Finally, we reached our destination, a little town called Malden, which is about five miles from Charleston, the present capital of the state. At that time, salt mining was the great industry in that part of West Virginia, and the little town of Malden was right in the midst of the salt furnaces.

01:06:14.080 --> 01:06:31.720
My stepfather had already secured a job at a salt furnace, and he had also secured a little cabin for us to live in. Our new house was no better than the one we had left on the old plantation in Virginia. In fact, in one respect, it was worse.

01:06:32.660 --> 01:06:53.040
Notwithstanding the poor condition of our plantation cabin, we were at all times sure of pure air. Our new home was in the midst of a cluster of cabins crowded closely together, and as there were no sanitary regulations, the filth about the cabins was often intolerable.

01:06:53.040 --> 01:07:09.200
Some of our neighbors were colored people, and some were the poorest and most ignorant and degraded white people. It was a motley mixture. Drinking, gambling, quarrels, fights, and shockingly immoral practices were frequent.

01:07:09.200 --> 01:07:26.980
All who lived in the little town were in one way or another connected with the salt business. Though I was a mere child, my stepfather put me and my brother at work in one of the furnaces. Often I began work as early as four o'clock in the morning.

01:07:26.980 --> 01:07:42.080
The first thing I ever learned in the way of book knowledge was while working in this salt furnace. Each salt packer had his barrels marked with a certain number. The number allocated to my stepfather was eighteen.

01:07:42.080 --> 01:08:01.740
At the close of the day's work, the boss of the packers would come around and put eighteen on each of our barrels, and I soon learned to recognize that figure wherever I saw it, and after a while got to the point where I could make that figure, though I knew nothing about any other figures or letters.

01:08:02.660 --> 01:08:23.040
From the time that I can remember having any thoughts about anything, I recall that I had an intense longing to learn to read. I determined, when quite a small child, that if I accomplished nothing else in life, I would in some way get enough education to enable me to read common books and newspapers.

01:08:23.040 --> 01:08:49.860
Soon after we got settled in some manor in our new cabin in West Virginia, I induced my mother to get hold of a book for me. How or where she got it I do not know, but in some way she procured an old copy of Webster's blue-backed spelling book, which contained the alphabet, followed by such meaningless words as ab, ba, ca, da.

01:08:49.860 --> 01:09:12.580
I began at once to devour this book, and I think that it was the first one I ever had in my hands. I had learned from somebody that the way to begin to read was to learn the alphabet, so I tried in all the ways I could think of to learn it, all of course without a teacher, for I could find no one to teach me.

01:09:12.580 --> 01:09:27.700
At that time there was not a single member of my race anywhere near us who could read, and I was too timid to approach any of the white people. In some way within a few weeks I mastered the greater portion of the alphabet.

01:09:27.700 --> 01:09:51.740
In all my efforts to learn to read, my mother shared fully my ambition, and sympathized with me, and aided me in every way that she could. Though she was totally ignorant, she had high ambitions for her children, and a large fund of good, hard, common sense which seemed to enable her to meet and master every situation.

01:09:51.740 --> 01:09:59.880
If I have done anything in life worth attention, I feel sure that I inherited the disposition from my mother.

01:10:00.760 --> 01:10:27.480
In the midst of my struggles and longing for an education, a young colored boy who had learned to read in the state of Ohio came to Malden. As soon as the colored people found out that he could read, a newspaper was secured, and at the close of nearly every day's work this young man would be surrounded by a group of men and women who were anxious to hear him read the news contained in the papers.

01:10:27.480 --> 01:10:37.480
How I used to envy this man. He seemed to me to be the one young man in all the world who ought to be satisfied with his attainments.

01:10:37.480 --> 01:11:01.360
About this time the question of having some kind of school opened for the colored children in the village began to be discussed by members of the race. As it would be the first school for Negro children that had ever been opened in that part of Virginia, it was, of course, to be a great event, and the discussion excited the wildest interest.

01:11:01.360 --> 01:11:23.420
The most perplexing question was where to find a teacher. The young man from Ohio who had learned to read the papers was considered, but his age was against him. In the midst of the discussion about a teacher, another young colored man from Ohio who had been a soldier in some way found his way into town.

01:11:23.420 --> 01:11:48.600
It was soon learned that he possessed a considerable education, and he was engaged by the colored people to teach their first school. As yet, no free schools had been started for colored people in that section. Hence, each family agreed to pay a certain amount per month, with the understanding that the teacher was to board round, that is, spend a day with each family.

01:11:48.600 --> 01:12:04.040
This was not bad for the teacher, for each family tried to provide the very best on the day the teacher was to be its guest. I recall that I looked forward with an anxious appetite to Teacher's Day at our little cabin.

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:16.140
This experience of a whole race beginning to go to school for the first time presents one of the most interesting studies that has ever occurred in connection with the development of any race.

01:12:16.740 --> 01:12:32.160
Few people who were not right in the midst of the scenes can form any exact idea of the intense desire which the people of my race showed for an education. As I have stated, it was a whole race trying to go to school.

01:12:32.160 --> 01:12:51.660
Few were too young and none too old to make the attempt to learn. As fast as any kind of teachers could be secured, not only were day schools filled, but night schools as well. The great ambition of the older people was to try to learn to read the Bible before they died.

01:12:51.660 --> 01:13:17.760
With this end in view, men and women who were 50 or 75 years old would often be found in the night school. Some day schools were formed soon after the freedom, but the principal book studied in the Sunday school was the spelling book. Day school, night school, Sunday school were always crowded and often many had to be turned away for want of room.

01:13:17.760 --> 01:13:41.820
The opening of the school in Canova Valley, however, brought to me one of the keenest disappointments that I ever experienced. I had been working in a salt furnace for several months and my stepfather had discovered that I had a financial value, and so when the school opened he decided that he could not spare me from my work.

01:13:41.820 --> 01:13:59.100
This decision seemed to cloud my every ambition. The disappointment was made all the more severe by reason of the fact that my place of work was where I could see the happy children passing to and from school mornings and afternoons.

01:13:59.100 --> 01:14:12.920
Despite this disappointment, however, I determined that I would learn something anyway. I applied myself with greater eagerness than ever to the mastering of what was in the blue-backed speller.

01:14:14.220 --> 01:14:32.580
My mother sympathized with me in my disappointment and sought to comfort me in all the ways she could and to help me find a way to learn. After a while I succeeded in making arrangements with the teacher to give me some lessons at night after the day's work was done.

01:14:32.580 --> 01:14:51.940
These night lessons were so welcome that I think I learned more at night than the other children did during the day. My own experiences in the night school gave me faith in the night school idea, which in after years I had to do both at Hampton and Tuskegee.

01:14:51.940 --> 01:15:20.340
But my boyish heart was still set upon going to the day school and I let no opportunity slip to push my case. Finally I won and was permitted to go to the school in the day for a few months with the understanding that I was to rise early in the morning and work in the furnace till nine o'clock and return immediately after school closed in the afternoon for at least two more hours of work.

01:15:20.340 --> 01:15:37.660
The schoolhouse was some distance from the furnace and as I had to work till nine o'clock and the school opened at nine, I found myself in a difficulty. School would always be begun before I reached it and sometimes my class had recited.

01:15:37.660 --> 01:15:59.420
To get around this difficulty I yielded to a temptation for which most people, I suppose, will condemn me. But since it is a fact I might as well state it. I have great faith in the power and influence of facts. It is seldom that anything is permanently gained by holding back a fact.

01:15:59.420 --> 01:16:12.740
There was a large clock in a little office in the furnace. This clock, of course, all the hundred or more workmen depended upon to regulate their hours of beginning and ending the day's work.

01:16:12.740 --> 01:16:39.280
I got the idea that the way for me to reach school on time was to move the clock hands from half past eight up to the nine o'clock mark. This I found myself doing morning after morning till the furnace boss discovered that something was wrong and locked the clock in a case. I did not mean to inconvenience anybody. I simply meant to reach that schoolhouse in time.

01:16:40.380 --> 01:16:58.020
When, however, I found myself at the school for the first time I also found myself confronted with two other difficulties. In the first place I found that all the other children were hats or caps on their heads and I had neither hat nor cap.

01:16:58.020 --> 01:17:21.980
In fact, I do not remember that up to the time of going to school I had ever worn any kind of covering upon my head, nor do I recall that either I or anyone else had even thought anything about the need for covering for my head. But, of course, when I saw how all the other boys were dressed I began to feel quite uncomfortable.

01:17:21.980 --> 01:17:44.460
As usual, I put the case before my mother and she explained to me that she had no money with which to buy a store hat, which was a rather new institution at that time among the members of my race and was considered quite the thing for young or old to own, but that she would find a way to help me out of the difficulty.

01:17:44.460 --> 01:17:55.300
She accordingly got two pieces of homespun, jeans, and sewed them together and I was soon the proud possessor of my first cap.

01:17:56.300 --> 01:18:18.000
The lesson that my mother taught me in this has always remained with me and I have tried as best I could to teach it to others. I have always felt proud whenever I think of the incident that my mother had strength of character enough not to be led into the temptation of seeming to be that which she was not,

01:18:18.000 --> 01:18:33.760
of trying to impress my schoolmates and others with the fact that she was able to buy me a store hat when she was not. I have always felt proud that she refused to go into debt for that which she did not have the money to pay for.

01:18:33.760 --> 01:18:46.320
Since that time I have owned many kinds of caps and hats, but never one of which I have felt so proud of as the cap made of the two pieces of cloth sewed together by my mother.

01:18:46.320 --> 01:19:12.120
I have noted the fact, but without satisfaction I need not add, that several of the boys who began their careers with store hats and who were my schoolmates and used to join in the sport that was made of me because I had only a homespun cap have ended their careers in the penitentiary while others are not able now to buy any kind of hat.

01:19:12.120 --> 01:19:30.340
My second difficulty was with regard to my name, or rather a name. From the time that I could remember anything I had been called simply Booker. Before going to school it never occurred to me that it was needful or appropriate to have an additional name.

01:19:30.340 --> 01:19:51.640
When I heard the school roll called I noticed that all of the boys had at least two names and some of them indulged in what seemed to me to be the extravagance of having three. I was in deep perplexity because I knew that the teacher would demand of me at least two names and I had only one.

01:19:51.640 --> 01:20:14.740
By the time the occasion came for the enrolling of my name an idea occurred to me which I thought would make me equal to the situation and so when the teacher asked me what my full name was I calmly told him Booker Washington as if I had been called by that name all my life and by that name I have since been known.

01:20:14.740 --> 01:20:37.120
Later in my life I found that my mother had given me the name of Booker Tolliver soon after I was born but in some way that part of my name seemed to disappear and for a long while was forgotten but as soon as I found out about it I revived it and made my full name Booker Tolliver Washington.

01:20:37.120 --> 01:20:46.060
I think there are not many men in our country who have had the privilege of naming themselves in the way that I have.

01:20:46.060 --> 01:21:15.220
More than once I tried to picture myself in the position of a boy or man with an honored or distinguished ancestry which I could trace back through a period of hundreds of years and who had not only inherited name but fortune and a proud family homestead and yet I sometimes had the feeling that if I had inherited these and had been a member of a more popular race

01:21:15.220 --> 01:21:25.240
I should have been inclined to yield to the temptation of depending upon my ancestry and my color to do that for me which I should do for myself.

01:21:27.480 --> 01:21:38.520
Years ago I resolved that because I had no ancestry myself I would leave a record of which my children would be proud and which might encourage them to still greater effort.

01:21:38.520 --> 01:21:46.460
The world should not pass judgment upon the Negro and especially the Negro youth too quickly or too harshly.

01:21:46.860 --> 01:21:55.440
The Negro boy has obstacles, discouragements and temptations to battle that are little known to those not situated as he is.

01:21:56.000 --> 01:22:01.100
When a white boy undertakes a task it is taken for granted that he will succeed.

01:22:01.740 --> 01:22:07.040
On the other hand people are usually surprised if the Negro boy does not fail.

01:22:07.040 --> 01:22:12.660
In a word, the Negro youth starts out with the presumption against him.

01:22:13.240 --> 01:22:23.680
The influence of ancestry, however, is important in helping forward any individual or race if too much reliance is not placed upon it.

01:22:23.680 --> 01:22:40.820
Those who constantly direct attention to the Negro youth's moral weaknesses and compare his advancement with that of white youths do not consider the influence of the memories which cling about the old family homesteads.

01:22:41.200 --> 01:22:46.180
I have no idea, as I have stated elsewhere, who my grandmother was.

01:22:46.180 --> 01:22:54.500
I have or have had uncles and aunts and cousins, but I have no knowledge as to where most of them are.

01:22:54.620 --> 01:23:00.900
My case will illustrate that of hundreds of thousands of black people in every part of our country.

01:23:00.900 --> 01:23:16.420
The very fact that a white boy is conscious that if he fails in life he will disgrace the whole family record, extending back through many generations, is of tremendous value in helping him to resist temptations.

01:23:16.420 --> 01:23:30.660
The fact that the individual has behind and surrounded him proud family history and connection serves as a stimulus to help him to overcome obstacles when striving for success.

01:23:32.380 --> 01:23:38.780
The time that I was permitted to attend school during the day was short and my attendance was irregular.

01:23:38.780 --> 01:23:46.980
It was not long before I had to stop attending day school altogether and devote all my time again to work.

01:23:47.540 --> 01:23:49.700
I resorted to night school again.

01:23:50.280 --> 01:23:58.940
In fact, the greater part of the education I secured in my boyhood was gathered through the night school after my day's work was done.

01:23:59.700 --> 01:24:04.020
I had difficulty often in securing a satisfactory teacher.

01:24:04.740 --> 01:24:15.180
Sometimes after I had secured someone to teach me at night, I would find, much to my disappointment, that the teacher knew but little more than I did.

01:24:15.660 --> 01:24:21.280
Often I would have to walk several miles at night in order to recite my night school lessons.

01:24:21.280 --> 01:24:37.000
There was never a time in my youth, no matter how dark and discouraging the days might be, when one resolve did not continually remain with me, and that was a determination to secure an education at any cost.

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:51.160
Soon after we moved to West Virginia, my mother adopted into our family, notwithstanding our poverty, an orphan boy to whom afterward we gave the name of James B. Washington.

01:24:52.060 --> 01:24:55.260
He has ever since remained a member of the family.

01:24:56.580 --> 01:25:08.720
After I had worked in the salt furnace for some time, work was secured for me in a coal mine, which was operated mainly for the purpose of securing fuel for the salt furnace.

01:25:09.780 --> 01:25:12.480
Work in the coal mine I always dreaded.

01:25:12.480 --> 01:25:26.360
One reason for this was that anyone who worked in a coal mine was always unclean, at least while at work, and it was a very hard job to get one's skin clean after the day's work was over.

01:25:27.160 --> 01:25:36.040
Then it was fully a mile from the opening of the coal mine to the face of the coal, and all, of course, was in blackest darkness.

01:25:36.040 --> 01:25:44.120
I do not believe that one ever experiences anywhere else such darkness as he does in a coal mine.

01:25:44.460 --> 01:25:57.440
The mine was divided into a large number of different rooms or departments, and as I was never able to learn the location of all of these rooms, I many times found myself lost in the mine.

01:25:57.440 --> 01:26:12.680
To add to the horror of being lost, sometimes my light would go out, and then, if I did not happen to have a match, I would wander about in the darkness until by chance I found someone to give me a light.

01:26:13.420 --> 01:26:16.480
The work was not only hard, but it was dangerous.

01:26:17.140 --> 01:26:25.440
There was always the danger of being blown to pieces by a premature explosion of powder or of being crushed by a falling slate.

01:26:26.320 --> 01:26:33.600
Accidents from one or another of these causes were frequently occurring, and this kept me in constant fear.

01:26:34.580 --> 01:26:49.740
Many children of the tenderest years were compelled then, as it is now true, I fear, in most coal mining districts to spend the large part of their lives in these coal mines with little opportunity to get an education.

01:26:49.740 --> 01:27:00.850
And what is worse, I have often noted that, as a rule, young boys who begin life in a coal mine are often physically and mentally dwarfed.

01:27:01.940 --> 01:27:07.880
They soon lose the ambition to do anything else than continue as a coal miner.

01:27:09.140 --> 01:27:23.340
In those days and later as a young man, I used to picture in my imagination the feeling and ambitions of a white boy with absolutely no limit placed upon his aspirations and activities.

01:27:23.340 --> 01:27:37.320
I used to envy the white boy who had no obstacles placed in the way of his becoming a congressman, governor, bishop, or president by reason of the accident of his birth or race.

01:27:37.900 --> 01:27:48.960
I used to picture the way that I would act under such circumstances, how I would begin at the bottom and keep rising until I reached the highest round of success.

01:27:49.800 --> 01:27:55.160
In later years, I confess that I do not envy the white boy as I once did.

01:27:55.660 --> 01:28:07.080
I have learned that success is to be measured not so much by the position that one has reached in life as by the obstacles which he has overcome while trying to succeed.

01:28:07.080 --> 01:28:21.800
To look at from this standpoint, I almost reached the conclusion that often the Negro boy's birth and connection with an unpopular race is an advantage so far as real life is concerned.

01:28:22.480 --> 01:28:33.480
With few exceptions, the Negro youth must work harder and must perform his tasks even better than the white youth in order to secure recognition.

01:28:33.480 --> 01:28:48.240
But out of the hard and unusual struggle through which he is compelled to pass, he gets the strength and confidence that one misses whose pathway is comparatively smooth by reason of birth and race.

01:28:49.320 --> 01:29:00.180
From any point of view, I had rather be what I am, a member of the Negro race, than be able to claim membership with the most favored of any other race.

01:29:00.180 --> 01:29:18.600
I have always been made sad when I hear members of any race claiming rights or privileges or a certain badge of distinction on the grounds simply that they were members of this or that race, regardless of their own individual worth or attainments.

01:29:18.600 --> 01:29:47.980
I have been made to feel sad for such persons because I am conscious of the fact that mere connection with what is known as a superior race will not permanently carry an individual forward unless he has individual worth, and mere connection with what is regarded as an inferior race will not finally hold an individual back if he possesses intrinsic individual merit.

01:29:47.980 --> 01:30:07.300
Every persecuted individual and race should get much consolation out of the great human law, which is universal and eternal, that merit, no matter under what skin found, is, in the long run, recognized and rewarded.

01:30:08.220 --> 01:30:16.840
This I have said here not to call attention to myself as an individual, but to the race of which I am proud to belong.

01:30:37.860 --> 01:30:41.380
The Struggle for an Education

01:30:42.250 --> 01:30:47.460
One day, while at work in the coal mine, I happened to overhear two miners talking about

01:30:47.460 --> 01:30:51.020
a great school for colored people somewhere in Virginia.

01:30:51.860 --> 01:30:57.180
This was the first time that I had ever heard anything about any kind of school or college

01:30:57.180 --> 01:31:01.520
that was more pretentious than the little colored school in our town.

01:31:02.420 --> 01:31:07.780
In the darkness of the mine, I noiselessly crept as close as I could to the two men who

01:31:07.780 --> 01:31:08.440
were talking.

01:31:09.040 --> 01:31:14.660
I heard one tell the other that not only was the school established for the members of

01:31:14.660 --> 01:31:21.020
any race, but the opportunities that it provided by which poor but worthy students could work

01:31:21.020 --> 01:31:28.340
out all or a part of the cost of a board and at the same time be taught some trade or industry.

01:31:29.240 --> 01:31:34.320
As they went on describing the school, it seemed to me that it must be the greatest

01:31:34.320 --> 01:31:41.220
place on earth, and not even heaven presented more attractions for me at that time than

01:31:41.220 --> 01:31:47.700
I had the Hampton Normal and Agricultural Institute in Virginia about which these men

01:31:47.700 --> 01:31:48.380
were talking.

01:31:49.100 --> 01:31:55.720
I resolved at once to go to that school, although I had no idea where it was or how many miles

01:31:55.720 --> 01:31:58.480
away or how I was going to reach it.

01:31:58.880 --> 01:32:06.100
I remembered only that I was on fire constantly with one ambition, and that was to go to Hampton.

01:32:06.460 --> 01:32:08.600
This thought was with me day and night.

01:32:08.980 --> 01:32:14.600
After hearing of the Hampton Institute, I continued to work for a few months longer

01:32:14.600 --> 01:32:15.600
in the coal mine.

01:32:16.200 --> 01:32:22.020
While at work there, I heard of a vacant position in the household of General Lewis Ruffner,

01:32:22.620 --> 01:32:25.440
the owner of the salt furnace and coal mine.

01:32:26.020 --> 01:32:32.360
Mrs. Viola Ruffner, the wife of General Ruffner, was a Yankee woman from Vermont.

01:32:33.200 --> 01:32:38.580
Mrs. Ruffner had a reputation all through the vicinity for being very strict with her

01:32:38.580 --> 01:32:42.560
servants, and especially with the boys who tried to serve her.

01:32:43.020 --> 01:32:46.700
Few of them remained with her for more than two or three weeks.

01:32:47.320 --> 01:32:50.840
They all left with the same excuse, she was too strict.

01:32:51.540 --> 01:32:57.180
I decided, however, that I would rather try Mrs. Ruffner's house than remain in the coal

01:32:57.180 --> 01:33:00.980
mine, and so my mother applied to her for the vacant position.

01:33:01.620 --> 01:33:04.940
I was hired at a salary of five dollars per month.

01:33:05.580 --> 01:33:12.300
I had heard so much about Mrs. Ruffner's severity that I was almost afraid to see her and trembled

01:33:12.300 --> 01:33:14.240
when I went into her presence.

01:33:14.780 --> 01:33:20.500
I had not lived with her many weeks, however, before I began to understand her.

01:33:20.880 --> 01:33:26.820
I soon began to learn that, first of all, she wanted everything kept clean about her,

01:33:27.020 --> 01:33:33.320
that she wanted things done promptly and systematically, and at the bottom of everything she wanted

01:33:33.320 --> 01:33:35.400
absolute honesty and frankness.

01:33:36.080 --> 01:33:38.640
Nothing must be sullivan or slipshod.

01:33:39.160 --> 01:33:42.760
Every door, every fence must be kept in repair.

01:33:43.520 --> 01:33:49.680
I cannot now recall how long I lived with Mrs. Ruffner before going to Hampton, but

01:33:49.680 --> 01:33:52.080
I think it must have been a year and a half.

01:33:52.500 --> 01:33:58.580
At any rate, I here repeat what I have said more than once before, that the lessons that

01:33:58.580 --> 01:34:05.340
in the home of Mrs. Ruffner were as valuable to me as any education I have ever gotten

01:34:05.340 --> 01:34:06.400
anywhere else.

01:34:07.000 --> 01:34:12.760
Even to this day, I never see bits of paper scattered around the house or in the street

01:34:12.760 --> 01:34:15.500
that I do not want to pick them up at once.

01:34:15.800 --> 01:34:22.600
I never see a filthy yard that I do not want to clean it, a paling off a fence that I do

01:34:22.600 --> 01:34:29.100
not want to put it on, an unpainted or un-whitewashed house that I do not want to paint or whitewash

01:34:29.100 --> 01:34:36.480
it, or a button off one's clothes or a grease spot on them or on a floor that I do not want

01:34:36.480 --> 01:34:37.980
to call attention to it.

01:34:38.260 --> 01:34:43.940
From fearing Mrs. Ruffner, I soon learned to look upon her as one of my best friends.

01:34:44.660 --> 01:34:48.660
When she found that she could trust me, she did so implicitly.

01:34:49.100 --> 01:34:54.840
During the one or two winters that I was with her, she gave me an opportunity to go to school

01:34:54.840 --> 01:34:59.880
for an hour in the day during a portion of the winter months, but most of my studying

01:34:59.880 --> 01:35:06.500
was done at night, sometimes alone, sometimes under someone whom I could hire to teach me.

01:35:07.060 --> 01:35:12.520
Mrs. Ruffner always encouraged and sympathized with me in all my efforts to get an education.

01:35:13.200 --> 01:35:17.840
It was while living with her that I began to get together my first library.

01:35:18.620 --> 01:35:25.380
I secured a dry goods box, knocked out one side of it, put some shelves in it, and began

01:35:25.380 --> 01:35:31.240
putting into it every kind of book that I could get my hands upon and called it my library.

01:35:32.880 --> 01:35:38.740
Notwithstanding my success at Mrs. Ruffner's, I did not give up the idea of going to the

01:35:38.740 --> 01:35:39.960
Hampton Institute.

01:35:40.700 --> 01:35:47.800
In the fall of 1872 I determined to make an effort to get there, although, as I have stated,

01:35:48.320 --> 01:35:54.700
I had no definite idea of the direction in which Hampton was or of what it would cost

01:35:54.700 --> 01:35:55.540
to go there.

01:35:56.080 --> 01:36:02.280
I do not think that anyone thoroughly sympathized with me and my ambition to go to Hampton,

01:36:02.440 --> 01:36:07.820
unless it was my mother, and she was troubled with a grave fear that I was starting out

01:36:07.820 --> 01:36:09.320
on a wild goose chase.

01:36:09.980 --> 01:36:15.020
At any rate, I only got a half-hearted consent from her that I might start.

01:36:15.660 --> 01:36:20.900
The small amount of money that I had earned had been consumed by my stepfather and the

01:36:20.900 --> 01:36:27.360
remainder of the family, with the exception of a very few dollars, and so I had very little

01:36:27.360 --> 01:36:30.800
with which to buy clothes and pay my traveling expenses.

01:36:31.460 --> 01:36:37.100
My brother John helped me all that he could, but of course that was not a great deal, for

01:36:37.100 --> 01:36:43.500
his work was in a coal mine where he did not earn much, and most of what he did earn went

01:36:43.500 --> 01:36:46.420
in the directions of paying the household expenses.

01:36:48.220 --> 01:36:52.740
Perhaps the thing that touched and pleased me the most in connection with my starting

01:36:52.740 --> 01:36:58.760
for Hampton was the interest that many of the older colored people took in the matter.

01:36:59.160 --> 01:37:05.300
They had spent the best days of their lives in slavery and hardly expected to live to

01:37:05.300 --> 01:37:11.100
the time when they would see a member of their race leave home to attend a boarding school.

01:37:12.060 --> 01:37:17.120
Some of these older people would give me a nickel, others a quarter or a handkerchief.

01:37:18.120 --> 01:37:21.260
Finally the great day came and I started for Hampton.

01:37:21.920 --> 01:37:27.500
I had only a small cheap satchel that contained a few articles of clothing I could get.

01:37:27.760 --> 01:37:31.080
My mother at the time was rather weak and broken in health.

01:37:31.560 --> 01:37:36.700
I hardly expected to see her again and thus our parting was all the more sad.

01:37:37.380 --> 01:37:40.060
She however was very brave through it all.

01:37:40.900 --> 01:37:46.200
At that time there were no trains connecting that part of West Virginia with Eastern Virginia.

01:37:46.760 --> 01:37:52.200
Trains ran only a portion of the way and the remainder of the distance was traveled by

01:37:52.200 --> 01:37:53.080
stagecoaches.

01:37:53.540 --> 01:37:57.280
The distance from Malden to Hampton is about 500 miles.

01:37:57.950 --> 01:38:03.580
I had not been away from home many hours before it began to grow painfully evident that I

01:38:03.580 --> 01:38:06.460
did not have enough money to pay my fare to Hampton.

01:38:07.300 --> 01:38:09.560
One experience I shall long remember.

01:38:10.200 --> 01:38:15.560
I had been traveling over the mountains most of the afternoon in an old-fashioned stagecoach

01:38:15.560 --> 01:38:21.480
when, late in the evening, the coach stopped for the night at a common unpainted house

01:38:21.480 --> 01:38:22.600
called a hotel.

01:38:23.100 --> 01:38:26.160
All the other passengers except myself were whites.

01:38:26.750 --> 01:38:33.280
In my ignorance, I suppose that the little hotel existed for the purpose of accommodating

01:38:33.280 --> 01:38:36.360
the passengers who traveled on the stagecoach.

01:38:36.940 --> 01:38:41.820
The difference that the color of one's skin would make I had not thought anything about.

01:38:42.520 --> 01:38:48.260
After all the other passengers had been shown rooms and were getting ready for supper, I

01:38:48.260 --> 01:38:51.280
shyly presented myself before the man at the desk.

01:38:51.870 --> 01:38:57.540
It is true I had practically no money in my pocket with which to pay for bed or food,

01:38:58.060 --> 01:39:03.680
but I had hoped in some way to beg my way into the good graces of the landlord, for

01:39:03.680 --> 01:39:09.280
at that season in the mountains of Virginia the weather was cold and I wanted to get indoors

01:39:09.280 --> 01:39:10.140
for the night.

01:39:10.860 --> 01:39:16.820
Without asking as to whether I had any money, the man at the desk firmly refused to even

01:39:16.820 --> 01:39:20.300
consider the manner of providing me with food or lodging.

01:39:20.300 --> 01:39:25.440
This was my first experience in finding out what the color of my skin meant.

01:39:26.380 --> 01:39:31.080
In some way I managed to keep warm by walking about and so got through the night.

01:39:31.980 --> 01:39:38.400
My whole soul was so bent upon reaching Hampton that I did not have time to cherish any bitterness

01:39:38.400 --> 01:39:40.100
towards the hotel keeper.

01:39:40.680 --> 01:39:47.580
By walking, begging rides both in wagons and in the cars, in some way after a number of

01:39:47.580 --> 01:39:53.160
days, I reached the city of Richmond, Virginia, about 82 miles from Hampton.

01:39:53.880 --> 01:39:58.560
When I reached there, tired, hungry, and dirty, it was late in the night.

01:39:58.720 --> 01:40:03.360
I had never been in a large city, and this rather added to my misery.

01:40:04.340 --> 01:40:07.420
When I reached Richmond I was completely out of money.

01:40:08.060 --> 01:40:14.260
I had not a single acquaintance in the place, and being unused to city ways I did not know

01:40:14.260 --> 01:40:15.200
where to go.

01:40:15.640 --> 01:40:20.680
I applied at several places for lodging, but they all wanted money, and that was what I

01:40:20.680 --> 01:40:21.700
did not have.

01:40:22.980 --> 01:40:26.340
Knowing nothing else better to do, I walked the streets.

01:40:27.100 --> 01:40:32.540
In doing this I passed by many food stands where fried chicken and half-moon apple pies

01:40:32.540 --> 01:40:36.620
were piled high and made to present a most tempting appearance.

01:40:37.320 --> 01:40:42.380
At that time it seemed to me that I would have promised all that I expected to possess

01:40:42.380 --> 01:40:47.500
in the future, to have gotten hold of one of those chicken legs or one of those pies.

01:40:48.380 --> 01:40:52.200
But I could get neither of these nor anything else to eat.

01:40:52.560 --> 01:40:55.220
I must have walked the streets till after midnight.

01:40:55.760 --> 01:40:59.440
At last I became so exhausted that I could walk no longer.

01:41:00.020 --> 01:41:04.740
I was tired, I was hungry, I was everything but discouraged.

01:41:05.620 --> 01:41:11.280
Just about the time when I reached extreme physical exhaustion, I came upon a portion

01:41:11.280 --> 01:41:15.200
of a street where the bored sidewalk was considerably elevated.

01:41:15.900 --> 01:41:21.840
I waited for a few minutes till I was sure that no passers-by could see me, and then

01:41:21.840 --> 01:41:27.480
crept under the sidewalk and lay for the night upon the ground with my satchel of clothing

01:41:27.480 --> 01:41:28.280
for a pillow.

01:41:29.200 --> 01:41:33.060
Nearly all night I could hear the tramp of feet over my head.

01:41:33.780 --> 01:41:39.920
The next morning I found myself somewhat refreshed, but I was extremely hungry because it had

01:41:39.920 --> 01:41:43.160
been a long time since I had had sufficient food.

01:41:44.040 --> 01:41:49.260
As soon as it became light enough for me to see my surroundings, I noticed that I was

01:41:49.260 --> 01:41:54.660
near a large ship and that this ship seemed to be unloading a cargo of pig iron.

01:41:55.300 --> 01:42:01.520
I went at once to the vessel and asked the captain to permit me to help unload the vessel

01:42:01.520 --> 01:42:03.440
in order to get money for food.

01:42:04.180 --> 01:42:09.120
The captain, a white man who seemed to be kind-hearted, consented.

01:42:09.540 --> 01:42:15.220
I worked long enough to earn money for my breakfast, and it seems to me, as I remember

01:42:15.220 --> 01:42:19.600
it now, to have been about the best breakfast I have ever eaten.

01:42:20.100 --> 01:42:25.580
My work pleased the captain so well that he told me if I desired I could continue working

01:42:25.580 --> 01:42:27.340
for a small amount per day.

01:42:27.860 --> 01:42:29.840
This I was very glad to do.

01:42:30.340 --> 01:42:33.920
I continued working on this vessel for a number of days.

01:42:34.640 --> 01:42:41.200
After buying food with the small wages I received, there was not much left to add on the amount

01:42:41.200 --> 01:42:43.820
I must get to pay my way to Hampton.

01:42:44.340 --> 01:42:50.440
In order to economize in every way possible, so as to be sure to reach Hampton in a reasonable

01:42:50.440 --> 01:42:56.040
time, I continued to sleep under the same sidewalk that gave me shelter the first night

01:42:56.040 --> 01:42:57.000
I was in Richmond.

01:42:57.800 --> 01:43:04.420
Many years after that, the colored citizens of Richmond very kindly tendered me a reception

01:43:04.420 --> 01:43:07.700
at which there must have been two thousand people present.

01:43:08.440 --> 01:43:13.580
This reception was held not far from the spot where I slept the first night I spent in the

01:43:13.580 --> 01:43:19.680
city, and I must confess that my mind was more upon the sidewalk that first gave me

01:43:19.680 --> 01:43:24.360
shelter than upon the recognition, agreeable and cordial as it was.

01:43:25.200 --> 01:43:30.640
When I had saved what I considered enough money with which to reach Hampton, I thanked

01:43:30.640 --> 01:43:34.040
the captain of the vessel for his kindness and started again.

01:43:34.680 --> 01:43:40.760
Without any unusual occurrence, I reached Hampton with a surplus of exactly fifty cents

01:43:40.760 --> 01:43:42.760
with which to begin my education.

01:43:43.580 --> 01:43:49.620
To me it had been a long, eventful journey, but the first sight of the large three-story

01:43:49.620 --> 01:43:55.140
brick school building seemed to have rewarded me for all that I had undergone in order to

01:43:55.140 --> 01:43:55.980
reach the place.

01:43:56.640 --> 01:44:02.020
If the people who gave the money to provide that building could appreciate the influence

01:44:02.020 --> 01:44:09.200
the sight of it had upon me, as well as upon thousands of other years, they would feel

01:44:09.200 --> 01:44:11.520
all the more encouraged to make such gifts.

01:44:12.100 --> 01:44:16.780
It seemed to me to be the largest and most beautiful building I had ever seen.

01:44:17.220 --> 01:44:19.800
The sight of it seemed to give me new life.

01:44:20.280 --> 01:44:26.120
I felt that a new kind of existence had now begun, that life would now have a new meaning.

01:44:26.700 --> 01:44:32.140
I felt that I had reached the promised land, and I resolved to let no obstacle prevent

01:44:32.140 --> 01:44:38.020
me from putting forth the highest effort to fit myself to accomplish the most good in

01:44:38.020 --> 01:44:38.480
the world.

01:44:38.680 --> 01:44:44.480
As soon as possible after reaching the grounds of the Hampton Institute, I presented myself

01:44:44.480 --> 01:44:47.540
before the head teacher for an assignment to a class.

01:44:48.160 --> 01:44:54.040
Having been so long without proper food, a bath, and a change of clothing, I did not,

01:44:54.040 --> 01:45:00.240
of course, make a very favorable impression upon her, and I could see at once that there

01:45:00.240 --> 01:45:04.360
were doubts in her mind about the wisdom of admitting me as a student.

01:45:05.120 --> 01:45:10.820
I felt that I could hardly blame her if she got the idea that I was a worthless loafer

01:45:10.820 --> 01:45:11.600
or tramp.

01:45:12.320 --> 01:45:18.520
For some time she did not refuse to admit me, nor did she decide in my favor, and I

01:45:18.520 --> 01:45:24.480
continued to linger about her and to impress her with all the ways I could with my worthiness.

01:45:25.260 --> 01:45:30.900
In the meantime I saw her admitting other students, and that added greatly to my discomfort,

01:45:31.000 --> 01:45:37.080
for I felt deep down in my heart that I could do as well as they if I could only get a chance

01:45:37.080 --> 01:45:38.580
to show what was in me.

01:45:39.260 --> 01:45:43.080
After some hours had passed the head teacher said to me,

01:45:43.760 --> 01:45:46.780
The adjoining recitation room needs sweeping.

01:45:47.380 --> 01:45:49.420
Take the broom and sweep it.

01:45:50.180 --> 01:45:53.500
It occurred to me at once that here was my chance.

01:45:54.100 --> 01:45:56.780
Never did I receive an order with more delight.

01:45:57.180 --> 01:46:02.820
I knew that I could sweep, for Mrs. Ruffner had thoroughly taught me how to do that when

01:46:02.820 --> 01:46:03.880
I lived with her.

01:46:04.820 --> 01:46:07.680
I swept the recitation room three times.

01:46:08.020 --> 01:46:11.440
Then I got a dusting cloth and dusted it four times.

01:46:12.180 --> 01:46:17.860
All the woodwork around the walls, every bench, table, and desk I went over four times with

01:46:17.860 --> 01:46:18.940
my dusting cloth.

01:46:19.820 --> 01:46:25.120
Besides, every piece of furniture had been moved, and every closet and corner in the

01:46:25.120 --> 01:46:26.840
room had been thoroughly cleaned.

01:46:27.440 --> 01:46:33.400
I had the feeling that in the large measure my future depended upon the impression I made

01:46:33.400 --> 01:46:35.940
upon the teacher in the cleaning of that room.

01:46:36.580 --> 01:46:39.840
When I was through I reported to the head teacher.

01:46:40.420 --> 01:46:43.920
She was a Yankee woman who knew just where to look for dirt.

01:46:44.560 --> 01:46:50.060
She went into the room and inspected the floor and closets, then she took her handkerchief

01:46:50.060 --> 01:46:54.940
and rubbed it on the woodwork, about the walls, and over the table and benches.

01:46:56.000 --> 01:47:01.700
When she was unable to find one bit of dirt on the floor or a particle of dust on any

01:47:01.700 --> 01:47:07.160
of the furniture, she quietly remarked, I guess you will do to enter this institution.

01:47:08.020 --> 01:47:10.880
I was one of the happiest souls on earth.

01:47:11.360 --> 01:47:18.140
The sweeping of that room was my college examination, and never did any youth pass an examination

01:47:18.140 --> 01:47:24.680
for entrance into Harvard or Yale that gave him more genuine satisfaction.

01:47:25.360 --> 01:47:31.680
I have passed several examinations since then, but I have always felt that this was the best

01:47:31.680 --> 01:47:33.320
one I ever passed.

01:47:33.980 --> 01:47:38.440
I have spoken of my own experience in entering Hampton Institute.

01:47:39.120 --> 01:47:45.340
Perhaps few, if any, had anything like the same experience that I had, but about the

01:47:45.340 --> 01:47:50.420
same period there were hundreds who found their way to Hampton and other institutes

01:47:50.420 --> 01:47:54.840
after experiencing something of the same difficulties that I went through.

01:47:55.400 --> 01:48:00.600
The young men and women were determined to secure an education at any cost.

01:48:01.640 --> 01:48:06.620
The sweeping of the recitation room in the manner that I did it seems to have paved the

01:48:06.620 --> 01:48:08.420
way for me to get through Hampton.

01:48:09.160 --> 01:48:14.520
Miss Mary F. Mackey, the headteacher, offered me a position as janitor.

01:48:15.080 --> 01:48:20.680
This of course I gladly accepted, because it was a place where I could work out nearly

01:48:20.680 --> 01:48:22.300
all the cost of my board.

01:48:22.700 --> 01:48:26.040
The work was hard and tasking, but I stuck to it.

01:48:26.480 --> 01:48:31.940
I had a large number of rooms to care for, and had to work late into the night, while

01:48:31.940 --> 01:48:37.240
at the same time I had to rise by four o'clock in the morning in order to build the fires

01:48:37.240 --> 01:48:40.840
and have a little time in which to prepare my lessons.

01:48:41.720 --> 01:48:47.680
In all my career at Hampton, and ever since I have been out in the world, Miss Mary F.

01:48:47.680 --> 01:48:53.320
Mackey, the headteacher to whom I have referred, proved one of my strongest and most helpful

01:48:53.320 --> 01:48:53.900
friends.

01:48:54.500 --> 01:48:59.980
Her advice and encouragement were always helpful in strengthening me in the darkest hour.

01:49:00.840 --> 01:49:06.780
I have spoken of the impression that was made upon me by the buildings and the general appearance

01:49:06.780 --> 01:49:13.000
of the Hampton Institute, but I have not spoken of that which made the greatest and most lasting

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:16.040
impression on me, and that was a great man.

01:49:16.040 --> 01:49:21.120
The noblest, rarest human being that it has ever been my privilege to meet.

01:49:21.820 --> 01:49:25.240
I refer to the late General Samuel C. Armstrong.

01:49:26.560 --> 01:49:31.200
It has been my fortunate to meet personally many of what are called great characters,

01:49:31.280 --> 01:49:38.140
both in Europe and America, but I do not hesitate to say that I have never met any man who,

01:49:38.280 --> 01:49:42.120
in my estimation, was the equal of General Armstrong.

01:49:42.990 --> 01:49:49.100
Fresh from the degrading influences of the slave plantation and the coal mines, it was

01:49:49.100 --> 01:49:54.600
a rare privilege for me to be permitted to come into direct contact with such a character

01:49:54.600 --> 01:49:55.840
as General Armstrong.

01:49:56.540 --> 01:50:02.360
I shall always remember that the first time I went into his presence, he made the impression

01:50:02.360 --> 01:50:05.260
upon me of being a perfect man.

01:50:05.720 --> 01:50:09.460
I was made to feel that there was something about him that was superhuman.

01:50:09.460 --> 01:50:15.760
It was my privilege to know the general personally from the time I entered Hampton until he died,

01:50:16.040 --> 01:50:19.840
and the more I saw of him, the greater he grew in my estimation.

01:50:21.060 --> 01:50:26.480
One might have removed from Hampton all the buildings, classrooms, teachers, and industries,

01:50:27.200 --> 01:50:33.020
and given the men and women there the opportunity of coming into daily contact with General

01:50:33.020 --> 01:50:37.400
Armstrong, and that alone would have been a liberal education.

01:50:38.020 --> 01:50:44.960
The older I grow, the more I am convinced that there is no education which one can get

01:50:44.960 --> 01:50:51.500
from books and costly apparatus that is equal to that which can be gotten from contact with

01:50:51.500 --> 01:50:52.680
great men and women.

01:50:52.960 --> 01:50:58.580
Instead of studying books so constantly, how I wish our schools and colleges might learn

01:50:58.580 --> 01:51:00.440
to study men and thens.

01:51:01.560 --> 01:51:06.800
General Armstrong spent two of the last six months of his life in my home at Tuskegee.

01:51:06.800 --> 01:51:12.140
At that time he was paralyzed to the extent that he had lost control of his body and voice

01:51:12.140 --> 01:51:13.620
in a very large degree.

01:51:14.620 --> 01:51:19.760
Notwithstanding his affliction, he worked almost constantly day and night for the cause

01:51:19.760 --> 01:51:21.540
to which he had given his life.

01:51:22.060 --> 01:51:25.640
I never saw a man who so completely lost sight of himself.

01:51:26.160 --> 01:51:29.260
I do not believe that he ever had a selfish thought.

01:51:29.880 --> 01:51:35.660
He was just as happy in trying to assist some other institute in the South as he was when

01:51:35.660 --> 01:51:36.840
working for Hampton.

01:51:37.560 --> 01:51:42.580
Although he fought the Southern white man in the Civil War, I never heard him utter

01:51:42.580 --> 01:51:44.820
a bitter word against him afterward.

01:51:45.380 --> 01:51:51.020
On the other hand, he was constantly seeking to find ways by which he could be of service

01:51:51.020 --> 01:51:52.160
to the Southern whites.

01:51:53.060 --> 01:51:58.560
It would be difficult to describe the hold that he had upon the students at Hampton or

01:51:58.560 --> 01:52:00.060
the faith they had in him.

01:52:00.580 --> 01:52:03.040
In fact, he was worshipped by his students.

01:52:03.040 --> 01:52:08.260
It never occurred to me that General Armstrong could fail in anything that he undertook.

01:52:08.700 --> 01:52:13.180
There was almost no request that he could have made that would not have been complied

01:52:13.180 --> 01:52:13.580
with.

01:52:14.100 --> 01:52:19.840
When he was a guest at my home in Alabama and was so badly paralyzed that he had to

01:52:19.840 --> 01:52:26.140
be wheeled about in an invalids chair, I recall that one of the General's former students

01:52:26.140 --> 01:52:32.960
had occasion to push his chair up a long steep hill that taxed his strength to the utmost.

01:52:33.860 --> 01:52:38.640
When the top of the hill was reached, the former student, with a glow of happiness on

01:52:38.640 --> 01:52:40.300
his face, exclaimed,

01:52:40.660 --> 01:52:45.980
I am so glad that I have been permitted to do something that was real hard for the General

01:52:45.980 --> 01:52:47.100
before he dies.

01:52:47.520 --> 01:52:53.180
While I was a student at Hampton, the dormitories became so crowded that it was impossible to

01:52:53.180 --> 01:52:55.560
room for all who wanted to be admitted.

01:52:56.340 --> 01:53:02.320
In order to help remedy the difficulty, the General conceived the plan of putting up tents

01:53:02.320 --> 01:53:03.780
to be used as rooms.

01:53:04.740 --> 01:53:10.900
As soon as it became known that General Armstrong would be pleased if some of the older students

01:53:10.900 --> 01:53:16.040
would live in the tents during the winter, nearly every student in school volunteered

01:53:16.040 --> 01:53:16.720
to go.

01:53:16.980 --> 01:53:18.840
I was one of the volunteers.

01:53:19.240 --> 01:53:25.140
The winter that we spent in those tents was an intensely cold one, and we suffered severely.

01:53:25.760 --> 01:53:30.420
How much I am sure General Armstrong never knew, because we made no complaints.

01:53:31.100 --> 01:53:36.020
It was enough for us to know that we were pleasing General Armstrong, and that we were

01:53:36.020 --> 01:53:40.780
making it possible for an additional number of students to secure an education.

01:53:41.560 --> 01:53:47.300
More than once, during a cold night, when a stiff gale would be blowing, our tent was

01:53:47.300 --> 01:53:51.300
lifted bodily, and we would find ourselves in the open air.

01:53:52.040 --> 01:53:57.340
The General would usually pay a visit to the tents early in the morning, and his earnest,

01:53:57.720 --> 01:54:02.360
cheerful, encouraging voice would dispel any feeling of despondency.

01:54:03.300 --> 01:54:10.240
I have spoken of my admiration for General Armstrong, and yet he was but a type of that

01:54:10.240 --> 01:54:15.380
Christ-like body of men and women who went into the Negro schools at the close of the

01:54:15.380 --> 01:54:19.200
by the hundreds to assist in lifting up my race.

01:54:19.840 --> 01:54:26.960
The history of the world fails to show a higher, purer, and more unselfish class of men and

01:54:26.960 --> 01:54:30.580
women than those who found their way into those Negro schools.

01:54:32.040 --> 01:54:37.760
Life at Hampton was a constant revelation to me, was constantly taking me into a new

01:54:37.760 --> 01:54:38.180
world.

01:54:38.240 --> 01:54:44.380
The matter of having meals at regular hours, of eating on the tablecloth, using the napkin,

01:54:44.380 --> 01:54:50.640
the use of a bathtub and the toothbrush, as well as the use of sheets upon the bed were

01:54:50.640 --> 01:54:51.580
all new to me.

01:54:52.060 --> 01:54:58.300
I sometimes feel that almost the most valuable lesson I got at the Hampton Institute was

01:54:58.300 --> 01:55:00.820
in the use and value of the bath.

01:55:01.360 --> 01:55:06.900
I learned there for the first time some of its value, not only in keeping the body healthy,

01:55:07.360 --> 01:55:10.660
but in inspiring self-respect and promoting virtue.

01:55:11.180 --> 01:55:17.180
In all my travels in the South and elsewhere since leaving Hampton, I have always in some

01:55:17.180 --> 01:55:18.760
way sought my daily bath.

01:55:19.420 --> 01:55:24.820
To get it sometimes when I have been the guest of my own people in a single-roomed cabin

01:55:24.820 --> 01:55:30.720
has not always been easy to do, except by slipping away to some stream in the woods.

01:55:31.260 --> 01:55:36.640
I have always tried to teach my people that some provision for bathing should be the part

01:55:36.640 --> 01:55:37.580
of every house.

01:55:37.580 --> 01:55:43.840
For some time while a student at Hampton I possessed but a single pair of socks, but

01:55:43.840 --> 01:55:49.280
when I had worn these till they became soiled I would wash them at night and hang them by

01:55:49.280 --> 01:55:53.320
the fire to dry so that I might wear them again the next morning.

01:55:54.940 --> 01:55:58.400
The charge for my board at Hampton was ten dollars per month.

01:55:59.100 --> 01:56:03.400
I was expected to pay a part of this in cash and to work out the remainder.

01:56:03.840 --> 01:56:09.800
To meet this cash payment, as I have stated, I had just fifty cents when I reached the

01:56:09.800 --> 01:56:10.420
Institute.

01:56:11.220 --> 01:56:16.400
Apart from the very few dollars that my brother John was able to send me once in a while,

01:56:16.780 --> 01:56:19.220
I had no money with which to pay my board.

01:56:19.980 --> 01:56:25.800
I was determined from the first to make my work as a janitor so valuable that my services

01:56:25.800 --> 01:56:27.100
would be indispensable.

01:56:27.820 --> 01:56:33.880
This I succeeded in doing to such an extent that I was soon informed that I would be allowed

01:56:33.880 --> 01:56:36.760
the full cost of my board in return for my work.

01:56:37.560 --> 01:56:40.440
The cost of tuition was seventy dollars a year.

01:56:41.000 --> 01:56:44.560
This of course was wholly beyond my ability to provide.

01:56:45.280 --> 01:56:50.620
If I had been compelled to pay the seventy dollars for tuition in addition to providing

01:56:50.620 --> 01:56:54.820
for my board, I would have been compelled to leave the Hampton School.

01:56:54.820 --> 01:57:03.280
General Armstrong, however, very kindly got Mr. S. Griffiths Morgan of New Bedford, Massachusetts,

01:57:03.820 --> 01:57:08.040
to defray the cost of my tuition during the whole time I was at Hampton.

01:57:08.680 --> 01:57:14.720
After I finished the course at Hampton and had interned upon my life work at Tuskegee,

01:57:15.260 --> 01:57:18.440
I had the pleasure of meeting Mr. Morgan several times.

01:57:19.260 --> 01:57:24.840
After having been for a while at Hampton, I found myself in difficulty because I did

01:57:24.840 --> 01:57:26.320
not have books and clothing.

01:57:27.120 --> 01:57:32.360
Usually, however, I got around the trouble about books by borrowing from those who were

01:57:32.360 --> 01:57:34.000
more fortunate than myself.

01:57:34.920 --> 01:57:38.480
As to clothes, when I reached Hampton I had practically nothing.

01:57:39.140 --> 01:57:42.260
Everything that I possessed was in a small hand satchel.

01:57:42.880 --> 01:57:49.100
My anxiety about clothing was increased because of the fact that General Armstrong made a

01:57:49.100 --> 01:57:54.300
personal inspection of the young man in ranks to see that their clothes were clean.

01:57:54.980 --> 01:58:00.080
Shoes had to be polished, there must be no buttons off the clothing, and no grease spots.

01:58:00.740 --> 01:58:06.520
To wear one suit of clothing continually while at work and in the classroom, and at the same

01:58:06.520 --> 01:58:10.640
time keep it clean, was rather a hard problem for me to solve.

01:58:10.640 --> 01:58:16.220
In some way I managed to get on until the teachers learned that I was in earnest and

01:58:16.220 --> 01:58:21.540
meant to succeed, and then some of them were kind enough to see that I was partly supplied

01:58:21.540 --> 01:58:25.680
with second-hand clothing that had been sent in barrels from the North.

01:58:26.440 --> 01:58:30.740
These barrels proved a blessing to hundreds of poor but deserving students.

01:58:31.100 --> 01:58:34.860
Without them I questioned whether I would have ever gotten through Hampton.

01:58:35.680 --> 01:58:40.620
When I first went to Hampton I do not recall that I had ever slept in a bed that had two

01:58:40.620 --> 01:58:41.600
sheets on it.

01:58:42.200 --> 01:58:46.520
In those days there were not many buildings there, and room was very precious.

01:58:47.160 --> 01:58:52.600
There were seven other boys in the same room with me, most of them however students who

01:58:52.600 --> 01:58:54.200
had been there for some time.

01:58:54.680 --> 01:58:56.740
The sheets were quite a puzzle to me.

01:58:57.120 --> 01:59:02.700
The first night I slept under both of them, the second night I slept on top of them, but

01:59:02.700 --> 01:59:08.520
by watching the other boys I learned my lesson in this and have been trying to follow it

01:59:08.520 --> 01:59:10.840
ever since and to teach it to others.

01:59:11.120 --> 01:59:15.060
I was among the youngest of the students who were in Hampton at the time.

01:59:15.440 --> 01:59:19.720
Most of the students were men and women, some as old as forty years of age.

01:59:20.320 --> 01:59:26.940
As I now recall the scene of my first year, I do not believe that one often has the opportunity

01:59:26.940 --> 01:59:33.300
of coming into contact with three or four hundred men and women who were so tremendously

01:59:33.840 --> 01:59:36.580
in earnest as these men and women were.

01:59:37.420 --> 01:59:40.740
Every hour was occupied in study or work.

01:59:41.280 --> 01:59:47.660
Nearly all of them had enough actual contact with the world to teach them the need of education.

01:59:48.520 --> 01:59:54.200
Many of the older ones were, of course, too old to master the textbooks very thoroughly,

01:59:55.080 --> 02:00:00.420
and it was often sad to watch their struggles, but they made up in earnest much of which

02:00:00.420 --> 02:00:01.580
they lacked in books.

02:00:01.580 --> 02:00:08.420
Many of them were as poor as I was, and besides having to wrestle with books, they had to

02:00:08.420 --> 02:00:13.560
struggle with the poverty which had prevented them having the necessities of life.

02:00:14.180 --> 02:00:20.020
Many of them had aged parents who were dependent upon them, and some of them were men who had

02:00:20.020 --> 02:00:24.440
wives to support in some way they had to provide for.

02:00:24.940 --> 02:00:30.540
The great and prevailing idea that seemed to take possession of everyone was to prepare

02:00:30.540 --> 02:00:33.420
himself to lift up the people at his home.

02:00:34.000 --> 02:00:40.160
No one seemed to think of himself, and the officers and teachers what a rare set of human

02:00:40.160 --> 02:00:41.220
beings they were.

02:00:41.660 --> 02:00:45.720
They worked for the students day and night, in seasons and out of season.

02:00:46.300 --> 02:00:50.160
They seemed happy only when they were helping the student in some manner.

02:00:50.980 --> 02:00:56.360
Whenever it is written, and I hope it will be, the part that the Yankee teachers played

02:00:56.360 --> 02:01:02.440
in the education of the Negroes immediately after the war will make one of the most thrilling

02:01:02.440 --> 02:01:05.200
parts of the history of this country.

02:01:06.220 --> 02:01:11.820
The time is not far distant when the whole South will appreciate this service in a way

02:01:11.820 --> 02:01:14.360
that it has not yet been able to.

02:01:38.230 --> 02:01:43.280
At the end of my first year at Hampton I was confronted with another difficulty.

02:01:43.280 --> 02:01:46.540
Most of the students went home to spend their vacation.

02:01:46.880 --> 02:01:50.940
I had no money with which to go home, but I had to go somewhere.

02:01:51.620 --> 02:01:56.100
In those days very few students were permitted to remain at the school during vacation.

02:01:56.620 --> 02:02:01.860
It made me feel very sad and homesick to see the other students preparing to leave and starting

02:02:01.860 --> 02:02:07.900
for home. I not only had no money with which to go home, but I had none with which to go anywhere.

02:02:08.520 --> 02:02:13.100
In some way, however, I had gotten hold of an extra secondhand coat,

02:02:13.480 --> 02:02:18.680
which I thought was a pretty valuable coat. This I decided to sell in order to get a little

02:02:18.680 --> 02:02:24.660
money for traveling expenses. I had a good deal of boyish pride and I tried to hide as far as I

02:02:24.660 --> 02:02:31.000
could from the other students the fact that I had no money and nowhere to go. I made it known to a

02:02:31.000 --> 02:02:37.060
few people in the town of Hampton that I had this coat to sell, and after a good deal of persuading,

02:02:37.060 --> 02:02:42.220
one colored man promised to come to my room to look the coat over and consider the matter of

02:02:42.220 --> 02:02:47.940
buying it. This cheered my drooping spirits considerably. Early the next morning my

02:02:47.940 --> 02:02:52.840
prospective customer appeared. After looking the garment over carefully, he asked me how much I

02:02:52.840 --> 02:02:58.200
wanted for it. I told him I thought it was worth three dollars. He seemed to agree with me as the

02:02:58.200 --> 02:03:04.490
price, but remarked in the most matter of fact way, I tell you what I will do. I will take the

02:03:04.490 --> 02:03:10.330
coat and will pay you five cents cash down and pay the rest of the money as soon as I can get it.

02:03:11.330 --> 02:03:15.930
It is not hard to imagine what my feelings were at the time.

02:03:16.950 --> 02:03:22.070
With this disappointment I gave up all hope of getting out of the town of Hampton for my

02:03:22.070 --> 02:03:27.510
vacation work. I wanted very much to go where I might secure work that would at least pay me

02:03:27.510 --> 02:03:33.370
enough to purchase some much needed clothing and other necessities. In a few days practically all

02:03:33.370 --> 02:03:39.150
students and teachers had left for their homes and this served to depress my spirits even more.

02:03:39.830 --> 02:03:45.210
After trying for several days in and near the town of Hampton I finally secured work in a restaurant

02:03:45.210 --> 02:03:52.030
at Fortress Monroe. The wages however were very little more than my board. At night and between

02:03:52.030 --> 02:03:57.850
meals I found considerable time for study and reading and in this direction I improved myself

02:03:57.850 --> 02:04:04.190
very much during the summer. When I left school at the end of my first year I owed the institution

02:04:04.190 --> 02:04:11.570
16 dollars that I had not been able to work out. It was my greatest ambition during the summer

02:04:11.570 --> 02:04:18.850
to save money enough with which to pay this debt. I felt that this was a debt of honor and that I

02:04:18.850 --> 02:04:24.270
could hardly bring myself to the point of even trying to enter school again till it was paid.

02:04:25.070 --> 02:04:31.570
I economized in every way that I could think of, did my own washing and went without necessary

02:04:31.570 --> 02:04:38.610
garments but still I found my summer vacation ending and I did not have the 16 dollars.

02:04:39.470 --> 02:04:46.630
One day during the last week of my stay in the restaurant I found under one of the tables a crisp

02:04:46.630 --> 02:04:53.370
new 10 dollar bill. I could hardly contain myself. I was so happy as it was not my place of business.

02:04:53.370 --> 02:04:59.250
I felt it to be the proper thing to show the money to the proprietor. This I did. He seemed

02:04:59.250 --> 02:05:06.210
as glad as I was but he coolly explained to me that as it was his place of business he had the

02:05:06.210 --> 02:05:13.850
right to keep the money and he proceeded to do so. This I confess was another pretty hard blow to me.

02:05:14.810 --> 02:05:21.910
I will not say that I became discouraged for as I now look back over my life I do not recall that

02:05:21.910 --> 02:05:27.890
I ever became discouraged over anything that set out to that I set out to accomplish.

02:05:28.510 --> 02:05:34.350
I have begun everything with the idea that I could succeed and I never had much patience with the

02:05:34.350 --> 02:05:41.330
multitudes of people who were always ready to explain why one cannot succeed. I determined to

02:05:41.330 --> 02:05:46.770
face the situation just as it was. At the end of the week I went to the treasurer of the Hampton

02:05:47.370 --> 02:05:54.210
General J.F.B. Marshall and told him frankly my condition. To my gratification he told me that

02:05:54.210 --> 02:05:59.790
I could re-enter the institution and that he would trust me to pay the debt when I could.

02:06:00.550 --> 02:06:07.070
During the second year I continued to work as a janitor. The education that I received at Hampton

02:06:07.070 --> 02:06:12.610
out of the textbooks was but a small part of what I learned there. One of the things that impressed

02:06:12.610 --> 02:06:19.510
itself upon me deeply the second year was the usefulness of the teachers. It was hard for me

02:06:19.510 --> 02:06:25.230
to understand how any individuals could bring themselves to the point where they could be so

02:06:25.230 --> 02:06:30.950
happy and working for others. Before the end of the year I think I began learning that those who

02:06:30.950 --> 02:06:37.410
are happiest are those who do the most for others. This lesson I have tried to carry with me ever

02:06:37.410 --> 02:06:44.930
since. I also learned a valuable lesson at Hampton by coming into contact with the best breeds of

02:06:44.930 --> 02:06:51.370
livestock and foals. No student I think who has had the opportunity of doing this could go out

02:06:51.370 --> 02:06:57.950
into the world and content himself with the poorest grades. Perhaps the most valuable thing

02:06:57.950 --> 02:07:03.870
that I got out of my second year was an understanding of the use and value of the Bible.

02:07:04.590 --> 02:07:09.850
Miss Natalie Lord, one of the teachers from Portland, Maine, taught me how to use and

02:07:09.850 --> 02:07:15.830
love the Bible. Before this I had never cared a great deal about it but now I learned to love

02:07:15.830 --> 02:07:22.370
to read the Bible not only for the spiritual help which it gives but on account of it as literature.

02:07:22.950 --> 02:07:29.110
The lessons taught me in this respect took such a hold upon me that at the present time when I am

02:07:29.110 --> 02:07:35.290
home no matter how busy I am I always make it a rule to read a chapter or a portion of a chapter

02:07:35.290 --> 02:07:42.690
in the morning before beginning the work of the day. Whatever ability I may have as a public speaker

02:07:42.690 --> 02:07:49.310
I owe a measure to Miss Lord. When she found out that I had some inclination in this direction

02:07:49.310 --> 02:07:55.790
she gave me private lessons in the matter of breathing, emphasis, and articulation. Simply

02:07:55.790 --> 02:08:01.570
to be able to talk in public for the sake of talking has never had the least attraction to

02:08:01.570 --> 02:08:07.890
me. In fact I consider that there is nothing so empty and unsatisfactory as mere abstract

02:08:07.890 --> 02:08:14.270
public speaking but from my earliest childhood I have had a desire to do something to make the

02:08:14.270 --> 02:08:20.250
world better and then to be able to speak to the world about that thing. The debating societies

02:08:20.250 --> 02:08:26.110
at Hampton were a constant source of delight to me. These were held on Saturday evening and

02:08:26.110 --> 02:08:32.030
during my whole life at Hampton I do not recall that I missed a single meeting. I not only attended

02:08:32.030 --> 02:08:37.970
the weekly debating society but was instrumental in organizing an additional society. I noticed

02:08:37.970 --> 02:08:43.790
that between the time when supper was over and the time to begin evening study there were about 20

02:08:43.790 --> 02:08:50.350
which the young men usually spent in idle gossip. About 20 of us formed a society for the purpose

02:08:50.350 --> 02:08:56.670
of utilizing this time in debate or in practice in public speaking. Few persons ever derived more

02:08:56.670 --> 02:09:04.550
happiness or benefit from the use of 20 minutes of time than we did in this way. At the end of my

02:09:04.550 --> 02:09:10.530
second year at Hampton by the help of some money sent to me by my mother and brother John supplemented

02:09:10.530 --> 02:09:16.030
by a small gift from one of the teachers at Hampton I was enabled to return to my home in

02:09:16.030 --> 02:09:23.150
Malden West Virginia to spend my vacation. When I reached home I found that the salt furnaces were

02:09:23.150 --> 02:09:28.210
not running and that the coal mine was not being operated on account of the miners being on strike.

02:09:28.870 --> 02:09:34.030
This was something which it seemed usually occurred whenever the men got two or three months ahead in

02:09:34.030 --> 02:09:39.710
their savings. During the strike of course they spent all that they had saved and would often

02:09:39.710 --> 02:09:45.410
return to work in debt at the same wages or would move to another mine at considerable expense.

02:09:45.990 --> 02:09:52.450
In either case my observations convinced me that the miners were worse off at the end of the strike.

02:09:53.110 --> 02:09:59.290
Before the days of strikes in that section of the country I knew miners who had considerable money

02:09:59.290 --> 02:10:04.970
in the bank but as soon as the professional labor agitators got control the savings of

02:10:04.970 --> 02:10:10.790
even the more thrifty ones began disappearing. My mother and other members of my family were of

02:10:10.790 --> 02:10:16.150
course much rejoiced to see me and to note the improvement that I had made during my two years

02:10:16.150 --> 02:10:21.970
absence. The rejoicing on the part of all classes of the colored people and especially the older

02:10:21.970 --> 02:10:28.870
ones over my return was almost pathetic. I had to pay a visit to each family and take a meal with

02:10:29.610 --> 02:10:35.870
and at each place tell the story of my experiences at Hampton. In addition to this I had to speak

02:10:35.870 --> 02:10:42.230
before the church and Sunday school and at various other places. The thing that I was most in search

02:10:42.230 --> 02:10:49.810
of though work I could not find. There was no work on account of the strike. I spent nearly the whole

02:10:49.810 --> 02:10:55.330
of the first month of my vacation in an effort to find something to do by which I could earn money

02:10:55.330 --> 02:11:00.230
pay my way back to Hampton and save a little money to use there after reaching there.

02:11:01.430 --> 02:11:06.550
Toward the end of the first month I went to a place a considerable distance from my home to

02:11:06.550 --> 02:11:12.150
try to find employment. I did not succeed and it was a night and it was night before I got

02:11:12.150 --> 02:11:17.710
started on my return. When I had gotten within a mile or so of my home I was so completely tired

02:11:17.710 --> 02:11:23.410
out that I could not walk any further and I went into an old abandoned house to spend the

02:11:23.410 --> 02:11:28.730
night. About three o'clock in the morning my brother John found me asleep in this house

02:11:28.730 --> 02:11:35.710
and broke to me as gently as he could the sad news that our dear mother had died during the night.

02:11:36.810 --> 02:11:44.010
This seemed to me the saddest and blankest moment in my life. For several years my mother had not

02:11:44.010 --> 02:11:51.390
been in good health but I had no idea when I parted from her the previous day that I should never see

02:11:51.390 --> 02:11:58.770
her alive again. Besides that I had always had an intense desire to be with her when she did pass

02:11:58.770 --> 02:12:05.510
away. One of the chief ambitions which spurred me on at Hampton was that I might be able to get to be

02:12:05.510 --> 02:12:11.210
in a position in which I could better make my mother comfortable and happy. She had so often

02:12:11.210 --> 02:12:16.770
expressed the wish that she might be permitted to live to see her children educated and started out

02:12:16.770 --> 02:12:22.630
the world. In a very short time after the death of my mother our little home was in confusion.

02:12:23.330 --> 02:12:27.790
My sister Amanda, although she tried to do the best she could, was too young to know

02:12:27.790 --> 02:12:34.010
anything about keeping house and my stepfather was not able to hire a housekeeper. Sometimes we had

02:12:34.010 --> 02:12:39.770
food cooked for us and sometimes we did not. I remember that more than once a can of tomatoes

02:12:39.770 --> 02:12:45.870
and some crackers constituted a meal. Our clothing went uncared for and everything about our home was

02:12:45.870 --> 02:12:54.170
in a tumble down condition. It seems to me that this was the most dismal period of my life.

02:12:55.310 --> 02:13:02.190
My good friend Mrs. Ruffner, to whom I have already referred, always made me welcome at her home

02:13:02.190 --> 02:13:08.290
and assisted me in many ways during this trying period. Before the end of the vacation she gave

02:13:08.290 --> 02:13:13.010
me some work and this together with work in a coal mine at some distance from my home

02:13:13.010 --> 02:13:19.030
enabled me to earn a little money. At one time it looked as if I would have to give up the idea

02:13:19.030 --> 02:13:25.590
of returning to Hampton but my heart was so set on returning that I determined not to give up

02:13:25.590 --> 02:13:30.910
going back without a struggle. I was very anxious to secure some clothes for the winter

02:13:30.910 --> 02:13:36.790
but in this I was disappointed except for a few garments which my brother John secured for me.

02:13:37.730 --> 02:13:42.450
Notwithstanding my need of money and clothing I was very happy in the fact that I had secured

02:13:42.450 --> 02:13:48.610
enough money to pay my traveling expenses back to Hampton. Once there I knew that I could make

02:13:48.610 --> 02:13:54.050
myself so useful as a janitor that I could in some way get through the school year.

02:13:55.130 --> 02:14:00.170
Three weeks before the time of the opening of the term to Hampton I was pleasantly surprised to

02:14:00.170 --> 02:14:06.850
receive a letter from my good friend Miss Mary F. Mackey, the lady principal asking me to return

02:14:06.850 --> 02:14:12.430
to Hampton two weeks before the opening of the school in order that I might assist her in cleaning

02:14:12.430 --> 02:14:18.190
the buildings and getting things in order for the new school year. This was just the opportunity I

02:14:18.190 --> 02:14:25.030
wanted. It gave me a chance to secure a credit in the treasurer's office. I started for Hampton at

02:14:25.030 --> 02:14:31.490
once. During these two weeks I was taught a lesson which I shall never forget. Miss Mackey was a

02:14:31.490 --> 02:14:37.770
member of one of the oldest and most cultured families of the north and yet for two weeks she

02:14:37.770 --> 02:14:43.170
worked by my side cleaning windows, dusting rooms, putting beds in order and what not.

02:14:43.730 --> 02:14:48.390
She felt that things would not be in condition for the opening of school unless every window

02:14:48.390 --> 02:14:54.130
pane was perfectly clean and she took the greatest satisfaction in helping to clean them herself.

02:14:54.690 --> 02:15:00.850
The work which I have described she did every year that I was at Hampton. It was hard for me

02:15:00.850 --> 02:15:06.030
at this time to understand how a woman of her education and social standing could take such

02:15:06.030 --> 02:15:11.470
delight in performing such service in order to assist in the elevation of an unfortunate race.

02:15:12.150 --> 02:15:18.290
Ever since then I have had no patience with any school for my race in the south which did not

02:15:18.290 --> 02:15:25.070
teach its students the dignity of labor. During my last year at Hampton every minute of my time

02:15:25.070 --> 02:15:32.210
that was not occupied with my duties as a janitor was devoted to hard study. I was determined

02:15:32.210 --> 02:15:38.770
if possible to make such a record in my class as would cause me to be placed on the honor roll

02:15:38.770 --> 02:15:47.890
of commencement speakers. This I was successful in doing. It was June of 1875 when I finished

02:15:47.890 --> 02:15:52.950
the regular course of study at Hampton. The greatest benefits that I got out of my life

02:15:52.950 --> 02:15:59.670
at Hampton Institute perhaps may be classified under two heads. First was contact with a great

02:15:59.670 --> 02:16:07.090
man General S. C. Armstrong who I repeat was in my opinion the rarest strongest and most

02:16:07.090 --> 02:16:13.390
beautiful character that it has ever been my privilege to meet. Second at Hampton for the

02:16:13.390 --> 02:16:20.010
first time I learned what education was expected to do for an individual. Before going there I had a

02:16:20.010 --> 02:16:25.810
good deal of the then rather prevalent idea among our people that to secure an education meant to

02:16:25.810 --> 02:16:33.370
have a good easy time free from all necessity for manual labor. At Hampton I not only learned

02:16:33.370 --> 02:16:40.010
that it was not a disgrace to labor but learned to love labor not alone for its financial value

02:16:40.010 --> 02:16:46.230
but for labor's own sake and for the independence and self-reliance which the ability to do something

02:16:46.230 --> 02:16:52.770
which the world wants done brings. At that institution I got my first taste of what it

02:16:52.770 --> 02:16:58.750
means to live a life of usefulness my first knowledge of the fact that the happiest individuals

02:16:58.750 --> 02:17:06.250
are those who do the most to make others useful and happy. I was completely out of money when I

02:17:06.250 --> 02:17:12.150
graduated. In company with other Hampton students I secured a place as a table waiter in a summer

02:17:12.150 --> 02:17:22.550
hotel in Connecticut and managed to borrow enough money with which to get there. I had not been in

02:17:22.550 --> 02:17:28.950
nothing about waiting on a hotel table. They had waiter however supposed that I was an accomplished

02:17:28.950 --> 02:17:33.910
waiter. He soon gave me charge of the table at which there sat four or five wealthy and

02:17:34.590 --> 02:17:41.430
rather aristocratic people. My ignorance of how to wait upon them was so apparent that they

02:17:41.430 --> 02:17:46.330
scolded me in such a severe manner that I became frightened and left their table leaving them sitting

02:17:46.330 --> 02:17:51.890
there without food. As a result of this I was reduced from the position of waiter to that of a

02:17:51.890 --> 02:17:58.930
carrier. But I determined to learn the business of waiting and did so within a few weeks and was

02:17:58.930 --> 02:18:04.910
restored to my former position. I have had the satisfaction of being a guest in this hotel

02:18:05.490 --> 02:18:12.290
several times since I was a waiter there. At the close of the hotel season I returned to my former

02:18:12.290 --> 02:18:19.170
home in Malden and was elected to teach the colored school at that place. This was the beginning of

02:18:19.170 --> 02:18:25.070
one of the happiest periods of my life. I now felt that I had the opportunity to help the people

02:18:25.070 --> 02:18:32.370
of my hometown to a higher life. I felt from the first that mere book education was not all that

02:18:32.370 --> 02:18:37.890
the young people of the town needed. I began my work at eight o'clock in the morning and as a rule

02:18:37.890 --> 02:18:43.770
it did not end until ten o'clock at night. In addition to the usual routine of teaching I

02:18:43.770 --> 02:18:48.730
taught the pupils to comb their hair and to keep their hands and faces clean as well as their

02:18:48.730 --> 02:18:55.010
clothing. I gave special attention to teaching them the proper use of the toothbrush and the

02:18:55.010 --> 02:19:02.410
bath. In all my teaching I have watched carefully the influence of the toothbrush and I am convinced

02:19:02.410 --> 02:19:10.230
that there are few single agencies of civilization that are more far-reaching. There were so many of

02:19:10.230 --> 02:19:15.990
the older boys and girls in the town as well as men and women who had to work in their daytime

02:19:15.990 --> 02:19:20.910
and still were craving an opportunity for an education that I soon opened a night school.

02:19:21.490 --> 02:19:27.830
From the first this was crowded every night being about as large as the school that I taught in a

02:19:27.830 --> 02:19:35.210
day. The efforts of some of the men and women who in many cases were over 50 years of age to learn

02:19:35.210 --> 02:19:41.850
were in some cases very pathetic. My day and night school work was not all that I undertook.

02:19:41.850 --> 02:19:47.950
I established a small reading room and a debating society. On Sundays I taught two Sunday schools

02:19:47.950 --> 02:19:53.590
one in the town of Malden in the afternoon and the other in the morning at a place three miles

02:19:53.590 --> 02:19:59.130
distant from Malden. In addition to this I gave private lessons to several young men

02:19:59.130 --> 02:20:04.890
whom I was fitting to send to the Hampton Institute without regard to pay and with little

02:20:04.890 --> 02:20:09.970
thought of it. I taught anyone who wanted to learn anything that I could teach him.

02:20:09.970 --> 02:20:17.190
I was supremely happy in the opportunity of being able to assist somebody else. I did receive

02:20:17.190 --> 02:20:22.050
however a small salary from the public fund for my work as a public school teacher.

02:20:24.050 --> 02:20:28.170
During the time that I was a student at Hampton my older brother John

02:20:28.170 --> 02:20:35.190
not only assisted me all that he could but worked all of the time in the coal mines in order to

02:20:35.190 --> 02:20:42.050
the family. He willingly neglected his own education that he might help me. It was my

02:20:42.050 --> 02:20:47.030
earnest wish to help him to prefer to enter Hampton and to save money to assist him in

02:20:47.030 --> 02:20:53.350
his expenses there. Both of these objects I was successful in accomplishing. In three years

02:20:53.350 --> 02:20:58.490
my brother finished the course at Hampton and he is now holding the important position

02:20:58.490 --> 02:21:05.010
of superintendent of industries at Tuskegee. When he returned from Hampton we both combined

02:21:05.010 --> 02:21:10.010
our efforts and savings to send our adopted brother James through the Hampton Institute.

02:21:10.710 --> 02:21:17.330
This we succeeded in doing and he is now the postmaster at the Tuskegee Institute. The year

02:21:18.150 --> 02:21:25.230
1877 which was my second year of teaching in Malden I spent very much as I did the first.

02:21:26.190 --> 02:21:33.190
It was while my home was at Malden that what was known as the Ku Klux Klan was in the height of

02:21:33.900 --> 02:21:39.410
the Ku Klux were bands of men who had joined themselves together for the purpose of regulating

02:21:39.410 --> 02:21:44.670
the conduct of the colored people especially with the object of preventing the members of the race

02:21:44.670 --> 02:21:51.570
from exercising any influence in politics. They corresponded somewhat with the patrollers

02:21:51.570 --> 02:21:57.550
of whom I used to hear a great deal during the days of slavery when I was a small boy. The

02:21:57.550 --> 02:22:03.170
patrollers were bands of white men usually young men who were organized largely for the purpose of

02:22:03.170 --> 02:22:08.470
regulating the conduct of the slaves at night in such matters as preventing the slaves from

02:22:08.470 --> 02:22:13.550
going from one plantation to another without passes and for preventing them from holding any

02:22:13.550 --> 02:22:18.510
kind of meetings without permission and without presence at those meetings of at least one white

02:22:18.510 --> 02:22:25.790
man. Like the patrollers the Ku Klux operated almost wholly at night they were however more

02:22:25.790 --> 02:22:32.430
cruel than the patrollers. Their objects in the main were to crush out the political aspirations

02:22:32.430 --> 02:22:38.250
of the negroes but they did not confine themselves to this because school houses as well as churches

02:22:38.250 --> 02:22:45.470
were burned by them and many innocent persons were made to suffer. During this period not a few

02:22:45.470 --> 02:22:53.210
colored people lost their lives. As a young man the acts of these lawless bands made a great

02:22:53.210 --> 02:22:58.750
impression upon me. I saw one open battle take place at Malden between some of the colored and

02:22:58.750 --> 02:23:05.430
white people. There must have been not far from a hundred persons engaged on each side.

02:23:06.150 --> 02:23:12.910
Many on both sides were seriously injured among them General Louis Ruffner the husband of my

02:23:12.910 --> 02:23:19.990
friend Mrs. Viola Ruffner. General Ruffner tried to defend the colored people and for this he was

02:23:19.990 --> 02:23:27.210
knocked down and so seriously wounded that he never completely recovered. It seemed to me as I

02:23:27.210 --> 02:23:32.430
watched this struggle between members of the two races that there was no hope for our people in

02:23:32.430 --> 02:23:38.950
this country. The Ku Klux period was I think the darkest part of the Reconstruction days.

02:23:40.230 --> 02:23:45.410
I have referred to this unpleasant part of the history of the South simply for the purpose of

02:23:45.410 --> 02:23:51.490
calling attention to the great change that has taken place since the days of the Ku Klux. Today

02:23:51.490 --> 02:23:57.910
there are no such organizations in the South and the fact that such ever existed is almost

02:23:57.910 --> 02:24:03.770
forgotten by both races. There are a few places in the South now where public sentiment would

02:24:03.770 --> 02:24:08.370
permit such organizations to exist.

02:24:32.990 --> 02:24:35.910
Up From Slavery by Booker T. Washington.

02:24:36.790 --> 02:24:40.310
The Reconstruction Period.

02:24:42.790 --> 02:24:51.490
The years from 1867 to 1878, I think may be called the period of reconstruction. This

02:24:51.490 --> 02:24:57.030
included the time that I spent as a student at Hampton and as a teacher in West Virginia.

02:24:58.010 --> 02:25:03.860
During the whole of the Reconstruction Period, two ideas were constantly agitating in the

02:25:03.860 --> 02:25:09.040
minds of the colored people, or at least in the minds of a large part of the race. One

02:25:09.040 --> 02:25:14.960
of these was the craze for Greek and Latin learning, and the other was a desire to hold

02:25:14.960 --> 02:25:21.540
office. It could not have been expected that a people who had spent generations in slavery

02:25:21.540 --> 02:25:27.500
and before that generations in the darkest heathenism could at first form any proper

02:25:27.500 --> 02:25:33.700
conception of what an education meant. In every part of the South during the Reconstruction

02:25:33.700 --> 02:25:40.640
Period, schools both day and night were filled to overflowing with people of all ages and

02:25:40.860 --> 02:25:47.920
conditions, some being as far along in age as 60 and 70 years. The ambition to secure

02:25:47.920 --> 02:25:55.320
an education was most praiseworthy and encouraging. The idea, however, was too prevalent that

02:25:55.320 --> 02:26:01.400
as soon as one secured a little education, in some unexplainable way he would be free

02:26:01.400 --> 02:26:07.040
from most of the hardships of the world and at any rate could live without manual labor.

02:26:08.080 --> 02:26:13.880
There was a further feeling that a knowledge, however little, of the Greek and Latin languages

02:26:13.880 --> 02:26:19.560
would make one a very superior human being, something bordering almost on the supernatural.

02:26:20.480 --> 02:26:26.060
I remember that the first colored man whom I saw who knew something about foreign languages

02:26:26.060 --> 02:26:33.840
impressed me at the time as being a man of all others to be envied. Naturally, most of

02:26:33.840 --> 02:26:40.340
our people who received some little education became teachers or preachers. While among

02:26:40.340 --> 02:26:47.140
those two classes there were many capable, earnest, godly men and women, still a large

02:26:47.140 --> 02:26:53.620
proportion took up teaching or preaching as an easy way to make a living. Many became

02:26:53.620 --> 02:26:59.560
teachers who could do little more than write their names. I remember there came into our

02:26:59.560 --> 02:27:05.340
neighborhood one of this class who was in search of a school to teach and the question

02:27:05.340 --> 02:27:10.540
arose while he was there as to the shape of the earth and how he could teach the children

02:27:10.540 --> 02:27:17.560
concerning the subject. He explained his position in the matter by saying that he was prepared

02:27:17.560 --> 02:27:23.360
to teach that the earth was either flat or round according to the preference of a majority

02:27:23.360 --> 02:27:31.060
of his patrons. The ministry was the profession that suffered most and still suffers, though

02:27:31.060 --> 02:27:37.340
there has been great improvement, on account of not only ignorant but in many cases immoral

02:27:37.340 --> 02:27:44.680
men who claimed that they were called to preach. In the earlier days of freedom, almost every

02:27:44.680 --> 02:27:50.900
colored man who learned to read would receive a call to preach within a few days after he

02:27:50.900 --> 02:27:57.100
began reading. At my home in West Virginia, the process of being called to the ministry

02:27:57.100 --> 02:28:03.960
was a very interesting one. Usually the call came when the individual was sitting in church.

02:28:04.740 --> 02:28:10.760
Without warning, the one called would fall upon the floor as if struck by a bullet and

02:28:10.760 --> 02:28:16.620
would lie there for hours, speechless and motionless. Then the news would spread all

02:28:16.620 --> 02:28:22.840
through the neighborhood that this individual had received a call. If he were inclined to

02:28:22.840 --> 02:28:30.100
resist the summons, he would fall or be made to fall a second or third time. In the end,

02:28:30.260 --> 02:28:37.780
he always yielded to the call. While I wanted an education badly, I confess that in my youth

02:28:37.780 --> 02:28:42.780
I had a fear that when I had learned to read and write very well, I would receive one of

02:28:42.780 --> 02:28:50.260
these calls. But for some reason, my call never came. When we add the number of wholly

02:28:50.260 --> 02:28:56.780
ignorant men who preached or exhorted to that of those who possessed something of an education,

02:28:57.480 --> 02:29:03.460
it can be seen at a glance that the supply of ministers was large. In fact, some time

02:29:03.460 --> 02:29:09.520
ago I knew a certain church that had a total membership of about 200 and 18 of that number

02:29:09.520 --> 02:29:16.060
were ministers. But I repeat, in many communities in the South, the character of the ministry

02:29:16.060 --> 02:29:21.580
is being improved, and I believe that within the next two or three decades, a very large

02:29:21.580 --> 02:29:27.580
proportion of the unworthy ones will have disappeared. The calls to preach, I am glad

02:29:27.580 --> 02:29:33.400
to say, are not nearly so numerous now as they were formerly, and the calls to some

02:29:33.400 --> 02:29:39.200
industrial occupation are growing more numerous. The improvement that has taken place in the

02:29:39.200 --> 02:29:43.680
character of the teachers is even more marked than in the case of the ministers.

02:29:45.760 --> 02:29:51.020
During the whole of the Reconstruction period, our people throughout the South looked to

02:29:51.020 --> 02:29:56.440
the federal government for everything, very much as a child looks to its mother. This

02:29:56.440 --> 02:30:02.080
was not unnatural. The central government gave them freedom, and the whole nation had

02:30:02.080 --> 02:30:08.000
been enriched for more than two centuries by the labor of the negro. Even as a youth

02:30:08.000 --> 02:30:13.780
and later in manhood, I had the feeling that it was cruelly wrong in the central government

02:30:13.780 --> 02:30:19.320
at the beginning of our freedom to fail to make some provision for the general education

02:30:19.320 --> 02:30:24.720
of our people in addition to what the states might do, so that the people would be the

02:30:24.720 --> 02:30:31.920
better prepared for the duties of citizenship. It is easy to find fault, to remark what might

02:30:31.920 --> 02:30:37.940
have been done, and perhaps, after all, and under the circumstances, those in charge of

02:30:37.940 --> 02:30:43.900
the conduct of affairs did the only thing that could be done at the time. Still, as

02:30:43.900 --> 02:30:49.200
I look back now over the entire period of our freedom, I cannot help feeling that it

02:30:49.200 --> 02:30:54.060
would have been wiser if some plan could have been put in operation which would have made

02:30:54.060 --> 02:31:00.860
the possession of a certain amount of education or property, or both, a test for the exercise

02:31:00.860 --> 02:31:07.080
of the franchise, and a way provided by which this test should be made to apply honestly

02:31:07.080 --> 02:31:14.740
and squarely to both the white and black races. Though I was but little more than a youth

02:31:14.740 --> 02:31:20.400
during the period of Reconstruction, I had the feeling that mistakes were being made,

02:31:20.700 --> 02:31:27.220
and that things could not remain in the condition that they were in then very long. I felt that

02:31:27.220 --> 02:31:34.380
the Reconstruction policy, so far as it related to my race, was in a large measure on a false

02:31:34.380 --> 02:31:41.300
foundation, was artificial and forced. In many cases, it seemed to me that the ignorance

02:31:41.300 --> 02:31:48.140
of my race was being used as a tool with which to help white men into office, and that there

02:31:48.140 --> 02:31:53.650
was an element in the North which wanted to punish the southern white men by forcing the

02:31:53.650 --> 02:31:59.470
Negro into positions over the heads of the southern whites. I felt that the Negro would

02:31:59.470 --> 02:32:06.650
be the one to suffer for this in the end. Besides, the general political agitation drew the attention

02:32:06.650 --> 02:32:12.810
of our people away from the more fundamental matters of perfecting themselves in the industries

02:32:12.810 --> 02:32:21.030
at their doors and in securing property. The temptations to enter political life were so

02:32:21.030 --> 02:32:27.850
alluring that I came very near yielding to them at one time, but I was kept from doing so by the

02:32:27.850 --> 02:32:33.390
feeling that I would be helping in a more substantial way by assisting in the laying of

02:32:33.390 --> 02:32:41.190
the foundation of the race through a generous education of the hand, head, and heart. I saw

02:32:41.190 --> 02:32:47.130
colored men who were members of the state legislatures and county officers who in some

02:32:47.130 --> 02:32:54.910
cases could not read or write and whose morals were as weak as their education. Not long ago,

02:32:55.150 --> 02:33:00.450
when passing through the streets of a certain city in the South, I heard some brick masons

02:33:00.450 --> 02:33:06.170
calling out from the top of a two-story brick building on which they were working for the

02:33:06.170 --> 02:33:11.950
governor to hurry up and bring up some more bricks. Several times I heard the command,

02:33:11.950 --> 02:33:20.150
hurry up governor, hurry up governor. My curiosity was aroused to such an extent that I made inquiry

02:33:20.150 --> 02:33:27.330
as to who the governor was and soon found that he was a colored man who at one time had held the

02:33:27.330 --> 02:33:34.010
position of lieutenant governor of his state. But not all the colored people who were in office

02:33:34.010 --> 02:33:40.050
during Reconstruction were unworthy of their positions by any means. Some of them, like the

02:33:40.050 --> 02:33:48.210
great Senator B.K. Bruce, Governor Pinchback, and many others, were strong, upright, useful men.

02:33:49.110 --> 02:33:55.550
Neither were all the class designated as carpetbaggers dishonorable men. Some of them,

02:33:55.850 --> 02:34:02.970
like ex-Governor Bullock of Georgia, were men of high character and usefulness. Of course,

02:34:03.090 --> 02:34:08.770
the colored people, so largely without education and wholly without experience in government,

02:34:08.770 --> 02:34:16.230
made tremendous mistakes, just as many people similarly situated would have done. Many of the

02:34:16.230 --> 02:34:22.710
Southern whites have a feeling that if the Negro is permitted to exercise his political rights now

02:34:22.710 --> 02:34:28.930
to any degree, the mistakes of the Reconstruction period will repeat themselves. I do not think

02:34:28.930 --> 02:34:35.230
this would be true, because the Negro is a much stronger and wiser man than he was 35 years ago,

02:34:35.230 --> 02:34:41.670
and he is fast learning the lesson that he cannot afford to act in a manner that will alienate his

02:34:41.670 --> 02:34:48.650
Southern white neighbors from him. More and more, I am convinced that the final solution of the

02:34:48.650 --> 02:34:55.310
political end of our race problem will be for each state that finds it necessary to change the law

02:34:55.310 --> 02:35:02.690
bearing upon the franchise to make the law apply with absolute honesty and without opportunity for

02:35:02.690 --> 02:35:10.430
double dealing or evasion to both races alike. Any other course, my daily observation in the

02:35:10.430 --> 02:35:17.690
South convinces me, will be unjust to the Negro, unjust to the white man, and unfair to the rest

02:35:17.690 --> 02:35:24.150
of the state and the Union, and will be, like slavery, a sin that at some time we shall have

02:35:24.150 --> 02:35:34.410
to pay for. In the fall of 1878, after having taught school in Malden for two years, and after

02:35:34.410 --> 02:35:40.710
I had succeeded in preparing several of the young men and women, besides my two brothers, to enter

02:35:40.710 --> 02:35:48.630
the Hampton Institute, I decided to spend some months in study at Washington D.C. I remained

02:35:48.630 --> 02:35:55.050
there for eight months. I derived a great deal of benefit from the studies which I pursued,

02:35:55.510 --> 02:36:02.310
and I came into contact with some strong men and women. At the institution I attended,

02:36:02.770 --> 02:36:09.090
there was no industrial training given to the students, and I had an opportunity of comparing

02:36:09.090 --> 02:36:15.330
the influence of an institution with no industrial training with that of one like the Hampton

02:36:15.330 --> 02:36:22.710
Institute that emphasizes the industries. At this school, I found the students, in most cases,

02:36:22.950 --> 02:36:28.550
had more money, were better dressed, wore the latest style of all manner of clothing,

02:36:28.550 --> 02:36:36.270
and in some cases were more brilliant mentally. At Hampton, it was a standing rule that while the

02:36:36.270 --> 02:36:41.190
institution would be responsible for securing someone to pay the tuition for the students,

02:36:41.190 --> 02:36:47.650
the men and women themselves must provide for their own board, books, clothing, and room

02:36:47.970 --> 02:36:55.830
wholly by work, or partly by work and partly in cash. At the institution at which I now was,

02:36:56.450 --> 02:37:02.070
I found that a large portion of the students, by some means, had their personal expenses paid for

02:37:02.070 --> 02:37:07.690
them. At Hampton, the student was constantly making the effort, through the industries,

02:37:07.690 --> 02:37:12.930
to help himself, and that very effort was of immense value in character building.

02:37:13.810 --> 02:37:19.670
The students at the other schools seemed to be less self-dependent. They seemed to give more

02:37:19.670 --> 02:37:26.370
attention to mere outward appearances. In a word, they did not appear to me to be beginning at the

02:37:26.370 --> 02:37:33.350
bottom, on a real solid foundation, to the extent that they were at Hampton. They knew more about

02:37:33.350 --> 02:37:39.270
Latin and Greek when they left school, but they seemed to know less about life and its conditions

02:37:39.270 --> 02:37:44.530
as they would meet it at their homes. Having lived for a number of years in the midst of

02:37:44.530 --> 02:37:50.690
comfortable surroundings, they were not as much inclined as the Hampton students to go into the

02:37:50.690 --> 02:37:56.690
country districts of the South, where there was little of comfort, to take up work for our people,

02:37:57.130 --> 02:38:02.490
and they were more inclined to yield to the temptation to become hotel waiters and Pullman

02:38:02.490 --> 02:38:11.170
car porters as their life work. During the time I was a student at Washington, the city was crowded

02:38:11.170 --> 02:38:17.090
with colored people, many of whom had recently come from the South. A large proportion of these

02:38:17.090 --> 02:38:22.350
people had been drawn to Washington because they felt that they could lead a life of ease there.

02:38:23.450 --> 02:38:32.470
Others had secured minor government positions, and still another large class was there in the

02:38:32.470 --> 02:38:37.390
colored men, some of them very strong and brilliant, were in the House of Representatives

02:38:37.390 --> 02:38:44.430
at that time, and one, the Honorable B.K. Bruce, was in the Senate. All this tended to make

02:38:44.430 --> 02:38:50.630
Washington an attractive place for members of the colored race. Then, too, they knew that at all

02:38:50.630 --> 02:38:56.490
times they could have the protection of the law in the District of Columbia. The public schools

02:38:56.490 --> 02:39:03.130
in Washington for colored people were better then than they were elsewhere. I took great interest

02:39:03.130 --> 02:39:09.570
in studying the life of our people there closely at that time. I found that while among them there

02:39:09.570 --> 02:39:15.930
was a large element of substantial, worthy citizens, there was also a superficiality about

02:39:15.930 --> 02:39:22.730
the life of a large class that greatly alarmed me. I saw young colored men who were not earning

02:39:22.730 --> 02:39:29.290
more than four dollars a week spend two dollars or more for a buggy on Sunday to ride up and down

02:39:29.290 --> 02:39:35.110
Pennsylvania Avenue in, in order that they might try to convince the world that they were worth

02:39:35.110 --> 02:39:41.670
thousands. I saw other young men who received seventy-five or one hundred dollars per month

02:39:41.670 --> 02:39:47.870
from the government who were in debt at the end of every month. I saw men who but a few months

02:39:47.870 --> 02:39:55.110
previous were members of Congress, then without employment and in poverty. Among a large class,

02:39:55.210 --> 02:39:59.250
there seemed to be a dependence upon the government for every conceivable thing.

02:40:00.150 --> 02:40:04.650
The members of this class had little ambition to create a position for themselves,

02:40:05.130 --> 02:40:10.910
but wanted the federal officials to create one for them. How many times I wished then,

02:40:11.050 --> 02:40:17.350
and have often wished since, that by some power of magic I might remove the great bulk of these

02:40:17.350 --> 02:40:24.230
into the county districts and plant them upon the soil, upon the solid and never deceptive

02:40:24.230 --> 02:40:30.150
foundation of Mother Nature, where all nations and races that have ever succeeded have gotten

02:40:30.150 --> 02:40:37.190
their start. A start that at first may be slow and toilsome, but one that nevertheless is real.

02:40:39.370 --> 02:40:44.850
In Washington, I saw girls whose mothers were earning their living by laundering.

02:40:45.730 --> 02:40:49.950
These girls were taught by their mothers, in a rather crude way it is true,

02:40:50.550 --> 02:40:56.630
the industry of laundering. Later, these girls entered the public schools and remained there

02:40:56.630 --> 02:41:02.830
perhaps six or eight years. When the public school course was finally finished, they wanted

02:41:02.830 --> 02:41:09.490
more costly dresses, more costly hats and shoes. In a word, while their wants have been increased,

02:41:09.970 --> 02:41:14.310
their ability to supply their wants had not been increased in the same degree.

02:41:15.230 --> 02:41:20.950
On the other hand, their six or eight years of book education had weaned them away from the

02:41:20.950 --> 02:41:27.590
occupation of their mothers. The result of this was in too many cases that the girls went to the

02:41:27.590 --> 02:41:33.830
bad. I often thought how much wiser it would have been to give these girls the same amount

02:41:33.830 --> 02:41:40.170
of maternal training, and I favor any kind of training, whether in the languages or mathematics,

02:41:40.170 --> 02:41:46.270
that give strength and culture to the mind, but at the same time to give them the most

02:41:46.270 --> 02:41:52.010
thorough training in the latest and best methods of laundering and other kindred occupations.

02:42:10.170 --> 02:42:10.950
you

02:42:36.190 --> 02:42:38.850
BLACK RACE AND RED RACE

02:42:40.030 --> 02:42:52.630
During the year that I spent in Washington, and for some little time before this, there had been considerable agitation in the state of West Virginia over the question of moving the capital of the state from Wheeling to some other central point.

02:42:53.290 --> 02:43:00.230
As a result of this, the legislature designated three cities to be voted upon by the citizens of the state as the permanent seat of government.

02:43:00.810 --> 02:43:04.550
Among these cities was Charleston, only five miles from Malden, my home.

02:43:04.550 --> 02:43:15.530
At the close of my school year in Washington, I was very pleasantly surprised to receive, from a committee of three white people in Charleston, an invitation to canvas the state in the interests of that city.

02:43:16.050 --> 02:43:26.170
This invitation I accepted, and spent nearly three months in speaking in various parts of the state. Charleston was successful in winning the prize, and is now the permanent seat of government.

02:43:26.870 --> 02:43:40.810
The reputation that I made as a speaker during this campaign induced a number of persons to make an earnest effort to get me to enter political life, but I refused, still believing that I could find other service which would prove of more permanent value to my race.

02:43:41.390 --> 02:43:52.850
Even then I had a strong feeling that what our people most needed was to get a foundation in education, industry, and property, and for this I felt that they could better afford to strive than for political preferment.

02:43:52.850 --> 02:44:08.750
As for my individual self, it appeared to me to be reasonably certain that I could succeed in political life, but I had a feeling that it would be a rather selfish kind of success, individual success, at the cost of failing to do my duty and assisting in laying a foundation for the masses.

02:44:09.650 --> 02:44:23.490
At this period in the progress of our race, a very large proportion of the young men who went to school or to college did so with the express determination to prepare themselves to be great lawyers, or congressmen, and many of the women planned to become music teachers.

02:44:24.230 --> 02:44:34.190
But I had a reasonably fixed idea, even at that early period in my life, that there was a need for something to be done to prepare the way for successful lawyers, congressmen, and music teachers.

02:44:34.730 --> 02:44:42.050
I felt that the conditions were a good deal like those of an old colored man during the days of slavery who wanted to learn how to play on the guitar.

02:44:42.570 --> 02:44:54.130
In his desire to take guitar lessons he applied to one of his young masters to teach him, but the young man, not having much faith in the ability of the slave to master the guitar at his age, sought to discourage him by telling him,

02:44:54.130 --> 02:45:06.750
Uncle Jake, I will give you guitar lessons, but, Jake, I will have to charge you three dollars for the first lesson, two dollars for the second lesson, and one dollar for the third lesson, but I will charge you only twenty-five cents for that last lesson.

02:45:07.530 --> 02:45:15.410
Uncle Jake answered, All right, boss, I hires you on them terms, but, boss, I want you to be sure and give me that last lesson first.

02:45:16.250 --> 02:45:25.850
Soon after my work and connection with the removal of the capital was finished, I received an invitation which gave me great joy and which at the same time was a very pleasant surprise.

02:45:26.510 --> 02:45:34.230
This was a letter from General Armstrong inviting me to return to Hampton at the next commencement to deliver what was called the post-graduate address.

02:45:34.630 --> 02:45:37.090
This was an honor which I had not dreamed of receiving.

02:45:37.650 --> 02:45:41.030
With much care I prepared the best address that I was capable of.

02:45:41.330 --> 02:45:43.990
I chose for my subject the force that wins.

02:45:44.750 --> 02:45:59.470
As I returned to Hampton for the purpose of delivering this address, I went over much of the same ground, now, however, entirely covered by railroad, that I had traversed nearly six years before when I first sought entrance into Hampton Institute as a student.

02:45:59.830 --> 02:46:02.390
Now I was able to ride the whole distance in the train.

02:46:02.810 --> 02:46:06.070
I was constantly contrasting this with my first journey to Hampton.

02:46:06.070 --> 02:46:14.450
I think I may say, without seeming egotism, that it is seldom that five years have wrought such a change in the life and aspirations of an individual.

02:46:15.970 --> 02:46:19.430
At Hampton I received a warm welcome from teachers and students.

02:46:19.850 --> 02:46:31.130
I found that during my absence from Hampton the Institute each year had been getting closer to the real needs and conditions of our people, that the industrial reaching as well as that of the academic department had greatly improved.

02:46:31.130 --> 02:46:45.990
The plan of the school was not modeled after that of any other institution than in existence, but every improvement was made under the magnificent leadership of General Armstrong solely with the view of meeting and helping the needs of our people as they presented themselves at the time.

02:46:46.750 --> 02:46:59.070
Too often, it seems to me, in missionary and educational work among underdeveloped races, people yield to the temptation of doing that which was done a hundred years before, or as being done in other communities a thousand miles away.

02:46:59.070 --> 02:47:07.470
The temptation often is to run each individual through a certain educational mold, regardless of the condition of the subject or the end to be accomplished.

02:47:07.810 --> 02:47:09.970
This was not so at Hampton Institute.

02:47:10.990 --> 02:47:18.490
The address which I delivered on commencement day seems to have pleased everyone, and many kind and encouraging words were spoken to me regarding it.

02:47:18.490 --> 02:47:32.430
Soon after my return to my home in West Virginia, where I had planned to continue teaching, I was again surprised to receive a letter from General Armstrong asking me to return to Hampton partly as a teacher and partly to pursue some supplementary studies.

02:47:33.590 --> 02:47:35.830
This was in the summer of 1879.

02:47:35.830 --> 02:47:50.290
Soon after I began my first teaching in West Virginia, I had picked out four of the brightest and most promising of my pupils in addition to my two brothers, to whom I have already referred, and had given them special attention with the view of having them go to Hampton.

02:47:50.750 --> 02:47:56.810
They had gone there, and in each case the teachers had found them so well prepared that they entered advanced classes.

02:47:57.290 --> 02:48:01.250
This fact, it seems, led to my being called back to Hampton as a teacher.

02:48:01.250 --> 02:48:10.410
One of the young men that I sent to Hampton in this way is now Dr. Samuel E. Courtney, a successful physician in Boston and a member of the school board of that city.

02:48:11.630 --> 02:48:17.830
About this time the experiment was being tried for the first time by General Armstrong of educating Indians at Hampton.

02:48:18.410 --> 02:48:23.890
Few people then had any confidence in the ability of the Indians to receive education and to profit by it.

02:48:24.390 --> 02:48:28.830
General Armstrong was anxious to try the experiment systematically on a large scale.

02:48:28.830 --> 02:48:38.170
He secured from the reservations in the western states over 100 wild and for the most part perfectly ignorant Indians, the greater proportion of whom were young men.

02:48:38.690 --> 02:48:44.310
The special work which the general desired me to do was to be a sort of house father to the Indian young men.

02:48:44.810 --> 02:48:50.550
That is, I was to live in the building with them and have the charge of their discipline, clothing, rooms, and so on.

02:48:50.910 --> 02:48:56.650
This was a very tempting offer, but I had become so much absorbed in my work in West Virginia that I dreaded to give it up.

02:48:57.130 --> 02:49:04.550
However, I tore myself away from it. I did not know how to refuse to perform any service that General Armstrong desired of me.

02:49:06.250 --> 02:49:10.870
On going to Hampton, I took up my residence in a building with about 75 Indian youths.

02:49:11.630 --> 02:49:15.150
I was the only person in the building who was not a member of their race.

02:49:15.710 --> 02:49:18.970
At first I had a good deal of doubt about my abilities to succeed.

02:49:18.970 --> 02:49:24.770
But I knew that the average Indian felt himself above the white man, and of course he felt himself far above the negro,

02:49:25.330 --> 02:49:31.090
largely on account of the fact that the negro having submitted to slavery, a thing which the Indian would never do.

02:49:31.590 --> 02:49:36.270
The Indians in the Indian territory owned a large number of slaves during the days of slavery.

02:49:36.970 --> 02:49:42.650
Aside from this, there was a general feeling that the attempt to educate and civilize the red men at Hampton would be a failure.

02:49:43.290 --> 02:49:48.210
All of this made me proceed very cautiously, for I felt keenly the great responsibility.

02:49:48.210 --> 02:49:53.870
But I was determined to succeed. It was not long before I had the complete confidence of the Indians,

02:49:54.370 --> 02:49:58.210
and not only this, but I think I am safe in saying that I had their love and respect.

02:49:58.710 --> 02:50:04.870
I found that they were about like any other human beings, that they responded to kind treatment and resented ill-treatment.

02:50:05.230 --> 02:50:09.030
They were continually planning to do something that would add to my happiness and comfort.

02:50:09.650 --> 02:50:16.130
The things that they disliked most, I think, were to have their long hair cut, to give up wearing their blankets, and to cease smoking.

02:50:16.130 --> 02:50:23.390
But no white American ever thinks that any other race is wholly civilized until he wears the white man's clothes, eats the white man's food,

02:50:23.690 --> 02:50:27.010
speaks the white man's language, and professes the white man's religion.

02:50:27.970 --> 02:50:31.470
When the difficulty of learning the English language was subtracted,

02:50:31.510 --> 02:50:38.290
I found that in the matter of learning trades and in mastering academic studies there was little difference between the colored and Indian students.

02:50:38.890 --> 02:50:45.230
It was a constant delight to me to note the interest which the colored students took in trying to help the Indians in every way possible.

02:50:45.230 --> 02:50:51.870
There were a few of the colored students who felt that the Indians ought not to be admitted to Hampton, but these were in the minority.

02:50:52.470 --> 02:50:56.710
Whenever they were asked to do so, the Negro students gladly took the Indians as roommates,

02:50:57.150 --> 02:51:01.050
in order that they might teach them to speak English and to acquire civilized habits.

02:51:02.650 --> 02:51:10.550
I have often wondered if there was a white institution in this country whose students would have welcomed the incoming of more than a hundred companions of another race,

02:51:10.910 --> 02:51:14.510
in the cordial way that these black students at Hampton welcomed the red ones.

02:51:14.510 --> 02:51:20.650
How often I have wanted to say to white students that they lift themselves up in proportion as they help to lift others,

02:51:20.990 --> 02:51:28.190
and the more unfortunate the race and the lower the scale of civilization, the more does one raise oneself by giving the assistance.

02:51:29.170 --> 02:51:33.270
This reminds me of a conversation which I once had with the Honorable Frederick Douglass.

02:51:33.910 --> 02:51:40.530
At one time Mr. Douglass was traveling in the state of Pennsylvania and was forced, on account of his color, to ride in the baggage car,

02:51:40.530 --> 02:51:45.610
in spite of the fact that he had paid the same price for his passage that the other passengers had paid.

02:51:46.470 --> 02:51:52.090
When some of the white passengers went into the baggage car to console Mr. Douglass, and one of them said to him,

02:51:52.090 --> 02:51:58.870
I am sorry, Mr. Douglass, that you have been degraded in this manner, Mr. Douglass straightened himself up on the box upon which he was sitting,

02:51:58.970 --> 02:52:04.650
and replied, They cannot degrade Frederick Douglass. The soul that is within me no man can degrade.

02:52:04.650 --> 02:52:10.350
I am not the one that is being degraded on account of this treatment, but those who are inflicting it upon me.

02:52:11.330 --> 02:52:15.930
In one part of the country where the law demands the separation of the races on the railroad trains,

02:52:16.510 --> 02:52:23.250
I saw at one time a rather amusing instance which showed how difficult it is sometimes to know where the black begins and the white ends.

02:52:24.310 --> 02:52:32.010
There was a man who was well known in his community as a negro, but who was so white that even an expert would have hard work to classify him as a black man.

02:52:32.010 --> 02:52:36.110
This man was riding in the part of the train set aside for the colored passengers.

02:52:36.710 --> 02:52:40.010
When the train conductor reached him, he showed at once that he was perplexed.

02:52:40.670 --> 02:52:44.990
If the man was a negro, the conductor did not want to send him to the white people's coach.

02:52:45.370 --> 02:52:50.910
At the same time, if he was a white man, the conductor did not want to insult him by asking him if he was a negro.

02:52:52.370 --> 02:52:58.310
The official looked him over carefully, examining his hair, eyes, nose, and hands, but still seemed puzzled.

02:52:58.310 --> 02:53:02.390
Finally, to solve the difficulty, he stooped over and peeped at the man's feet.

02:53:02.870 --> 02:53:06.870
When I saw the conductor examining the feet of the man in question, I said to myself,

02:53:07.230 --> 02:53:08.170
That will settle it.

02:53:08.590 --> 02:53:14.390
And so it did, for the train man promptly decided that the passenger was a negro and let him remain where he was.

02:53:14.770 --> 02:53:18.870
I congratulated myself that my race was fortunate in not losing one of its members.

02:53:19.790 --> 02:53:27.890
My experience has been that the time to test a true gentleman is to observe him when he is in contact with individuals of a race that is less fortunate than his own.

02:53:27.890 --> 02:53:37.150
This is illustrated in no better way than by observing the conduct of the old-school type of southern gentleman when he is in contact with his former slaves or their descendants.

02:53:38.030 --> 02:53:47.490
An example of what I mean is shown in the story told of George Washington, who, meeting a colored man in the road once, who politely lifted his hat, lifted his own in return.

02:53:48.030 --> 02:53:51.970
Some of his white friends who saw the incident criticized Washington for his action.

02:53:51.970 --> 02:53:54.950
In reply to their criticism, George Washington said,

02:53:55.230 --> 02:54:00.050
Do you suppose that I am going to permit a poor, ignorant, colored man to be more polite than I am?

02:54:00.970 --> 02:54:08.290
While I was in charge of the Indian boys at Hampton, I had one or two experiences which illustrate the curious workings of caste in America.

02:54:09.050 --> 02:54:13.150
One of the Indian boys was taken ill, and it became my duty to take him to Washington,

02:54:13.630 --> 02:54:20.130
deliver him over to the Secretary of the Interior, and get a receipt for him in order that he might be returned to his western reservation.

02:54:20.910 --> 02:54:24.230
At that time I was rather ignorant of the ways of the world.

02:54:24.650 --> 02:54:33.890
During my journey to Washington on a steamboat, when the bell rang for dinner, I was careful to wait and not enter the dining room until after the greater part of the passengers had finished their meal.

02:54:34.370 --> 02:54:36.730
Then, with my charge, I went to the dining saloon.

02:54:37.250 --> 02:54:41.730
The man in charge politely informed me that the Indian could be served, but that I could not.

02:54:42.170 --> 02:54:48.550
I never could understand how he knew just where to draw the color line, since the Indian and I were of about the same complexion.

02:54:48.550 --> 02:54:51.590
The steward, however, seemed to be an expert in this manner.

02:54:52.150 --> 02:54:57.190
I had been directed by the authorities at Hampton to stop at a certain hotel in Washington with my charge,

02:54:57.510 --> 02:55:04.710
but when I went to this hotel the clerk stated that he would be glad to receive the Indian into the house, but said that he could not accommodate me.

02:55:05.670 --> 02:55:09.710
An illustration of something of this same feeling came under my observation afterward.

02:55:09.710 --> 02:55:18.310
I happened to find myself in a town in which so much excitement and indignation were being expressed that it seemed likely for a time that there would be a lynching.

02:55:18.910 --> 02:55:22.770
The occasion of the trouble was that a dark-skinned man had stopped at the local hotel.

02:55:23.730 --> 02:55:31.790
Investigation, however, developed the fact that this individual was a citizen of Morocco, and that while traveling in this country he spoke the English language.

02:55:32.190 --> 02:55:37.310
As soon as it was learned that he was not an American negro, all the signs of indignation disappeared.

02:55:37.310 --> 02:55:44.150
The man, who was now the innocent cause of the excitement, though, found it prudent after that not to speak English.

02:55:45.170 --> 02:55:49.070
At the end of my first year with the Indians there came another opening for me at Hampton,

02:55:49.490 --> 02:55:56.210
which, as I look back over my life now, seems to have come providentially to help me prepare for my work at Tuskegee later.

02:55:56.930 --> 02:56:04.750
General Armstrong had found out that there was quite a number of young colored men and women who were intensely in earnest in wishing to get an education,

02:56:04.750 --> 02:56:11.830
but who were prevented from entering Hampton Institute because they were too poor to be able to pay any portion of the cost of their board,

02:56:12.050 --> 02:56:14.210
or even to supply themselves with books.

02:56:14.890 --> 02:56:18.750
He conceived the idea of starting a night school in connection with the Institute,

02:56:19.250 --> 02:56:23.390
into which a limited number of the most promising of these young men and women would be received,

02:56:23.930 --> 02:56:28.870
on condition that they were to work for ten hours during the day and attend school for two hours at night.

02:56:29.170 --> 02:56:32.510
They were to be paid something above the cost of their board for their work.

02:56:32.510 --> 02:56:38.230
The greater part of their earnings was to be reserved in the school's treasury as a fund to be drawn on to pay their board

02:56:38.230 --> 02:56:43.230
when they had become students in the day school, after they had spent one or two years in the night school.

02:56:43.710 --> 02:56:48.130
In this way they would obtain a start in their books and a knowledge of some trade or industry,

02:56:48.530 --> 02:56:51.710
in addition to the other far-reaching benefits of the Institution.

02:56:53.350 --> 02:56:57.270
General Armstrong asked me to take charge of the night school, and I did so.

02:56:57.270 --> 02:57:02.690
At the beginning of this school there were about twelve strong, earnest men and women who entered the class.

02:57:03.230 --> 02:57:08.410
During the day the greater part of the young men worked in the school's sawmill, and the young women worked in the laundry.

02:57:08.930 --> 02:57:16.110
The work was not easy in either place, but in all my teaching I never taught pupils who gave me so much genuine satisfaction as these did.

02:57:16.630 --> 02:57:19.470
They were good students, and mastered their work thoroughly.

02:57:20.410 --> 02:57:24.930
They were so much in earnest that only the ringing of the retiring bell would make them stop studying,

02:57:24.930 --> 02:57:30.050
and often they would urge me to continue the lessons after the usual hour for going to bed had come.

02:57:30.890 --> 02:57:34.770
These students showed so much earnestness, both in their hard work during the day,

02:57:35.170 --> 02:57:40.230
as well as in their application to their studies at night, that I gave them the name of the Plucky Class,

02:57:40.690 --> 02:57:43.870
a name which soon grew popular and spread throughout the Institution.

02:57:44.410 --> 02:57:47.790
After a student had been in the night school long enough to prove what was in it,

02:57:48.050 --> 02:57:51.210
I gave him a printed certificate which read something like this.

02:57:51.210 --> 02:57:56.410
This is to certify that James Smith is a member of the Plucky Class of the Hampton Institute,

02:57:56.630 --> 02:57:58.570
and is in good and regular standing.

02:57:59.410 --> 02:58:04.530
The students prized these certificates highly, and they added greatly to the popularity of the night school.

02:58:05.010 --> 02:58:11.210
Within a few weeks this department had grown to such an extent that there were about 25 students in attendance.

02:58:11.650 --> 02:58:15.630
I have followed the course of many of these 25 men and women ever since then,

02:58:15.830 --> 02:58:20.370
and they are now holding important and useful positions in nearly every part of the South.

02:58:20.370 --> 02:58:26.070
The night school at Hampton, which started with only 12 students, now numbers between 3 and 400,

02:58:26.530 --> 02:58:30.210
and is one of the permanent and most important features of the Institution.

02:58:54.210 --> 02:58:56.550
EARLY DAYS at Tuskegee.

02:58:57.610 --> 02:59:02.510
During the time that I had charge of the Indians and the Knight School at Hampton,

02:59:02.850 --> 02:59:07.870
I pursued some studies myself, under the direction of the instructors there.

02:59:08.530 --> 02:59:12.870
One of these instructors was the Reverend Doctor H. B. Frizzle,

02:59:13.510 --> 02:59:18.130
the present principal of the Hampton Institute, General Armstrong's successor.

02:59:19.970 --> 02:59:25.790
In May 1881, near the close of my first year in teaching the Knight School,

02:59:25.790 --> 02:59:32.850
in a way that I had not dared expect, the opportunity opened for me to begin my life work.

02:59:33.810 --> 02:59:38.190
One night in the chapel, after the usual chapel exercises were over,

02:59:38.770 --> 02:59:44.230
General Armstrong referred to the fact that he had received a letter from some gentleman in Alabama

02:59:44.230 --> 02:59:49.650
asking him to recommend someone to take charge of what was to be a normal school

02:59:49.650 --> 02:59:53.930
for the colored people in the little town of Tuskegee in that state.

02:59:55.830 --> 03:00:01.770
These gentlemen seemed to take it for granted that no colored man suitable for the position could be secured,

03:00:02.170 --> 03:00:07.010
and they were expecting the general to recommend a white man for the place.

03:00:08.470 --> 03:00:12.430
The next day, General Armstrong sent for me to come to his office,

03:00:12.950 --> 03:00:18.070
and, much to my surprise, asked me if I thought I could fill the position in Alabama.

03:00:19.030 --> 03:00:22.110
I told him that I would be willing to try.

03:00:23.390 --> 03:00:27.310
Accordingly, he wrote to the people who had applied to him for the information

03:00:27.310 --> 03:00:30.350
that he did not know of any white man to suggest,

03:00:30.930 --> 03:00:36.070
but if they would be willing to take a colored man, he had one whom he could recommend.

03:00:37.290 --> 03:00:39.630
In this letter he gave them my name.

03:00:41.490 --> 03:00:45.210
Several days passed before anything more was heard about the matter.

03:00:46.270 --> 03:00:50.570
Sometime afterward, one Sunday evening, during the chapel exercises,

03:00:51.370 --> 03:00:54.390
a messenger came in and handed the general a telegram.

03:00:55.190 --> 03:00:58.690
At the end of the exercises he read the telegram to the school.

03:00:59.530 --> 03:01:02.410
In substance, these were its words.

03:01:03.350 --> 03:01:07.330
Booker T. Washington will suit us. Send him at once.

03:01:08.950 --> 03:01:13.090
There was a great deal of joy expressed among the students and teachers,

03:01:13.090 --> 03:01:16.090
and I received very hearty congratulations.

03:01:17.310 --> 03:01:20.130
I began to get ready at once to go to Tuskegee.

03:01:20.810 --> 03:01:26.210
I went by way of my old home in West Virginia, where I remained for several days,

03:01:26.630 --> 03:01:29.190
after which I proceeded to Tuskegee.

03:01:30.690 --> 03:01:34.770
I found Tuskegee to be a town of about 2,000 inhabitants,

03:01:35.370 --> 03:01:37.290
nearly one half of whom were colored.

03:01:37.810 --> 03:01:41.550
It was in what was known as the Black Belt of the South.

03:01:41.550 --> 03:01:44.810
In the county in which Tuskegee is situated,

03:01:45.250 --> 03:01:49.330
the colored people outnumbered the whites by about three to one.

03:01:50.210 --> 03:01:52.530
In some of the adjoining and nearby counties,

03:01:52.990 --> 03:01:56.970
the proportion was not far from six colored persons to one white.

03:01:59.270 --> 03:02:03.090
I have often been asked to define the term Black Belt.

03:02:03.790 --> 03:02:08.890
So far as I can learn, the term was first used to designate a part of the country

03:02:08.890 --> 03:02:11.610
which was distinguished by the color of the soil.

03:02:12.650 --> 03:02:17.150
The part of the country possessing this thick, dark, and naturally rich soil

03:02:17.150 --> 03:02:21.670
was, of course, the part of the South where the slaves were most profitable,

03:02:22.110 --> 03:02:25.650
and consequently, they were taken there in the largest numbers.

03:02:27.330 --> 03:02:32.490
Later, and especially since the war, the term seems to be used wholly in a political sense,

03:02:32.490 --> 03:02:37.510
that is, to designate the counties where the black people outnumbered the whites.

03:02:39.030 --> 03:02:43.890
Before going to Tuskegee, I had expected to find there a building

03:02:43.890 --> 03:02:47.950
and all the necessary apparatus ready for me to begin teaching.

03:02:48.850 --> 03:02:51.850
To my disappointment, I found nothing of the kind.

03:02:52.450 --> 03:02:57.750
I did find, though, that which no costly building and apparatus can supply.

03:02:58.410 --> 03:03:02.950
Hundreds of hungry, earnest souls who wanted to secure knowledge.

03:03:04.810 --> 03:03:07.690
Tuskegee seemed an ideal place for the school.

03:03:08.530 --> 03:03:11.950
It was in the midst of the great bulk of the Negro population

03:03:11.950 --> 03:03:16.950
and was rather secluded, being five miles from the main line of railroad

03:03:16.950 --> 03:03:20.030
with which it was connected by a short line.

03:03:20.870 --> 03:03:23.370
During the days of slavery, and since,

03:03:23.370 --> 03:03:27.390
the town had been a center for the education of the white people.

03:03:28.490 --> 03:03:32.970
This was an added advantage for the reason that I found the white people

03:03:32.970 --> 03:03:38.650
possessing a degree of culture and education that is not surpassed by many localities.

03:03:39.550 --> 03:03:43.570
While the colored people were ignorant, they had not, as a rule,

03:03:44.050 --> 03:03:47.750
degraded and weakened their bodies by vices such as are common

03:03:47.750 --> 03:03:50.710
to the lower class of people in the larger cities.

03:03:51.470 --> 03:03:56.050
In general, I found the relations between the two races pleasant.

03:03:57.110 --> 03:04:02.870
For example, the largest, and I think at that time the only hardware store in the town,

03:04:03.290 --> 03:04:07.430
was owned and operated jointly by a colored man and a white man.

03:04:08.290 --> 03:04:11.850
This co-partnership continued until the death of the white partner.

03:04:13.970 --> 03:04:18.030
I found that about a year previous to my going to Tuskegee,

03:04:18.030 --> 03:04:22.310
some of the colored people who had heard something of the work of education

03:04:22.310 --> 03:04:26.270
being done at Hampton had applied to the state legislature,

03:04:26.830 --> 03:04:30.350
through the representatives, for a small appropriation

03:04:30.350 --> 03:04:33.610
to be used in starting a normal school in Tuskegee.

03:04:34.630 --> 03:04:38.550
This request the legislature had complied with to the extent

03:04:38.550 --> 03:04:41.910
of granting an annual appropriation of $2,000.

03:04:42.990 --> 03:04:46.350
I soon learned, however, that this money could be used only

03:04:46.350 --> 03:04:48.990
for the payment of the salaries of the instructors,

03:04:49.370 --> 03:04:53.970
and that there was no provision for securing land, buildings, or apparatus.

03:04:55.410 --> 03:04:59.170
The task before me did not seem a very encouraging one.

03:05:00.010 --> 03:05:03.170
It seemed much like making bricks without straw.

03:05:03.870 --> 03:05:08.750
The colored people were overjoyed, and were constantly offering their services

03:05:08.750 --> 03:05:12.890
in any way in which they could be of assistance in getting the school started.

03:05:14.610 --> 03:05:18.950
My first task was to find a place in which to open the school.

03:05:19.710 --> 03:05:22.050
After looking the town over with some care,

03:05:22.470 --> 03:05:27.970
the most suitable place that could be secured seemed to be a rather dilapidated shanty

03:05:27.970 --> 03:05:29.830
near the colored Methodist church,

03:05:30.150 --> 03:05:33.570
together with the church itself as a sort of assembly room.

03:05:34.570 --> 03:05:39.490
Both the church and the shanty were in about as bad condition as was possible.

03:05:40.290 --> 03:05:45.210
I recall that during the first months of school that I taught in this building,

03:05:45.510 --> 03:05:49.030
it was in such poor repair that whenever it rains,

03:05:49.450 --> 03:05:52.990
one of the older students would very kindly leave his lessons

03:05:52.990 --> 03:05:57.930
and hold an umbrella over me while I heard the recitations of the others.

03:05:58.630 --> 03:06:01.970
I remember also that on more than one occasion

03:06:01.970 --> 03:06:05.910
my landlady held an umbrella over me while I ate breakfast.

03:06:07.830 --> 03:06:10.190
At the time I went to Alabama,

03:06:10.670 --> 03:06:14.010
the colored people were taking considerable interest in politics,

03:06:14.550 --> 03:06:19.310
and they were very anxious that I should become one of them politically in every respect.

03:06:20.130 --> 03:06:23.790
They seemed to have a little distrust of strangers in this regard.

03:06:24.430 --> 03:06:29.570
I recall that one man, who seemed to have been designated by the others

03:06:29.570 --> 03:06:31.570
to look after my political destiny,

03:06:31.570 --> 03:06:34.850
came to me on several occasions and said,

03:06:35.050 --> 03:06:36.910
with a good deal of earnestness,

03:06:37.790 --> 03:06:41.530
We wants you to be sure to vote just like we votes.

03:06:42.390 --> 03:06:46.290
We can't read the newspapers very much, but we know how to vote,

03:06:46.490 --> 03:06:49.530
and we wants you to vote just like we votes.

03:06:50.350 --> 03:06:51.190
He added,

03:06:51.830 --> 03:06:55.650
We watches the white man, and we keeps watching the white man

03:06:55.650 --> 03:06:58.610
till we find out which way the white man's going to vote,

03:06:58.610 --> 03:07:02.750
and when we finds out which way the white man's going to vote,

03:07:03.010 --> 03:07:05.530
then we votes exactly the other way.

03:07:05.970 --> 03:07:07.910
Then we know we's right.

03:07:09.630 --> 03:07:12.910
I am glad to add, however, that at the present time

03:07:12.910 --> 03:07:15.350
the disposition to vote against the white man,

03:07:15.490 --> 03:07:18.610
merely because he is white, is largely disappearing,

03:07:19.090 --> 03:07:21.390
and the race is learning to vote from principle

03:07:21.390 --> 03:07:25.970
for what the voter considers to be the best interests of both races.

03:07:26.830 --> 03:07:32.330
I reached Tuskegee, as I have said, early in June 1881.

03:07:33.350 --> 03:07:37.030
The first month I spent in finding accommodations for the school

03:07:37.030 --> 03:07:39.250
and in traveling through Alabama,

03:07:39.850 --> 03:07:42.510
examining into the actual life of the people,

03:07:43.370 --> 03:07:45.090
especially in the court districts,

03:07:45.510 --> 03:07:48.870
and in getting the school advertised among the class of people

03:07:48.870 --> 03:07:50.910
that I wanted to have attend it.

03:07:51.890 --> 03:07:54.870
The most of my traveling was done over the country roads,

03:07:54.870 --> 03:08:00.010
with a mule and a cart or a mule and a buggy wagon for conveyance.

03:08:00.670 --> 03:08:04.070
I ate and slept with the people in their little cabins.

03:08:04.770 --> 03:08:07.690
I saw their farms, their schools, their churches.

03:08:08.170 --> 03:08:10.630
Since, in the case of most of these visits,

03:08:10.850 --> 03:08:14.550
there had been no notice given in advance that a stranger was expected,

03:08:14.830 --> 03:08:18.650
I had the advantage of seeing the real, everyday life of the people.

03:08:20.070 --> 03:08:23.670
In the plantation districts, I found that, as a rule,

03:08:23.670 --> 03:08:25.730
the whole family slept in one room,

03:08:26.170 --> 03:08:28.650
and that, in addition to the immediate family,

03:08:29.050 --> 03:08:33.190
there sometimes were relatives, or others not related to the family,

03:08:33.550 --> 03:08:35.030
who slept in the same room.

03:08:35.970 --> 03:08:40.410
On more than one occasion, I went outside the house to get ready for bed,

03:08:40.790 --> 03:08:43.350
or to wait until the family had gone to bed.

03:08:43.950 --> 03:08:47.210
They usually contrived some kind of a place for me to sleep,

03:08:47.570 --> 03:08:50.870
either on the floor or in a special part of another's bed.

03:08:51.730 --> 03:08:54.370
Rarely was there any place provided in the cabin

03:08:54.370 --> 03:08:57.430
where one could bathe even the face and hands,

03:08:57.890 --> 03:09:02.530
but usually some provision was made for this outside the home, in the yard.

03:09:04.270 --> 03:09:08.310
The common diet of the people was fat pork and cornbread.

03:09:08.990 --> 03:09:12.750
At times, I have eaten in cabins where they had only cornbread

03:09:12.750 --> 03:09:16.130
and black-eyed peas cooked in plain water.

03:09:17.110 --> 03:09:22.370
The people seemed to have no other idea than to live on this fat meat and cornbread.

03:09:23.230 --> 03:09:26.190
The meat, and the meal of which the bread was made,

03:09:26.550 --> 03:09:29.670
having been bought at a high price at a store in town,

03:09:30.770 --> 03:09:35.130
notwithstanding the fact that the land all about the cabin homes

03:09:35.130 --> 03:09:39.450
could easily have been made to produce nearly every kind of garden vegetable

03:09:39.450 --> 03:09:41.850
that is raised anywhere in the country.

03:09:42.790 --> 03:09:46.390
Their one object seemed to be to plant nothing but cotton,

03:09:47.130 --> 03:09:51.670
and in many cases cotton was planted up to the very door of the cabin.

03:09:53.530 --> 03:09:56.990
In these cabin homes I often found sewing machines

03:09:57.390 --> 03:10:00.850
which had been bought, or were being bought on installments,

03:10:01.950 --> 03:10:04.630
frequently at a cost of as much as $60,

03:10:05.630 --> 03:10:10.710
or showy clocks for which the occupants of the cabins had paid $12 or $14.

03:10:12.290 --> 03:10:17.450
I remember that on one occasion when I went into one of these cabins for dinner

03:10:17.450 --> 03:10:22.030
when I sat down to the table for a meal with the four members of the family,

03:10:22.650 --> 03:10:25.870
I noticed that, while there were five of us at the table,

03:10:26.470 --> 03:10:29.690
there was but one fork for the five of us to use.

03:10:31.130 --> 03:10:33.830
Naturally, there was an awkward pause on my part.

03:10:34.590 --> 03:10:39.090
In the opposite corner of the cabin was an organ for which the people told me

03:10:39.090 --> 03:10:43.010
they were paying $60 in monthly installments.

03:10:48.030 --> 03:10:51.850
In most cases the sewing machine was not used.

03:10:52.350 --> 03:10:56.210
The clocks were so worthless that they did not keep correct time,

03:10:56.710 --> 03:10:59.930
and if they had, in nine cases out of ten,

03:11:00.350 --> 03:11:04.550
there would have been no one in the family who could have told the time of day,

03:11:04.550 --> 03:11:10.650
while the organ, of course, was rarely used for one of a person who could play upon it.

03:11:12.430 --> 03:11:14.530
In the case to which I have referred,

03:11:14.950 --> 03:11:18.950
where the family sat down to the table for the meal at which I was their guest,

03:11:19.610 --> 03:11:23.370
I could see plainly that this was an awkward and unusual proceeding,

03:11:23.970 --> 03:11:25.690
and was done in my honor.

03:11:26.610 --> 03:11:30.330
In most cases, when the family got up in the morning, for example,

03:11:30.330 --> 03:11:36.270
the wife would put a piece of meal in a frying pan and put a lump of dough in a skillet,

03:11:36.510 --> 03:11:38.050
as they called it.

03:11:38.630 --> 03:11:41.170
These utensils would be placed on the fire,

03:11:41.670 --> 03:11:45.450
and in ten or fifteen minutes breakfast would be ready.

03:11:46.750 --> 03:11:52.110
Frequently the husband would take his bread and meat in his hand and start for the field,

03:11:52.530 --> 03:11:53.830
eating as he walked.

03:11:54.690 --> 03:11:57.750
The mother would sit down in a corner and eat her breakfast,

03:11:57.750 --> 03:12:02.790
perhaps from a plate and perhaps directly from the skillet or frying pan,

03:12:03.410 --> 03:12:08.530
while the children would eat their portion of the bread and meat while running about the yard.

03:12:09.370 --> 03:12:12.790
At certain seasons of the year, when meat was scarce,

03:12:13.370 --> 03:12:18.310
it was rarely that the children who were not old enough or strong enough to work in the fields

03:12:18.310 --> 03:12:20.130
would have the luxury of meat.

03:12:21.850 --> 03:12:26.330
The breakfast over, and with practically no attention given to the house,

03:12:26.330 --> 03:12:31.210
the whole family would, as a general thing, proceed to the cotton field.

03:12:33.490 --> 03:12:37.310
Every child that was large enough to carry a hoe was put to work,

03:12:37.670 --> 03:12:41.210
and the baby, for usually there was at least one baby,

03:12:41.630 --> 03:12:43.990
would be laid down at the end of the cotton row

03:12:43.990 --> 03:12:49.570
so that its mother could give it a certain amount of attention when she had finished chopping her row.

03:12:50.310 --> 03:12:55.410
The noon meal and the supper were taken in much the same way as the breakfast.

03:12:57.010 --> 03:13:02.150
All the days of the family would be spent after much the same routine,

03:13:02.970 --> 03:13:04.870
except Saturday and Sunday.

03:13:05.710 --> 03:13:12.570
On Saturday the whole family would spend at least half a day, and often a whole day, in town.

03:13:13.090 --> 03:13:17.430
The idea in going to town was, I suppose, to do shopping,

03:13:17.430 --> 03:13:21.150
but all the shopping that the whole family had money for

03:13:21.150 --> 03:13:24.970
could have been attended to in ten minutes by one person.

03:13:26.470 --> 03:13:30.590
Still, the whole family remained in town for most of the day,

03:13:31.050 --> 03:13:34.490
spending the greater part of the time in standing on the streets,

03:13:35.030 --> 03:13:39.870
the women too often sitting about somewhere, smoking or dipping snuff.

03:13:40.810 --> 03:13:43.970
Sunday was usually spent in going to some big meeting.

03:13:44.970 --> 03:13:51.570
With few exceptions, I found that the crops were mortgaged in the counties where I went,

03:13:51.890 --> 03:13:54.670
and that most of the colored farmers were in debt.

03:13:55.650 --> 03:13:59.290
The state had not been able to build schoolhouses in the country districts,

03:13:59.750 --> 03:14:04.530
and, as a rule, the schools were taught in churches or in log cabins.

03:14:05.210 --> 03:14:11.110
More than once, while on my journeys, I found that there was no provision made in the house,

03:14:11.110 --> 03:14:15.430
used for school purposes, for heating the building during winter.

03:14:16.330 --> 03:14:20.030
And, consequently, a fire had to be built in the yard,

03:14:20.350 --> 03:14:24.910
and the teacher and pupils passed in and out of the house as they got cold or warm.

03:14:25.750 --> 03:14:29.370
With few exceptions, I found the teachers in these country schools

03:14:29.630 --> 03:14:34.850
to be miserably poor in preparation for their work, and poor in moral character.

03:14:35.970 --> 03:14:39.530
The schools were in session from three to five months.

03:14:39.530 --> 03:14:42.950
There was practically no apparatus in the schoolhouses,

03:14:43.210 --> 03:14:46.290
except that occasionally there was a rough blackboard.

03:14:47.630 --> 03:14:50.470
I recall that one day I went into a schoolhouse,

03:14:50.890 --> 03:14:56.190
or rather into an abandoned log cabin that was being used as a schoolhouse,

03:14:56.630 --> 03:15:00.470
and found five pupils who were studying a lesson from one book.

03:15:01.470 --> 03:15:05.270
Two of these on the front seat were using the book between them.

03:15:05.270 --> 03:15:09.970
Behind these were two others peeping over the shoulders of the first two,

03:15:10.470 --> 03:15:16.650
and behind the four was a fifth little fellow who was peeping over the shoulders of all four.

03:15:18.150 --> 03:15:22.330
What I have said concerning the character of the schoolhouses and teachers

03:15:22.330 --> 03:15:27.810
will also apply quite accurately as the description of the church buildings and the ministers.

03:15:28.630 --> 03:15:32.170
I met some very interesting characters during my travels.

03:15:32.170 --> 03:15:36.790
As illustrating the peculiar mental processes of the country people,

03:15:37.650 --> 03:15:43.050
I remember that I asked one colored man, who was about sixty years old,

03:15:43.250 --> 03:15:45.310
to tell me something of his history.

03:15:45.850 --> 03:15:51.410
He said that he had been born in Virginia and sold into Alabama in 1845.

03:15:52.330 --> 03:15:55.510
I asked him how many were sold at the same time.

03:15:55.510 --> 03:15:56.470
He said,

03:16:01.490 --> 03:16:08.330
In giving all these descriptions of what I saw during my month of travel in the country around Tuskegee,

03:16:08.730 --> 03:16:15.970
I wish my readers to keep in mind the fact that there were many encouraging exceptions to the conditions which I have described.

03:16:16.830 --> 03:16:19.970
I have stated in such plain words what I saw,

03:16:19.970 --> 03:16:27.750
mainly for the reason that later I want to emphasize the encouraging changes that have taken place in the community,

03:16:28.330 --> 03:16:34.350
not wholly by the work of the Tuskegee school, but by that of other institutions as well.

03:17:05.830 --> 03:17:11.570
I confess that what I saw during my month of travel and investigation left me with a very

03:17:11.570 --> 03:17:17.310
heavy heart. The work to be done in order to lift these people up seemed almost beyond

03:17:17.310 --> 03:17:22.910
accomplishing. I was only one person, and it seemed to me that the little effort which

03:17:22.910 --> 03:17:28.890
I could put forth could go such a short distance toward bringing about results. I wondered

03:17:28.890 --> 03:17:36.130
if I could accomplish anything, and if it were worthwhile for me to try. Of one thing

03:17:36.130 --> 03:17:41.830
I felt more strongly convinced than ever after spending this month and seeing the actual

03:17:41.830 --> 03:17:48.610
life of the colored people, and that was that in order to lift them up, something must be

03:17:48.610 --> 03:17:55.770
done more than merely to imitate New England education as it then existed. I saw more clearly

03:17:55.770 --> 03:18:01.270
than ever the wisdom of the system which General Armstrong had inaugurated at Hampton.

03:18:02.150 --> 03:18:07.570
To take the children of such people as I had been among for a month, and each day give

03:18:07.570 --> 03:18:15.510
them a few hours of mere book education, I felt would be almost a waste of time. After

03:18:15.510 --> 03:18:23.390
consultation with the citizens of Tuskegee, I set July 4, 1881 as the day for the opening

03:18:23.390 --> 03:18:28.630
of the school in the little shanty and church which had been secured for its accommodation.

03:18:29.550 --> 03:18:34.370
The white people, as well as the colored, were greatly interested in the starting of

03:18:34.370 --> 03:18:40.690
the new school, and the opening day was looked forward to with much earnest discussion. There

03:18:40.690 --> 03:18:45.830
were not a few white people in the vicinity of Tuskegee who looked with some disfavor

03:18:45.830 --> 03:18:51.390
upon the project. They questioned its value to the colored people, and had a fear that

03:18:51.390 --> 03:18:57.030
it might result in bringing about trouble between the races. Some had the feeling that

03:18:57.030 --> 03:19:03.850
in proportion as the negro received education, in the same proportion would his value decrease

03:19:03.850 --> 03:19:09.890
as an economic factor in the state. These people feared the result of education would

03:19:09.890 --> 03:19:14.770
be that the negroes would leave the farms and that it would be difficult to secure them

03:19:14.770 --> 03:19:16.090
for domestic service.

03:19:18.030 --> 03:19:23.810
The white people who questioned the wisdom of starting this new school had in their minds

03:19:23.810 --> 03:19:30.250
pictures of what was called an educated negro, with a high hat, imitation gold eyeglasses,

03:19:30.810 --> 03:19:38.210
a showy walking stick, kid gloves, fancy boots and what not, in a word, a man who was determined

03:19:38.210 --> 03:19:44.370
to live by his wits. It was difficult for these people to see how education would produce

03:19:44.370 --> 03:19:50.690
any other kind of a colored man. In the midst of all the difficulties which I encountered

03:19:50.690 --> 03:19:55.970
in getting the little school started, and since then through a period of nineteen years,

03:19:56.510 --> 03:20:02.050
there are two men among all the many friends of the school in Tuskegee upon whom I have

03:20:02.050 --> 03:20:07.810
depended constantly for advice and guidance, and the success of the undertaking is largely

03:20:07.810 --> 03:20:14.930
due to these men from whom I have never sought anything in vain. I mention them simply as

03:20:14.930 --> 03:20:21.730
types. One is a white man and an ex-slave holder, Mr. George W. Campbell. The other

03:20:21.730 --> 03:20:28.250
is a black man and an ex-slave, Mr. Louis Adams. These were the men who wrote to General

03:20:28.250 --> 03:20:35.390
Armstrong for a teacher. Mr. Campbell is a merchant and banker and had had little experience

03:20:35.390 --> 03:20:42.290
in dealing with matters pertaining to education. Mr. Adams was a mechanic and had learned the trades

03:20:42.290 --> 03:20:48.570
of shoemaking, harness-making and tinsmithing during the days of slavery. He had never been

03:20:48.570 --> 03:20:54.210
to a school a day in his life, but in some way he had learned to read and write while a slave.

03:20:55.090 --> 03:21:01.910
From the first, these two men saw clearly what my plan of education was, sympathized with me,

03:21:01.910 --> 03:21:08.330
and supported me in every effort. In the days which were darkest financially for the school,

03:21:08.890 --> 03:21:14.570
Mr. Campbell was never appealed to when he was not willing to extend all the aid in his power.

03:21:15.250 --> 03:21:22.930
I do not know two men, one an ex-slave holder, one an ex-slave, whose advice and judgment I would

03:21:22.930 --> 03:21:27.990
feel more like following in everything which concerns the life and development of the school

03:21:27.990 --> 03:21:35.450
at Tuskegee than those of these two men. I have always felt that Mr. Adams, in a large degree,

03:21:36.030 --> 03:21:41.570
derived his unusual power of mind from the training given his hands in the process of

03:21:41.570 --> 03:21:48.970
mastering well three trades during the days of slavery. If one goes today into any southern town

03:21:48.970 --> 03:21:55.750
and asks for the leading and most reliable colored man in the community, I believe that in five cases

03:21:56.270 --> 03:22:03.510
he will be directed to a negro who learned a trade during the days of slavery. On the morning

03:22:03.510 --> 03:22:10.930
that the school opened, thirty students reported for admission. I was the only teacher. The students

03:22:10.930 --> 03:22:17.170
were about equally divided between the sexes. Most of them lived in Macon County, the county

03:22:17.170 --> 03:22:23.810
in which Tuskegee is situated, and of which it is the county seat. A great many more students

03:22:23.810 --> 03:22:28.730
wanted to enter the school, but it had been decided to receive only those who were above

03:22:28.730 --> 03:22:35.450
fifteen years of age and who had previously received some education. The greater part of

03:22:35.450 --> 03:22:41.730
the thirty were public school teachers, and some of them were nearly forty years of age. With the

03:22:41.730 --> 03:22:47.710
teachers came some of their former pupils, and when they were examined it was amusing to note

03:22:47.710 --> 03:22:54.310
that in several cases the pupil entered a higher class than did his former teacher. It was also

03:22:54.310 --> 03:23:00.290
interesting to note how many big books some of them had studied and how many high sounding

03:23:00.290 --> 03:23:06.190
subjects some of them claimed to have mastered. The bigger the book and the longer the name of

03:23:06.190 --> 03:23:12.350
the subject, the prouder they felt of their accomplishment. Some had studied Latin and one

03:23:12.350 --> 03:23:20.970
or two Greek. This, they thought, entitled them to special distinction. In fact, one of the saddest

03:23:20.970 --> 03:23:26.930
things I saw during the month of travel which I have described was a young man who had attended

03:23:26.930 --> 03:23:33.850
some high school sitting down in a one-room cabin with grease on his clothing, filth all around him,

03:23:34.050 --> 03:23:41.490
and weeds in the yard and garden, engaged in studying a French grammar. The students who came

03:23:41.490 --> 03:23:47.970
first seemed to be fond of memorizing long and complicated rules in grammar and mathematics,

03:23:48.450 --> 03:23:53.610
but had little thought or knowledge of applying these rules to their everyday affairs of their

03:23:53.610 --> 03:24:00.610
life. One subject which they liked to talk about and tell me that they had mastered in arithmetic

03:24:00.610 --> 03:24:07.950
was banking and discount, but I soon found out that neither they nor almost anyone in the

03:24:07.950 --> 03:24:15.170
neighborhood in which they had lived had ever had a bank account. In registering the names of the

03:24:15.170 --> 03:24:22.050
students, I found that almost every one of them had one or more middle initials. When I asked what

03:24:22.050 --> 03:24:29.890
the J stood for in the name of John J. Jones, it was explained to me that this was a part of his

03:24:29.890 --> 03:24:36.510
entitles. Most of the students wanted to get an education because they thought it would enable

03:24:36.510 --> 03:24:43.550
them to earn more money as school teachers. Notwithstanding what I have said about them in these

03:24:43.550 --> 03:24:49.710
respects, I have never seen a more earnest and willing company of young men and women than these

03:24:49.710 --> 03:24:55.710
students were. They were all willing to learn the right thing as soon as it was shown them what was

03:24:55.710 --> 03:25:02.490
right. I was determined to start them off on a solid and thorough foundation so far as their

03:25:02.490 --> 03:25:09.090
books were concerned. I soon learned that most of them had the merest smattering of the high sounding

03:25:09.090 --> 03:25:15.830
things that they had studied. While they could locate the desert of Sahara or the capital of

03:25:15.830 --> 03:25:22.550
China on an artificial globe, I found out that the girls could not locate the proper places for the

03:25:22.550 --> 03:25:28.790
knives and forks on an actual dinner table or the places on which the bread and meat should be set.

03:25:29.610 --> 03:25:36.630
I had to summon a good deal of courage to take a student who had been studying cube root and banking

03:25:36.630 --> 03:25:43.810
and discount and explain to him that the wisest thing for him to do first was thoroughly master

03:25:43.810 --> 03:25:51.570
the multiplication table. The number of pupils increased each week until by the end of the first

03:25:51.570 --> 03:25:59.050
month there were nearly 50. Many of them, however, said that as they could remain only for two or

03:25:59.050 --> 03:26:05.290
three months they wanted to enter a high class and get a diploma the first year if possible.

03:26:06.510 --> 03:26:13.930
At the end of the first six weeks a new and rare face entered the school as a co-teacher. This was

03:26:13.930 --> 03:26:22.950
Miss Olivia A. Davidson who later became my wife. Miss Davidson was born in Ohio and received her

03:26:22.950 --> 03:26:30.110
preparatory education in the public schools of that state. When little more than a girl she heard

03:26:30.110 --> 03:26:36.550
of the need of teachers in the south. She went to the state of Mississippi and began teaching there.

03:26:37.190 --> 03:26:44.470
Later she taught in the city of Memphis. While teaching in Mississippi one of her pupils became

03:26:44.470 --> 03:26:51.130
ill with smallpox. Everyone in the community was so frightened that no one would nurse the boy.

03:26:52.010 --> 03:26:58.270
Miss Davidson closed her school and remained by the bedside of the boy night and day until he

03:26:58.270 --> 03:27:06.250
recovered. While she was at her Ohio home on her vacation the worst epidemic of yellow fever broke

03:27:06.250 --> 03:27:13.330
out in Memphis Tennessee that perhaps has ever occurred in the south. When she heard of this she

03:27:13.330 --> 03:27:20.390
at once telegraphed the mayor of Memphis offering her services as a yellow fever nurse although she

03:27:20.390 --> 03:27:27.670
had never had the disease. Miss Davidson's experience in the south showed her that the

03:27:27.670 --> 03:27:34.070
people needed something more than mere book learning. She heard of the Hampton system of

03:27:34.070 --> 03:27:40.070
education and decided that this was what she wanted in order to prepare herself for better work

03:27:40.070 --> 03:27:48.010
in the south. The attention of Mrs. Mary Hemingway of Boston was attracted to her rare ability.

03:27:48.930 --> 03:27:55.510
Through Mrs. Hemingway's kindness and generosity Miss Davidson after graduating at Hampton

03:27:55.990 --> 03:28:02.070
received an opportunity to complete a two years course of training at the Massachusetts State

03:28:02.070 --> 03:28:10.130
Normal School at Framingham. Before she went to Framingham someone suggested to Miss Davidson

03:28:10.130 --> 03:28:16.570
that since she was so very light in color she might find it more comfortable not to be known

03:28:16.570 --> 03:28:24.130
as a colored woman in this school in Massachusetts. She at once replied that under no circumstances

03:28:24.130 --> 03:28:31.190
and for no considerations would she consent to deceive anyone in regard to her racial identity.

03:28:32.130 --> 03:28:39.350
Soon after her graduation from the Framingham institution Miss Davidson came to Tuskegee

03:28:39.350 --> 03:28:45.950
bringing into the school many valuable and fresh ideas as to the best methods of teaching as well

03:28:45.950 --> 03:28:52.750
as a rare moral character and a life of unselfishness that I think has seldom been equaled.

03:28:53.670 --> 03:28:59.330
No single individual did more toward laying the foundations of the Tuskegee Institute

03:28:59.330 --> 03:29:05.630
so as to ensure the successful work that has been done there than Olivia A. Davidson.

03:29:07.150 --> 03:29:12.130
Miss Davidson and I began consulting as to the future of the school from the first.

03:29:12.970 --> 03:29:17.850
The students were making progress in learning books and in development of their minds

03:29:18.370 --> 03:29:24.350
but it became apparent at once that if we were to make any permanent impression upon those who had

03:29:24.350 --> 03:29:31.410
come to us for training we must do something besides teach them mere books. The students had

03:29:31.410 --> 03:29:37.170
come from homes where they had had no opportunities for lessons which would teach them how to care for

03:29:37.170 --> 03:29:43.710
their bodies. With few exceptions the homes in Tuskegee in which the students boarded

03:29:43.710 --> 03:29:49.790
were but little improvement upon those from which they had come. We wanted to teach the students how

03:29:49.790 --> 03:29:55.350
to bathe, how to care for their teeth and clothing. We wanted to teach them what to eat

03:29:55.350 --> 03:30:02.030
and how to eat it properly and how to care for their rooms. Aside from this we wanted to give

03:30:02.030 --> 03:30:08.230
them such a practical knowledge of some one industry together with the spirit of industry

03:30:08.230 --> 03:30:13.950
thrift and economy that they would be sure of knowing how to make a living after they had left

03:30:13.950 --> 03:30:20.470
us. We wanted to teach them to study actual things instead of mere books alone.

03:30:21.950 --> 03:30:28.110
We found that the most of our students came from the country districts where agriculture in some

03:30:28.110 --> 03:30:34.610
form or other was the main dependence of the people. We learned that about 85 percent of the

03:30:34.610 --> 03:30:41.370
colored people in the gulf states depended upon agriculture for their living. Since this was true

03:30:41.370 --> 03:30:47.550
we wanted to be careful not to educate our students out of sympathy with agricultural life

03:30:47.550 --> 03:30:53.570
so that they would be attracted from the country to the cities and yield to the temptation of

03:30:53.570 --> 03:30:59.990
trying to live by their wits. We wanted to give them such an education as would fit a large

03:30:59.990 --> 03:31:05.910
proportion of them to be teachers and at the same time cause them to return to the plantation

03:31:05.910 --> 03:31:11.990
districts and show the people there how to put new energy and new ideas into farming

03:31:11.990 --> 03:31:16.950
as well as into the intellectual and moral and religious life of the people.

03:31:18.370 --> 03:31:25.070
All these ideas and needs crowded themselves upon us with a seriousness that seemed well nigh

03:31:25.070 --> 03:31:32.570
overwhelming. What were we to do? We had only the little old shanty and the abandoned church

03:31:32.570 --> 03:31:37.850
which the good colored people of the town of Tuskegee had kindly loaned us for the accommodation

03:31:37.850 --> 03:31:44.830
of the classes. The number of students was increasing daily. The more we saw of them and

03:31:44.830 --> 03:31:50.350
the more we traveled through the country districts the more we saw that our efforts were reaching

03:31:50.350 --> 03:31:56.130
to only a partial degree the actual needs of the people whom we wanted to lift up through the

03:31:56.130 --> 03:32:03.390
medium of the students whom we should educate and send out as leaders. The more we talked with the

03:32:03.390 --> 03:32:08.990
students who were then coming to us from several parts of the state the more we found that the

03:32:08.990 --> 03:32:14.350
chief ambition among a large proportion of them was to get an education so that they would not

03:32:14.350 --> 03:32:21.150
have to work any longer with their hands. This is illustrated by a story told of a colored man in

03:32:21.150 --> 03:32:28.610
Alabama who one hot day in July while he was at work in a cotton field suddenly stopped and looking

03:32:28.610 --> 03:32:36.750
toward the skies said oh lord the cotton them so grassy to work them so hard and the sun them so

03:32:36.750 --> 03:32:44.050
hot that I believe this docum called to preach. About three months after the opening of the school

03:32:44.050 --> 03:32:50.290
and at the time when we were in the greatest anxiety about our work there came into market

03:32:50.290 --> 03:32:57.170
for sale an old and abandoned plantation which was situated about a mile from the town of Tuskegee.

03:32:57.990 --> 03:33:04.690
The mansion house or big house as it would have been called which had been occupied by the owners

03:33:04.690 --> 03:33:11.670
during slavery had been burned. After making a careful examination of the place it seemed to

03:33:11.670 --> 03:33:16.470
be just the location that we wanted in order to make our work effective and permanent.

03:33:17.350 --> 03:33:24.230
But how were we to get it? The price asked for it was very little only five hundred dollars

03:33:24.230 --> 03:33:31.790
but we had no money and we were strangers in the town and had no credit. The owner of the land

03:33:31.790 --> 03:33:37.990
agreed to let us occupy the place if we could make a payment of two hundred and fifty dollars down

03:33:37.990 --> 03:33:43.290
with the understanding that the remaining two hundred and fifty dollars must be paid within

03:33:43.290 --> 03:33:51.070
a year. Although five hundred dollars was cheap for the land it was a large sum when one did not

03:33:51.070 --> 03:33:58.470
have any part of it. In the midst of the difficulty I summoned a great deal of courage and wrote to

03:33:58.470 --> 03:34:05.330
my friend general J.F.B. Marshall the treasurer of the Hampton Institute putting the situation

03:34:05.330 --> 03:34:11.170
before him and beseeching him to lend me the two hundred and fifty dollars on my own personal

03:34:11.170 --> 03:34:18.430
responsibility. Within a few days a reply came to the effect that he had no authority

03:34:18.430 --> 03:34:24.390
to lend me the money belonging to the Hampton Institute but that he would gladly lend me the

03:34:24.390 --> 03:34:31.290
amount needed from his own personal funds. I confess that the securing of this money in this

03:34:31.290 --> 03:34:39.630
way was a great surprise to me as well as a source of gratification. Up to that time I never had had

03:34:39.630 --> 03:34:46.070
in my possession so much money as one hundred dollars at a time and the loan which I had asked

03:34:46.070 --> 03:34:53.450
General Marshall for seemed a tremendously large sum to me. The fact of my being responsible for

03:34:53.450 --> 03:35:00.670
the repaying of such a large amount of money weighed very heavily upon me. I lost no time

03:35:00.670 --> 03:35:07.870
in getting ready to move the school on to the new farm. At the time we occupied the place there was

03:35:07.870 --> 03:35:15.490
standing upon it a cabin formerly used as a dining room, an old kitchen, a stable, and an old hen

03:35:15.490 --> 03:35:22.530
house. Within a few weeks we had all of these structures in use. The stable was repaired and

03:35:22.530 --> 03:35:28.550
used as a recitation room and very presently the hen house was utilized for the same purpose.

03:35:29.750 --> 03:35:35.550
I recall that one morning when I told an old colored man who lived near and who sometimes helped

03:35:35.550 --> 03:35:41.530
me that our school had grown so large that it would be necessary for us to use the hen house

03:35:41.530 --> 03:35:47.270
for school purposes and that I wanted him to help me give it a thorough cleaning out the next day

03:35:47.790 --> 03:35:54.290
he replied in the most earnest manner what you mean boss you surely ain't going to clean out

03:35:54.290 --> 03:36:01.470
the hen house into daytime. Nearly all the work of getting the new location ready for school purposes

03:36:01.470 --> 03:36:08.850
was done by the students after school was over in the afternoon. As soon as we got the cabins

03:36:08.850 --> 03:36:14.610
in condition to be used I determined to clear up some land so that we could plant a crop.

03:36:15.570 --> 03:36:22.290
When I explained my plan to the young man I noticed that they did not seem to take to it very kindly.

03:36:22.690 --> 03:36:29.950
It was hard for them to see the connection between clearing land and an education. Besides,

03:36:29.950 --> 03:36:36.070
many of them had been school teachers and they questioned whether or not clearing land would be

03:36:36.070 --> 03:36:43.130
in keeping with their dignity. In order to relieve them from any embarrassment each afternoon after

03:36:43.130 --> 03:36:50.610
school I took my axe and led the way to the woods. When they saw that I was not afraid or ashamed to

03:36:50.610 --> 03:36:58.330
work they began to assist with more enthusiasm. We kept at the work each afternoon until we had

03:36:58.330 --> 03:37:06.250
about 20 acres and had planted a crop. In the meantime Miss Davidson was devising plans to

03:37:06.250 --> 03:37:14.230
repay the loan. Her first effort was made by holding festivals or suppers. She made a personal

03:37:14.230 --> 03:37:20.210
canvas among the white and colored families in the town of Tuskegee and got them to agree to

03:37:20.210 --> 03:37:26.110
give something like a cake a chicken bread or pies that could be sold at the festival.

03:37:26.730 --> 03:37:30.690
Of course the colored people were glad to give anything that they could spare

03:37:30.690 --> 03:37:36.850
but I want to add that Miss Davidson did not apply to a single white family so far as I now

03:37:36.850 --> 03:37:43.210
remember that failed to donate something and in many ways the white families showed their interest

03:37:43.210 --> 03:37:50.050
in the school. Several of these festivals were held and quite a little sum of money was raised.

03:37:50.690 --> 03:37:57.850
A canvas was also made among the people of both races for direct gifts of money and most of those

03:37:57.850 --> 03:38:05.030
applied to gave small sums. It was often pathetic to note the gifts of the older colored people

03:38:05.030 --> 03:38:11.710
most of whom had spent their best days in slavery. Sometimes they would give five cents sometimes

03:38:11.710 --> 03:38:19.730
25 cents. Sometimes the contribution was a quilt or a quantity of sugar cane. I recall one old

03:38:19.730 --> 03:38:25.790
colored woman who was about 70 years of age who came to see me when we were raising money to pay

03:38:25.790 --> 03:38:33.390
for the farm. She hobbled into the room where I was leaning on a cane. She was clad in rags

03:38:33.390 --> 03:38:41.250
but they were clean. She said, Mr. Washington, God knows I spent the best days of my life in

03:38:41.250 --> 03:38:48.610
slavery. God knows I is ignorant and poor but she added, I knows what you and Miss Davidson

03:38:48.610 --> 03:38:54.730
is trying to do. I knows you is trying to make better men and better women for the colored race.

03:38:55.410 --> 03:39:01.690
I ain't got no money but I want you to take these six eggs what I've been saving up and I want you

03:39:01.690 --> 03:39:09.130
to put these six eggs into education of these boys and gals. Since the work at Tuskegee started

03:39:09.130 --> 03:39:14.250
it has been my privilege to receive many gifts for the benefit of the institution

03:39:14.250 --> 03:39:19.780
but never any I think that touched me so deeply as this one.

03:39:54.910 --> 03:40:04.890
The coming of Christmas, that first year of our residence in Alabama, gave us an opportunity to get a farther insight into the real life of the people.

03:40:05.790 --> 03:40:17.330
The first thing that reminded us that Christmas had arrived was the four-day visits of scores of children wrapping at our doors, asking for Christmas gifts, Christmas gifts.

03:40:17.330 --> 03:40:26.070
Between the hours of two o'clock and five o'clock in the morning, I presume that we must have had a half-hundred such calls.

03:40:26.830 --> 03:40:30.690
This custom prevails throughout this portion of the South today.

03:40:31.570 --> 03:40:41.710
During the days of slavery, it was a custom quite generally observed throughout all the southern states to give the colored people a week of holiday at Christmas,

03:40:42.250 --> 03:40:47.010
or to allow the holiday to continue as long as the yule log lasted.

03:40:48.150 --> 03:40:53.710
The male members of the race, and often the female members, were expected to get drunk.

03:40:53.710 --> 03:41:01.670
We found that for a whole week the colored people in and around Tuskegee dropped work the day before Christmas,

03:41:02.230 --> 03:41:09.150
and that it was difficult for anyone to perform any service from the time they stopped work until after the New Year.

03:41:10.430 --> 03:41:18.770
Persons who at other times did not use strong drink thought it quite the proper thing to indulge in it rather freely during the Christmas week.

03:41:18.770 --> 03:41:25.830
There was a widespread hilarity and a free use of guns, pistols, and gunpowder generally.

03:41:26.870 --> 03:41:31.530
The sacredness of the season seemed to have been almost wholly lost sight of.

03:41:33.830 --> 03:41:41.490
During this first Christmas vacation, I went some distance from the town to visit the people on one of the large plantations.

03:41:41.490 --> 03:41:52.390
In their poverty and ignorance, it was pathetic to see their attempts to get joy out of the season that in most parts of the country is so sacred and so dear to the heart.

03:41:53.430 --> 03:42:04.130
In one cabin, I noticed that all that the five children had to remind them of the coming of Christ was a single bunch of firecrackers which they had divided among them.

03:42:04.130 --> 03:42:14.950
In another cabin, where there were at least a half dozen persons, they only had ten cents worth of ginger cakes which had been bought in the store the day before.

03:42:15.810 --> 03:42:19.570
In another family, they had only a few pieces of sugar cane.

03:42:20.330 --> 03:42:33.130
In still another cabin, I found nothing but a new jug of cheap mean whiskey which the husband and wife were making free use of, notwithstanding the fact that the husband was one of the local ministers.

03:42:33.130 --> 03:42:44.150
In a few instances, I found that the people had gotten hold of some bright colored cards that had been designed for advertising purposes and were making the most of these.

03:42:45.050 --> 03:42:48.530
In other homes, some member of the family had bought a new pistol.

03:42:49.410 --> 03:43:01.450
In the majority of cases, there was nothing to be seen in the cabin to remind one of the coming of the Savior, except that the people had ceased work in the fields and were lounging about their homes.

03:43:02.190 --> 03:43:09.610
At night during Christmas week, they usually had what they called a frolic in some cabin on the plantation.

03:43:10.370 --> 03:43:19.810
That meant a kind of rough dance where there was likely to be a good deal of whiskey used and where there might be some shooting or cutting with razors.

03:43:20.870 --> 03:43:38.950
While I was making this Christmas visit, I met an old colored man who was one of the numerous local preachers who tried to convince me from the experience Adam had in the Garden of Eden that God had cursed all labor and that therefore it was a sin for any man to work.

03:43:39.510 --> 03:43:43.690
For that reason, this man sought to do as little work as possible.

03:43:43.690 --> 03:43:52.590
He seemed at that time to be supremely happy because he was living, as he expressed it, through one week that was free from sin.

03:43:54.050 --> 03:44:02.590
In the school, we made a special effort to teach our students the meaning of Christmas and to give them lessons in its proper observance.

03:44:02.590 --> 03:44:16.890
In this, we have been successful to a degree that makes me feel safe in saying that the season now has a new meaning, not only through all that immediate region, but in a measure wherever our graduates have gone.

03:44:17.870 --> 03:44:35.010
At the present time, one of the most satisfactory features of the Christmas and Thanksgiving season at Tuskegee is the unselfish and beautiful way in which our graduates and students spend their time in administering to the comfort and happiness of others, especially the unfortunate.

03:44:36.250 --> 03:44:45.230
Not long ago, some of our young men spent a holiday in rebuilding a cabin for a helpless colored woman who was about 75 years old.

03:44:45.230 --> 03:44:54.790
At another time, I remember that I made it known in chapel one night that a very poor student was suffering from cold because he needed a coat.

03:44:55.550 --> 03:44:59.270
The next morning, two coats were sent to my office for him.

03:45:00.730 --> 03:45:07.910
I have referred to the disposition on the part of the white people in the town of Tuskegee and vicinity to help the school.

03:45:08.550 --> 03:45:14.590
From the first, I resolved to make the school a real part of the community in which it was located.

03:45:15.450 --> 03:45:27.010
I was determined that no one should have the feeling that it was a foreign institution dropped down in the midst of the people for which they had no responsibility and in which they had no interest.

03:45:27.010 --> 03:45:38.310
I noticed that the very fact that they had been asking to contribute toward the purchase of the land made them begin to feel as if it was going to be their school to a large degree.

03:45:39.270 --> 03:45:46.510
I noted that just in proportion, as we made the white people feel that the institution was a part of the life of the community,

03:45:46.510 --> 03:45:58.530
and that while we wanted to make friends in Boston, for example, we also wanted to make white friends in Tuskegee and that we wanted to make the school of real service to all the people.

03:45:58.890 --> 03:46:01.990
Their attitude toward the school became favorable.

03:46:02.990 --> 03:46:22.050
Perhaps I might add right here, what I hope to demonstrate later, that, so far as I know, the Tuskegee school at the present time has no warmer and more enthusiastic friends anywhere than it has among the white citizens of Tuskegee and throughout the state of Alabama and the entire south.

03:46:22.890 --> 03:46:34.250
From the first, I have advised our people in the south to make friends in every straightforward, manly way with their next door neighbor, whether he be a black man or a white man.

03:46:34.570 --> 03:46:44.770
I have also advised them, where no principle is at stake, to consult the interests of their local communities and to advise with their friends in regard to their voting.

03:46:46.170 --> 03:46:52.890
For several months, the work of securing the money with which to pay for the farm went on without ceasing.

03:46:53.490 --> 03:47:08.090
At the end of three months, enough was secured to repay the loan of $250 to General Marshall, and within two months more, we had secured the entire $500 and had received a deed of the 100 acres of land.

03:47:08.090 --> 03:47:11.330
This gave us a great deal of satisfaction.

03:47:12.070 --> 03:47:27.210
It was not only a source of satisfaction to secure a permanent location for the school, but it was equally satisfactory to know that the greater part of the money with which it was paid for had been gotten from the white and colored people in the town of Tuskegee.

03:47:28.190 --> 03:47:34.710
The most of this money was obtained by holding festivals and concerts and from small individual donations.

03:47:36.030 --> 03:47:47.150
Our next effort was in the direction of increasing the cultivation of the land so as to secure some return from it and at the same time give the students training in agriculture.

03:47:48.090 --> 03:47:55.750
All the industries at Tuskegee have been started in natural and logical order, growing out of the needs of a community settlement.

03:47:56.510 --> 03:47:59.810
We began with farming because we wanted something to eat.

03:48:00.970 --> 03:48:09.830
Many of the students also were able to remain in school but a few weeks at a time because they had so little money with which to pay their board.

03:48:10.710 --> 03:48:26.190
Thus, another object which made it desirable to get an industrial system started was in order to make it available as a means of helping the students to earn money enough so that they might be able to remain in school during the nine-month session of the school year.

03:48:27.550 --> 03:48:36.350
The first animal that the school came into possession of was an old blind horse given us by one of the white citizens of Tuskegee.

03:48:37.190 --> 03:48:52.170
Perhaps I may add here that at the present time the school owns over 200 horses, colts, mules, cows, calves and oxen and about 700 hogs and pigs as well as a large number of sheep and goats.

03:48:53.350 --> 03:49:11.610
The school was constantly growing in numbers so much so that after we had got the farm paid for, the cultivation of the land begun and the old cabins which we had found on the place somewhat repaired, we turned our attention toward providing a large substantial building.

03:49:12.210 --> 03:49:21.690
After having given a good deal of thought to the subject, we finally had the plans drawn for a building that was estimated to cost about $6,000.

03:49:22.570 --> 03:49:34.750
This seemed to us a tremendous sum but we knew that the school must go backward or forward and that our work would mean little unless we could get hold of the students in their home life.

03:49:36.010 --> 03:49:43.270
One incident which occurred about this time gave me a great deal of satisfaction as well as surprise.

03:49:43.270 --> 03:50:07.090
When it became known in the town that we were discussing the plans for a new large building, a southern white man who was operating a sawmill not far from Tuskegee came to me and said that he would gladly put all the lumber necessary to erect the building on the grounds with no other guarantee for payment than my word that it would be paid for when we secured some money.

03:50:07.090 --> 03:50:13.990
I told the man frankly that at the time we did not have in our hands $1 of the money needed.

03:50:15.010 --> 03:50:19.870
Notwithstanding this, he insisted on being allowed to put the lumber on the grounds.

03:50:20.810 --> 03:50:25.290
After we had secured some portion of the money, we permitted him to do this.

03:50:26.090 --> 03:50:37.010
Ms. Davidson again began the work of securing in various ways small contributions for the new building from the white and colored people in and near Tuskegee.

03:50:37.690 --> 03:50:45.750
I think I never saw a community of people so happy over anything as were the colored people over the prospect of this new building.

03:50:46.410 --> 03:50:58.910
One day when we were holding a meeting to secure funds for its erection, an old antebellum colored man came a distance of 12 miles and brought in his ox cart a large hog.

03:50:59.690 --> 03:51:14.550
When the meeting was in progress, he rose in the midst of the company and said that he had no money which he could give, but he had raised two fine hogs and that he had brought one of them as a contribution toward the expenses of the building.

03:51:14.550 --> 03:51:25.450
He closed his announcement by saying, any nigger that's got any love for his race or any respect for himself will bring a hog to the next meeting.

03:51:26.770 --> 03:51:33.870
Quite a number of men in the community also volunteered to give several days work each toward the erection of the building.

03:51:35.390 --> 03:51:44.270
After we had secured all the help that we could in Tuskegee, Ms. Davidson decided to go north for the purpose of securing additional funds.

03:51:45.110 --> 03:51:51.230
For weeks she visited individuals and spoke in churches and before Sunday schools and other organizations.

03:51:51.990 --> 03:51:55.250
She found this work quite trying and often embarrassing.

03:51:55.250 --> 03:52:02.790
The school was not known, but she was not long in winning her way into the confidence of the best people in the north.

03:52:04.330 --> 03:52:12.130
The first gift from any northern person was received from a New York lady whom Ms. Davidson met on the boat that was bringing her north.

03:52:12.830 --> 03:52:23.670
They fell into a conversation and the northern lady became so much interested in the effort being made at Tuskegee that before they parted Ms. Davidson was handed a check for $50.

03:52:23.670 --> 03:52:37.510
For some time before our marriage and also after it, Ms. Davidson kept up the work of securing money in the north and in the south by interesting people by personal visits and through correspondence.

03:52:38.570 --> 03:52:45.730
At the same time she kept in close touch with the work at Tuskegee as lady principal and classroom teacher.

03:52:45.730 --> 03:52:54.210
In addition to this, she worked among the older people in and near Tuskegee and taught a Sunday school class in the town.

03:52:55.190 --> 03:53:02.410
She was never very strong, but never seemed happy unless she was giving all of her strength to the cause which she loved.

03:53:03.350 --> 03:53:13.830
Often at night after spending the day and going from door to door trying to interest persons in the work at Tuskegee, she would be so exhausted that she could not undress herself.

03:53:13.830 --> 03:53:27.030
A lady upon whom she called in Boston afterward told me that at one time when Ms. Davidson called her to see and send up her card, the lady was detained a little before she could see Ms. Davidson.

03:53:27.590 --> 03:53:33.270
And when she entered the parlor, she found Ms. Davidson so exhausted that she had fallen asleep.

03:53:34.950 --> 03:53:48.010
While putting up our first building, which was named Porter Hall after Mr. A.H. Porter of Brooklyn, New York who gave a generous sum toward its erection, the need for money became acute.

03:53:48.770 --> 03:53:54.430
I had given one of our creditors a promise that upon a certain day he should be paid $400.

03:53:55.410 --> 03:53:58.850
On the morning of that day we did not have a dollar.

03:53:58.850 --> 03:54:08.350
The mail arrived at the school at 10 o'clock and in this mail there was a check sent by Ms. Davidson for exactly $400.

03:54:09.210 --> 03:54:13.270
I could relate many instances of almost the same character.

03:54:14.250 --> 03:54:17.690
This $400 was given by two ladies in Boston.

03:54:17.690 --> 03:54:33.410
Two years later when the work at Tuskegee had grown considerably and when we were in the midst of a season when we were so much in need of money that the future looked doubtful and gloomy, the same two Boston ladies sent us $6,000.

03:54:34.610 --> 03:54:40.130
Words cannot describe our surprise or the encouragement that the gift brought to us.

03:54:40.130 --> 03:54:47.590
Perhaps I might add here that for 14 years these same friends have sent us $6,000 a year.

03:54:49.050 --> 03:54:58.510
As soon as the plans were drawn for the new building, the students began digging out the earth where the foundations were to be laid, working after the regular classes were over.

03:54:58.510 --> 03:55:10.790
They had not fully outgrown the idea that it was hardly the proper thing for them to use their hands since they had come there, as one of them expressed it, to be educated and not to work.

03:55:11.810 --> 03:55:17.990
Gradually though I noted with satisfaction that a sentiment in favor of work was gaining ground.

03:55:18.570 --> 03:55:25.370
After a few weeks of hard work the foundations were ready and a day was appointed for the laying of the cornerstone.

03:55:26.570 --> 03:55:38.270
When it is considered that the laying of this cornerstone took place in the heart of the South, in the black belt, in the center of that part of our country that was most devoted to slavery,

03:55:38.890 --> 03:55:51.950
that at that time slavery had been abolished only about 16 years, that only 16 years before no Negro could be taught from books without the teacher receiving the condemnation of the law or of public sentiment,

03:55:51.950 --> 03:55:59.750
when all this is considered, the scene that was witnessed on that spring day at Tuskegee was a remarkable one.

03:56:00.590 --> 03:56:04.610
I believe there are few places in the world where it could have taken place.

03:56:05.890 --> 03:56:12.770
The principal address was delivered by the Honorable Wadie Thompson, the Superintendent of Education for the county.

03:56:12.770 --> 03:56:24.130
About the cornerstone were gathered the teachers, the students, their parents and friends, the county officials, who were white, and all the leading white men in that vicinity,

03:56:24.630 --> 03:56:32.390
together with many of the black men and women whom the same white people but a few years before had held a title to as property.

03:56:33.350 --> 03:56:40.690
The members of both races were anxious to exercise the privilege of placing under the cornerstone some memento.

03:56:41.870 --> 03:56:46.650
Before the building was completed, we passed through some very trying seasons.

03:56:47.330 --> 03:56:54.890
More than once our hearts were made to bleed, as it were, because bills were falling due that we did not have the money to meet.

03:56:55.490 --> 03:57:04.290
Perhaps no one who has not gone through the experience, month after month, of trying to erect buildings and provide equipment for a school

03:57:04.290 --> 03:57:11.250
when no one knew where the money was to come from, can properly appreciate the difficulties under which we labored.

03:57:11.970 --> 03:57:19.110
During the first years at Tuskegee, I recall that night after night I would roll and toss on my bed without sleep

03:57:19.110 --> 03:57:23.650
because of the anxiety and uncertainty which we were in regarding money.

03:57:24.290 --> 03:57:32.810
I knew that, in a large degree, we were trying an experiment, that of testing whether or not it was possible for Negroes

03:57:32.810 --> 03:57:36.810
to build up and control the affairs of a large education institution.

03:57:38.010 --> 03:57:41.890
I knew that if we failed, it would injure the whole race.

03:57:42.590 --> 03:57:44.970
I knew that the presumption was against us.

03:57:45.550 --> 03:57:52.350
I knew that in the case of white people beginning such an enterprise, it would be taken for granted that they were going to succeed.

03:57:52.350 --> 03:57:57.270
But in our case, I felt that people would be surprised if we succeeded.

03:57:58.230 --> 03:58:05.950
All this made a burden which pressed down on us, sometimes it seemed, at the rate of a thousand pounds to the square inch.

03:58:07.910 --> 03:58:15.350
In all our difficulties and anxieties, however, I never went to a white or a black person in the town of Tuskegee

03:58:15.350 --> 03:58:21.330
for any assistance that was in their power to render, without being helped according to their means.

03:58:21.950 --> 03:58:27.870
More than a dozen times, when bills figuring up into the hundreds of dollars were falling due,

03:58:28.430 --> 03:58:31.850
I applied to the white men of Tuskegee for small loans,

03:58:32.510 --> 03:58:38.170
often borrowing small amounts from as many as a half dozen persons to meet our obligations.

03:58:39.250 --> 03:58:45.210
One thing I was determined to do from the first, and that was to keep the credit of the school high.

03:58:46.030 --> 03:58:50.890
And this, I think I can say without boasting, we have done all through these years.

03:58:51.870 --> 03:58:57.350
I shall always remember a bit of advice given me by Mr. George W. Campbell,

03:58:57.830 --> 03:59:03.910
the white man to whom I have referred to as the one who induced General Armstrong to send me to Tuskegee.

03:59:04.810 --> 03:59:10.030
Soon after I entered upon the work, Mr. Campbell said to me in his fatherly way,

03:59:10.670 --> 03:59:14.630
Washington, always remember that credit is capital.

03:59:16.070 --> 03:59:21.550
At one time, when we were in the greatest distress for money that we ever experienced,

03:59:22.130 --> 03:59:25.530
I placed the situation frankly before General Armstrong.

03:59:26.450 --> 03:59:32.990
Without hesitation, he gave me his personal check for all the money which he had saved for his own use.

03:59:33.810 --> 03:59:38.110
This was not the only time that General Armstrong helped Tuskegee in this way.

03:59:38.590 --> 03:59:42.090
I do not think I have ever made this fact public before.

03:59:43.410 --> 03:59:48.710
During the summer of 1882, at the end of the first year's work of the school,

03:59:49.110 --> 03:59:53.610
I was married to Miss Fannie N. Smith of Malden, West Virginia.

03:59:54.330 --> 03:59:57.650
We began keeping house in Tuskegee early in the fall.

03:59:58.370 --> 04:00:03.610
This made a home for our teachers, who now had been increased to four in number.

04:00:04.430 --> 04:00:07.830
My wife was also a graduate of the Hampton Institute.

04:00:07.830 --> 04:00:11.830
After earnest and constant work in the interests of the school,

04:00:12.310 --> 04:00:17.930
together with her housekeeping duties, my wife passed away in May 1884.

04:00:18.730 --> 04:00:23.270
One child, Portia M. Washington, was born during our marriage.

04:00:24.610 --> 04:00:30.570
From the first, my wife most earnestly devoted her thoughts and time to the work of the school,

04:00:31.050 --> 04:00:35.030
and was completely one with me in every interest and ambition.

04:00:35.030 --> 04:00:43.030
She passed away, however, before she had an opportunity of seeing what the school was designed to be.

04:01:09.130 --> 04:01:14.870
Up From Slavery by Booker T. Washington

04:01:15.650 --> 04:01:19.230
A Harder Task Than Making Bricks Without Straw.

04:01:20.390 --> 04:01:31.370
From the very beginning at Tuskegee, I was determined to have the students do not only the agricultural and domestic work, but to have them erect their own buildings.

04:01:32.010 --> 04:01:57.550
My plan was to have them, while performing this service, taught the latest and best methods of labor, so that the school would not only get the benefit of their efforts, but the students themselves would be taught to see not only utility in labor, but beauty and dignity, would be taught, in fact, how to lift labor up for mere drudgery and toil, and would learn to love work for its own sake.

04:01:58.430 --> 04:02:12.090
My plan was not to teach them to work in the old way, but to show them how to make the forces of nature, air, water, steam, electricity, horsepower, assist them in their labor.

04:02:13.090 --> 04:02:23.170
At first, many advised against the experiment of having the buildings erected by the labor of the students, but I was determined to stick to it.

04:02:23.510 --> 04:02:36.230
I told those who doubted the wisdom of the plan that I knew that our first buildings would not be so comfortable or so complete in their finish as buildings erected by the experienced hands of outside workmen,

04:02:36.230 --> 04:02:47.870
but that in the teaching of civilization, self-help, and self-reliance, the erection of buildings by the students themselves would more than compensate for any lack of comfort or fine finish.

04:02:48.570 --> 04:03:00.490
I further told those who doubted the wisdom of this plan that the majority of our students came to us in poverty from the cabins of the cotton, sugar, and rice plantations of the South,

04:03:01.130 --> 04:03:06.490
and that while I knew it would please the students very much to place them at once in finely constructed buildings,

04:03:07.050 --> 04:03:14.570
I felt that it would be following out a more natural process of development to teach them how to construct their own buildings.

04:03:15.410 --> 04:03:20.810
Mistakes I knew would be made, but these mistakes would teach us valuable lessons for the future.

04:03:21.730 --> 04:03:31.090
During the now 19 years existence of the Tuskegee School, the plan of having the buildings erected by student labor has been adhered to.

04:03:31.290 --> 04:03:40.850
In this time, 40 buildings, counting small and large, have been built, and all except four are almost wholly the product of student labor.

04:03:41.710 --> 04:03:50.870
As an additional result, hundreds of men are now scattered throughout the South who receive their knowledge of mechanics while being taught how to erect these buildings.

04:03:51.870 --> 04:03:57.090
Skill and knowledge are now handed down from one set of students to another in this way,

04:03:57.550 --> 04:04:06.490
until at the present time a building of any description or size can be constructed wholly by our students and instructors.

04:04:06.490 --> 04:04:15.450
From the drawing of the plans to the putting in of the electric fixtures, without going off the grounds for a single workman.

04:04:16.810 --> 04:04:26.250
Not a few times, when a new student has been led into the temptation of marring the looks of some building by lead pencil marks or by the cuts of a jackknife,

04:04:26.690 --> 04:04:33.270
I have heard an old student remind him, don't do that, that is our building, I helped put it up.

04:04:34.050 --> 04:04:40.450
In the early days of the school, I think my most trying experience was in the matter of brick making.

04:04:41.530 --> 04:04:49.670
As soon as we got the farm work reasonably well started, we directed our next efforts toward the industry of making bricks.

04:04:50.510 --> 04:04:58.870
We needed these for use in connection with the erection of our own buildings, but there was also another reason for establishing this industry.

04:04:59.470 --> 04:05:07.090
There was no brick yard in the town, and in addition to our own needs, there was demand for bricks in the general market.

04:05:08.190 --> 04:05:14.710
I had always sympathized with the children of Israel in their task of making bricks without straw,

04:05:15.670 --> 04:05:21.030
but ours was the task of making bricks with no money and no experience.

04:05:21.950 --> 04:05:28.270
In the first place, the work was hard and dirty, and it was difficult to get the students to help.

04:05:29.070 --> 04:05:36.570
When it came to brick making, their distaste for manual labor in connection with book education became especially manifest.

04:05:37.430 --> 04:05:44.070
It was not a pleasant task for one to stand in the mud pit for hours, with the mud up to his knees.

04:05:44.730 --> 04:05:48.010
More than one man became disgusted and left the school.

04:05:49.430 --> 04:05:54.670
We tried several locations before we opened up a pit that furnished brick clay.

04:05:54.670 --> 04:06:04.550
I had always supposed that brick making was very simple, but I soon found out by better experience that it required special skill and knowledge,

04:06:04.890 --> 04:06:07.470
particularly in the burning of the bricks.

04:06:08.690 --> 04:06:16.070
After a good deal of effort, we molded about 25,000 bricks and put them into a kiln to be burned.

04:06:16.790 --> 04:06:23.650
This kiln turned out to be a failure, because it was not properly constructed or properly burned.

04:06:24.270 --> 04:06:27.430
We began it once, however, on a second kiln.

04:06:27.890 --> 04:06:30.650
This, for some reason, also proved a failure.

04:06:31.610 --> 04:06:37.530
The failure of this kiln made it still more difficult to get the students to take part in the work.

04:06:38.450 --> 04:06:43.310
Several of the teachers, however, who had been trained in the industries at Hampton,

04:06:43.590 --> 04:06:49.250
volunteered their services, and in some way we succeeded in getting a third kiln ready for burning.

04:06:49.990 --> 04:06:53.330
The burning of a kiln required about a week.

04:06:53.850 --> 04:06:59.890
Toward the latter part of the week, when it seemed as if we were going to have a good many thousand bricks in a few hours,

04:07:00.410 --> 04:07:04.110
in the middle of the night, the kiln fell.

04:07:04.490 --> 04:07:06.270
For the third time, we had failed.

04:07:07.510 --> 04:07:13.650
The failure of this last kiln left me without a single dollar with which to make another experiment.

04:07:14.710 --> 04:07:18.770
Most of the teachers advised the abandoning of the effort to make bricks.

04:07:19.630 --> 04:07:26.130
In the midst of my troubles, I thought of a watch, which had come into my possession years before.

04:07:27.070 --> 04:07:33.610
I took the watch to the city of Montgomery, which was not far distant, and placed it in a pawn shop.

04:07:34.470 --> 04:07:43.450
I secured cash upon it to the amount of fifteen dollars, with which to renew the brick-making experiment.

04:07:43.450 --> 04:07:51.890
I returned to Tuskegee, and with the help of the fifteen dollars, rallied our rather demoralized and discouraged forces,

04:07:52.490 --> 04:07:54.730
and began a fourth attempt to make bricks.

04:07:55.630 --> 04:07:58.610
This time, I am glad to say, we were successful.

04:07:59.290 --> 04:08:05.710
Before I got hold of any money, the time limit on my watch had expired, and I have never seen it since.

04:08:06.190 --> 04:08:08.770
But I have never regretted the loss of it.

04:08:09.650 --> 04:08:16.810
Brick-making has now become such an important industry at the school that last season our students manufactured

04:08:16.810 --> 04:08:23.310
twelve hundred thousand of first-class bricks of a quality stable to be sold in any market.

04:08:24.030 --> 04:08:28.410
Aside from this, scores of young men have mastered the brick-making trade,

04:08:29.070 --> 04:08:32.150
both the making of bricks by hand and by machinery,

04:08:32.890 --> 04:08:36.910
and are now engaged in this industry in many parts of the South.

04:08:36.910 --> 04:08:43.970
The making of these bricks taught me an important lesson in regard to the relations of the two races in the South.

04:08:44.630 --> 04:08:49.910
Many white people who had had no contact with the school, and perhaps no sympathy with it,

04:08:50.290 --> 04:08:54.650
came to us to buy bricks, because they found out that ours were good bricks.

04:08:55.170 --> 04:08:59.270
They discovered that we were supplying a real want in the community.

04:08:59.910 --> 04:09:04.270
The making of these bricks caused many of the white residents of the neighborhood

04:09:04.270 --> 04:09:09.670
to begin to feel that the education of the Negro was not making him worthless,

04:09:10.110 --> 04:09:16.150
but that in educating our students we were adding something to the wealth and comfort of the community.

04:09:17.010 --> 04:09:22.410
As the people of the neighborhood came to us to buy bricks, we got acquainted with them.

04:09:22.570 --> 04:09:24.950
They traded with us, and we with them.

04:09:25.670 --> 04:09:28.770
Our business interests became intermingled.

04:09:29.190 --> 04:09:33.530
We had something which they wanted. They had something which we wanted.

04:09:34.350 --> 04:09:39.430
This, in a large measure, helped to lay the foundation for the pleasant relations

04:09:39.430 --> 04:09:44.570
that have continued to exist between us and the white people in that section,

04:09:45.230 --> 04:09:47.750
and which now extend throughout the South.

04:09:48.950 --> 04:09:52.330
Wherever one of our brickmakers has gone in the South,

04:09:52.610 --> 04:09:58.410
we find that he has something to contribute to the well-being of the community into which he has gone.

04:09:59.170 --> 04:10:04.090
Something that has made the community feel that, in a degree, it is indebted to him,

04:10:04.410 --> 04:10:08.130
and perhaps, to a certain extent, dependent upon him.

04:10:08.650 --> 04:10:13.250
In this way, pleasant relations between the races have been stimulated.

04:10:14.350 --> 04:10:18.210
My experience is that there is something in human nature

04:10:18.210 --> 04:10:22.890
which always makes an individual recognize and reward merit,

04:10:23.450 --> 04:10:26.590
no matter under what color of skin merit is found.

04:10:27.210 --> 04:10:31.130
I have found, too, that it is the visible, the tangible,

04:10:31.430 --> 04:10:35.290
that goes a long ways in softening prejudices.

04:10:35.890 --> 04:10:40.150
The actual site of a first-class house that a Negro has built

04:10:40.150 --> 04:10:45.070
is ten times more potent than pages of discussion about a house

04:10:45.070 --> 04:10:48.010
that he ought to build, or perhaps could build.

04:10:49.270 --> 04:10:53.750
The same principle of industrial education has been carried out

04:10:53.750 --> 04:10:57.670
in the building of our own wagons, carts, and buggies from the first.

04:10:58.650 --> 04:11:03.970
We now own and use on our farm and about the school dozens of these vehicles,

04:11:04.530 --> 04:11:08.290
and every one of them has been built by the hands of the students.

04:11:09.270 --> 04:11:13.150
Aside from this, we help supply the local market with these vehicles.

04:11:14.030 --> 04:11:18.510
The supplying of them to the people in the community has had the same effect

04:11:18.510 --> 04:11:23.330
as the supplying of bricks, and the man who learns at Tuskegee

04:11:23.330 --> 04:11:28.030
to build and repair wagons and carts is regarded as a benefactor

04:11:28.030 --> 04:11:31.050
by both races and the community where he goes.

04:11:31.970 --> 04:11:35.430
The people with whom he lives and works are going to think twice

04:11:35.430 --> 04:11:37.490
before they part with such a man.

04:11:38.930 --> 04:11:42.870
The individual who can do something that the world wants done

04:11:42.870 --> 04:11:46.850
will, in the end, make his way regardless of race.

04:11:46.850 --> 04:11:52.270
One man may go into a community prepared to supply the people there

04:11:52.270 --> 04:11:55.130
with an analysis of Greek sentences.

04:11:55.850 --> 04:11:58.930
The community may not at the time be prepared for

04:11:58.930 --> 04:12:01.230
or feel the need of Greek analysis,

04:12:01.990 --> 04:12:07.330
but it may feel its need of bricks and houses and wagons.

04:12:07.710 --> 04:12:10.470
If the man can supply the need for those,

04:12:10.890 --> 04:12:14.510
then it will lead eventually to a demand for the first product,

04:12:14.510 --> 04:12:18.550
and with the demand will come the ability to appreciate it

04:12:18.550 --> 04:12:19.950
and to profit by it.

04:12:20.970 --> 04:12:25.570
About the time that we succeeded in burning our first kiln of bricks,

04:12:26.090 --> 04:12:28.870
we began facing, in an emphasized form,

04:12:29.270 --> 04:12:32.630
the objection of the students to being taught to work.

04:12:33.450 --> 04:12:37.090
By this time, it had gotten to be pretty well advertised

04:12:37.090 --> 04:12:40.890
throughout the state that every student who came to Tuskegee,

04:12:40.890 --> 04:12:44.770
no matter what his financial ability might be,

04:12:45.070 --> 04:12:46.450
must learn some industry.

04:12:46.950 --> 04:12:49.870
Quite a number of letters came from parents protesting

04:12:49.870 --> 04:12:53.510
against their children engaging in labor while they were in school.

04:12:54.270 --> 04:12:57.490
Other parents came to the school to protest in person.

04:12:58.350 --> 04:13:02.090
Most of the new students brought a written or verbal request

04:13:02.090 --> 04:13:05.730
from their parents to the effect that they wanted their children

04:13:05.730 --> 04:13:07.110
taught nothing but books.

04:13:07.110 --> 04:13:10.230
The more books, the larger they were,

04:13:10.510 --> 04:13:12.930
and the longer the title spread among them,

04:13:13.350 --> 04:13:16.850
the better pleased the students and their parents seemed to be.

04:13:18.270 --> 04:13:20.430
I gave little heed to these protests,

04:13:21.170 --> 04:13:25.710
except that I lost no opportunity to go into as many parts of the state

04:13:25.710 --> 04:13:29.550
as I could for the purpose of speaking to the parents

04:13:29.550 --> 04:13:33.910
and showing them the value of industrial education.

04:13:34.770 --> 04:13:39.250
Besides, I talked to the students constantly on the subject.

04:13:40.610 --> 04:13:44.090
Notwithstanding the unpopularity of industrial work,

04:13:44.550 --> 04:13:48.250
the school continued to increase in numbers to such an extent

04:13:48.250 --> 04:13:52.250
that by the middle of the second year there was an attendance

04:13:52.250 --> 04:13:58.150
of about 150 representing almost all parts of the state of Alabama

04:13:58.150 --> 04:14:00.770
and including a few from other states.

04:14:01.890 --> 04:14:07.670
In the summer of 1882, Ms. Davidson and I both went north

04:14:07.670 --> 04:14:10.830
and engaged in the work of raising funds

04:14:10.830 --> 04:14:13.250
for the completion of our new building.

04:14:14.330 --> 04:14:16.590
On my way north, I stopped in New York

04:14:16.590 --> 04:14:19.050
to try to get a letter of recommendation

04:14:19.050 --> 04:14:21.910
from an officer of a missionary organization

04:14:22.390 --> 04:14:27.150
who had become somewhat acquainted with me a few years previous.

04:14:27.710 --> 04:14:30.710
This man not only refused to give me the letter

04:14:30.710 --> 04:14:34.650
but advised me most earnestly to go back home at once

04:14:34.650 --> 04:14:37.530
and not make any attempt to get money,

04:14:37.590 --> 04:14:40.430
for he was quite sure that I would never get more

04:14:40.430 --> 04:14:42.750
than enough to pay my traveling expenses.

04:14:43.730 --> 04:14:47.570
I thanked him for his advice and proceeded on with my journey.

04:14:48.930 --> 04:14:52.650
The first place I went to in the north was Northampton, Massachusetts,

04:14:53.210 --> 04:14:55.470
where I spent nearly a half day

04:14:55.470 --> 04:14:58.370
in looking for a colored family with whom I could board,

04:14:59.150 --> 04:15:02.070
never dreaming that any hotel would admit me.

04:15:02.430 --> 04:15:06.350
I was greatly surprised when I found that I would have no trouble

04:15:06.350 --> 04:15:08.810
in becoming accommodated at a hotel.

04:15:10.150 --> 04:15:13.330
We were successful in getting money enough

04:15:13.330 --> 04:15:16.190
so that on Thanksgiving Day of that year

04:15:16.190 --> 04:15:20.730
we held our first service in the chapel of Porter Hall,

04:15:21.190 --> 04:15:23.070
although the building was not completed.

04:15:23.810 --> 04:15:27.950
In looking about for someone to preach the Thanksgiving sermon,

04:15:28.570 --> 04:15:33.770
I found one of the rarest men that it has ever been my privilege to know.

04:15:35.070 --> 04:15:38.010
This was the Reverend Robert C. Bedford,

04:15:38.610 --> 04:15:42.050
a white man from Wisconsin who was then pastor

04:15:42.050 --> 04:15:46.150
of a little colored congregational church in Montgomery, Alabama.

04:15:47.010 --> 04:15:51.050
Before going to Montgomery to look for someone to preach this sermon,

04:15:51.050 --> 04:15:53.290
I had never heard of Mr. Bedford.

04:15:53.650 --> 04:15:55.390
He had never heard of me.

04:15:56.050 --> 04:15:58.790
He gladly consented to come to Tuskegee

04:15:58.790 --> 04:16:00.670
and hold the Thanksgiving service.

04:16:01.550 --> 04:16:03.630
It was the first service of the kind

04:16:03.630 --> 04:16:06.530
that the colored people there had ever observed

04:16:07.130 --> 04:16:11.230
and what a deep interest they manifested in it.

04:16:12.050 --> 04:16:15.370
The sight of the new building made it a day of Thanksgiving

04:16:15.370 --> 04:16:16.990
for them never to be forgotten.

04:16:17.970 --> 04:16:21.970
Mr. Bedford consented to become one of the trustees of the school

04:16:21.970 --> 04:16:25.210
and in that capacity and as a worker for it,

04:16:25.570 --> 04:16:28.280
he has been connected with it for 18 years.

04:16:29.070 --> 04:16:31.530
During this time, he has borne the school

04:16:31.530 --> 04:16:33.690
upon his heart night and day

04:16:33.690 --> 04:16:37.950
and is never so happy as when he is performing some service

04:16:37.950 --> 04:16:40.410
no matter how humble for it.

04:16:41.230 --> 04:16:44.230
He completely obliterates himself in everything

04:16:44.230 --> 04:16:47.290
and looks only for permission to serve

04:16:47.290 --> 04:16:49.790
where service is most disagreeable

04:16:49.790 --> 04:16:52.130
and where others would not be attracted.

04:16:52.830 --> 04:16:54.710
In all my relations with him,

04:16:55.090 --> 04:16:56.770
he has seemed to me to approach

04:16:56.770 --> 04:16:59.090
as nearly to the spirit of the master

04:16:59.090 --> 04:17:01.730
as almost any man I have ever met.

04:17:03.030 --> 04:17:06.250
A little later, there came into the service of the school

04:17:06.250 --> 04:17:10.710
another man, quite young at the time and fresh from Hampton,

04:17:10.710 --> 04:17:12.850
without whose service the school

04:17:12.850 --> 04:17:15.250
never would have become what it is.

04:17:16.010 --> 04:17:17.990
This was Mr. Warren Logan,

04:17:18.850 --> 04:17:21.650
who now for 17 years has been the treasurer

04:17:21.650 --> 04:17:24.630
of the institute and the acting principal

04:17:24.630 --> 04:17:25.890
during my absence.

04:17:26.590 --> 04:17:29.950
He has always shown a degree of unselfishness

04:17:29.950 --> 04:17:32.290
and an amount of business tact

04:17:32.290 --> 04:17:34.210
coupled with a clear judgment

04:17:34.570 --> 04:17:37.090
that has kept the school in good condition

04:17:37.090 --> 04:17:40.230
no matter how long I have been absent from it.

04:17:40.970 --> 04:17:43.150
During all the financial stress

04:17:43.150 --> 04:17:45.110
through which the school has passed,

04:17:45.750 --> 04:17:49.110
his patience and faith in our ultimate success

04:17:49.110 --> 04:17:50.230
have not left him.

04:17:51.770 --> 04:17:53.470
As soon as our first building

04:17:53.470 --> 04:17:54.950
was near enough to completion

04:17:54.950 --> 04:17:58.090
so that we could occupy a portion of it

04:17:58.090 --> 04:18:00.850
which was near the middle of the second year of the school,

04:18:01.610 --> 04:18:03.270
we opened the boarding department.

04:18:03.910 --> 04:18:06.730
Students had become coming from quite a distance

04:18:06.730 --> 04:18:08.710
and in such increasing numbers

04:18:08.710 --> 04:18:10.350
that we felt more and more

04:18:10.350 --> 04:18:12.790
that we were merely skimming over the surface

04:18:12.790 --> 04:18:14.750
and that we were not getting hold

04:18:14.750 --> 04:18:16.390
of the students in their home life.

04:18:17.730 --> 04:18:19.710
We had nothing but the students

04:18:19.710 --> 04:18:21.750
and their appetites with which

04:18:21.750 --> 04:18:23.350
to begin a boarding department.

04:18:24.210 --> 04:18:25.850
No provision had been made

04:18:25.850 --> 04:18:28.530
in the new building for a kitchen and dining room,

04:18:28.530 --> 04:18:31.190
but we discovered that by digging out

04:18:31.190 --> 04:18:33.390
a large amount of earth from under the building,

04:18:33.390 --> 04:18:36.810
we could make a partially lighted basement room

04:18:36.810 --> 04:18:39.830
that could be used for a kitchen and dining room.

04:18:40.410 --> 04:18:42.130
Again, I called on the students

04:18:42.130 --> 04:18:43.350
to volunteer for work,

04:18:43.550 --> 04:18:46.190
this time to assist in digging out the basement.

04:18:47.090 --> 04:18:48.130
This they did

04:18:48.130 --> 04:18:49.870
and in a few weeks,

04:18:50.750 --> 04:18:53.470
we had a place to cook and eat in

04:18:53.470 --> 04:18:55.950
although it was very rough and uncomfortable.

04:18:56.950 --> 04:18:58.570
Anyone seeing the place now

04:18:58.570 --> 04:19:00.890
would never believe that it was once used

04:19:00.890 --> 04:19:01.950
for a dining room.

04:19:01.950 --> 04:19:05.070
The most serious problem though

04:19:05.070 --> 04:19:06.890
was to get the boarding department

04:19:06.890 --> 04:19:08.410
started off in running order

04:19:08.410 --> 04:19:11.430
with nothing to do within the way of furniture

04:19:11.430 --> 04:19:13.790
and with no money with which to buy anything.

04:19:14.790 --> 04:19:16.110
The merchants in the town

04:19:16.110 --> 04:19:18.750
would let us have what food we wanted on credit.

04:19:19.450 --> 04:19:21.170
In fact, in those earlier years

04:19:21.170 --> 04:19:22.910
I was constantly embarrassed

04:19:22.910 --> 04:19:25.610
because people seemed to have more faith in me

04:19:25.610 --> 04:19:26.810
than I had in myself.

04:19:27.250 --> 04:19:29.290
It was pretty hard to cook however

04:19:29.290 --> 04:19:30.430
without stoves

04:19:30.430 --> 04:19:32.750
and awkward to eat without dishes.

04:19:33.630 --> 04:19:36.010
At first, the cooking was done out of doors

04:19:36.010 --> 04:19:38.310
in the old fashioned primitive style

04:19:38.310 --> 04:19:41.150
in pots and skillets placed over a fire.

04:19:42.170 --> 04:19:43.790
Some of the carpenter's benches

04:19:43.790 --> 04:19:46.290
that had been used in the construction of the building

04:19:46.290 --> 04:19:47.770
were utilized for tables.

04:19:48.610 --> 04:19:49.530
As for dishes,

04:19:50.050 --> 04:19:52.590
there were too few to make it worthwhile

04:19:52.590 --> 04:19:55.050
to spend time in describing them.

04:19:56.150 --> 04:19:58.630
No one connected with the boarding department

04:19:58.630 --> 04:20:00.230
seemed to have any idea

04:20:00.230 --> 04:20:02.070
that meals must be served

04:20:02.070 --> 04:20:04.170
at certain fixed and regular hours

04:20:04.430 --> 04:20:06.530
and this was a source of great worry.

04:20:07.430 --> 04:20:08.990
Everything was so out of joint

04:20:08.990 --> 04:20:10.610
and so inconvenient that

04:20:10.610 --> 04:20:12.510
I feel safe in saying

04:20:12.510 --> 04:20:14.410
that for the first two weeks

04:20:14.410 --> 04:20:16.890
something was wrong at every meal.

04:20:17.390 --> 04:20:18.990
Either the meat was not done

04:20:18.990 --> 04:20:20.350
or had been burnt

04:20:20.350 --> 04:20:23.010
or the salt had been left out of the bread

04:20:23.010 --> 04:20:25.170
or the tea had been forgotten.

04:20:26.370 --> 04:20:27.450
Early one morning

04:20:27.450 --> 04:20:30.150
I was standing near the dining room door

04:20:30.150 --> 04:20:32.790
listening to the complaints of the students.

04:20:33.430 --> 04:20:34.810
The complaints that morning

04:20:34.810 --> 04:20:37.270
were especially emphatic and numerous

04:20:37.830 --> 04:20:40.350
because the whole breakfast had been a failure.

04:20:41.050 --> 04:20:42.130
One of the girls

04:20:42.130 --> 04:20:44.790
who had failed to get any breakfast

04:20:44.790 --> 04:20:46.950
came out and went to the well

04:20:46.950 --> 04:20:48.450
to draw some water to drink

04:20:48.450 --> 04:20:50.830
and to take the place of breakfast

04:20:50.830 --> 04:20:52.710
which she had not been able to get.

04:20:53.610 --> 04:20:54.930
When she reached the well

04:20:54.930 --> 04:20:56.810
she found that the rope was broken

04:20:56.810 --> 04:20:58.970
and that she could get no water.

04:20:59.750 --> 04:21:01.090
She turned from the well

04:21:01.090 --> 04:21:03.690
and said in the most discouraged tone

04:21:03.690 --> 04:21:05.550
not knowing that I was there

04:21:05.550 --> 04:21:06.710
where I could hear her

04:21:06.710 --> 04:21:09.110
we can't even get water

04:21:09.110 --> 04:21:10.230
to drink at this school.

04:21:10.910 --> 04:21:13.090
I think no one remark ever came

04:21:13.090 --> 04:21:14.990
so near to discouraging me

04:21:14.990 --> 04:21:15.830
as that one.

04:21:16.950 --> 04:21:18.950
At another time when Mr. Bedford

04:21:18.950 --> 04:21:20.890
whom I have already spoken of

04:21:20.890 --> 04:21:22.070
as one of our trustees

04:21:22.070 --> 04:21:24.770
and a devoted friend of the institution

04:21:24.770 --> 04:21:26.350
was visiting the school.

04:21:27.290 --> 04:21:28.610
He was given a bedroom

04:21:28.610 --> 04:21:30.750
immediately over the dining room.

04:21:31.190 --> 04:21:32.850
Early in the morning he was awakened

04:21:32.850 --> 04:21:35.030
by a rather animated discussion

04:21:35.030 --> 04:21:37.210
between two boys in the dining room below.

04:21:38.010 --> 04:21:39.690
The discussion was over the question

04:21:39.690 --> 04:21:41.390
as to whose turn it was

04:21:41.390 --> 04:21:43.430
to use the coffee cup that morning.

04:21:44.670 --> 04:21:46.010
One boy won the case

04:21:46.010 --> 04:21:47.210
by proving that

04:21:47.210 --> 04:21:48.110
for three mornings

04:21:48.110 --> 04:21:50.150
he had not had an opportunity

04:21:50.150 --> 04:21:51.890
to use the cup at all.

04:21:51.890 --> 04:21:53.750
But gradually

04:21:53.750 --> 04:21:55.790
with patience and hard work

04:21:55.790 --> 04:21:57.970
we brought order out of chaos

04:21:57.970 --> 04:22:00.030
just as will be true

04:22:00.030 --> 04:22:02.150
of any problem if we stick to it

04:22:02.150 --> 04:22:03.570
with patience and wisdom

04:22:03.570 --> 04:22:04.850
and earnest effort.

04:22:05.850 --> 04:22:07.950
As I look back now over that

04:22:07.950 --> 04:22:09.070
part of our struggle

04:22:09.070 --> 04:22:12.070
I am glad to see that we had it.

04:22:12.330 --> 04:22:13.930
I am glad that we endured

04:22:13.930 --> 04:22:16.310
all those discomforts and inconveniences.

04:22:16.650 --> 04:22:17.890
I am glad

04:22:17.890 --> 04:22:19.930
that our students had to dig out the place

04:22:19.930 --> 04:22:21.490
for their kitchen and dining room.

04:22:22.190 --> 04:22:24.690
I am glad that our first boarding place

04:22:24.690 --> 04:22:26.070
was in the dismal

04:22:26.070 --> 04:22:28.030
ill-lighted and damp basement.

04:22:28.930 --> 04:22:30.110
Had we started in a

04:22:30.110 --> 04:22:32.150
fine, attractive, convenient room

04:22:32.150 --> 04:22:34.310
I fear we would have lost

04:22:34.310 --> 04:22:36.390
our heads and become stuck up.

04:22:36.810 --> 04:22:37.930
It means a great deal

04:22:37.930 --> 04:22:40.290
I think to start off on a foundation

04:22:40.290 --> 04:22:42.490
which one has made for oneself.

04:22:44.150 --> 04:22:45.950
When our old students return

04:22:45.950 --> 04:22:48.410
to Tuskegee now, as they often do

04:22:48.410 --> 04:22:51.050
and go into our large, beautiful

04:22:51.050 --> 04:22:52.970
well-ventilated and well-lighted

04:22:52.970 --> 04:22:53.810
dining room

04:22:53.810 --> 04:22:56.450
and see tempting, well-cooked food

04:22:56.450 --> 04:22:58.750
largely grown by the students themselves

04:22:59.370 --> 04:23:00.850
and see tables

04:23:00.850 --> 04:23:02.870
neat tablecloths and napkins

04:23:02.870 --> 04:23:05.070
and faces of flowers upon the tables

04:23:05.070 --> 04:23:06.870
and hear singing birds

04:23:06.870 --> 04:23:08.850
and note that each meal is served

04:23:08.850 --> 04:23:10.290
exactly upon the minute

04:23:10.290 --> 04:23:11.330
with no disorder

04:23:11.330 --> 04:23:14.710
and with almost no complaint coming from the hundreds

04:23:14.710 --> 04:23:16.750
that now fill our dining room.

04:23:16.750 --> 04:23:19.430
They too often say to me

04:23:19.430 --> 04:23:20.510
that they are glad

04:23:20.510 --> 04:23:22.210
that we started as we did

04:23:22.210 --> 04:23:24.890
and built ourselves up year by year

04:23:24.890 --> 04:23:27.090
by a slow and natural process

04:23:27.390 --> 04:23:28.390
of growth.

04:23:56.310 --> 04:23:59.330
MAKING THEIR BEDS BEFORE THEY COULD LY ON THEM.

04:23:59.890 --> 04:24:04.510
A little later, in the history of the school, we had a visit from General J. F. B. Marshall,

04:24:05.010 --> 04:24:10.030
the treasurer of the Hampton Institute, who had had faith enough to lend us the first

04:24:10.030 --> 04:24:13.610
$250 with which to make a payment down on the farm.

04:24:14.210 --> 04:24:17.810
He remained with us a week, and made a careful inspection of everything.

04:24:18.390 --> 04:24:22.470
He seemed well pleased with our progress, and wrote back interesting and encouraging

04:24:22.470 --> 04:24:23.590
reports to Hampton.

04:24:24.170 --> 04:24:29.050
A little later, Miss Mary F. Mackey, the teacher who had given me the sweeping examination

04:24:29.050 --> 04:24:34.330
when I entered Hampton, came to see us, and still later General Armstrong himself came.

04:24:35.190 --> 04:24:40.070
At the time of the visits of these Hampton friends, the number of teachers at Tuskegee

04:24:40.070 --> 04:24:44.650
had increased considerably, and most of the new teachers were graduates of the Hampton

04:24:44.650 --> 04:24:45.250
Institute.

04:24:45.710 --> 04:24:50.250
We gave our Hampton friends, especially General Armstrong, a cordial welcome.

04:24:50.650 --> 04:24:54.430
They were all surprised and pleased at the rapid progress that the school had made within

04:24:54.430 --> 04:24:55.430
so short a time.

04:24:55.890 --> 04:24:59.710
The colored people from miles around came to the school to get a look at General Armstrong,

04:25:00.250 --> 04:25:01.770
about whom they had heard so much.

04:25:02.370 --> 04:25:06.490
The General was not only welcomed by the members of my own race, but by the Southern white

04:25:06.490 --> 04:25:07.430
people as well.

04:25:08.070 --> 04:25:12.310
This first visit, which General Armstrong made to Tuskegee, gave me an opportunity to

04:25:12.310 --> 04:25:15.870
get an insight into his character such as I had not before had.

04:25:16.430 --> 04:25:19.030
I referred to his interest in the Southern white people.

04:25:19.490 --> 04:25:25.030
Before this, I had had the thought that General Armstrong, having fought the Southern white

04:25:25.030 --> 04:25:29.570
men, rather cherished a feeling of bitterness toward the white South, and was interested

04:25:29.570 --> 04:25:31.650
in helping only the colored men there.

04:25:32.270 --> 04:25:36.490
But this visit convinced me that I did not know the greatness and the generosity of the

04:25:36.490 --> 04:25:36.730
man.

04:25:37.190 --> 04:25:41.650
I soon learned by his visits to the Southern white people, and from his conversations with

04:25:41.650 --> 04:25:46.610
them, that he was as anxious about the prosperity and the happiness of the white race as the

04:25:46.610 --> 04:25:46.950
black.

04:25:47.350 --> 04:25:51.710
He cherished no bitterness against the South, and was happy when an opportunity offered

04:25:51.710 --> 04:25:53.190
for manifesting his sympathy.

04:25:53.710 --> 04:25:58.950
In all my acquaintance with General Armstrong, I never heard him speak, in public or in private,

04:25:59.350 --> 04:26:02.030
a single bitter word against the white men in the South.

04:26:02.470 --> 04:26:07.510
From his example in this respect, I learned the lesson that great men cultivate love,

04:26:07.850 --> 04:26:11.150
and that only little men cherish a spirit of hatred.

04:26:11.510 --> 04:26:16.070
I learned that assistance given to the weak makes the one who gives it strong, and that

04:26:16.070 --> 04:26:18.830
oppression of the unfortunate makes one weak.

04:26:19.490 --> 04:26:24.350
It is now long ago that I learned this lesson from General Armstrong, and resolved that

04:26:24.350 --> 04:26:29.510
I would permit no man, no matter what his color might be, to narrow and degrade my soul

04:26:29.510 --> 04:26:30.850
by making me hate him.

04:26:31.350 --> 04:26:36.590
With God's help, I believe that I have completely rid myself of any ill feeling toward the Southern

04:26:36.590 --> 04:26:40.690
white men, for any wrong that he may have inflicted upon my race.

04:26:41.370 --> 04:26:46.090
I am made to feel just as happy now when I am rendering service to Southern white men

04:26:46.090 --> 04:26:49.290
as when the service is rendered to a member of my own race.

04:26:49.890 --> 04:26:55.470
I pity from the bottom of my heart any individual who is so unfortunate as to get into the habit

04:26:55.470 --> 04:26:56.870
of holding race prejudice.

04:26:57.670 --> 04:27:02.470
The more I consider the subject, the more strongly I am convinced that the most harmful

04:27:02.470 --> 04:27:06.950
effect of the practice to which the people in certain sections of the South have felt

04:27:06.950 --> 04:27:11.650
themselves compelled to resort in order to get rid of the force of the Negro's ballot

04:27:11.650 --> 04:27:16.410
is not wholly the wrong done to the Negro, but in the permanent injury to the morals

04:27:16.410 --> 04:27:17.290
of the white man.

04:27:17.830 --> 04:27:22.690
The wrong to the Negro is temporary, but to the morals of the white man, the injury is

04:27:22.690 --> 04:27:23.090
permanent.

04:27:23.950 --> 04:27:28.610
I have noted time and time again that when an individual perjures himself in order to

04:27:28.610 --> 04:27:33.690
break the force of the black man's ballot, he soon learns to practice dishonesty in other

04:27:33.690 --> 04:27:38.670
relations of life, not only where the Negro is concerned, but equally so where a white

04:27:38.670 --> 04:27:39.590
man is concerned.

04:27:40.030 --> 04:27:44.790
The white man who begins by cheating a Negro usually ends by cheating a white man.

04:27:45.290 --> 04:27:50.190
The white man who begins to break the law by lynching a Negro soon yields to the temptation

04:27:50.190 --> 04:27:51.330
to lynch a white man.

04:27:52.090 --> 04:27:56.890
All this, it seems to me, makes it important that the whole nation lend a hand in trying

04:27:56.890 --> 04:27:59.130
to lift the burden of ignorance from the South.

04:28:00.230 --> 04:28:03.990
Another thing that is becoming more apparent each year in the development of education

04:28:03.990 --> 04:28:09.510
in the South is the influence of General Armstrong's idea of education, and this

04:28:09.510 --> 04:28:12.610
not upon the blacks alone, but upon the whites also.

04:28:13.110 --> 04:28:17.930
At the present time, there is almost no southern state that is not putting forth efforts in

04:28:17.930 --> 04:28:23.410
the direction of securing industrial education for its white boys and girls, and in most

04:28:23.410 --> 04:28:28.090
cases it is easy to trace the history of these efforts back to General Armstrong.

04:28:28.970 --> 04:28:33.950
Soon after the opening of our humble boarding department, students began coming to us in

04:28:33.950 --> 04:28:34.950
still larger numbers.

04:28:35.550 --> 04:28:40.110
For weeks we not only had to contend with the difficulty of providing board with no

04:28:40.110 --> 04:28:43.770
money, but also with that of providing sleeping accommodations.

04:28:44.490 --> 04:28:47.550
For this purpose we rented a number of cabins near the school.

04:28:48.090 --> 04:28:52.530
These cabins were in a dilapidated condition, and during the winter months the students

04:28:52.530 --> 04:28:55.470
who occupied them necessarily suffered from the cold.

04:28:56.210 --> 04:29:00.710
We charged the students $8 a month, all they were able to pay, for their board.

04:29:01.230 --> 04:29:04.870
This included besides board, room, fuel, and washing.

04:29:05.150 --> 04:29:09.630
We also gave the students credit on their board bills for all the work which they did

04:29:09.630 --> 04:29:13.070
for the school, which was of any value to the institution.

04:29:13.690 --> 04:29:19.210
The cost of tuition, which was $50 a year for each student, we had to secure then, as

04:29:19.210 --> 04:29:20.630
now, wherever we could.

04:29:21.310 --> 04:29:26.010
This small charge in cash gave us no capital with which to start a boarding department.

04:29:26.490 --> 04:29:29.550
The weather during the second winter of our work was very cold.

04:29:30.070 --> 04:29:33.450
We were not able to provide enough bed clothes to keep the students warm.

04:29:33.970 --> 04:29:39.550
In fact, for some time we were not able to provide, except in a few cases, bedsteads

04:29:39.550 --> 04:29:40.910
and mattresses of any kind.

04:29:41.450 --> 04:29:46.030
During the coldest nights I was so troubled about the discomfort of the students that

04:29:46.030 --> 04:29:47.450
I could not sleep myself.

04:29:47.930 --> 04:29:52.430
I recall that on several occasions I went in the middle of the night to the shanties

04:29:52.430 --> 04:29:56.290
occupied by the young men for the purpose of confronting them.

04:29:57.190 --> 04:30:01.490
Often I found some of them sitting huddled around a fire, with the one blanket which

04:30:01.490 --> 04:30:06.290
we had been able to provide wrapped around them, trying in this way to keep warm.

04:30:06.770 --> 04:30:10.490
During the whole night some of them did not attempt to lie down.

04:30:10.770 --> 04:30:16.090
One morning, when the night previous had been unusually cold, I asked those of the students

04:30:16.090 --> 04:30:20.290
in the chapel who thought that they had been frostbitten during the night to raise their

04:30:20.290 --> 04:30:20.730
hands.

04:30:21.350 --> 04:30:22.650
Three hands went up.

04:30:23.190 --> 04:30:27.690
Notwithstanding these experiences, there was almost no complaining on the part of the students.

04:30:28.210 --> 04:30:31.210
They knew that we were doing the best that we could for them.

04:30:31.790 --> 04:30:36.450
They were happy in the privilege of being permitted to enjoy any kind of opportunity

04:30:36.450 --> 04:30:39.750
that would enable them to improve their condition.

04:30:40.170 --> 04:30:44.390
They were constantly asking what they might do to lighten the burdens of the teachers.

04:30:45.110 --> 04:30:50.430
I have heard it stated more than once, both in the North and in the South, that colored

04:30:50.430 --> 04:30:55.030
people would not obey and respect each other when one member of the race is placed in a

04:30:55.030 --> 04:30:56.830
position of authority over others.

04:30:57.750 --> 04:31:02.410
In regard to this general belief in these statements, I can say that during the nineteen

04:31:02.410 --> 04:31:08.750
years of my experience at Tuskegee, I never, either by word or act, have been treated with

04:31:08.750 --> 04:31:12.530
disrespect by any student or officer connected with the institution.

04:31:13.210 --> 04:31:17.950
On the other hand, I am constantly embarrassed by the many acts of thoughtful kindness.

04:31:18.530 --> 04:31:23.570
The students do not seem to want to see me carry a large book or a satchel or any kind

04:31:23.570 --> 04:31:24.730
of burden through the grounds.

04:31:25.330 --> 04:31:29.070
In such cases more than one always offers to relieve me.

04:31:29.790 --> 04:31:34.290
I almost never go out of my office when the rain is falling that some student does not

04:31:34.290 --> 04:31:38.650
come to my side with an umbrella and asks to be allowed to hold it over me.

04:31:39.170 --> 04:31:44.250
While writing upon this subject, it is a pleasure for me to add that in all my contact with

04:31:44.250 --> 04:31:48.610
the white people of the South, I have never received a single personal insult.

04:31:49.170 --> 04:31:54.370
The white people in and near Tuskegee, to an especial degree, seem to count it as a

04:31:54.370 --> 04:31:58.970
privilege to show me all the respect within their power, and often go out of their way

04:31:58.970 --> 04:31:59.770
to do this.

04:32:00.230 --> 04:32:04.430
Not very long ago, I was making a journey between Dallas, Texas and Houston.

04:32:05.070 --> 04:32:09.090
In some way it became known in advance that I was on the train.

04:32:10.190 --> 04:32:14.730
At nearly every station at which the train stopped, numbers of white people, including

04:32:14.730 --> 04:32:20.230
in most cases of the officials of the town, came aboard and introduced themselves and

04:32:20.230 --> 04:32:23.450
thanked me heartily for the work that I was trying to do for the South.

04:32:24.210 --> 04:32:29.310
On another occasion, when I was making a trip from Augusta, Georgia to Atlanta, being rather

04:32:29.310 --> 04:32:32.810
tired from much travel, I rode in a Pullman Sleeper.

04:32:32.810 --> 04:32:37.730
When I went into the car, I found there two ladies from Boston whom I knew well.

04:32:38.370 --> 04:32:43.010
These good ladies were perfectly ignorant, it seems, of the customs of the South, and

04:32:43.010 --> 04:32:47.070
in the goodness of their hearts insisted that I take a seat with them in their section.

04:32:48.190 --> 04:32:50.490
After some hesitation, I consented.

04:32:51.050 --> 04:32:55.650
I had been there but a few minutes when one of them, without my knowledge, ordered supper

04:32:55.650 --> 04:32:57.350
to be served for the three of us.

04:32:57.730 --> 04:32:59.390
This embarrassed me still further.

04:32:59.390 --> 04:33:04.030
The car was full of southern white men, most of whom had their eyes on our party.

04:33:04.710 --> 04:33:09.270
When I found that supper had been ordered, I tried to contrive some excuse that would

04:33:09.270 --> 04:33:13.570
permit me to leave the section, but the ladies insisted that I must eat with them.

04:33:13.990 --> 04:33:17.950
I finally settled back in my seat with a sigh and said to myself,

04:33:18.330 --> 04:33:19.950
I am in for it now, sure.

04:33:20.550 --> 04:33:25.210
To add further to the embarrassment of the situation, soon after the supper was placed

04:33:25.210 --> 04:33:30.010
on the table, one of the ladies remembered that she had in her satchel a special kind

04:33:30.010 --> 04:33:31.570
of tea which she wished served.

04:33:32.130 --> 04:33:37.370
And as she said she felt quite sure the porter did not know how to brew it properly, she

04:33:37.370 --> 04:33:40.770
insisted upon getting up and preparing and serving it herself.

04:33:41.330 --> 04:33:45.670
At last the meal was over and it seemed the longest one that I had ever eaten.

04:33:46.270 --> 04:33:51.390
When we were through, I decided to get myself out of the embarrassing situation and go to

04:33:51.390 --> 04:33:54.550
the smoking room where most of the men were by that time.

04:33:54.550 --> 04:33:56.410
To see how the land lay.

04:33:56.930 --> 04:34:02.090
In the meantime, however, it had become known in some way throughout the car who I was.

04:34:02.530 --> 04:34:07.550
When I went into the smoking room, I was never more surprised in my life than when each man,

04:34:07.910 --> 04:34:13.150
nearly every one of them a citizen of Georgia, came up and introduced himself to me and thanked

04:34:13.150 --> 04:34:16.350
me earnestly for the work that I was trying to do for the whole South.

04:34:16.850 --> 04:34:21.050
This was not flattery, because each one of these individuals knew that he had nothing

04:34:21.050 --> 04:34:22.730
to gain by trying to flatter me.

04:34:23.290 --> 04:34:28.810
From the first I have sought to impress the students with the idea that Tuskegee is not

04:34:28.810 --> 04:34:34.770
my institution or that of the officers, but that it is their institution and that they

04:34:34.770 --> 04:34:38.490
have as much interest in it as any of the trustees or instructors.

04:34:39.190 --> 04:34:44.010
I have further sought to have them feel that I am at the institution as their friend and

04:34:44.010 --> 04:34:46.590
advisor and not as their overseer.

04:34:47.090 --> 04:34:51.630
It has been my aim to have them speak with directness and frankness about anything that

04:34:51.630 --> 04:34:53.210
concerns the life of the school.

04:34:54.070 --> 04:35:00.150
Two or three times a year, I ask the students to write me a letter criticizing or making

04:35:00.150 --> 04:35:04.330
complaints or suggestions about anything connected with the institution.

04:35:04.930 --> 04:35:09.390
When this is not done, I have them meet me in the chapel for a heart-to-heart talk about

04:35:09.390 --> 04:35:10.610
the conduct of the school.

04:35:11.150 --> 04:35:15.570
There are no meetings with our students that I enjoy more than these, and none are more

04:35:15.570 --> 04:35:17.350
helpful to me in planning the future.

04:35:18.010 --> 04:35:23.130
These meetings, it seems to me, enable me to get at the very heart of all the concerns

04:35:23.130 --> 04:35:23.690
the school.

04:35:24.090 --> 04:35:29.430
Few things help an individual more than to place responsibility upon him and to let him

04:35:29.430 --> 04:35:30.630
know that you trust him.

04:35:31.170 --> 04:35:36.330
When I have read our labor troubles between employers and employees, I have often thought

04:35:36.330 --> 04:35:41.590
that many strikes and similar disturbances might be avoided if the employers would cultivate

04:35:41.590 --> 04:35:47.170
the habit of getting nearer to the employees, of consulting and advising them, and letting

04:35:47.170 --> 04:35:49.810
them feel that the interests of the two are the same.

04:35:50.450 --> 04:35:55.490
Every individual responds to confidence, and this is not more true of any race than of

04:35:55.490 --> 04:35:56.470
the negroes.

04:35:56.650 --> 04:36:01.510
Let them once understand that you are unselfishly interested in them, and you can lead them

04:36:01.510 --> 04:36:02.570
to any extent.

04:36:03.310 --> 04:36:08.370
It was my aim from the first at Tuskegee to not only have the buildings erected by the

04:36:08.370 --> 04:36:13.110
students themselves, but to have them make their own furniture as far as was possible.

04:36:13.430 --> 04:36:18.250
I now marvel at the patience of the students while sleeping upon the floor while waiting

04:36:18.250 --> 04:36:23.770
for some kind of bedstead to be constructed, or at their sleeping without any kind of a

04:36:23.770 --> 04:36:27.050
mattress while waiting for something that looked like a mattress to be made.

04:36:27.670 --> 04:36:32.470
In the early days we had very few students who had been used to handling carpenters'

04:36:32.550 --> 04:36:38.070
tools, and the bedsteads made by the students then were very rough and very weak.

04:36:38.670 --> 04:36:43.090
Not unfrequently when I went into the students' rooms in the morning I would find at least

04:36:43.090 --> 04:36:45.350
two bedsteads lying about on the floor.

04:36:45.470 --> 04:36:48.690
The problem of providing mattresses was a difficult one to solve.

04:36:49.070 --> 04:36:53.590
We finally mastered this, however, by getting some cheap cloth and sewing pieces of this

04:36:53.590 --> 04:36:55.410
together as to make large bags.

04:36:55.890 --> 04:37:00.790
These bags we filled with the pine straw, or as it is sometimes called pine needles,

04:37:01.330 --> 04:37:03.310
which we secured from the forest nearby.

04:37:03.770 --> 04:37:09.090
I am glad to say that the industry of mattress making has grown steadily since then and has

04:37:09.090 --> 04:37:14.330
such an extent that at the present time it is an important branch of the work which is

04:37:14.330 --> 04:37:19.570
taught systematically to a number of our girls, and that the mattresses that now come out

04:37:19.570 --> 04:37:24.030
of the mattress shop at Tuskegee are about as good as those bought in the average store.

04:37:24.610 --> 04:37:29.250
For some time after the opening of the boarding department we had no chairs in the students'

04:37:29.390 --> 04:37:31.430
bedrooms or in the dining rooms.

04:37:31.650 --> 04:37:36.810
Instead of chairs we used stools which the students constructed by nailing together three

04:37:36.810 --> 04:37:38.070
pieces of rough board.

04:37:39.210 --> 04:37:43.470
As a rule the furniture in the students' rooms during the early days of the school

04:37:43.470 --> 04:37:48.350
consisted of a bed, some stools, and sometimes a rough table made by the students.

04:37:48.870 --> 04:37:53.350
The plan of having the students make the furniture is still followed, but the number of pieces

04:37:53.350 --> 04:37:58.190
in a room has been increased and the workmanship has so improved that little fault can be found

04:37:58.190 --> 04:37:59.390
with the articles now.

04:37:59.950 --> 04:38:04.470
One thing that I have always insisted upon at Tuskegee is that everywhere there should

04:38:04.470 --> 04:38:05.910
be absolute cleanliness.

04:38:06.550 --> 04:38:11.070
Over and over again the students were reminded in those first years, and are reminded now,

04:38:11.430 --> 04:38:15.990
that people would excuse us for our poverty, for our lack of comforts and conveniences,

04:38:16.510 --> 04:38:19.070
but that they would not excuse us for dirt.

04:38:19.990 --> 04:38:24.210
Another thing that has been insisted upon at the school is the use of the toothbrush.

04:38:31.710 --> 04:38:35.790
No student is permitted to retain who does not keep and use a toothbrush.

04:38:36.450 --> 04:38:41.550
Several times in recent years students have come to us who brought with them almost no

04:38:41.550 --> 04:38:43.230
other article except a toothbrush.

04:38:43.710 --> 04:38:48.090
They had heard from the lips of other students about our insisting upon the use of this,

04:38:48.330 --> 04:38:52.390
and so, to make a good impression, they brought at least a toothbrush with them.

04:38:52.890 --> 04:38:57.750
I remember that one morning not long ago I went with the lady principal on her usual

04:38:57.750 --> 04:39:00.270
morning tour of inspection of the girls' rooms.

04:39:00.630 --> 04:39:04.670
We found one room that contained three girls who had recently arrived at the school.

04:39:05.350 --> 04:39:10.410
When I asked them if they had toothbrushes, one of the girls replied, pointing to a brush,

04:39:10.750 --> 04:39:12.510
Yes sir, this is our brush.

04:39:12.770 --> 04:39:14.270
We bought it together yesterday.

04:39:15.190 --> 04:39:17.770
It did not take them long to learn a different lesson.

04:39:18.890 --> 04:39:23.350
It has been interesting to note the effect that the use of the toothbrush has had in

04:39:23.350 --> 04:39:26.730
bringing about a higher degree of civilization among the students.

04:39:27.390 --> 04:39:33.170
With few exceptions, I have noticed that if we can get a student to the point where when

04:39:33.170 --> 04:39:38.150
the first or second toothbrush disappears, he of his own motion buys another.

04:39:38.770 --> 04:39:41.750
I have not been disappointed in the future of that individual.

04:39:42.450 --> 04:39:46.190
Absolute cleanliness of the body has been insisted upon from the first.

04:39:46.710 --> 04:39:50.350
The students have been taught to bathe as regularly as they take their meals.

04:39:50.910 --> 04:39:55.290
This lesson we began teaching before we had anything in the shape of a bathhouse.

04:39:55.290 --> 04:40:00.390
Most of the students came from plantation districts, and often we had to teach them

04:40:00.390 --> 04:40:06.290
how to sleep at night, that is, whether between the two sheets, after we got to the point

04:40:06.290 --> 04:40:09.490
where we could provide them two sheets, or under both of them.

04:40:09.990 --> 04:40:14.390
Naturally, I found it difficult to teach them to sleep between two sheets when we were able

04:40:14.390 --> 04:40:15.570
to supply but one.

04:40:15.970 --> 04:40:19.530
The importance of the use of the nightgown received the same attention.

04:40:20.230 --> 04:40:25.030
For a long time, one of the most difficult tasks was to teach the students that all the

04:40:25.030 --> 04:40:29.830
buttons were to be kept on their clothes, and that there must be no torn places or

04:40:29.830 --> 04:40:30.490
grease spots.

04:40:31.090 --> 04:40:36.090
This lesson, I am pleased to be able to say, has been so thoroughly learned and so faithfully

04:40:36.090 --> 04:40:41.270
handed down from year to year by one set of students to another, that often at the present

04:40:41.270 --> 04:40:45.830
time when the students march out of the chapel in the evening and their dress is inspected,

04:40:46.270 --> 04:40:50.030
as it is every night, not one button is found to be missing.

04:40:53.850 --> 04:40:56.510
Making their beds before they could lie on them.

04:41:25.170 --> 04:41:26.370
RAISING MONEY.

04:41:26.970 --> 04:41:31.910
When we opened our boarding department, we provided rooms in the attic of Porter Hall,

04:41:31.970 --> 04:41:34.550
our first building, for a number of girls.

04:41:35.170 --> 04:41:39.170
But the number of students of both sexes continued to increase.

04:41:39.890 --> 04:41:45.330
We could find rooms outside the school grounds for many of the young men, but the girls we

04:41:45.330 --> 04:41:47.690
did not care to expose in this way.

04:41:48.730 --> 04:41:54.050
Very soon the problem of providing more rooms for the girls, as well as a larger boarding

04:41:54.050 --> 04:41:57.050
department for all the students, grew serious.

04:41:57.650 --> 04:42:02.690
As a result, we finally decided to undertake the construction of a still larger building,

04:42:03.250 --> 04:42:08.090
a building that would contain rooms for the girls and boarding accommodations for all.

04:42:08.710 --> 04:42:13.490
After having had a preliminary sketch of the needed building made, we found that it would

04:42:13.490 --> 04:42:15.150
cost about $10,000.

04:42:15.810 --> 04:42:18.670
We had no money whatever with which to begin.

04:42:19.230 --> 04:42:22.130
Still we decided to give the needed building a name.

04:42:22.550 --> 04:42:27.590
We knew we could name it, even though we were in doubt about our ability to secure the means

04:42:27.590 --> 04:42:28.690
for its construction.

04:42:29.710 --> 04:42:35.930
We decided to call the proposed building Alabama Hall, in honor of the state in which we were

04:42:35.930 --> 04:42:36.430
laboring.

04:42:37.270 --> 04:42:42.410
Again, Miss Davidson began making efforts to enlist the interest and help of the colored

04:42:42.410 --> 04:42:45.150
and white people in and near Tuskegee.

04:42:45.670 --> 04:42:48.890
They responded willingly, in proportion to their means.

04:42:49.510 --> 04:42:54.690
The students, as in the case of our first building, Porter Hall, began digging out the

04:42:54.690 --> 04:42:57.530
dirt in order to allow the laying of the foundations.

04:42:58.210 --> 04:43:03.890
When we seemed at the end of our resources so far as securing money was concerned, something

04:43:03.890 --> 04:43:09.110
occurred which showed the greatness of General Armstrong, something which proved how far

04:43:09.110 --> 04:43:11.530
he was above the ordinary individual.

04:43:12.230 --> 04:43:17.810
When we were in the midst of great anxiety as to where and how we were to get funds for

04:43:17.810 --> 04:43:23.470
the new building, I received a telegram from General Armstrong asking me if I could spend

04:43:23.470 --> 04:43:29.950
a month traveling with him through the North and asking me if I could do so to come to

04:43:29.950 --> 04:43:30.970
Hampton at once.

04:43:31.090 --> 04:43:35.990
Of course I accepted General Armstrong's invitation and went to Hampton immediately.

04:43:36.550 --> 04:43:41.490
On arriving there I found that the General had decided to take a quartet of singers through

04:43:41.490 --> 04:43:47.110
the North and hold meetings for a month in important cities, at which meetings he and

04:43:47.110 --> 04:43:48.070
I were to speak.

04:43:48.970 --> 04:43:53.990
Imagine my surprise when the General told me, further, that these meetings were to be

04:43:53.990 --> 04:44:00.210
held not in the interests of Hampton, but in the interests of Tuskegee, and that the

04:44:00.210 --> 04:44:04.030
Hampton Institute was to be responsible for all the expenses.

04:44:04.450 --> 04:44:09.950
Although he never told me so in so many words, I found that General Armstrong took this method

04:44:09.950 --> 04:44:15.910
of introducing me to the people of the North, as well as for the sake of securing some immediate

04:44:15.910 --> 04:44:19.170
funds to be used in the erection of Alabama Hall.

04:44:19.790 --> 04:44:24.850
A weak and narrow man would have reasoned that all the money which came to Tuskegee

04:44:24.850 --> 04:44:29.270
in this way would be just so much taken from the Hampton Institute.

04:44:29.790 --> 04:44:34.510
But none of these selfish or short-sighted feelings ever entered the breast of General

04:44:34.510 --> 04:44:35.070
Armstrong.

04:44:35.650 --> 04:44:39.330
He was too big to be little, too good to be mean.

04:44:39.870 --> 04:44:44.770
He knew that the people in the North who gave money gave it for the purpose of helping the

04:44:44.770 --> 04:44:50.170
whole cause of Negro civilization, and not merely for the advancement of any one school.

04:44:51.070 --> 04:44:57.090
The General knew, too, that the way to strengthen Hampton was to make it a center of unselfish

04:44:57.090 --> 04:45:00.550
power in the working out of the whole Southern problem.

04:45:01.190 --> 04:45:06.650
In regard to the addresses which I was to make in the North, I recall just one piece

04:45:06.650 --> 04:45:08.950
of advice which the General gave me.

04:45:09.410 --> 04:45:12.930
He said, Give them an idea for every word.

04:45:13.430 --> 04:45:18.890
I think it would be hard to improve upon this advice, and it might be made to apply to all

04:45:18.890 --> 04:45:19.850
public speaking.

04:45:20.410 --> 04:45:25.050
From that time to the present I have always tried to keep his advice in mind.

04:45:25.950 --> 04:45:32.630
Meetings were held in New York, Brooklyn, Boston, Philadelphia, and other large cities,

04:45:33.010 --> 04:45:39.150
and at all of these meetings General Armstrong pleased, together with myself, for help, not

04:45:39.150 --> 04:45:41.390
for Hampton, but for Tuskegee.

04:45:42.190 --> 04:45:47.490
At these meetings, and a special effort was made to secure help for the building of Alabama

04:45:47.490 --> 04:45:52.570
Hall, as well as to introduce the school to the attention of the General public.

04:45:53.410 --> 04:45:56.770
In both these respects, the meetings proved successful.

04:45:57.450 --> 04:46:02.030
After that kindly introduction, I began going north alone to secure funds.

04:46:02.570 --> 04:46:08.270
During the last 15 years, I had been compelled to spend a large proportion of my time away

04:46:09.030 --> 04:46:13.710
in an effort to secure money to provide for the growing needs of the institution.

04:46:14.390 --> 04:46:18.750
In my efforts to get funds, I have had some experiences that may be of interest to my

04:46:18.750 --> 04:46:19.150
readers.

04:46:19.630 --> 04:46:24.350
Time and time again I have been asked, by people who are trying to secure money for

04:46:24.350 --> 04:46:30.390
philanthropic purposes, what rule or rules I followed to secure the interest and help

04:46:30.390 --> 04:46:34.030
of people who were able to contribute money to worthy objects.

04:46:34.850 --> 04:46:40.390
As far as the science of what is called begging can be reduced to rules, I would say that

04:46:40.390 --> 04:46:42.050
I have had but two rules.

04:46:42.770 --> 04:46:49.250
First, always to do my whole duty regarding making our work known to individuals and organizations.

04:46:50.410 --> 04:46:53.010
And second, not to worry about the results.

04:46:53.710 --> 04:46:56.990
This second rule has been the hardest for me to live up to.

04:46:57.510 --> 04:47:02.330
When bills are on the eve of falling due, with not a dollar in hand with which to meet

04:47:02.330 --> 04:47:07.970
it is pretty difficult to learn not to worry, although I think I am learning more and more

04:47:07.970 --> 04:47:14.250
each year that all worry simply consumes, and to no purpose, just so much physical and

04:47:14.250 --> 04:47:17.750
mental strength that might otherwise be given to effective work.

04:47:18.130 --> 04:47:24.230
After considerable experience in coming into contact with wealthy and noted men, I have

04:47:24.230 --> 04:47:28.850
observed that those who have accomplished the greatest results are those who, quote,

04:47:28.850 --> 04:47:34.970
keep under the body, end quote, are those who never grow excited or lose self-control,

04:47:35.270 --> 04:47:39.790
but are always calm, self-possessed, patient and polite.

04:47:40.390 --> 04:47:45.210
I think that President William McKinley is the best example of a man of this class that

04:47:45.210 --> 04:47:46.170
I have ever seen.

04:47:46.930 --> 04:47:53.470
In order to be successful in any kind of undertaking, I think the main thing is for one to grow

04:47:53.470 --> 04:47:56.290
to the point where he completely forgets himself.

04:47:56.810 --> 04:47:59.890
That is, to lose himself in a great cause.

04:48:00.450 --> 04:48:06.210
In proportion as one loses himself in the way, in the same degree does he get the highest

04:48:06.210 --> 04:48:07.770
happiness out of his work.

04:48:08.250 --> 04:48:13.510
My experience in getting money for Tuskegee has taught me to have no patience with those

04:48:13.510 --> 04:48:18.770
people who are always condemning the rich because they are rich and because they do

04:48:18.770 --> 04:48:20.990
not give more to objects of charity.

04:48:21.530 --> 04:48:26.950
In the first place, those who are guilty of such sweeping criticisms do not know how many

04:48:26.950 --> 04:48:32.230
people would be made poor and how much suffering would result if wealthy people were to part

04:48:32.230 --> 04:48:38.090
all at once with any large proportion of their wealth in a way to disorganize and cripple

04:48:38.090 --> 04:48:39.550
great business enterprises.

04:48:40.250 --> 04:48:45.310
Then very few persons have any idea of the large number of applications for help that

04:48:45.310 --> 04:48:47.810
rich people are constantly being flooded with.

04:48:48.240 --> 04:48:52.610
I know wealthy people who receive as much as twenty calls a day for help.

04:48:53.330 --> 04:48:58.930
More than once when I have gone into the offices of rich men, I have found half a dozen persons

04:48:58.930 --> 04:49:04.090
waiting to see them, and all come for the same purpose, that of securing money.

04:49:04.310 --> 04:49:09.930
And all these calls in person to say nothing of the applications received through the mails.

04:49:10.470 --> 04:49:16.330
Very few people have any idea of the amount of money given away by persons who never permit

04:49:16.330 --> 04:49:17.730
their names to be known.

04:49:18.330 --> 04:49:24.350
I have often heard persons condemned for not giving away money who, to my knowledge, were

04:49:24.350 --> 04:49:30.490
giving away thousands of dollars every year so quietly that the world knew nothing about it.

04:49:31.230 --> 04:49:36.550
As an example of this, there are two ladies in New York whose names rarely appear in print,

04:49:36.590 --> 04:49:42.970
but who, in a quiet way, have given us the means with which to erect three large and

04:49:42.970 --> 04:49:46.250
important buildings during the last eight years.

04:49:47.010 --> 04:49:51.350
Besides the gift of these buildings, they have made other generous donations to the

04:49:51.350 --> 04:49:51.710
school.

04:49:52.290 --> 04:49:57.570
And they not only help Tuskegee, but they are constantly seeking opportunities to help

04:49:57.570 --> 04:49:58.830
other worthy causes.

04:49:59.230 --> 04:50:04.330
Although it has been my privilege to be the medium through which a good many hundred thousand

04:50:04.330 --> 04:50:09.570
dollars have been received for the work at Tuskegee, I have always avoided what the world

04:50:12.270 --> 04:50:19.130
I often tell people that I have never, quote, begged any money and that I am not a, quote,

04:50:19.370 --> 04:50:19.990
beggar.

04:50:20.550 --> 04:50:26.570
My experience and observation have convinced me that persistent asking outright for money

04:50:26.570 --> 04:50:30.230
from the rich does not, as a rule, secure help.

04:50:30.810 --> 04:50:35.730
I have usually proceeded on the principle that persons who possess sense enough to earn

04:50:35.730 --> 04:50:41.210
money have sense enough to know how to give it away, and that the mere making known of

04:50:41.210 --> 04:50:46.730
the facts regarding Tuskegee, and especially the facts regarding the work of the graduates,

04:50:47.150 --> 04:50:49.590
has been more effective than outright begging.

04:50:50.350 --> 04:50:56.230
I think that the presentation of facts on a high, dignified plane is all the begging

04:50:56.230 --> 04:50:58.070
that most rich people care for.

04:50:58.510 --> 04:51:03.950
While the work of going from door to door and from office to office is hard, disagreeable,

04:51:03.950 --> 04:51:08.830
and costly in bodily strength, yet it does have some compensations.

04:51:09.450 --> 04:51:13.350
Such work gives one a rare opportunity to study human nature.

04:51:13.990 --> 04:51:19.510
It also has its compensations in giving one an opportunity to meet some of the best people

04:51:19.510 --> 04:51:20.250
in the world.

04:51:20.910 --> 04:51:25.270
To be more correct, I think I should say the best people in the world.

04:51:25.750 --> 04:51:31.090
When one takes a broad survey of the country, he will find that the most useful and influential

04:51:31.090 --> 04:51:36.470
people in it are those who take the deepest interest in institutions that exist for the

04:51:36.470 --> 04:51:38.930
purpose of making the world better.

04:51:40.190 --> 04:51:45.810
At one time, when I was in Boston, I called at the door of a rather wealthy lady and was

04:51:45.810 --> 04:51:48.670
admitted to the vestibule and sent up my card.

04:51:49.470 --> 04:51:54.770
While I was waiting for an answer, her husband came in and asked me in the most abrupt manner

04:51:54.770 --> 04:51:55.550
what I wanted.

04:51:55.550 --> 04:52:01.870
When I tried to explain the object of my call, he became still more ungentlemanly in his

04:52:01.870 --> 04:52:06.830
words and manner, and finally grew so excited that I left the house without waiting for

04:52:06.830 --> 04:52:08.350
a reply from the lady.

04:52:08.970 --> 04:52:13.650
A few blocks from that house I called to see a gentleman who received me in the most cordial

04:52:13.650 --> 04:52:14.030
manner.

04:52:14.530 --> 04:52:19.890
He wrote me his check for a generous sum, and then, before I had an opportunity to thank

04:52:19.890 --> 04:52:20.810
him, said,

04:52:21.310 --> 04:52:26.810
I am so grateful to you, Mr. Washington, for giving me the opportunity to help a good cause.

04:52:27.430 --> 04:52:29.470
It is a privilege to have a share in it.

04:52:29.810 --> 04:52:34.030
We in Boston are constantly indebted to you for doing our work.

04:52:34.790 --> 04:52:40.030
My experience in securing money convinces me that the first type of man is growing more

04:52:40.030 --> 04:52:43.630
rare all the time and that the latter type is increasing.

04:52:43.890 --> 04:52:49.570
That is, that more and more rich people are coming to regard men and women who apply to

04:52:49.570 --> 04:52:55.330
them for help for worthy objects, not as beggars, but as agents for doing their work.

04:52:55.670 --> 04:53:00.310
In the city of Boston I have rarely called upon an individual for funds that I have not

04:53:00.310 --> 04:53:05.570
been thanked for calling, usually before I could get an opportunity to thank the donor

04:53:05.570 --> 04:53:06.290
for the money.

04:53:07.070 --> 04:53:12.990
In that city the donors seem to feel, in a large degree, that an honor is being conferred

04:53:12.990 --> 04:53:15.350
upon them and they are being permitted to give.

04:53:15.950 --> 04:53:21.450
Nowhere else have I met with, in so large a measure, this fine and Christ-like spirit

04:53:21.450 --> 04:53:26.910
as in the city of Boston, although there are many notable instances of it outside that

04:53:26.910 --> 04:53:27.230
city.

04:53:27.770 --> 04:53:31.710
I repeat my belief that the world is growing in the direction of giving.

04:53:32.430 --> 04:53:37.990
I repeat that the main rule by which I have been guided in collecting money is to do my

04:53:37.990 --> 04:53:43.190
full duty in regard to giving people who have money an opportunity for help.

04:53:44.410 --> 04:53:49.790
In the early years of the Tuskegee School I walked the streets or traveled country roads

04:53:49.790 --> 04:53:53.290
in the north for days and days without receiving a dollar.

04:53:53.850 --> 04:53:58.750
Often as it happened, when during the week I had been disappointed in not getting a cent

04:53:58.750 --> 04:54:03.730
from the very individuals from whom I most expected help, and when I was almost broken

04:54:03.730 --> 04:54:09.890
down and discouraged, that generous help has come from someone who I had had little idea

04:54:09.890 --> 04:54:11.510
would give at all.

04:54:11.990 --> 04:54:18.070
I recall that on one occasion I obtained information that led me to believe that a gentleman who

04:54:18.070 --> 04:54:23.870
lived about two miles out in the country from Stamford, Connecticut, might become interested

04:54:23.870 --> 04:54:28.410
in our efforts at Tuskegee if our conditions and needs were presented to him.

04:54:29.230 --> 04:54:34.250
On an unusually cold and stormy day I walked the two miles to see him.

04:54:34.710 --> 04:54:38.790
After some difficulty I succeeded in securing an interview with him.

04:54:39.130 --> 04:54:44.390
He listened with some degree of interest to what I had to say, but did not give me anything.

04:54:45.110 --> 04:54:50.750
I could not help having the feeling that, in a measure, the three hours that I had spent

04:54:50.750 --> 04:54:53.030
in seeing him had been thrown away.

04:54:53.810 --> 04:54:57.370
Still I had followed my usual rule of doing my duty.

04:54:57.890 --> 04:55:02.190
If I had not seen him I should have felt unhappy over neglect of duty.

04:55:02.910 --> 04:55:08.790
Two years after this visit a letter came to Tuskegee from this man, which read like this.

04:55:09.470 --> 04:55:14.950
Enclosed, I send you a New York draft for ten thousand dollars to be used in furtherance

04:55:14.950 --> 04:55:15.710
of your work.

04:55:16.230 --> 04:55:21.750
I had placed the sum in my will for your school, but deem it wiser to give it to you while

04:55:21.750 --> 04:55:22.330
I live.

04:55:22.810 --> 04:55:26.550
I recall with pleasure your visit to me two years ago.

04:55:27.570 --> 04:55:33.090
I can hardly imagine any occurrence which could have given me more genuine satisfaction

04:55:33.090 --> 04:55:34.950
than the receipt of this draft.

04:55:35.430 --> 04:55:40.790
It was by far the largest single donation which up to that time the school had ever

04:55:40.790 --> 04:55:41.410
received.

04:55:42.030 --> 04:55:47.510
It came at a time when an unusually long period had passed since we had received any money.

04:55:48.150 --> 04:55:53.370
We were in great distress because of lack of funds, and the nervous strain was tremendous.

04:55:53.370 --> 04:55:59.890
It is difficult for me to think of any situation that is more trying on the nerves than that

04:55:59.890 --> 04:56:05.650
of conducting a large institution with heavy obligations to meet, without knowing where

04:56:05.650 --> 04:56:10.050
the money is to come from to meet these obligations from month to month.

04:56:10.570 --> 04:56:16.370
In our case I felt a double responsibility, and this made the anxiety all the more intense.

04:56:17.090 --> 04:56:22.030
If the institution had been officered by white persons and had failed, it would have injured

04:56:22.030 --> 04:56:23.790
the cause of Negro education.

04:56:24.310 --> 04:56:29.970
But I knew that the failure of our institution, officered by Negroes, would not only mean

04:56:29.970 --> 04:56:36.530
the loss of a school, but would cause people, in a large degree, to lose faith in the ability

04:56:36.530 --> 04:56:37.950
of the entire race.

04:56:38.390 --> 04:56:45.090
The receipt of this draft for $10,000 under all these circumstances partially lifted a

04:56:45.090 --> 04:56:48.570
burden that had been pressing down upon me for days.

04:56:49.070 --> 04:56:54.230
From the beginning of our work to the present, I have always had the feeling, and lose no

04:56:54.230 --> 04:56:59.590
opportunity to impress our teachers with the same idea, that the school will always be

04:56:59.590 --> 04:57:06.350
supported in proportion as the inside of the institution is kept clean and pure and wholesome.

04:57:07.330 --> 04:57:12.910
The first time I ever saw the late Collis P. Huntington, the great railroad man, he

04:57:12.910 --> 04:57:15.050
gave me $2 for our school.

04:57:15.470 --> 04:57:22.770
The last time I saw him, which was a few months before he died, he gave me $50,000 toward

04:57:22.770 --> 04:57:24.050
our endowment fund.

04:57:25.110 --> 04:57:29.690
Between these two gifts there were others of generous proportions which came every year

04:57:29.690 --> 04:57:32.090
from both Mr. and Mrs. Huntington.

04:57:32.870 --> 04:57:38.430
Some people may say that it was Tuskegee's good luck that brought us this gift of $50,000.

04:57:39.090 --> 04:57:42.630
No, it was not luck. It was hard work.

04:57:42.630 --> 04:57:48.730
Nothing ever comes to me that is worth having except as the result of hard work.

04:57:49.430 --> 04:57:54.990
When Mr. Huntington gave me the first $2, I did not blame him for not giving me more,

04:57:55.330 --> 04:58:01.390
but made up my mind that I was going to convince him by tangible results that we were worthy

04:58:01.390 --> 04:58:02.690
of larger gifts.

04:58:03.250 --> 04:58:09.190
For a dozen years I made a strong effort to convince Mr. Huntington of the value of our

04:58:09.190 --> 04:58:09.530
work.

04:58:10.030 --> 04:58:16.570
I noted that just in proportion as the usefulness of the school grew, his donations increased.

04:58:17.090 --> 04:58:22.450
Never did I meet an individual who took a more kindly and sympathetic interest in our

04:58:22.450 --> 04:58:24.610
school than did Mr. Huntington.

04:58:25.050 --> 04:58:30.970
He not only gave money to us, but took time in which to advise me, as a father would a

04:58:30.970 --> 04:58:34.130
son, about the general conduct of the school.

04:58:34.880 --> 04:58:39.530
More than once I have found myself in some pretty tight places while collecting money

04:58:39.530 --> 04:58:45.350
in the North. The following incident I have never related but once before, for the reason

04:58:45.350 --> 04:58:47.690
that I feared that people would not believe it.

04:58:47.790 --> 04:58:52.750
One morning I found myself in Providence, Rhode Island, without a cent of money with

04:58:52.750 --> 04:58:58.470
which to buy breakfast. In crossing the street to see a lady from whom I hoped to get some

04:58:59.030 --> 04:59:05.890
I found a bright new 25 cent piece in the middle of the street track. I not only had

04:59:05.890 --> 04:59:11.210
this 25 cents for my breakfast, but within a few minutes I had a donation from the lady

04:59:11.210 --> 04:59:12.970
on whom I had started to call.

04:59:13.910 --> 04:59:20.390
At one of our commencements I was bold enough to invite the Rev. E. Winchester Donald, D.D.,

04:59:20.390 --> 04:59:27.530
Rector of Trinity Church, Boston, to preach the commencement sermon. As we then had no

04:59:27.530 --> 04:59:32.650
room large enough to accommodate all who would be present, the place of meeting was under

04:59:32.650 --> 04:59:39.770
a large improvised arbor, built partly of brush and partly of rough boards. Soon after

04:59:39.770 --> 04:59:45.710
Dr. Donald had begun speaking the rain came down in torrents and he had to stop while

04:59:45.710 --> 04:59:47.590
someone held an umbrella over him.

04:59:47.970 --> 04:59:53.190
The boldness of what I had done never dawned upon me until I saw the picture made by the

04:59:53.190 --> 04:59:59.070
Rector of Trinity Church standing before that large audience under an old umbrella waiting

04:59:59.070 --> 05:00:04.650
for the rain to cease so that he could go on with his address. It was not very long

05:00:04.650 --> 05:00:10.290
before the rain ceased and Dr. Donald finished his sermon, and an excellent sermon it was,

05:00:10.430 --> 05:00:15.830
too, in spite of the weather. After he had gone to his room and had gotten the wet threads

05:00:15.830 --> 05:00:21.570
of his clothes dry, Dr. Donald ventured the remark that a large chapel at Tuskegee would

05:00:21.570 --> 05:00:27.190
not be out of place. The next day a letter came from two ladies who were then travelling

05:00:27.190 --> 05:00:32.830
in Italy, saying they had decided to give us the money for such a chapel as we needed.

05:00:33.550 --> 05:00:39.210
A short time ago we received twenty thousand dollars from Mr. Andrew Carnegie to be used

05:00:39.210 --> 05:00:44.730
for the purpose of erecting a new library building. Our first library and reading room

05:00:44.730 --> 05:00:50.290
were in a corner of a shanty, and the whole thing occupied a space about five by twelve

05:00:50.290 --> 05:00:56.730
feet. It required ten years of work before I was able to secure Mr. Carnegie's interest

05:00:56.730 --> 05:01:02.230
and help. The first time I saw him ten years ago he seemed to take but little interest

05:01:02.230 --> 05:01:07.890
in our school, but I was determined to show him that we were worthy of his help. After

05:01:07.890 --> 05:01:16.910
ten years of hard work I wrote him a letter reading as follows. December 15, 1900. Mr.

05:01:16.910 --> 05:01:26.690
Andrew Carnegie, 5 West 51st Street, New York. Dear sir, complying with the request which

05:01:26.690 --> 05:01:32.670
you made of me when I saw you at your residence a few days ago, I now submit in writing an

05:01:32.670 --> 05:01:41.970
appeal for a library building for our institution. We have 1,100 students, 86 officers and instructors

05:01:41.970 --> 05:01:47.990
together with their families, and about 200 colored people living near the school, all

05:01:47.990 --> 05:01:55.070
of whom would make use of the library building. We have over 12,000 books, periodicals, etc.,

05:01:55.070 --> 05:02:00.530
gifts from our friends, but we have no suitable place for them, and we have no suitable reading

05:02:00.530 --> 05:02:05.850
room. Our graduates go to work in every section of the South, and whatever knowledge might

05:02:05.850 --> 05:02:10.690
be obtained in the library would serve to assist in the elevation of the whole Negro

05:02:10.690 --> 05:02:17.850
race. Such a building as we need could be erected for about $20,000. All of the work

05:02:17.850 --> 05:02:24.550
for the building, such as brick making, brick masonry, carpentry, blacksmithing, etc., would

05:02:24.550 --> 05:02:29.710
be done by the students. The money which you would give would not only supply the building,

05:02:30.150 --> 05:02:34.130
but the erection of the building would give a large number of students an opportunity

05:02:34.130 --> 05:02:39.830
to learn the building trades, and the students would use the money paid to them to keep themselves

05:02:39.830 --> 05:02:45.030
in school. I do not believe that a similar amount of money often could be made to go

05:02:45.030 --> 05:02:51.670
so far in uplifting a whole race. If you wish further information, I shall be glad to furnish

05:02:51.670 --> 05:02:56.230
it. Yours truly, Booker T. Washington, Principal.

05:02:56.890 --> 05:03:02.910
The next mail brought back the following reply. I will be very glad to pay the bills for the

05:03:02.910 --> 05:03:09.810
library building as they are incurred to the extent of $20,000, and I am glad of this opportunity

05:03:09.830 --> 05:03:16.290
to show the interest I have in your noble work. I have found that strict business methods

05:03:16.290 --> 05:03:21.970
go a long way in securing the interest of rich people. It has been my constant aim at

05:03:21.970 --> 05:03:27.910
Tuskegee to carry out, in our financial and other operations, such business methods as

05:03:27.910 --> 05:03:31.050
would be approved of by any New York banking house.

05:03:31.650 --> 05:03:37.530
I have spoken of several large gifts to the school, but by far the greater proportion

05:03:37.530 --> 05:03:43.070
of the money that has built up the institution has come in the form of small donations from

05:03:43.070 --> 05:03:48.810
persons of moderate means. It is upon these small gifts, which carry with them the interest

05:03:48.810 --> 05:03:54.250
of hundreds of donors, that any philanthropic work must depend largely for its support.

05:03:54.990 --> 05:04:00.070
In my efforts to get money, I have often been surprised at the patience and deep interest

05:04:00.070 --> 05:04:05.570
of the ministers who are besieged on every hand and at all hours of the day for help.

05:04:05.930 --> 05:04:11.570
If no other consideration had convinced me of the value of the Christian life, the Christ-like

05:04:11.570 --> 05:04:17.450
work which the Church of all denominations in America has done during the last 35 years

05:04:17.450 --> 05:04:23.650
for the elevation of the black man would have made me a Christian. In a large degree it

05:04:23.650 --> 05:04:28.550
has been the pennies, the nickels, and the dimes which have come from the Sunday schools,

05:04:28.970 --> 05:04:34.510
the Christian Endeavor Societies, and the Missionary Societies, as well as from the Church proper

05:04:34.510 --> 05:04:40.590
that have helped to elevate the Negro at so rapid a rate. This speaking of small gifts

05:04:40.590 --> 05:04:47.410
reminds me to say that very few Tuskegee graduates fail to send us an annual contribution. These

05:04:47.410 --> 05:04:54.770
contributions range from 25 cents up to $10. Soon after beginning our third year's work,

05:04:54.850 --> 05:05:00.250
we were surprised to receive money from three special sources, and up to the present time

05:05:00.250 --> 05:05:06.270
we have continued to receive help from them. First, the State Legislature of Alabama increased

05:05:06.270 --> 05:05:14.190
its annual appropriation from $2,000 to $3,000. I might add that still later it increased

05:05:14.190 --> 05:05:22.470
this sum to $4,500 a year. The effort to secure this increase was led by the Honorable M.F.

05:05:22.590 --> 05:05:29.230
Foster, the member of the Legislature from Tuskegee. Second, we received $1,000 from

05:05:29.230 --> 05:05:35.090
the John F. Slater Fund. Our work seemed to please the trustees of this fund as they soon

05:05:35.090 --> 05:05:40.370
began increasing their annual grant. This has been added to from time to time until

05:05:40.370 --> 05:05:46.830
at present we receive $11,000 annually from the fund. The other help to which I have referred

05:05:46.830 --> 05:05:53.650
came in the shape of an allowance from the Peabody Fund. This was at first $500, but

05:05:53.650 --> 05:06:00.610
it has since been increased to $1,500. The effort to secure help from the Slater and

05:06:00.610 --> 05:06:06.290
Peabody Funds brought me into contact with two rare men, men who have had much to do

05:06:06.290 --> 05:06:12.790
in shaping the policy for the education of the Negro. I refer to the Honorable J. L.

05:06:12.790 --> 05:06:18.850
M. Curry of Washington, who is the general agent for these two funds, and Mr. Morris

05:06:19.630 --> 05:06:25.930
of New York. Dr. Curry is a native of the South, an ex-Confederate soldier, yet I do

05:06:25.930 --> 05:06:30.610
not believe there is any man in the country who is more deeply interested in the highest

05:06:30.610 --> 05:06:37.390
welfare of the Negro than Dr. Curry, or one who is more free from race prejudice. He enjoys

05:06:37.390 --> 05:06:42.570
the unique distinction of possessing to an equal degree of confidence of the black man

05:06:42.570 --> 05:06:48.790
and the southern white man. I shall never forget the first time I met him. It was in

05:06:48.790 --> 05:06:54.370
Richmond, Virginia, where he was then living. I had heard much about him. When I first went

05:06:54.370 --> 05:06:59.870
into his presence, trembling because of my youth and inexperience, he took me by the

05:06:59.870 --> 05:07:06.050
hand so cordially and spoke such encouraging words and gave me such helpful advice regarding

05:07:06.050 --> 05:07:12.910
the proper course to pursue, that I came to know him then, as I have known him ever since,

05:07:13.230 --> 05:07:19.730
as a high example of one who is constantly and unselfishly at work for the betterment

05:07:19.730 --> 05:07:27.010
of humanity. Mr. Morris K. Jessup, the treasurer of the Slater Fund, I refer to because I know

05:07:27.010 --> 05:07:32.930
of no man of wealth and large and complicated business responsibilities who gives not only

05:07:32.930 --> 05:07:38.710
money but his time and thought to the subject of the proper method of elevating the Negro

05:07:38.710 --> 05:07:44.330
to the extent that is true of Mr. Jessup. It is very largely through this effort and

05:07:44.330 --> 05:07:49.730
influence that during the last few years the subject of industrial education has assumed

05:07:49.730 --> 05:07:54.070
the importance that it has, and has been placed on its present footing.

05:08:04.230 --> 05:08:05.630
Thank you.

05:08:07.630 --> 05:08:32.330
UP FROM SLAVERY CHAPTER XIII.

05:08:32.330 --> 05:08:35.150
2,000 miles for a five-minute speech.

05:08:36.950 --> 05:08:41.330
Soon after the opening of our boarding department, quite a number of students, who evidently

05:08:41.330 --> 05:08:45.850
were worthy, but who were so poor that they did not have any money to pay even the small

05:08:45.850 --> 05:08:48.910
charges at the school, began applying for admission.

05:08:49.450 --> 05:08:52.050
This class was composed of both men and women.

05:08:52.470 --> 05:08:57.690
It was a great trial to refuse admission to these applicants, and in 1884 we established

05:08:57.690 --> 05:08:59.930
a night school to accommodate a few of them.

05:09:00.550 --> 05:09:05.090
The night school was organized on a plan similar to the one which I had helped to establish

05:09:05.090 --> 05:09:05.710
at Hampton.

05:09:06.190 --> 05:09:08.830
At first it was composed of about a dozen students.

05:09:09.370 --> 05:09:13.250
They were admitted to the night school only when they had no money with which to pay any

05:09:13.250 --> 05:09:15.330
part of their board in the regular day school.

05:09:15.690 --> 05:09:19.970
It was further required that they must work for ten hours during the day at some trade

05:09:19.970 --> 05:09:24.250
or industry, and study academic branches for two hours during the evening.

05:09:24.690 --> 05:09:28.050
This was the requirement for the first one or two years of their stay.

05:09:28.430 --> 05:09:32.470
They were to be paid something above the cost of their board, with the understanding that

05:09:32.470 --> 05:09:36.610
all of their earnings, except a very small part, were to be reserved in the school's

05:09:36.610 --> 05:09:41.010
treasury to be used for paying their board in the regular day school after they had entered

05:09:41.010 --> 05:09:41.770
that department.

05:09:42.330 --> 05:09:48.110
The night school, started in this manner, has grown, until there are at present 457

05:09:48.110 --> 05:09:49.770
students enrolled in it alone.

05:09:50.430 --> 05:09:54.590
There could hardly be a more severe test of a student's worth than this branch of the

05:09:54.590 --> 05:09:55.490
institute's work.

05:09:56.030 --> 05:10:00.530
It is largely because it furnishes such a good opportunity to test the backbone of a

05:10:00.530 --> 05:10:04.090
student that I place such high value upon our night school.

05:10:04.810 --> 05:10:09.070
Anyone who is willing to work ten hours a day at the brickyard or in the laundry through

05:10:09.070 --> 05:10:13.790
one or two years, in order that he or she may have the privilege of studying academic

05:10:13.790 --> 05:10:18.510
branches for two hours in the evening, has enough bottom to warrant being further educated.

05:10:19.510 --> 05:10:24.150
After the student has left the night school, he enters the day school, where he takes academic

05:10:24.150 --> 05:10:27.670
branches four days in a week, and works at his trade two days.

05:10:28.150 --> 05:10:31.730
Besides this, he usually works at his trade during the three summer months.

05:10:32.210 --> 05:10:37.030
As a rule, after a student has succeeded in going through the night school test, he finds

05:10:37.030 --> 05:10:40.390
a way to finish the regular course in industrial and academic training.

05:10:41.130 --> 05:10:45.650
No student, no matter how much money he may be able to command, is permitted to go through

05:10:45.650 --> 05:10:47.370
school without doing manual labor.

05:10:47.910 --> 05:10:51.930
In fact, the industrial work is now as popular as the academic branches.

05:10:52.370 --> 05:10:57.050
Some of the most successful men and women who have graduated from the institution obtained

05:10:57.050 --> 05:10:58.590
their start in the night school.

05:10:59.490 --> 05:11:03.650
While a great deal of stress is laid upon the industrial side of the work at Tuskegee,

05:11:03.990 --> 05:11:08.210
we do not neglect or overlook in any degree the religious and spiritual side.

05:11:08.750 --> 05:11:13.750
The school is strictly undenominational, but it is thoroughly Christian, and the spiritual

05:11:13.750 --> 05:11:15.670
training of the students is not neglected.

05:11:16.130 --> 05:11:21.370
Our preaching service, prayer meetings, Sunday school, Christian Endeavor Society, Young

05:11:21.370 --> 05:11:26.330
Men's Christian Association, and various missionary organizations testify to this.

05:11:27.150 --> 05:11:32.990
In 1885, Miss Olivia Davidson, to whom I have already referred as being largely responsible

05:11:32.990 --> 05:11:37.170
for the success of the school during its early history, and I were married.

05:11:37.790 --> 05:11:42.290
During our married life, she continued to divide her time and strength between our home

05:11:42.290 --> 05:11:43.470
and the work for the school.

05:11:44.070 --> 05:11:48.630
She not only continued to work in the school at Tuskegee, but also kept up her habit of

05:11:48.630 --> 05:11:50.310
going north to secure funds.

05:11:50.850 --> 05:11:56.830
In 1889, she died, after four years of happy married life and eight years of hard and happy

05:11:56.830 --> 05:11:57.750
work for the school.

05:11:58.450 --> 05:12:03.430
She literally wore herself out in her never ceasing efforts in behalf of the work that

05:12:03.430 --> 05:12:04.510
she so dearly loved.

05:12:05.090 --> 05:12:09.990
During our married life, there were born to us two bright, beautiful boys, Booker Tolliver

05:12:09.990 --> 05:12:11.230
and Ernest Davidson.

05:12:11.710 --> 05:12:16.370
The older of these, Booker, has already mastered the brickmaker's trade at Tuskegee.

05:12:17.530 --> 05:12:21.050
I have often been asked how I began the practice of public speaking.

05:12:21.650 --> 05:12:25.890
In answer, I would say that I never planned to give any large part of my life to speaking

05:12:25.890 --> 05:12:26.470
in public.

05:12:26.990 --> 05:12:31.930
I have always had more of an ambition to do things than to merely talk about doing them.

05:12:32.290 --> 05:12:36.390
It seems that when I went north with General Armstrong to speak at the series of public

05:12:36.390 --> 05:12:44.950
meetings to which I have referred, the President of the National Educational Association, the

05:12:44.950 --> 05:12:46.830
and heard me speak.

05:12:47.270 --> 05:12:51.550
A few days afterward, he sent me an invitation to deliver an address at the next meeting

05:12:51.550 --> 05:12:53.170
of the Educational Association.

05:12:53.870 --> 05:12:56.310
This meeting was to be held in Madison, Wisconsin.

05:12:56.790 --> 05:12:58.290
I accepted the invitation.

05:12:58.610 --> 05:13:01.610
This was, in a sense, the beginning of my public speaking career.

05:13:02.510 --> 05:13:07.770
On the evening that I spoke before the Association, there must have been not far from four thousand

05:13:07.770 --> 05:13:08.730
persons present.

05:13:09.290 --> 05:13:13.870
Without my knowing it, there were a large number of people present from Alabama and

05:13:13.870 --> 05:13:15.430
some from the town of Tuskegee.

05:13:16.110 --> 05:13:19.970
These white people afterward frankly told me that they went to this meeting expecting

05:13:19.970 --> 05:13:24.530
to hear the South roundly abused, but were pleasantly surprised to find that there was

05:13:24.530 --> 05:13:26.310
no word of abuse in my address.

05:13:26.810 --> 05:13:31.010
On the contrary, the South was given credit for all the praiseworthy things that it had

05:13:31.010 --> 05:13:31.350
done.

05:13:32.010 --> 05:13:36.690
A white lady who was a teacher in a college in Tuskegee wrote back to the local paper

05:13:36.690 --> 05:13:41.270
that she was gratified, as well as surprised, to note the credit which I gave the white

05:13:41.270 --> 05:13:44.090
people of Tuskegee for their help in getting the school started.

05:13:44.790 --> 05:13:48.750
This address at Madison was the first that I had delivered that in any large measure

05:13:48.750 --> 05:13:50.950
dealt with the general problem of the races.

05:13:51.590 --> 05:13:55.550
Those who heard it seemed to be pleased with what I said and with the general position

05:13:55.550 --> 05:13:56.290
that I took.

05:13:57.290 --> 05:14:01.850
When I first came to Tuskegee, I determined that I would make it my home, that I would

05:14:01.850 --> 05:14:05.930
take as much pride in the right actions of the people of the town as any white man could

05:14:05.930 --> 05:14:11.090
do, and that I would, at the same time, deplore the wrongdoing of the people as much as any

05:14:11.090 --> 05:14:11.650
white man.

05:14:12.230 --> 05:14:16.610
I determined never to say anything in a public address in the North that I would not be willing

05:14:16.610 --> 05:14:17.590
to say in the South.

05:14:18.210 --> 05:14:23.170
I early learned that it is a hard matter to convert an individual by abusing him, and

05:14:23.170 --> 05:14:27.630
that this is more often accomplished by giving credit for all the praiseworthy actions performed

05:14:27.630 --> 05:14:31.050
than by calling attention alone to all the evil done.

05:14:31.990 --> 05:14:36.670
While pursuing this policy, I have not failed, at the proper time and in the proper manner,

05:14:36.670 --> 05:14:41.610
to call attention in no uncertain terms to the wrongs which any part of the South has

05:14:41.610 --> 05:14:42.610
been guilty of.

05:14:42.990 --> 05:14:47.750
I have found that there is a large element in the South that is quick to respond to straightforward,

05:14:48.350 --> 05:14:50.510
honest criticism of any wrong policy.

05:14:51.110 --> 05:14:56.850
As a rule, the place to criticize the South, when criticism is necessary, is in the South,

05:14:57.010 --> 05:14:58.050
not in Boston.

05:14:58.610 --> 05:15:03.910
A Boston man who came to Alabama to criticize Boston would not affect so much good, I think,

05:15:03.910 --> 05:15:07.530
as one who had his word of criticism to say in Boston.

05:15:08.890 --> 05:15:13.470
In this address at Madison, I took the ground that the policy to be pursued with references

05:15:13.470 --> 05:15:18.830
to the races was, by every honorable means, to bring them together, and to encourage the

05:15:18.830 --> 05:15:22.930
cultivation of friendly relations, instead of doing that which would embitter.

05:15:23.390 --> 05:15:28.570
I further contended that, in relation to his vote, the negro should more and more consider

05:15:28.570 --> 05:15:33.150
the interests of the community in which he lived, rather than seek alone to please someone

05:15:33.150 --> 05:15:36.270
who lived a thousand miles away from him and from his interests.

05:15:37.130 --> 05:15:42.290
In this address, I said that the whole future of the negro rested largely upon the question

05:15:42.290 --> 05:15:47.350
as to whether he should make himself, through his skill, intelligence, and character, of

05:15:47.350 --> 05:15:52.210
such undeniable value to the community in which he lived, that the community could not

05:15:52.210 --> 05:15:53.430
dispense with his presence.

05:15:53.870 --> 05:15:58.590
I said that any individual who learned to do something better than anybody else, learned

05:15:59.250 --> 05:16:05.050
in an uncommon manner, had solved his problem, regardless of the color of his skin, and that,

05:16:05.190 --> 05:16:09.650
in proportion, as the negro learned to produce what other people wanted and must have, in

05:16:09.650 --> 05:16:11.790
the same proportion would he be respected.

05:16:12.850 --> 05:16:18.550
I spoke of an instance where one of our graduates had produced 266 bushels of sweet potatoes

05:16:18.550 --> 05:16:24.130
from an acre of ground, in a community where the average production had been only 49 bushels

05:16:24.130 --> 05:16:24.770
to the acre.

05:16:25.350 --> 05:16:29.830
He had been able to do this by reason of his knowledge of the chemistry of the soil, and

05:16:29.830 --> 05:16:32.590
by his knowledge of improved methods of agriculture.

05:16:33.250 --> 05:16:37.670
The white farmers in the neighborhood respected him, and came to him for ideas regarding the

05:16:37.670 --> 05:16:38.750
raising of sweet potatoes.

05:16:39.310 --> 05:16:43.850
These white farmers honored and respected him because he, by his skill and knowledge,

05:16:44.190 --> 05:16:48.090
had added something to the wealth and the comfort of the community in which he lived.

05:16:48.690 --> 05:16:53.550
I explained that my theory of education for the negro would not, for example, confine

05:16:53.550 --> 05:16:58.570
him for all time to farm life, to the production of the best and the most sweet potatoes, but

05:16:58.570 --> 05:17:03.350
that, if he succeeded in this line of industry, he could lay the foundations upon which his

05:17:03.350 --> 05:17:07.670
children and grandchildren could grow to higher and more important things in life.

05:17:08.290 --> 05:17:13.430
Such, in brief, were some of the views I advocated in this first address, dealing with the broad

05:17:13.430 --> 05:17:18.950
question of the relations of the two races, and since that time I have not found any reason

05:17:18.950 --> 05:17:21.570
for changing my views on any important point.

05:17:22.590 --> 05:17:27.970
In my early life I used to cherish a feeling of ill-will toward any one who spoke in bitter

05:17:27.970 --> 05:17:32.290
terms against the negro, or who advocated measures that tended to oppress the black

05:17:32.290 --> 05:17:36.410
man, or take from him opportunities for growth in the most complete manner.

05:17:36.930 --> 05:17:41.390
Now, whenever I hear any one advocating measures that are meant to curtail the development

05:17:41.390 --> 05:17:44.490
of another, I pity the individual who would do this.

05:17:44.850 --> 05:17:49.550
I know that the one who makes this mistake does so because of his own lack of opportunity

05:17:49.550 --> 05:17:50.990
for the highest kind of growth.

05:17:51.590 --> 05:17:55.970
I pity him because I know that he is trying to stop the progress of the world, and because

05:17:55.970 --> 05:18:00.590
I know that in time the development and the ceaseless advance of humanity will make him

05:18:00.590 --> 05:18:02.670
ashamed of his weak and narrow position.

05:18:03.230 --> 05:18:07.010
One might as well try to stop the progress of a mighty railroad train by throwing his

05:18:07.010 --> 05:18:11.530
body across the track, as to try to stop the growth of the world in the direction of giving

05:18:11.530 --> 05:18:17.470
mankind more intelligence, more culture, more skill, more liberty, and in the direction

05:18:17.470 --> 05:18:20.350
extending more sympathy and more brotherly kindness.

05:18:21.330 --> 05:18:26.370
The address which I delivered at Madison before the National Educational Association gave

05:18:26.370 --> 05:18:31.630
me a rather wide introduction in the North, and soon after that opportunities began offering

05:18:31.630 --> 05:18:34.050
themselves for me to address audiences there.

05:18:35.350 --> 05:18:40.270
I was anxious, however, that the way might also be open for me to speak directly to a

05:18:40.270 --> 05:18:42.330
representative southern white audience.

05:18:42.790 --> 05:18:47.630
A partial opportunity of this kind, one that seemed to me might serve as an entering wedge,

05:18:48.170 --> 05:18:54.010
presented itself in 1893, when the International Meeting of Christian Workers was held at Atlanta,

05:18:54.170 --> 05:18:54.490
Georgia.

05:18:55.050 --> 05:18:59.690
When this invitation came to me, I had engagements in Boston that seemed to make it impossible

05:18:59.690 --> 05:19:00.970
for me to speak in Atlanta.

05:19:01.650 --> 05:19:06.190
Still, after looking over my list of dates and places carefully, I found that I could

05:19:06.190 --> 05:19:10.650
take a train from Boston that would get me into Atlanta about thirty minutes before my

05:19:10.650 --> 05:19:15.010
address was to be delivered, and that I could remain in that city before taking another

05:19:15.010 --> 05:19:15.870
train for Boston.

05:19:16.530 --> 05:19:21.550
My invitation to speak in Atlanta stipulated that I was to confine my address to five minutes.

05:19:22.070 --> 05:19:26.710
The question, then, was whether or not I could put enough into a five-minute address to make

05:19:26.710 --> 05:19:28.610
it worthwhile for me to make such a trip.

05:19:29.350 --> 05:19:33.590
I knew that the audience would be largely composed of the most influential class of

05:19:33.590 --> 05:19:37.570
white men and women, and that it would be a rare opportunity for me to let them know

05:19:37.570 --> 05:19:41.810
what we were trying to do at Tuskegee, as well as to speak to them about the relations

05:19:41.810 --> 05:19:42.530
of the races.

05:19:43.010 --> 05:19:44.650
So I decided to make the trip.

05:19:45.030 --> 05:19:50.230
I spoke for five minutes to an audience of two thousand people, composed mostly of southern

05:19:50.230 --> 05:19:51.350
and northern whites.

05:19:51.970 --> 05:19:55.150
What I said seemed to be received with favour and enthusiasm.

05:19:55.750 --> 05:20:00.590
The Atlanta papers of the next day commented in friendly terms on my address, and a good

05:20:00.590 --> 05:20:02.850
deal was said about it in different parts of the country.

05:20:02.850 --> 05:20:08.110
I felt that I had in some degree accomplished my object, that of getting a hearing from

05:20:08.110 --> 05:20:09.810
the dominant class of the South.

05:20:11.470 --> 05:20:16.590
The demands made upon me for public addresses continued to increase, coming in about equal

05:20:16.590 --> 05:20:19.170
numbers from my own people and from northern whites.

05:20:19.510 --> 05:20:24.350
I gave as much time to these addresses as I could spare from the immediate work at Tuskegee.

05:20:24.970 --> 05:20:29.350
Most of the addresses in the North were made for the direct purpose of getting funds with

05:20:29.350 --> 05:20:30.710
which to support the school.

05:20:31.350 --> 05:20:35.430
Those delivered before the coloured people had for their main object the impressing upon

05:20:35.430 --> 05:20:40.950
them the importance of industrial and technical education in addition to academic and religious

05:20:40.950 --> 05:20:41.430
training.

05:20:42.450 --> 05:20:47.390
I now come to that one of the incidents in my life which seems to have excited the greatest

05:20:47.390 --> 05:20:51.790
amount of interest, and which perhaps went further than anything else in giving me a

05:20:51.790 --> 05:20:54.590
reputation that in a sense might be called national.

05:20:55.110 --> 05:20:59.430
I refer to the address which I delivered at the opening of the Atlanta Cotton States and

05:20:59.430 --> 05:21:05.410
International Exposition at Atlanta, Georgia, September 18, 1895.

05:21:06.370 --> 05:21:10.250
So much has been said and written about this incident, and so many questions have been

05:21:10.250 --> 05:21:14.710
asked me concerning the address that perhaps I may be excused for taking up the matter

05:21:14.710 --> 05:21:15.610
with some detail.

05:21:16.250 --> 05:21:21.110
The five-minute address in Atlanta, which I came from Boston to deliver, was possibly

05:21:21.110 --> 05:21:25.310
the prime cause for an opportunity being given me to make the second address there.

05:21:25.770 --> 05:21:31.990
In the spring of 1895 I received a telegram from prominent citizens in Atlanta asking

05:21:31.990 --> 05:21:36.270
me to accompany a committee from that city to Washington for the purpose of appearing

05:21:36.270 --> 05:21:40.770
before a committee of Congress in the interest of securing government help for the exposition.

05:21:41.730 --> 05:21:46.390
The committee was composed of about 25 of the most prominent and most influential white

05:21:46.390 --> 05:21:47.130
men of Georgia.

05:21:47.870 --> 05:21:52.130
All the members of this committee were white men except Bishop Grant, Bishop Gaines, and

05:21:52.130 --> 05:21:52.730
myself.

05:21:53.330 --> 05:21:57.170
The mayor and several other city and state officials spoke before the committee.

05:21:57.650 --> 05:21:59.710
They were followed by the two colored bishops.

05:21:59.950 --> 05:22:02.190
My name was the last on the list of speakers.

05:22:02.530 --> 05:22:07.210
I had never before appeared before such a committee, nor had I ever delivered any address

05:22:07.210 --> 05:22:08.550
in the capital of the nation.

05:22:09.050 --> 05:22:13.630
I had many misgivings as to what I ought to say, and as to the impression that my address

05:22:13.630 --> 05:22:14.130
would make.

05:22:14.550 --> 05:22:19.250
While I cannot recall in detail what I said, I remember that I tried to impress upon the

05:22:19.630 --> 05:22:24.610
the earnestness and plainness of any language that I could command, that if Congress wanted

05:22:24.610 --> 05:22:29.150
to do something which would assist in ridding the south of the race question and making

05:22:29.150 --> 05:22:33.950
friends between the two races, it should, in every proper way, encourage the material

05:22:33.950 --> 05:22:36.330
and intellectual growth of both races.

05:22:36.990 --> 05:22:42.330
I said that the Atlanta exposition would present an opportunity for both races to show what

05:22:42.330 --> 05:22:47.210
advance they had made since freedom, and would, at the same time, afford encouragement to

05:22:47.210 --> 05:22:48.950
to make still greater progress.

05:22:49.570 --> 05:22:54.290
I tried to emphasize the fact that while the negro should not be deprived by unfair means

05:22:54.290 --> 05:22:59.890
of the franchise, political agitation alone would not save him, and that back of the ballot

05:22:59.890 --> 05:23:05.790
he must have property, industry, skill, economy, intelligence, and character, and that no race

05:23:05.790 --> 05:23:08.030
without these elements could permanently succeed.

05:23:08.470 --> 05:23:12.430
I said that in granting the appropriation, Congress could do something that would prove

05:23:12.430 --> 05:23:17.190
to be of real and lasting value to both races, and that it was the first great opportunity

05:23:17.190 --> 05:23:20.690
of the kind that had been presented since the close of the Civil War.

05:23:21.610 --> 05:23:25.710
I spoke for fifteen or twenty minutes, and was surprised at the close of my address to

05:23:25.710 --> 05:23:30.010
receive the hearty congratulations of the Georgia Committee and of the members of Congress

05:23:30.010 --> 05:23:30.730
who were present.

05:23:31.330 --> 05:23:36.670
The Committee was unanimous in making a favorable report, and in a few days the bill passed

05:23:36.670 --> 05:23:37.170
Congress.

05:23:37.850 --> 05:23:41.970
With the passing of this bill, the success of the Atlanta exposition was assured.

05:23:42.770 --> 05:23:47.770
Soon after this trip to Washington, the directors of the exposition decided that it would be

05:23:47.770 --> 05:23:52.290
a fitting recognition of the colored race to erect a large and attractive building which

05:23:52.290 --> 05:23:55.930
should be devoted wholly to showing the progress of the negro since freedom.

05:23:56.970 --> 05:24:01.330
It was further decided to have the building designed and erected wholly by negro mechanics.

05:24:01.950 --> 05:24:03.430
This plan was carried out.

05:24:03.810 --> 05:24:08.190
In design, beauty, and general finish, the negro building was equal to the others on

05:24:08.190 --> 05:24:08.710
the grounds.

05:24:10.010 --> 05:24:15.290
After it was decided to have a separate negro exhibit, the question arose as to who should

05:24:15.290 --> 05:24:16.250
take care of it.

05:24:16.510 --> 05:24:20.590
The officials of the exposition were anxious that I should assume this responsibility,

05:24:20.970 --> 05:24:25.870
but I declined to do so on the plea that the work at Tuskegee at that time demanded my

05:24:25.870 --> 05:24:26.790
time and strength.

05:24:27.330 --> 05:24:32.810
Largely at my suggestion, Mr. I. Garland Penn of Lynchburg, Virginia, was selected to be

05:24:32.810 --> 05:24:34.230
at the head of the negro department.

05:24:34.530 --> 05:24:36.310
I gave him all the aid that I could.

05:24:36.310 --> 05:24:40.150
The negro exhibit as a whole was large and creditable.

05:24:40.870 --> 05:24:44.490
The two exhibits in this department which attracted the greatest amount of attention

05:24:44.490 --> 05:24:48.250
were those from the Hampton Institute and the Tuskegee Institute.

05:24:48.830 --> 05:24:52.950
The people who seemed to be the most surprised as well as pleased at what they saw in the

05:24:52.950 --> 05:24:55.430
negro building were the southern white people.

05:24:56.430 --> 05:25:01.590
As the day for the opening of the exposition drew near, the board of directors began preparing

05:25:01.590 --> 05:25:03.630
the program for the opening exercises.

05:25:04.230 --> 05:25:09.090
In the discussion from day to day of the various features of this program, the question came

05:25:09.090 --> 05:25:14.350
up as to the advisability of putting a member of the negro race on for one of the opening

05:25:14.350 --> 05:25:19.150
addresses, since the negroes had been asked to take such a prominent part of the exposition.

05:25:19.790 --> 05:25:24.350
It was argued further that such recognition would mark the good feeling prevailing between

05:25:24.350 --> 05:25:25.090
the two races.

05:25:25.750 --> 05:25:29.670
Of course there were those who were opposed to any such recognition of the rights of the

05:25:29.670 --> 05:25:34.830
But the board of directors, composed of men who represented the best and most progressive

05:25:34.830 --> 05:25:39.790
element in the south, had their way, and voted to invite a black man to speak on the opening

05:25:39.790 --> 05:25:40.210
day.

05:25:41.610 --> 05:25:45.810
The next thing was to decide upon the person who was thus to represent the negro race.

05:25:46.450 --> 05:25:51.010
After the question had been canvassed for several days, the directors voted unanimously

05:25:51.010 --> 05:25:56.190
to ask me to deliver one of the opening day addresses, and in a few days after that I

05:25:56.190 --> 05:25:57.830
received the official invitation.

05:25:58.810 --> 05:26:03.270
The receiving of this invitation brought to me a sense of responsibility that it would

05:26:03.270 --> 05:26:06.450
be hard for any one not placed in my position to appreciate.

05:26:07.110 --> 05:26:09.870
What were my feelings when this invitation came to me?

05:26:10.090 --> 05:26:14.570
I remembered that I had been a slave, that my early years had been spent in the lowest

05:26:14.570 --> 05:26:19.370
depths of poverty and ignorance, and that I had had little opportunity to prepare me

05:26:19.370 --> 05:26:21.290
for such a responsibility as this.

05:26:21.730 --> 05:26:26.290
It was only a few years before that time that any white man in the audience might have claimed

05:26:26.290 --> 05:26:31.150
me as his slave, and it was easily possible that some of my former owners might be present

05:26:31.150 --> 05:26:32.110
to hear me speak.

05:26:32.950 --> 05:26:37.730
I knew too that this was the first time in the entire history of the negro that a member

05:26:37.730 --> 05:26:41.770
of my race had been asked to speak from the same platform with white southern men and

05:26:41.770 --> 05:26:44.470
women on any important national occasion.

05:26:45.030 --> 05:26:49.690
I was asked now to speak to an audience composed of the wealth and culture of the white south,

05:26:50.110 --> 05:26:52.450
the representatives of my former masters.

05:26:52.970 --> 05:26:56.790
I knew too that while the greater part of my audience would be composed of southern

05:26:56.790 --> 05:27:02.130
people, yet there would be present a large number of northern whites, as well as a great

05:27:02.130 --> 05:27:04.310
many men and women of my own race.

05:27:04.990 --> 05:27:09.290
I was determined to say nothing that I did not feel from the bottom of my heart to be

05:27:09.290 --> 05:27:10.090
true and right.

05:27:10.530 --> 05:27:14.910
When the invitation came to me there was not one word of intimation as to what I should

05:27:14.910 --> 05:27:16.890
say or as to what I should admit.

05:27:17.590 --> 05:27:21.050
In this I felt that the board of directors had paid a tribute to me.

05:27:21.050 --> 05:27:26.050
They knew that by one sentence I could have blasted in a large degree the success of the

05:27:26.050 --> 05:27:26.650
exposition.

05:27:27.250 --> 05:27:31.810
I was also painfully conscious of the fact that, while I must be true to my own race

05:27:31.810 --> 05:27:37.350
and my utterances, I had it in my power to make such an ill-timed address as would result

05:27:37.350 --> 05:27:42.270
in preventing any similar invitation being extended to a black man again for years to

05:27:42.270 --> 05:27:42.570
come.

05:27:42.990 --> 05:27:48.010
I was equally determined to be true to the north, as well as to the best element of the

05:27:48.470 --> 05:27:49.850
in what I had to say.

05:27:51.390 --> 05:27:56.270
The papers, north and south, had taken up the discussion of my coming speech, and as

05:27:56.270 --> 05:27:59.950
the time for it drew nearer this discussion became more and more widespread.

05:28:01.190 --> 05:28:05.650
Not a few of the southern white papers were unfriendly to the idea of my speaking.

05:28:06.670 --> 05:28:10.590
From my own race I received many suggestions as to what I ought to say.

05:28:10.990 --> 05:28:15.510
I prepared myself as best I could for the address, but as the 18th of September drew

05:28:16.090 --> 05:28:20.530
the heavier my heart became, and the more I feared that my effort would prove a failure

05:28:20.530 --> 05:28:21.470
and a disappointment.

05:28:22.870 --> 05:28:27.270
The invitation had come at a time when I was very busy with my schoolwork, as it was the

05:28:27.270 --> 05:28:28.510
beginning of our school year.

05:28:29.030 --> 05:28:33.250
After preparing my address, I went through it, as I usually do with those utterances

05:28:33.250 --> 05:28:38.710
which I consider particularly important, with Mrs. Washington, and she approved what I intended

05:28:38.710 --> 05:28:39.270
to say.

05:28:39.790 --> 05:28:45.290
On the 16th of September, the day before I was to start for Atlanta, so many of the Tuskegee

05:28:45.290 --> 05:28:50.250
teachers expressed a desire to hear my address that I consented to read it to them in a body.

05:28:50.850 --> 05:28:56.190
When I had done so, and had heard their criticisms and comments, I felt somewhat relieved, since

05:28:56.190 --> 05:28:58.410
they seemed to think well of what I had to say.

05:28:59.650 --> 05:29:04.510
On the morning of September 17th, together with Mrs. Washington and my three children,

05:29:04.790 --> 05:29:06.070
I started for Atlanta.

05:29:06.470 --> 05:29:10.990
I felt a good deal, as I suppose a man feels when he is on his way to the gallows.

05:29:11.610 --> 05:29:15.850
In passing through the town of Tuskegee, I met a white farmer who lived some distance

05:29:15.850 --> 05:29:16.730
out in the country.

05:29:17.170 --> 05:29:19.110
In a jesting manner, this man said,

05:29:19.150 --> 05:29:23.970
Washington, you have spoken before the northern white people, the negroes in the south, and

05:29:23.970 --> 05:29:28.230
to us country white people in the south, but Atlanta, tomorrow, you will have before you

05:29:28.230 --> 05:29:31.250
the northern whites, the southern whites, and the negroes altogether.

05:29:31.650 --> 05:29:34.470
I am afraid that you have got yourself in a tight place.

05:29:35.250 --> 05:29:40.190
This farmer diagnosed the situation correctly, but his frank words did not add anything to

05:29:40.190 --> 05:29:40.790
my comfort.

05:29:41.830 --> 05:29:46.510
In the course of the journey from Tuskegee to Atlanta, both colored and white people

05:29:46.510 --> 05:29:50.890
came to the train to point me out, and discussed with perfect freedom, in my hearings, what

05:29:50.890 --> 05:29:52.650
was going to take place the next day.

05:29:53.010 --> 05:29:54.970
We were met by a committee in Atlanta.

05:29:55.510 --> 05:29:59.910
Almost the first thing that I heard, when I got off the train in that city, was an expression

05:29:59.910 --> 05:30:02.970
something like this, from an old colored man nearby.

05:30:03.670 --> 05:30:07.750
That's to man of my race what's going to make a speech at the exposition tomorrow.

05:30:07.750 --> 05:30:09.870
I is sure going to hear him.

05:30:11.330 --> 05:30:15.130
Atlanta was literally packed at the time, with people from all parts of the country,

05:30:15.370 --> 05:30:20.350
and with representatives of foreign governments, as well as with military and civic organizations.

05:30:21.130 --> 05:30:25.650
The afternoon papers had forecasts of the next day's proceedings, in flaring headlines.

05:30:26.290 --> 05:30:28.210
All this tended to add to my burden.

05:30:28.690 --> 05:30:30.370
I did not sleep much that night.

05:30:30.590 --> 05:30:34.470
The next morning, before day, I went carefully over what I planned to say.

05:30:34.470 --> 05:30:38.110
I also kneeled down and asked God's blessing upon my effort.

05:30:38.630 --> 05:30:42.490
Right here, perhaps, I ought to add that I make it a rule never to go before an audience

05:30:42.490 --> 05:30:46.910
on any occasion, without asking the blessing of God upon what I want to say.

05:30:47.570 --> 05:30:51.490
I also make it a rule to make a special preparation for each separate address.

05:30:51.950 --> 05:30:54.190
No two audiences are exactly alike.

05:30:54.530 --> 05:30:59.470
It is my aim to reach and talk to the heart of each individual audience, taking it into

05:30:59.470 --> 05:31:01.730
my confidence very much as I would a person.

05:31:02.110 --> 05:31:06.670
When I am speaking to an audience, I care little for how what I am saying is going to

05:31:06.670 --> 05:31:10.590
sound in the newspapers, or to another audience, or to an individual.

05:31:11.110 --> 05:31:15.730
At the time, the audience before me absorbs all my sympathy, thought, and energy.

05:31:16.650 --> 05:31:20.970
Early in the morning, a committee called to escort me to my place in the procession, which

05:31:20.970 --> 05:31:23.290
was to march to the exposition grounds.

05:31:23.910 --> 05:31:28.430
In this procession were prominent colored citizens and carriages, as well as several

05:31:28.430 --> 05:31:30.270
Negro military organizations.

05:31:30.270 --> 05:31:34.890
I noted that the exposition officials seemed to go out of their way to see that all of

05:31:34.890 --> 05:31:38.930
the colored people in the procession were properly placed and properly treated.

05:31:39.910 --> 05:31:44.230
The procession was about three hours in reaching the exposition grounds, and during all of

05:31:44.230 --> 05:31:47.890
this time the sun was shining down upon us disagreeably hot.

05:31:48.510 --> 05:31:53.390
When we reached the grounds, the heat, together with my nervous anxiety, made me feel as if

05:31:53.390 --> 05:31:57.770
I were about ready to collapse, and to feel that my address was not going to be a success.

05:31:58.170 --> 05:32:02.550
When I entered the audience room, I found it packed with humanity from bottom to top,

05:32:02.850 --> 05:32:05.530
and there were thousands outside who could not get in.

05:32:06.110 --> 05:32:09.290
The room was very large, and well suited to public speaking.

05:32:09.810 --> 05:32:13.670
When I entered the room, there were vigorous cheers from the colored portion of the audience,

05:32:14.050 --> 05:32:16.190
and faint cheers from some of the white people.

05:32:16.630 --> 05:32:20.790
I had been told, while I had been in Atlanta, that while many white people were going to

05:32:20.790 --> 05:32:25.350
be present to hear me speak simply out of curiosity, and that others who would be present

05:32:25.350 --> 05:32:29.610
would be in full sympathy with me, there was a still larger element of the audience which

05:32:29.610 --> 05:32:33.610
would consist of those who were going to be present for the purpose of hearing me make

05:32:33.610 --> 05:32:38.850
a fool of myself, or at least of hearing me say some foolish thing, so that they could

05:32:38.850 --> 05:32:42.370
say to the officials who had invited me to speak, I told you so.

05:32:43.290 --> 05:32:48.470
One of the trustees of the Tuskegee Institute, as well as my personal friend, Mr. William

05:32:48.470 --> 05:32:53.790
H. Baldwin, Jr., was at the time General Manager of the Southern Railroad, and happened to

05:32:53.790 --> 05:32:55.350
in Atlanta on that day.

05:32:55.650 --> 05:33:00.090
He was so nervous about the kind of reception that I would have, and the effect that my

05:33:00.090 --> 05:33:04.330
speech would produce, that he could not persuade himself to go into the building, but walked

05:33:04.330 --> 05:33:08.710
back and forth in the grounds outside until the opening exercises were over.

05:33:30.430 --> 05:33:34.410
XIV. The Atlanta Exposition Address.

05:33:35.110 --> 05:33:39.130
The Atlanta Exposition, at which I had been asked to make an address as a representative

05:33:39.130 --> 05:33:45.030
of the Negro race, as stated in the last chapter, was opened with a short address from Governor Bullock.

05:33:45.550 --> 05:33:50.450
After other interesting exercises, including an invocation from Bishop Nelson of Georgia,

05:33:50.710 --> 05:33:55.470
a dedicatory owed by Albert Howell, Jr., and addresses by the President of the Exposition,

05:33:55.650 --> 05:33:59.850
and Mrs. Joseph Thompson, the President of the Woman's Board, Governor Bullock introduced me

05:33:59.850 --> 05:34:06.010
with the words, We have with us today a representative of Negro enterprise and Negro civilization.

05:34:07.110 --> 05:34:12.010
When I arose to speak there was considerable cheering, especially from the colored people.

05:34:12.590 --> 05:34:17.270
As I remember it now, the thing that was uppermost in my mind was the desire to say something that

05:34:17.270 --> 05:34:22.070
would cement the friendship of the races and bring about hearty cooperation between them.

05:34:22.230 --> 05:34:27.010
So far as my outward surroundings were concerned, the only thing that I recall distinctly now

05:34:27.010 --> 05:34:31.270
is that when I got up I saw thousands of eyes looking intently into my face.

05:34:31.590 --> 05:34:33.750
The following is the address which I delivered.

05:34:35.010 --> 05:34:38.870
Mr. President, and gentlemen of the Board of Directors and Citizens,

05:34:39.730 --> 05:34:43.070
one third of the population of the South is of the Negro race.

05:34:43.870 --> 05:34:48.690
No enterprise seeking the material, civil, or moral welfare of this section can disregard

05:34:48.690 --> 05:34:51.830
this element of our population and reach the highest success.

05:34:52.230 --> 05:34:57.890
I but convey to you, Mr. President and Directors, the sentiment of the masses of my race when I say

05:34:57.890 --> 05:35:02.950
that in no way have the value and manhood of the American Negro been more fittingly and generously

05:35:02.950 --> 05:35:08.510
recognized than by the managers of this magnificent exposition at every stage of its progress.

05:35:08.830 --> 05:35:12.550
It is a recognition that will do more to cement the friendship of the two races

05:35:12.550 --> 05:35:15.030
than any occurrence since the dawn of our freedom.

05:35:15.350 --> 05:35:20.550
Not only this, but the opportunity here afforded will awaken among us a new era of industrial

05:35:20.550 --> 05:35:26.610
progress. Ignorant and inexperienced, it is not strange that in the first years of our new life

05:35:26.610 --> 05:35:31.890
we began at the top instead of at the bottom, that a seat in Congress or the State Legislature

05:35:31.890 --> 05:35:36.970
was more sought than real estate or industrial skill, that the political convention or stump

05:35:36.970 --> 05:35:41.090
speaking had more attractions than starting a dairy farm or a truck garden.

05:35:42.310 --> 05:35:46.190
A ship lost at sea for many days suddenly sighted a friendly vessel.

05:35:46.810 --> 05:35:49.450
From the mast of the unfortunate vessel was seen a signal,

05:35:49.630 --> 05:35:55.850
Water, water, we die of thirst. The answer from the friendly vessel at once came back,

05:35:55.850 --> 05:35:59.810
Cast down your bucket where you are. A second time the signal,

05:35:59.850 --> 05:36:04.470
Water, water, send us water, ran up from the distressed vessel and was answered,

05:36:04.870 --> 05:36:09.650
Cast down your bucket where you are. And a third and fourth signal for water was answered,

05:36:09.830 --> 05:36:13.810
Cast down your bucket where you are. The captain of the distressed vessel,

05:36:13.910 --> 05:36:18.010
at last heeding the injunction, cast down his bucket and it came up full of fresh,

05:36:18.190 --> 05:36:23.130
sparkling water from the mouth of the Amazon River. To those of my race who depend on

05:36:23.130 --> 05:36:27.570
their condition in a foreign land, or who underestimate the importance of cultivating

05:36:27.570 --> 05:36:31.890
friendly relations with a southern white man, who is their next door neighbour, I would say,

05:36:32.270 --> 05:36:37.010
Cast down your bucket where you are. Cast it down in making friends in every manly way,

05:36:37.130 --> 05:36:41.330
of the people of all races by whom we are surrounded. Cast it down in agriculture,

05:36:41.710 --> 05:36:46.630
mechanics, in commerce, in domestic service and in the professions. And in this connection it is

05:36:46.630 --> 05:36:51.030
well to bear in mind that whatever other sins the South may be called to bear, when it comes to

05:36:51.030 --> 05:36:55.570
pure and simple business, it is in the South that the Negro is given a man's chance in the

05:36:55.570 --> 05:37:00.530
commercial world, and in nothing is this exposition more eloquent than in emphasising this chance.

05:37:00.750 --> 05:37:05.630
Our greatest danger is that, in the great leap from slavery to freedom, we may overlook the fact

05:37:05.630 --> 05:37:10.950
that the masses of us are to live by the production of our hands, and fail to keep in mind that we

05:37:10.950 --> 05:37:16.350
shall prosper in proportion as we learn to dignify and glorify common labour, and put brains and

05:37:16.350 --> 05:37:21.190
skill into the common occupations of life, shall prosper in proportion as we learn to draw the

05:37:21.190 --> 05:37:25.970
line between the superficial and the substantial, the ornamental gougas of life and the useful.

05:37:26.530 --> 05:37:31.650
No race can prosper till it learns that there is as much dignity in tilling a field as in writing

05:37:31.650 --> 05:37:37.470
a poem. It is at the bottom of life we must begin, and not at the top, nor should we permit our

05:37:37.470 --> 05:37:42.150
grievances to overshadow our opportunities. To those of the white race who look to the

05:37:42.150 --> 05:37:46.890
those of foreign birth and strange tongue and habits of the prosperity of the South,

05:37:46.990 --> 05:37:52.810
were I permitted, I would repeat what I say to my own race. Cast down your bucket where you are.

05:37:53.430 --> 05:37:58.550
Cast it down among the eight millions of Negroes whose habits you know, whose fidelity and love

05:37:58.550 --> 05:38:03.150
you have tested in days when to have proved treacherous meant the ruin of your firesides.

05:38:03.430 --> 05:38:07.710
Cast down your bucket among these people who have, without strikes and labour wars,

05:38:07.710 --> 05:38:12.790
tilled your fields, cleared your forests, built your railroads and cities, and brought forth

05:38:12.790 --> 05:38:17.330
treasures from the bowels of the earth, and helped make possible this magnificent representation of

05:38:17.330 --> 05:38:22.510
the progress of the South. Casting down your bucket among my people, helping and encouraging

05:38:22.510 --> 05:38:28.370
them as you are doing on these grounds, and to education of head, hand, and heart, you will find

05:38:28.370 --> 05:38:32.990
that they will buy your surplus land, make blossom the waste places in your fields, and run your

05:38:32.990 --> 05:38:38.350
factories. While doing this, you can be sure in the future, as in the past, that you and your

05:38:38.350 --> 05:38:43.350
families will be surrounded by the most patient, faithful, law-abiding, and unresentful people that

05:38:43.350 --> 05:38:48.470
the world has seen. As we have proved our loyalty to you in the past, nursing your children,

05:38:48.670 --> 05:38:52.910
watching by the sick bed of your mothers and fathers, and often following them with tear-dimmed

05:38:52.910 --> 05:38:57.750
eyes to their graves, so in the future, in our humble way, we shall stand by you with a devotion

05:38:57.750 --> 05:39:02.550
that no foreigner can approach, ready to lay down our lives if need be in defense of yours,

05:39:03.150 --> 05:39:07.490
interlacing our industrial, commercial, civil, and religious life with yours in a way that

05:39:07.490 --> 05:39:12.630
shall make the interests of both races one. In all things that are purely social, we can be

05:39:12.630 --> 05:39:18.350
as separate as the fingers, yet one is the hand in all things essential to mutual progress.

05:39:18.990 --> 05:39:23.990
There is no defense or security for any of us, except in the highest intelligence and development

05:39:23.990 --> 05:39:28.270
of all. If anywhere there are efforts tending to curtail the fullest growth of the negro,

05:39:28.510 --> 05:39:32.970
let these efforts be turned into stimulating, encouraging, and making him the most useful

05:39:32.970 --> 05:39:37.850
and intelligent citizen. Efforts or means so invested will pay a thousand percent interest.

05:39:37.970 --> 05:39:42.390
These efforts will be twice blessed, blessing him that gives and him that takes.

05:39:42.850 --> 05:39:46.030
There is no escape through law of man or God from the inevitable.

05:39:46.630 --> 05:39:49.870
The laws of changeless justice bind, oppressor with oppressed,

05:39:49.870 --> 05:39:53.710
and close as sin and suffering joined, we march to fate abreast.

05:39:54.950 --> 05:39:58.630
Nearly sixteen millions of hands will aid you in pulling the load upward,

05:39:58.870 --> 05:40:03.310
or they will pull against you the load downward. We shall constitute one-third and more of the

05:40:03.310 --> 05:40:07.990
ignorance and crime of the South, or one-third its intelligence and progress. We shall contribute

05:40:07.990 --> 05:40:12.690
one-third to the business and industrial prosperity of the South, or we shall prove a veritable body

05:40:12.690 --> 05:40:17.230
of death, stagnating, depressing, retarding every effort to advance the body politic.

05:40:17.890 --> 05:40:22.990
Gentlemen of the Exposition, as we present you our humble effort at an exhibition of our progress,

05:40:23.430 --> 05:40:28.310
you must not expect over much. Starting thirty years ago with ownership here and there in a

05:40:28.310 --> 05:40:33.290
few quilts and pumpkins and chickens gathered from miscellaneous sources, remember the path that has

05:40:33.290 --> 05:40:38.910
led from these to the inventions and production of agricultural implements, buggies, steam engines,

05:40:39.150 --> 05:40:44.170
newspapers, books, statuary, carving, paintings, the management of drug stores and banks,

05:40:44.170 --> 05:40:49.410
has not been trodden without contact with thorns and thistles. While we take pride in what we

05:40:49.410 --> 05:40:54.070
exhibit as a result of our independent efforts, we do not for a moment forget that our part in

05:40:54.070 --> 05:40:58.970
this exhibition would fall far short of your expectations but for the constant help that has

05:40:58.970 --> 05:41:03.350
come to our education life, not only from the Southern States but especially from Northern

05:41:03.350 --> 05:41:07.890
philanthropists who have made their gifts a constant stream of blessing and encouragement.

05:41:08.230 --> 05:41:13.330
The wisest among my race understand that the agitation of questions of social equality is

05:41:13.330 --> 05:41:17.590
extremist folly, and that progress and the enjoyment of all the privileges that will come

05:41:17.590 --> 05:41:23.190
to us must be the result of severe and constant struggle rather than of artificial forcing.

05:41:23.410 --> 05:41:27.850
No race that has anything to contribute to the markets of the world is long in any degree

05:41:27.850 --> 05:41:34.290
ostracized. It is important and right that all privileges of the law be ours, but it is vastly

05:41:34.290 --> 05:41:39.090
more important that we be prepared for the exercises of these privileges. The opportunity

05:41:39.090 --> 05:41:44.210
to earn a dollar in a factory just now is worth infinitely more than the opportunity to spend a

05:41:44.210 --> 05:41:50.190
dollar in an opera house. In conclusion, may I repeat that nothing in thirty years has given

05:41:50.190 --> 05:41:55.630
us more hope and encouragement, and drawn us so near to you of the white race, as this opportunity

05:41:55.630 --> 05:42:00.310
offered by the exposition, and here bending, as it were, over the altar that represents the

05:42:00.310 --> 05:42:04.750
results of the struggles of your race and mine, both starting practically empty-handed three

05:42:04.750 --> 05:42:09.050
decades ago, I pledge that in your effort to work out the great and intricate problem which

05:42:09.050 --> 05:42:13.890
God has laid at the doors of the South, you shall have at all times the patient, sympathetic help

05:42:13.890 --> 05:42:19.150
of my race. Only let this be constantly in mind, that while from the representations in these

05:42:19.150 --> 05:42:24.870
buildings of the product of field, of forest, of mine, of factory, letters, and art, much good

05:42:24.870 --> 05:42:34.430
will come, yet far above and beyond material benefits will be that higher good, that, let us

05:42:34.430 --> 05:42:40.930
be in a determination to administer absolute justice in a willing obedience among all classes

05:42:40.930 --> 05:42:46.990
to the mandates of law. This, coupled with our material prosperity, will bring into our beloved

05:42:46.990 --> 05:42:54.150
South a new heaven and a new earth. The first thing that I remember after I had finished speaking

05:42:54.150 --> 05:42:58.270
was that Governor Bullock rushed across the platform and took me by the hand and that others

05:42:58.270 --> 05:43:03.490
did the same. I received so many and such hearty congratulations that I found it difficult to get

05:43:03.490 --> 05:43:08.170
out of the building. I did not appreciate to any degree, however, the impression which my address

05:43:08.170 --> 05:43:12.730
seemed to have made until the next morning when I went into the business part of the city. As soon

05:43:12.730 --> 05:43:17.470
as I was recognized I was surprised to find myself pointed out and surrounded by a crowd of men who

05:43:17.470 --> 05:43:22.230
wished to shake hands with me. This was kept up on every street onto which I went, to an extent

05:43:22.230 --> 05:43:26.670
which embarrassed me so much that I went back to my boarding place. The next morning I returned

05:43:26.670 --> 05:43:30.910
to Tuskegee. At the station in Atlanta and at almost all of the stations at which the trains

05:43:30.910 --> 05:43:35.250
stopped between that city and Tuskegee I found a crowd of people anxious to shake hands with me.

05:43:35.310 --> 05:43:39.510
The papers in all parts of the United States published the address in full and for months

05:43:39.510 --> 05:43:44.090
afterwards there were complementary editorial references to it. Mr. Carr Cowell, the editor

05:43:44.090 --> 05:43:48.610
of the Atlanta Constitution, telegraphed to a New York paper among other words the following.

05:43:49.510 --> 05:43:54.530
I do not exaggerate when I say that Professor Booker T. Washington's address yesterday was one

05:43:54.530 --> 05:43:58.830
of the most notable speeches, both as to character and as to the warmth of its reception,

05:43:58.830 --> 05:44:03.870
ever delivered to a southern audience. The address was a revelation. The whole speech

05:44:03.870 --> 05:44:08.610
is a platform upon which blacks and whites can stand with full justice to each other.

05:44:09.490 --> 05:44:11.550
The Boston transcript said editorially,

05:44:12.310 --> 05:44:16.550
The speech of Booker T. Washington at the Atlanta Exposition this week seems to have

05:44:16.550 --> 05:44:20.250
dwarfed all other proceedings and the Exposition itself. The sensation that

05:44:20.250 --> 05:44:22.590
it has caused in the press has never been equaled.

05:44:23.950 --> 05:44:28.290
I very soon began receiving all kinds of propositions from lecture bureaus and editors

05:44:28.290 --> 05:44:33.390
of magazines and papers to take the lecture platform and to write articles. One lecture

05:44:33.390 --> 05:44:39.250
bureau offered me $50,000 or $200 a night in expenses if I would place my services at its

05:44:39.250 --> 05:44:43.850
disposal for a given period. To all these communications I replied that my life work

05:44:43.850 --> 05:44:48.850
was at Tuskegee and that whenever I spoke it must be in the interests of Tuskegee School and my race

05:44:48.850 --> 05:44:52.530
and that I would enter into no arrangements that seemed to place a mere commercial value

05:44:52.530 --> 05:44:57.510
upon my services. Some days after its delivery I sent a copy of my address to the President

05:44:57.510 --> 05:45:01.930
of the United States, the Honorable Grover Cleveland. I received from him the following

05:45:01.930 --> 05:45:03.130
autograph reply.

05:45:04.330 --> 05:45:09.750
Greg Abels, Buzzards Bay, Massachusetts October 6, 1895

05:45:09.750 --> 05:45:12.050
Booker T. Washington, Esquire

05:45:12.050 --> 05:45:17.910
My dear sir, I thank you for sending me a copy of your address delivered at the Atlanta Exposition.

05:45:18.110 --> 05:45:23.090
I thank you with much enthusiasm for making the address. I have read it with intense interest

05:45:23.090 --> 05:45:27.230
and I think the Exposition would be fully justified if it did not do more than furnish

05:45:27.230 --> 05:45:32.490
the opportunity for its delivery. Your words cannot fail to delight and encourage all who wish well

05:45:32.490 --> 05:45:37.510
for your race, and if our colored fellow citizens do not from your utterances gather new hope and

05:45:37.510 --> 05:45:41.750
form new determinations to gain every valuable advantage offered them by their citizenship,

05:45:42.310 --> 05:45:47.110
it will be strange indeed. Yours very truly, Grover Cleveland

05:45:48.630 --> 05:45:54.110
Later I met Mr. Cleveland for the first time when, as President, he visited the Atlanta Exposition.

05:45:54.110 --> 05:45:59.010
At the request of myself and others he consented to spend an hour in the Negro building for the

05:45:59.010 --> 05:46:02.950
purpose of inspecting the Negro exhibit and of giving the colored people in attendance an

05:46:02.950 --> 05:46:07.390
opportunity to shake hands with him. As soon as I met Mr. Cleveland I became impressed with his

05:46:07.390 --> 05:46:12.630
simplicity, greatness, and rugged honesty. I have met him many times since then, both at public

05:46:12.630 --> 05:46:17.250
functions and at his private residence in Princeton, and the more I see of him the more I admire him.

05:46:17.310 --> 05:46:21.750
When he visited the Negro building in Atlanta he seemed to give himself up wholly, for that hour,

05:46:21.750 --> 05:46:26.010
to the colored people. He seemed to be as careful to shake hands with some old colored auntie,

05:46:26.130 --> 05:46:30.250
clad partially in rags, and to take as much pleasure in doing so as if he were greeting

05:46:30.250 --> 05:46:34.890
some millionaire. Many of the colored people took advantage of the occasion to get him to write his

05:46:34.890 --> 05:46:39.930
name in a book or on a slip of paper. He was as careful and patient in doing this as if he

05:46:39.930 --> 05:46:44.530
were putting his signature to some great state document. Mr. Cleveland has not only shown his

05:46:44.530 --> 05:46:49.350
friendship for me in many personal ways, but has always consented to do anything I have asked of

05:46:49.350 --> 05:46:54.190
him for our school. This he has done, whether it was to make a personal donation or to use his

05:46:54.190 --> 05:46:58.790
influence in securing the donations of others. Judging from my personal acquaintance with Mr.

05:46:58.970 --> 05:47:04.150
Cleveland I do not believe that he is conscious of possessing any color prejudice. He is too great

05:47:04.150 --> 05:47:09.810
for that. In my contact with people I find that, as a rule, it is only the little and narrow people

05:47:09.810 --> 05:47:15.030
who live for themselves, who never read good books, who do not travel, who never open up their souls

05:47:15.030 --> 05:47:19.190
in a way to permit them to come into contact with other souls with the great outside world.

05:47:19.310 --> 05:47:24.050
No man whose vision is bounded by color can come into contact with what is highest and best in the

05:47:24.050 --> 05:47:28.910
world. In meeting men in many places I have found that the happiest people are those who do the most

05:47:28.910 --> 05:47:34.490
for others. The most miserable are those who do the least. I have also found that few things,

05:47:34.490 --> 05:47:40.310
if any, are capable of making one so blind and narrow as race prejudice. I have often said to

05:47:40.310 --> 05:47:44.890
our students in the course of my talks to them on Sunday evenings in the chapel that the longer I

05:47:44.890 --> 05:47:49.730
live and the more experience I have of the world, the more I am convinced that, after all, the one

05:47:49.730 --> 05:47:54.870
thing that is most worth living for, and dying for if need be, is the opportunity of making someone

05:47:54.870 --> 05:48:01.330
else more happy and more useful. The colored people and the colored newspapers at first seemed

05:48:01.330 --> 05:48:05.510
to be greatly pleased with the character of my Atlanta address as well as with its reception,

05:48:05.710 --> 05:48:10.590
but after the first burst of enthusiasm began to die away and the colored people began reading the

05:48:10.590 --> 05:48:15.610
speech in cold type, some of them seemed to feel that they had been hypnotized. They seemed to feel

05:48:15.610 --> 05:48:20.750
that I had been too liberal in my remarks toward the Southern whites and that I had not spoken out

05:48:20.750 --> 05:48:25.870
strongly enough for what they termed the rights of my race. For a while there was reaction, so far as

05:48:25.870 --> 05:48:30.590
a certain element of my own race was concerned, but later these reactionary ones seemed to have

05:48:30.590 --> 05:48:36.170
been won over to my way of believing and acting. While speaking of changes in public sentiment,

05:48:36.170 --> 05:48:41.010
I recall that about ten years after the school at Tuskegee was established I had an experience

05:48:41.010 --> 05:48:46.650
that I shall never forget. Dr. Lyman Abbott, then the pastor of Plymouth Church and also editor of

05:48:46.650 --> 05:48:51.910
The Outlook, then the Christian Union, asked me to write a letter for his paper giving my opinion of

05:48:51.910 --> 05:48:57.050
the exact condition, mental and moral, of the colored ministers in the South as based upon my

05:48:57.050 --> 05:49:02.530
observations. I wrote the letter giving the exact facts as I conceived them to be. The picture

05:49:02.530 --> 05:49:08.150
painted was a rather black one, or since I am black shall I say white. It could not be otherwise

05:49:08.150 --> 05:49:13.490
with a race but a few years out of slavery, a race which had not had time or opportunity to produce

05:49:13.490 --> 05:49:18.190
a competent ministry. What I said soon reached every Negro ministry in the country, I think,

05:49:18.290 --> 05:49:22.650
and the letters of condemnation which I received from them were not few. I think that for a year

05:49:22.650 --> 05:49:27.310
after the publication of this article every association and every conference or religious

05:49:27.310 --> 05:49:32.870
of any kind of my race that met did not fail before adjourning to pass a resolution condemning

05:49:32.870 --> 05:49:38.770
me or calling upon me to retract or modify what I had said. Many of these organizations went so far

05:49:38.770 --> 05:49:43.390
in their resolutions as to advise parents to cease sending their children to Tuskegee.

05:49:43.630 --> 05:49:48.470
One association even appointed a missionary whose duty it was to warn the people against sending

05:49:48.470 --> 05:49:53.250
their children to Tuskegee. This missionary had a son in the school and I noticed that whatever

05:49:53.250 --> 05:49:57.510
the missionary might have said or done with regard to others he was careful not to take his

05:49:57.510 --> 05:50:02.670
son away from the institution. Many of the colored papers, especially those that were the organs of

05:50:02.670 --> 05:50:07.190
religious bodies, joined in the general course of condemnation and demands for retraction.

05:50:07.330 --> 05:50:11.390
During the whole time of the excitement and through all the criticism I did not utter a

05:50:11.390 --> 05:50:16.310
word of explanation or retraction. I knew that I was right and that time and the sober second

05:50:16.310 --> 05:50:20.670
thought of the people would vindicate me. It was not long before the bishops and other church

05:50:20.670 --> 05:50:25.470
leaders began to make careful investigation of the conditions of the ministry and they found out

05:50:25.470 --> 05:50:30.470
that I was right. In fact the oldest and most influential bishop in one branch of the Methodist

05:50:30.470 --> 05:50:36.170
Church said that my words were far too mild. Very soon public sentiment began making itself felt

05:50:36.170 --> 05:50:41.010
in demanding a purifying of the ministry. While this is not yet complete by any means,

05:50:41.230 --> 05:50:45.990
I think I may say without egotism, and I have been told by many of our most influential ministers,

05:50:46.210 --> 05:50:50.590
that my words had much to do with starting a demand for the placing of a higher type of men

05:50:50.590 --> 05:50:55.830
in the pulpit. I have had the satisfaction of having many who once condemned me thank me

05:50:55.830 --> 05:51:00.830
heartily for my frank words. The change of the attitude of the Negro ministry, so far as regards

05:51:00.830 --> 05:51:05.690
myself, is so complete that at the present time I have no warmer friends among any class than I

05:51:05.690 --> 05:51:10.070
have among the clergymen. The improvement in the character and life of the Negro ministers is one

05:51:10.070 --> 05:51:15.510
of the most gratifying evidences of the progress of the race. My experience with them, as well as

05:51:15.510 --> 05:51:19.710
other events in my life, convinced me that the thing to do, and one feels sure that he has said

05:51:19.710 --> 05:51:26.150
or done the right thing, and is condemned, is to stand still and keep quiet. If he is right,

05:51:26.350 --> 05:51:31.790
time will show it. In the midst of the discussion which was going on concerning my Atlanta speech,

05:51:31.990 --> 05:51:36.390
I received the letter which I give below from Dr. Gilman, the President of Johns Hopkins

05:51:36.390 --> 05:51:41.410
University, who had been made Chairman of the Judges of Award in connection with the Atlanta

05:51:41.950 --> 05:51:50.510
Exposition. Johns Hopkins University, Baltimore. President's Office, September 30, 1895.

05:51:51.510 --> 05:51:56.570
Dear Mr. Washington, Would it be agreeable to you to be one of the Judges of Award in

05:51:56.570 --> 05:52:01.950
the Department of Education at Atlanta? If so, I shall be glad to place your name upon the list.

05:52:02.290 --> 05:52:07.370
A line by Telegraph will be welcomed. Yours very truly, D.C. Gilman.

05:52:08.010 --> 05:52:12.450
I think I was even more surprised to receive this invitation than I had been to receive

05:52:12.450 --> 05:52:17.070
the invitation to speak at the opening of the exposition. It was to be part of my duty as one

05:52:17.070 --> 05:52:22.270
of the jurors to pass not only upon the exhibits of the colored schools, but also upon those of

05:52:22.270 --> 05:52:26.510
the white schools. I accepted the position and spent a month in Atlanta in performance

05:52:26.510 --> 05:52:31.170
of the duties which it entailed. The Board of Jurors was a large one, containing in all of

05:52:31.170 --> 05:52:35.990
sixty members. It was about equally divided between Southern white people and Northern white people.

05:52:35.990 --> 05:52:39.570
Among them were college presidents, leading scientists and men of letters,

05:52:39.950 --> 05:52:44.490
and specialists in many subjects. When the group of jurors to which I was assigned met for

05:52:44.490 --> 05:52:50.010
organization, Mr. Thomas Nelson Page, who was one of the number, moved that I be made Secretary of

05:52:50.010 --> 05:52:54.730
that division, and the motion was unanimously adopted. Nearly half of our division were

05:52:54.730 --> 05:52:59.030
Southern people. In performing my duties in the inspection of the exhibits of white schools,

05:52:59.210 --> 05:53:03.510
I was in every case treated with respect, and at the close of our labors I parted from my

05:53:03.510 --> 05:53:04.690
associates with regret.

05:53:05.870 --> 05:53:10.710
I am often asked to express myself more freely than I do upon the political condition and the

05:53:10.710 --> 05:53:15.690
political future of my race. These recollections of my experience in Atlanta give me the opportunity

05:53:15.690 --> 05:53:21.330
to do so briefly. My own belief is, although I have never before said so in so many words,

05:53:21.750 --> 05:53:25.710
that the time will come when the Negro in the South will be accorded all the political rights

05:53:25.710 --> 05:53:30.110
which his ability, character, and material possessions entitle him to. I think, though,

05:53:30.110 --> 05:53:34.690
that the opportunity to freely exercise such political rights will not come in any large

05:53:34.690 --> 05:53:39.310
degree through outside or artificial forcing, but will be accorded to the Negro by the Southern

05:53:39.310 --> 05:53:43.830
white people themselves, and that they will protect him in the exercise of those rights.

05:53:43.950 --> 05:53:48.050
Just as soon as the South gets over the old feeling that it is being forced by foreigners

05:53:48.050 --> 05:53:52.970
or aliens to do something which it does not want to do, I believe that the change in the

05:53:52.970 --> 05:53:57.590
direction that I have indicated is going to begin. In fact, there are indications that it

05:53:57.590 --> 05:54:02.750
is already beginning in a slight degree. Let me illustrate my meaning. Suppose that some

05:54:02.750 --> 05:54:06.870
months before the opening of the Atlanta Exposition there had been a general demand from the press

05:54:06.870 --> 05:54:11.390
and public platform outside the South that a Negro be given a place on the opening program,

05:54:11.390 --> 05:54:16.270
and that a Negro be placed upon the board of jurors of a ward. Would any such recognition

05:54:16.270 --> 05:54:21.290
of the race have taken place? I do not think so. The Atlanta officials went as far as they did

05:54:21.290 --> 05:54:25.810
because they felt it to be a pleasure, as well as a duty, to reward what they considered merit

05:54:25.810 --> 05:54:30.690
in the Negro race. Say what we will, there is something in human nature which we cannot blot

05:54:30.690 --> 05:54:36.450
out, which makes one man in the end recognize and reward merit in another, regardless of color or

05:54:36.450 --> 05:54:41.570
race. I believe it is the duty of the Negro, as the greater part of the race is already doing,

05:54:42.050 --> 05:54:46.430
to deport himself modestly in regard to political claims, depending upon the

05:54:46.430 --> 05:54:50.330
slow but sure influences that proceed from the possession of property, intelligence,

05:54:50.430 --> 05:54:54.830
and high character for the full recognition of his political rights. I think that the

05:54:54.830 --> 05:54:59.010
deporting of the full exercise of political rights is going to be a matter of natural

05:54:59.010 --> 05:55:04.310
slow growth, not an overnight gourd-vine affair. I do not believe that the Negro should cease

05:55:04.310 --> 05:55:08.910
voting, for a man cannot learn the exercise of self-government by ceasing to vote any more

05:55:08.910 --> 05:55:13.230
than a boy can learn to swim by keeping out of the water. But I do believe that in his voting

05:55:13.230 --> 05:55:18.230
he should more and more be influenced by those of intelligence and character who are his next door

05:55:18.230 --> 05:55:23.650
neighbors. I know colored men who, through the encouragement, help, and advice of Southern white

05:55:23.650 --> 05:55:28.410
people, have accumulated thousands of dollars worth of property, but who at the same time would

05:55:28.410 --> 05:55:32.510
never think of going to those same persons for advice concerning the casting of their ballots.

05:55:32.810 --> 05:55:38.250
This, it seems to me, is unwise and unreasonable, and should cease. In saying this I do not mean

05:55:38.250 --> 05:55:42.890
that the Negro should treacle, or not vote from principle, for the instant he ceases to vote from

05:55:42.890 --> 05:55:48.070
principle he loses the confidence and respect of the Southern white man even. I do not believe that

05:55:48.070 --> 05:55:51.910
any state should make a law that permits an ignorant and poverty-stricken white man to vote,

05:55:51.910 --> 05:55:56.590
and prevents a black man in the same condition from voting. Such a law is not only unjust,

05:55:56.790 --> 05:56:01.930
but it will react, as all unjust laws do, in time, for the effect of such a law is to encourage the

05:56:01.930 --> 05:56:06.930
Negro to secure education and property, and at the same time it encourages the white man to remain

05:56:06.930 --> 05:56:12.350
in ignorance and poverty. I believe that in time, through the operation of intelligence and friendly

05:56:12.350 --> 05:56:17.150
race relations, all cheating at the ballot box in the South will cease. It will become apparent

05:56:17.150 --> 05:56:21.750
that the white man who begins by cheating a Negro out of his ballot soon learns to cheat a white man

05:56:21.750 --> 05:56:26.790
out of his, and that the man who does this ends his career of dishonesty by the theft of property

05:56:26.790 --> 05:56:31.670
or by some equally serious crime. In my opinion, the time will come when the South will encourage

05:56:31.670 --> 05:56:36.930
all of its citizens to vote. It will see that it pays better, from every standpoint, to have healthy,

05:56:37.170 --> 05:56:42.190
vigorous life, than to have that political stagnation which always results when one half

05:56:42.190 --> 05:56:47.990
of the population has no share and no interest in the government. As a rule I believe in universal

05:56:47.990 --> 05:56:52.630
free suffrage, but I believe that in the South we are confronted with peculiar conditions that

05:56:52.630 --> 05:56:58.010
justify the protection of the ballot in many of the States, for a while at least, either by an

05:56:58.010 --> 05:57:02.650
education test, a property test, or by both combined, but whatever tests are required,

05:57:02.750 --> 05:57:06.230
they should be made to apply with equal and exact justice to both races.

05:57:19.190 --> 05:57:20.590
you

05:57:23.770 --> 05:57:24.410
15.

05:57:43.410 --> 05:57:46.610
THE SECRET OF SUCCESS IN PUBLIC SPEAKING.

05:57:47.450 --> 05:57:51.630
As to how my address at Atlanta was received by the audience in the Exposition Building,

05:57:51.630 --> 05:57:56.710
I think I prefer to let Mr. James Creelman, the noted war correspondent, tell.

05:57:57.290 --> 05:58:01.490
Mr. Creelman was present and telegraphed the following account to the New York World.

05:58:02.150 --> 05:58:07.550
Atlanta, September 18. While President Cleveland was waiting at Gray Gables today

05:58:07.550 --> 05:58:12.090
to send the electric spark that started the machinery of the Atlanta Exposition,

05:58:12.610 --> 05:58:21.090
a Negro Moses stood before a great audience of white people and delivered an oration that

05:58:21.090 --> 05:58:25.490
marched in a procession with the citizen soldiery of Georgia and Louisiana.

05:58:26.270 --> 05:58:30.210
The whole city is thrilling tonight with the realization of the extraordinary significance

05:58:30.210 --> 05:58:35.550
of these two unprecedented events. Nothing has happened since Henry Grady's immortal speech

05:58:35.550 --> 05:58:40.290
before the New England Society in New York that indicates so profoundly the spirit of the New

05:58:40.290 --> 05:58:46.350
South, except perhaps the opening of the Exposition itself. When Professor Booker T. Washington,

05:58:46.350 --> 05:58:50.470
principal of an industrial school for colored people in Tuskegee, Alabama,

05:58:50.710 --> 05:58:55.070
stood on the platform of the auditorium, with the sun shining over the heads of his auditors

05:58:55.070 --> 05:58:59.010
into his eyes, and with his whole face lit up with a fire of prophecy,

05:58:59.590 --> 05:59:02.390
Clark Howell, the successor of Henry Grady, said to me,

05:59:02.750 --> 05:59:06.570
That man's speech is the beginning of a moral revolution in America.

05:59:07.290 --> 05:59:11.750
It is the first time that a Negro has made a speech in the South on any important occasion

05:59:11.750 --> 05:59:16.350
before an audience composed of white men and women. It electrified the audience,

05:59:16.510 --> 05:59:19.790
and the response was as if it had come from the throat of a whirlwind.

05:59:20.590 --> 05:59:24.790
Mrs. Thompson had hardly taken her seat when all eyes were turned on a tall,

05:59:25.130 --> 05:59:29.830
tawny Negro sitting in the front row of the platform. It was Professor Booker T. Washington,

05:59:30.170 --> 05:59:34.410
president of the Tuskegee, Alabama, Normal and Industrial Institute,

05:59:34.690 --> 05:59:38.550
who must rank from this time forth as the foremost man of his race in America.

05:59:39.310 --> 05:59:42.850
Gilmore's band played the Star-Spangled Banner, and the audience cheered.

05:59:43.290 --> 05:59:46.670
The tune changed to Dixie, and the audience roared with shrill,

05:59:46.810 --> 05:59:52.290
High yeas. Again the music changed, this time to Yankee Doodle, and the clamor lessened.

05:59:52.970 --> 05:59:57.130
All this time the eyes of the thousands present looked straight at the Negro orator.

05:59:57.650 --> 06:00:02.650
A strange thing was to happen. A black man was to speak for his people, with none to interrupt him.

06:00:03.250 --> 06:00:06.130
As Professor Washington strode to the edge of the stage,

06:00:06.130 --> 06:00:10.730
the low descending sun shot fiery rays through the windows into his face.

06:00:11.290 --> 06:00:14.910
A great shout greeted him. He turned his head to avoid the blinding light,

06:00:14.990 --> 06:00:18.910
and moved about the platform for relief. Then he turned his wonderful countenance

06:00:18.910 --> 06:00:21.690
to the sun without a blink of the eyelids, and began to talk.

06:00:22.410 --> 06:00:26.970
There was a remarkable figure. Tall, bony, straight as a Sioux chief,

06:00:27.410 --> 06:00:33.010
high forehead, straight nose, heavy jaws, and strong, determined mouth, with big white teeth,

06:00:33.010 --> 06:00:38.190
piercing eyes, and a commanding manner. The Siouxs stood out on his bronzed neck,

06:00:38.490 --> 06:00:43.250
and his muscular right arm swung high in the air, with a lead pencil grasped in the clenched brown

06:00:43.250 --> 06:00:48.230
fist. His big feet were planted squarely, with the heels together and the toes turned out.

06:00:48.610 --> 06:00:53.170
His voice ranged out clear and true, and he paused impressively as he made each point.

06:00:53.790 --> 06:00:56.990
Within ten minutes the multitude was in an uproar of enthusiasm.

06:00:57.550 --> 06:01:01.030
Handkerchiefs were waved, canes were flourished, hats were tossed in the air.

06:01:01.030 --> 06:01:06.030
The fairest women of Georgia stood up and cheered. It was as if the orator had bewitched them.

06:01:06.730 --> 06:01:11.710
And when he held his dusky hand high above his head, with the fingers stretched wide apart,

06:01:12.070 --> 06:01:14.930
and said to the white people of the south on behalf of his race,

06:01:15.370 --> 06:01:18.690
In all things that are purely social we can be as separate as the fingers,

06:01:18.990 --> 06:01:22.170
yet one is the hand in all things essential to mutual progress,

06:01:22.490 --> 06:01:27.910
the great wave of sound dashed itself against the walls, and the whole audience was on its feet in

06:01:27.910 --> 06:01:32.490
delirium of applause, and I thought at that moment of the night when Henry Grady stood

06:01:32.490 --> 06:01:36.810
among the curling wreaths of tobacco smoke in Delmonico's banquet hall and said,

06:01:37.150 --> 06:01:42.330
I am a cavalier among roundheads. I have heard the great orators of many countries,

06:01:42.630 --> 06:01:46.750
but not even Gladstone himself could have pleaded a cause with most consummate power

06:01:46.750 --> 06:01:51.610
than did this angular negro, standing in a nimbus of sunshine, surrounded by the

06:01:51.610 --> 06:01:56.030
men who once fought to keep his race in bondage. The roar might swell ever so high,

06:01:56.030 --> 06:02:01.090
but the expression of his earnest face never changed. A ragged ebony giant,

06:02:01.430 --> 06:02:05.830
squatted on the floor in one of the aisles, watched the order with burning eyes and tremulous

06:02:05.830 --> 06:02:10.470
face until the supreme burst of applause came, and then the tears ran down his face.

06:02:11.010 --> 06:02:14.870
Most of the negroes in the audience were crying, perhaps without knowing just why.

06:02:15.570 --> 06:02:19.650
At the close of the speech, Governor Bullock rushed across the stage and seized the order's

06:02:19.650 --> 06:02:24.770
hand. Another shout greeted this demonstration, and for a few minutes the two men stood facing

06:02:24.770 --> 06:02:30.270
each other, hand in hand. So far as I could spare the time from the immediate work at Tuskegee,

06:02:30.630 --> 06:02:35.510
after my Atlanta address I accepted some of the invitations to speak in public which came to me,

06:02:35.850 --> 06:02:40.050
especially those that would take me into territory where I thought it would pay to plead the cause

06:02:40.050 --> 06:02:44.510
of my race, but I always did this with the understanding that I was to be free to talk

06:02:44.510 --> 06:02:49.850
about my life work and the needs of my people. I also had it understood that I was not to speak

06:02:49.850 --> 06:02:53.930
in the capacity of a professional lecturer or for mere commercial gain.

06:02:54.430 --> 06:02:59.050
In my efforts on the public platform I have never been able to understand why people come

06:02:59.050 --> 06:03:04.210
to hear me speak. This question I can never rid myself of. Time and time again, as I have stood

06:03:04.210 --> 06:03:08.570
in the street in front of a building and have seen men and women passing in large numbers into the

06:03:08.570 --> 06:03:12.870
audience room where I was to speak, I have felt ashamed that I should be the cause of people,

06:03:12.870 --> 06:03:18.450
as it seemed to me, wasting a valuable hour of their time. Some years ago I was to deliver an

06:03:18.450 --> 06:03:23.770
address before a literary society in Madison, Wisconsin. An hour before the time set for me to

06:03:23.770 --> 06:03:29.530
speak, a fierce snowstorm began and continued for several hours. I made up my mind that there would

06:03:29.530 --> 06:03:34.430
be no audience and that I should not have to speak, but as a matter of duty I went to the church and

06:03:34.430 --> 06:03:38.810
found it packed with people. The surprise gave me a shock that I did not recover from during the

06:03:38.810 --> 06:03:44.410
whole evening. People often ask me if I feel nervous before speaking, or else they suggest that

06:03:44.410 --> 06:03:49.590
since I speak often they suppose that I get used to it. In answer to this question I have to say

06:03:49.590 --> 06:03:54.750
that I always suffer intensely from nervousness before speaking. More than once, just before I was

06:03:54.750 --> 06:03:59.750
to make an important address, this nervous strain has been so great that I have resolved never again

06:03:59.750 --> 06:04:05.450
to speak in public. I not only feel nervous before speaking, but after I have finished I usually feel

06:04:05.450 --> 06:04:10.390
a sense of regret, because it seems to me as if I had left out of my address the main thing and the

06:04:10.390 --> 06:04:15.550
best thing that I had meant to say. There is a great compensation, though, for this preliminary

06:04:15.550 --> 06:04:20.210
nervous suffering that comes to me after I have been speaking for about ten minutes and have come

06:04:20.210 --> 06:04:24.030
to feel that I have really mastered my audience and that we have gotten into full and complete

06:04:24.030 --> 06:04:28.770
sympathy with each other. It seems to me that there is rarely such a combination of mental and

06:04:28.770 --> 06:04:33.510
physical delight in any effort as that which comes to a public speaker when he feels that he has a

06:04:33.510 --> 06:04:38.590
great audience completely within his control. There is a thread of sympathy and oneness that

06:04:38.590 --> 06:04:43.150
connects the public speaker with his audience that is just as strong as though it was something

06:04:43.150 --> 06:04:48.690
tangible and visible. If in an audience of a thousand people there is one person who is not

06:04:48.690 --> 06:04:53.730
in sympathy with my views or is inclined to be doubtful, cold, or critical, I can pick him out.

06:04:54.090 --> 06:04:58.890
When I have found him I usually go straight at him, and it is a great satisfaction to watch the

06:04:58.890 --> 06:05:03.970
process of his thawing out. I find that the most effective medicine for such individuals is

06:05:03.970 --> 06:05:08.870
administered at first in the form of a story, although I never tell an anecdote simply for

06:05:08.870 --> 06:05:13.910
the sake of telling one. That kind of thing, I think, is empty and hollow, and an audience

06:05:13.910 --> 06:05:19.150
soon finds it out. I believe that one always does himself and his audience an injustice when

06:05:19.150 --> 06:05:24.490
he speaks merely for the sake of speaking. I do not believe that one should speak unless, deep down

06:05:24.490 --> 06:05:29.170
in his heart, he feels convinced that he has a message to deliver. When one feels, from the

06:05:29.170 --> 06:05:33.430
bottom of his heart to the top of his head, that he has something to say that is going to help some

06:05:33.430 --> 06:05:38.610
individual, or some cause, then let him say it, and in delivering his message I do not believe

06:05:38.610 --> 06:05:43.990
that many of the artificial rules of elocution can, under such circumstances, help him very much.

06:05:44.510 --> 06:05:48.270
Although there are certain things, such as pauses, breathing, and pitch of voice,

06:05:48.290 --> 06:05:52.250
that are very important, none of these can take the place of soul in an address.

06:05:52.850 --> 06:05:57.210
When I have an address to deliver, I like to forget all about the rules for the proper use

06:05:57.210 --> 06:06:01.350
of the English language, and all about rhetoric and that sort of thing, and I like to make the

06:06:01.350 --> 06:06:06.430
audience forget all about these things, too. Nothing tends to throw me off my balance so quickly

06:06:06.430 --> 06:06:12.230
when I am speaking as to have someone leave the room. To prevent this, I make up my mind as a rule

06:06:12.230 --> 06:06:17.050
that I will try to make my address so interesting, will try to state so many interesting facts,

06:06:17.090 --> 06:06:21.790
one after another, that no one can leave. The average audience, I have come to believe,

06:06:21.990 --> 06:06:27.690
wants facts rather than generalities or sermonizing. Most people, I think, are able to drop proper

06:06:27.690 --> 06:06:31.570
conclusions if they are given the facts in an interesting form on which to base them.

06:06:32.430 --> 06:06:36.850
As to the kind of audience that I like best to talk to, I would put at the top of the list

06:06:36.850 --> 06:06:43.350
an organization of strong, wide-awake businessmen, such, for example, as is found in Boston, New York,

06:06:43.370 --> 06:06:48.970
Chicago, and Buffalo. I have found no other audience so quick to see a point and so responsive.

06:06:49.570 --> 06:06:53.210
Within the last few years, I have had the privilege of speaking before most of the

06:06:53.210 --> 06:06:58.890
organizations of this kind in the large cities of the United States. The best time to get hold of

06:06:58.890 --> 06:07:03.310
an organization of businessmen is after a good dinner, although I think that one of the worst

06:07:03.310 --> 06:07:07.970
instruments of torture that was ever invented is the custom which makes it necessary for a speaker

06:07:07.970 --> 06:07:12.610
to sit through a fourteen-course dinner every minute of the time feeling sure that his speech

06:07:12.610 --> 06:07:17.070
is going to prove a dismal failure and disappointment. I rarely take part in one

06:07:17.070 --> 06:07:21.050
of these long dinners that I do not wish that I could put myself back in the little cabin where

06:07:21.050 --> 06:07:25.850
I was a slave boy, and again go through the experience there, one that I shall never forget,

06:07:26.190 --> 06:07:31.270
of getting molasses to eat once a week from the big house. Our usual diet on the plantation was

06:07:31.270 --> 06:07:36.370
cornbread and pork, but on Sunday morning my mother was permitted to bring down a little molasses from

06:07:36.370 --> 06:07:41.650
the big house for her three children, and when it was received how I did wish that every day was Sunday.

06:07:42.090 --> 06:07:46.630
I would get my tin plate and hold it up for the sweet morsel, but I would always shut my eyes

06:07:46.630 --> 06:07:50.790
while the molasses was being poured out onto the plate, with the hope that when I opened them I

06:07:50.790 --> 06:07:55.630
would be surprised to see how much I had got. When I opened my eyes I would tip the plate in

06:07:55.630 --> 06:08:00.050
one direction and another so as to make the molasses spread all over it in the full belief

06:08:00.050 --> 06:08:03.730
that there would be more of it and that it would last longer if spread out in this way.

06:08:04.230 --> 06:08:08.630
So strong are my childish impressions of these Sunday morning feasts that it would be pretty

06:08:08.630 --> 06:08:13.190
hard for anyone to convince me that there is not more molasses on a plate when it is spread all over

06:08:13.190 --> 06:08:18.810
the plate than when it occupies a little corner, if there is a corner in a plate. At any rate,

06:08:18.810 --> 06:08:23.430
I have never believed in cornering syrup. My share of the syrup was usually about two

06:08:23.430 --> 06:08:28.330
table spoonfuls, and those two spoonfuls of molasses were much more enjoyable to me than

06:08:28.330 --> 06:08:33.990
is a fourteen course dinner after which I am to speak. Next to a company of businessmen I prefer

06:08:33.990 --> 06:08:38.650
to speak to an audience of southern people, of either race, together or taken separately.

06:08:39.210 --> 06:08:44.670
Their enthusiasm and responsiveness are a constant delight. The amens and that's the

06:08:44.670 --> 06:08:49.630
that comes spontaneously from the colored individuals are calculated to spur any speaker

06:08:49.630 --> 06:08:54.330
on to his best efforts. I think that next, in order of preference, I would place a college

06:08:54.330 --> 06:08:58.790
audience. It has been my privilege to deliver addresses at many of our leading colleges,

06:08:59.030 --> 06:09:04.110
including Harvard, Yale, Williams, Amherst, Fisk University, the University of Pennsylvania,

06:09:04.710 --> 06:09:09.450
Wellesley, the University of Michigan, Trinity College in North Carolina, and many others.

06:09:10.030 --> 06:09:13.050
When speaking directly in the interests of the Tuskegee Institute,

06:09:13.050 --> 06:09:17.730
I usually arrange, sometime in advance, a series of meetings in important centers.

06:09:18.190 --> 06:09:22.110
This takes me before churches, Sunday schools, Christian Endeavor societies,

06:09:22.510 --> 06:09:27.650
and men's and women's clubs. When doing this I sometimes speak before as many as four organizations

06:09:27.650 --> 06:09:33.390
in a single day. Three years ago, at the suggestion of Mr. Morris K. Jessup of New York,

06:09:33.710 --> 06:09:39.750
and Dr. J. L. M. Curry, the general agent of the fund, the trustees of the John F. Slater Fund

06:09:39.750 --> 06:09:44.210
voted a sum of money to be used in paying the expenses of Mrs. Washington and myself

06:09:44.210 --> 06:09:48.650
while holding a series of meetings among the colored people in the large centers of Negro

06:09:48.650 --> 06:09:55.390
population, especially in the large cities of the ex-slaveholding states. Each year during the last

06:09:55.390 --> 06:10:00.110
three years we have devoted some weeks to this work. The plan that we have followed has been for

06:10:00.110 --> 06:10:04.930
me to speak in the morning to the ministers, teachers, and professional men. In the afternoon,

06:10:05.110 --> 06:10:09.670
Mrs. Washington would speak to the women alone, and in the evening I spoke to a large mass

06:10:09.670 --> 06:10:14.750
meeting. In almost every case the meetings have been attended not only by the colored people

06:10:14.750 --> 06:10:20.270
in large numbers, but by the white people. In Chattanooga, Tennessee, for example, there was

06:10:20.270 --> 06:10:25.730
present at the mass meeting an audience of not less than 3,000 persons, and I was informed that

06:10:25.730 --> 06:10:31.190
800 of these were white. I have done no work that I really enjoyed more than this, or that I think

06:10:31.190 --> 06:10:37.230
has accomplished more good. These meetings have given Mrs. Washington and myself an opportunity

06:10:37.230 --> 06:10:42.510
to get first-hand accurate information as to the real condition of the race by seeing the people

06:10:42.510 --> 06:10:47.010
in their homes, their churches, their Sunday schools, and their places of work, as well as in

06:10:47.010 --> 06:10:52.710
the prisons and dens of crime. These meetings also gave us an opportunity to see the relations that

06:10:52.710 --> 06:10:58.170
exist between the races. I never feel so hopeful about the race as I do after being engaged in a

06:10:58.170 --> 06:11:02.690
series of these meetings. I know that on such occasions there is much that comes to the surface

06:11:02.690 --> 06:11:07.410
that is superficial and deceptive, but I have had experience enough not to be deceived by

06:11:07.410 --> 06:11:13.110
mere signs and fleeting enthusiasms. I have taken pains to go to the bottom of things and get facts

06:11:13.110 --> 06:11:18.610
in a cold, businesslike manner. I have seen the statement made lately by one who claims to know

06:11:18.610 --> 06:11:24.390
what he is talking about that, taking the whole Negro race into account, 90% of the Negro women

06:11:24.390 --> 06:11:30.090
are not virtuous. There never was a baser falsehood uttered concerning a race or a statement made that

06:11:30.090 --> 06:11:36.010
was less capable of being proved by actual facts. No one can come into contact with the race for 20

06:11:36.010 --> 06:11:41.050
years, as I have done in the heart of the South, without being convinced that the race is constantly

06:11:41.050 --> 06:11:46.670
making slow but sure progress materially, educationally, and morally. One might take

06:11:46.670 --> 06:11:51.150
up the life of the worst element in New York City, for example, and prove almost anything

06:11:51.150 --> 06:11:55.710
he wanted to prove concerning the white man, but all will agree that this is not a fair test.

06:11:56.450 --> 06:12:02.570
Early in the year 1897 I received a letter inviting me to deliver an address at the dedication of the

06:12:02.570 --> 06:12:08.810
Robert Goldshaw Monument in Boston. I accepted the invitation. It is not necessary for me,

06:12:08.830 --> 06:12:14.670
I am sure, to explain who Robert Goldshaw was and what he did. The monument to his memory stands

06:12:14.670 --> 06:12:20.030
near the head of the Boston Common, facing the State House. It is counted to be the most perfect

06:12:20.030 --> 06:12:25.070
piece of art of the kind to be found in the country. The exercises connected with the

06:12:25.070 --> 06:12:30.030
dedication were held in Music Hall in Boston, and the Great Hall was packed from top to bottom with

06:12:30.030 --> 06:12:35.170
one of the most distinguished audiences that ever assembled in the city. Among those present were

06:12:35.170 --> 06:12:40.730
more persons representing the famous old anti-slavery element that it is likely will ever be brought

06:12:40.730 --> 06:12:46.290
together in the country again. The late Honorable Roger Wolcott, then Governor of Massachusetts,

06:12:46.770 --> 06:12:51.410
was the presiding officer, and on the platform with him were many other officials and hundreds

06:12:51.410 --> 06:12:55.910
of distinguished men. A report of the meeting which appeared in the Boston transcript will

06:12:55.910 --> 06:13:00.970
describe it better than any words of mine could do. The core and kernel of yesterday's great noon

06:13:00.970 --> 06:13:05.930
meeting, in honor of the brotherhood of man in Music Hall, was the superb address of the Negro

06:13:05.930 --> 06:13:12.530
President of Tuskegee. Booker T. Washington received his Harvard A.M. last June, the first of his race,

06:13:12.770 --> 06:13:17.570
said Governor Wolcott, to receive an honorary degree from the oldest university in the land,

06:13:17.570 --> 06:13:23.330
and this for the wise leadership of his people. When Mr. Washington rose in the flag-filled,

06:13:23.630 --> 06:13:29.130
enthusiasm-warmed, patriotic, and glowing atmosphere of the Music Hall, people felt keenly

06:13:29.130 --> 06:13:34.570
that here was the civic justification of the old abolition spirit of Massachusetts, in his person

06:13:34.570 --> 06:13:39.610
the proof of her ancient and indomitable faith, in his strong, thorough, and rich oratory,

06:13:39.970 --> 06:13:47.550
the crown and glory of the old war days of suffering and strife. The scene was full of

06:13:47.550 --> 06:13:52.330
Boston was alive with the fire that is always hot in her heart for righteousness and truth.

06:13:52.910 --> 06:13:57.650
Rows and rows of people who are seldom seen at any public function, whose families of those who

06:13:57.650 --> 06:14:02.890
are certain to be out of town on a holiday, crowded the place to overflowing. The city was

06:14:02.890 --> 06:14:08.090
at her birthright feet in the persons of hundreds of her best citizens, men and women whose names

06:14:08.090 --> 06:14:13.750
and lives stand for the virtues that make for honorable civic pride. Battle music had filled

06:14:13.750 --> 06:14:19.650
the air. Ovation after ovation, applause warm and prolonged, had greeted the officers and friends

06:14:19.650 --> 06:14:25.530
of Colonel Shaw, the sculptor, St. Gaudens, the memorial committee, the governor and his staff,

06:14:25.810 --> 06:14:31.130
and the Negro soldiers of the 54th Massachusetts as they came upon the platform or entered the hall.

06:14:31.870 --> 06:14:37.090
Colonel Henry Lee, of Governor Andrew's old staff, had made a noble, simple presentation

06:14:37.090 --> 06:14:42.210
speech for the committee, paying tribute to Mr. John M. Forbes, in whose stead he served.

06:14:42.210 --> 06:14:45.930
Governor Wolcott had made his short, memorable speech, saying,

06:14:46.450 --> 06:14:50.510
Fort Wagner marked an epoch in the history of a race and called it into manhood.

06:14:51.250 --> 06:14:56.230
Mayor Quincy had received the monument for the city of Boston. The story of Colonel Shaw and

06:14:56.230 --> 06:15:00.810
his black regiment had been told in gallant words, and then, after the singing of,

06:15:01.090 --> 06:15:07.910
mine eyes have seen the glory of the coming of the Lord, Booker Washington arose. It was, of course,

06:15:07.910 --> 06:15:13.290
just the moment for him. The multitude, shaken out of its usual symphony concert calm,

06:15:13.790 --> 06:15:18.270
quivered with an excitement that was not suppressed. A dozen times it had sprung to

06:15:18.270 --> 06:15:23.970
its feet to cheer and wave and hurrah as one person. When this man of culture and voice and

06:15:23.970 --> 06:15:29.010
power, as well as a dark skin, began, and uttered the names of Starnes and of Andrew,

06:15:29.550 --> 06:15:34.150
feeling began to mount. You could see tears glisten in the eyes of soldiers and civilians.

06:15:34.150 --> 06:15:37.550
When the orator turned to the colored soldiers on the platform,

06:15:37.910 --> 06:15:43.150
to the color bearer of Fort Wagner, who smilingly bore still the flag he had never lowered,

06:15:43.250 --> 06:15:49.230
even when wounded, and said, To you, to the scarred and scattered remnants of the 54th,

06:15:49.270 --> 06:15:53.870
who, with empty sleeve and wanting leg, have honored this occasion with your presence,

06:15:54.250 --> 06:16:00.530
to you your commander is not dead. Though Boston erected no monument and history recorded no story,

06:16:00.530 --> 06:16:05.890
in you, and in the loyal race which you represent, Robert Gould Shaw would have a

06:16:05.890 --> 06:16:11.850
monument which time could not wear away. Then came the climax of the emotion of the day and the hour.

06:16:12.270 --> 06:16:17.590
It was Roger Wolcott, as well as the governor of Massachusetts, the individual representative

06:16:17.590 --> 06:16:22.350
of the people's sympathy, as well as the chief magistrate, who had first sprung to his feet and

06:16:22.350 --> 06:16:28.270
cried, Three cheers to Booker T. Washington! Among those on the platform was Sergeant William

06:16:28.270 --> 06:16:33.490
H. Carney of New Bedford, Massachusetts, the brave colored officer who was the color bearer at Fort

06:16:33.490 --> 06:16:38.690
Wagner and held the American flag. In spite of the fact that a large part of his regiment was killed,

06:16:38.970 --> 06:16:43.750
he escaped and exclaimed, after the battle was over, The old flag never touched the ground.

06:16:44.550 --> 06:16:49.710
This flag Sergeant Carney held in his hands as he sat on the platform, and when I turned to address

06:16:49.710 --> 06:16:54.350
the survivors of the colored regiment who were present and referred to Sergeant Carney, he rose

06:16:54.350 --> 06:16:59.910
as if by instinct and raised the flag. It has been my privilege to witness a good many satisfactory

06:16:59.910 --> 06:17:04.030
and rather sensational demonstrations in connection with some of my public addresses,

06:17:04.590 --> 06:17:09.130
but in dramatic effect I have never seen or experienced anything which equalled this.

06:17:09.610 --> 06:17:13.370
For a number of minutes the audience seemed to entirely lose control of itself.

06:17:14.210 --> 06:17:18.290
In the general rejoicing throughout the country which followed the close of the Spanish-American

06:17:18.290 --> 06:17:24.150
War, peace celebrations were arranged in several of the large cities. I was asked by President

06:17:24.150 --> 06:17:29.390
William R. Harper of the University of Chicago, who was chairman of the Committee of Invitations

06:17:29.390 --> 06:17:33.670
for the celebration to be held in the city of Chicago, to deliver one of the addresses

06:17:33.670 --> 06:17:39.030
at the celebration there. I accepted the invitation and delivered two addresses there during Jubilee

06:17:39.030 --> 06:17:44.090
week. The first of these, and the principal one, was given in the auditorium on the evening of

06:17:44.090 --> 06:17:49.690
Sunday, October 16. This was the largest audience that I have ever addressed in any part of the

06:17:49.690 --> 06:17:54.270
country, and besides speaking in the main auditorium I also addressed that same evening

06:17:54.270 --> 06:18:00.730
two overflow audiences in other parts of the city. It was said that there were 16,000 persons in the

06:18:00.730 --> 06:18:05.950
auditorium, and it seemed to me as if there were as many more on the outside trying to get in.

06:18:06.190 --> 06:18:10.430
It was impossible for anyone to get near the entrance without the aid of a policeman.

06:18:11.270 --> 06:18:15.750
President William McKinley attended this meeting, as did also the members of his cabinet,

06:18:15.750 --> 06:18:19.650
many foreign ministers, and a large number of Army and Navy officers,

06:18:19.930 --> 06:18:23.270
many of whom had distinguished themselves in the war which had just closed.

06:18:23.910 --> 06:18:30.650
The speakers, besides myself, on Sunday evening were Rabbi Emil G. Hirsch, Father Thomas P.

06:18:30.830 --> 06:18:36.510
Hodnett, and Dr. John H. Barrows. The Chicago Times Herald, in describing the meeting,

06:18:36.670 --> 06:18:37.490
said of my address,

06:18:45.750 --> 06:18:49.870
that white Americans might be free while black Americans remained in slavery,

06:18:50.650 --> 06:18:53.490
rehearsed the conduct of the Negroes with Jackson at New Orleans,

06:18:54.070 --> 06:18:58.270
drew a vivid and pathetic picture of the Southern slaves protecting and supporting the families of

06:18:58.270 --> 06:19:03.310
their masters while the latter were fighting to perpetuate black slavery, recounted the bravery

06:19:03.310 --> 06:19:08.830
of colored troops at Port Hudson and Forts Wagner and Pillow, and praised the heroism of the black

06:19:08.830 --> 06:19:13.650
regiments that stormed El Cani and Santiago to give freedom to the enslaved people of Cuba,

06:19:13.650 --> 06:19:18.590
forgetting, for the time being, the unjust discrimination that law and custom make against

06:19:18.590 --> 06:19:23.870
them in their own country. In all of these things, the speaker declared, his race had

06:19:23.870 --> 06:19:28.430
chosen the better part, and then he made his eloquent appeal to the consciences of the white

06:19:28.430 --> 06:19:33.930
Americans. When you have gotten the full story of the heroic conduct of the Negro in the Spanish-American

06:19:33.930 --> 06:19:39.370
War, have heard it from the lips of a Northern soldier and Southern soldier, from ex-abolitionists

06:19:39.370 --> 06:19:44.690
and ex-masters, then decide within yourselves whether a race that is thus willing to die for

06:19:44.690 --> 06:19:48.870
its country should not be given the highest opportunity to live for its country.

06:19:49.390 --> 06:19:53.670
The part of the speech which seems to arouse the wildest and most sensational enthusiasm

06:19:53.670 --> 06:19:57.870
was that in which I thanked the President for his recognition of the Negro in his appointments

06:19:57.870 --> 06:20:02.490
during the Spanish-American War. The President was sitting in a box at the right of the stage.

06:20:02.830 --> 06:20:06.950
When I addressed him, I turned toward the box, and as I finished the sentence thanking him for

06:20:06.950 --> 06:20:11.970
his generosity, the whole audience rose and cheered again and again, waving handkerchiefs

06:20:11.970 --> 06:20:17.230
and hats and canes, until the President arose in the box and bowed his acknowledgments. At that,

06:20:17.390 --> 06:20:21.110
the enthusiasm broke out again, and the demonstration was almost indescribable.

06:20:21.970 --> 06:20:26.250
One portion of my address at Chicago seemed to have been misunderstood by the Southern press,

06:20:26.610 --> 06:20:31.570
and some of the Southern papers took occasion to criticize me rather strongly. These criticisms

06:20:31.570 --> 06:20:35.990
continued for several weeks, until I finally received a letter from the editor of the Age

06:20:36.590 --> 06:20:41.670
published in Birmingham, Alabama, asking me if I would say just what I meant by this part of the

06:20:41.670 --> 06:20:47.170
address. I replied to him in a letter which seemed to satisfy my critics. In this letter I said that

06:20:47.170 --> 06:20:52.230
I had made it a rule never to say before a Northern audience anything that I would not say before an

06:20:52.230 --> 06:20:56.970
audience in the South. I said that I did not think it was necessary for me to go into extended

06:20:56.970 --> 06:21:02.230
explanations. If my 17 years of work in the heart of the South had not been explanation enough,

06:21:02.230 --> 06:21:07.390
I did not see how words could explain. I said that I made the same plea that I had made in

06:21:07.390 --> 06:21:12.390
my address in Atlanta for the blotting out of race prejudice in commercial and civil relations.

06:21:13.030 --> 06:21:17.230
I said that what is termed social recognition was a question which I never discussed,

06:21:17.510 --> 06:21:21.730
and then I quoted from my Atlanta address what I had said there in regard to that subject.

06:21:22.530 --> 06:21:27.170
In meeting crowds of people at public gatherings, there is one type of individual that I dread.

06:21:27.550 --> 06:21:32.150
I mean the crank. I have become so accustomed to these people now that I can pick them out

06:21:32.150 --> 06:21:36.890
at a distance when I see them elbowing their way up to me. The average crank has a long beard,

06:21:37.070 --> 06:21:42.250
poorly cared for, a lean narrow face, and wears a black coat. The front of his vest and coat are

06:21:42.250 --> 06:21:47.870
slick with grease, and his trousers bag at the knees. In Chicago, after I had spoken at a meeting,

06:21:47.970 --> 06:21:52.830
I met one of these fellows. They usually have some process for curing all of the ills of the

06:21:52.830 --> 06:21:59.030
world at once. This Chicago specimen had a patent process by which he said Indian corn could be kept

06:21:59.030 --> 06:22:04.070
through a period of three or four years, and he felt sure that if the Negro race in the South would,

06:22:04.130 --> 06:22:09.890
as a whole, adopt his process, it would settle the whole race question. It mattered nothing that I

06:22:09.890 --> 06:22:14.330
tried to convince him that our present problem was to teach the Negroes how to produce enough corn

06:22:14.330 --> 06:22:19.630
to last them through one year. Another Chicago crank had a scheme by which he wanted me to join

06:22:19.630 --> 06:22:24.450
him in an effort to close up all the national banks in the country. If that was done, he felt

06:22:24.450 --> 06:22:29.330
sure it would put the Negro on his feet. The number of people who stand ready to consume

06:22:29.330 --> 06:22:34.930
one's time to no purpose is almost countless. At one time I spoke before a large audience in

06:22:34.930 --> 06:22:39.510
Boston in the evening. The next morning I was awakened by having a card brush my room,

06:22:39.730 --> 06:22:44.350
and with it a message that someone was anxious to see me. Thinking that it must be something

06:22:44.350 --> 06:22:49.470
very important, I dressed hastily and went down. When I reached the hotel office I found a blank

06:22:49.470 --> 06:22:53.450
innocent-looking individual waiting for me, who coolly remarked,

06:22:53.770 --> 06:22:56.910
I heard you talk at a meeting last night. I rather liked your talking,

06:22:56.990 --> 06:22:59.230
so I came in this morning to hear you talk some more.

06:23:00.230 --> 06:23:04.450
I am often asked how it is possible for me to superintend the work at Tuskegee,

06:23:04.710 --> 06:23:09.830
and at the same time to be so much away from the school. In partial answer to this, I would say

06:23:09.830 --> 06:23:14.430
that I think I have learned, in some degree at least, to disregard the old maxim which says,

06:23:14.430 --> 06:23:20.030
do not get others to do that which you can do yourself. My motto on the other hand is,

06:23:20.270 --> 06:23:26.010
do not do that which others can do as well. One of the most encouraging signs in connection with

06:23:26.010 --> 06:23:30.830
the Tuskegee school is found in the fact that the organization is so thorough that the daily work

06:23:30.830 --> 06:23:36.090
of the school is not dependent upon the presence of any one individual. The whole executive force,

06:23:36.230 --> 06:23:42.530
including instructors and clerks, now numbers 86. This force is so organized and subdivided

06:23:42.530 --> 06:23:47.470
that the machinery of the school goes on day by day like clockwork. Most of our teachers have been

06:23:47.470 --> 06:23:52.630
connected with the institutions for a number of years and are as much interested in it as I am.

06:23:53.210 --> 06:23:58.730
In my absence, Mr. Warren Logan, the treasurer, who has been at the school 17 years, is the

06:23:58.730 --> 06:24:04.470
executive. He is efficiently supported by Mrs. Washington and by my faithful secretary, Mr. Emmet

06:24:04.470 --> 06:24:09.430
J. Scott, who handles the bulk of my correspondence and keeps me in daily touch with the life of the

06:24:09.430 --> 06:24:14.090
school and who also keeps me informed of whatever takes place in the south that concerns the race.

06:24:14.550 --> 06:24:19.770
I owe more to his tact, wisdom, and hard work than I can describe. The main executive work

06:24:19.770 --> 06:24:24.610
of the school, whether I am at Tuskegee or not, centers in what we call the executive council.

06:24:25.230 --> 06:24:29.470
This council meets twice a week and is composed of the nine persons who are at the head of the

06:24:29.470 --> 06:24:35.470
nine departments of the school. For example, Mrs. B.K. Bruce, the lady principal, the widow

06:24:35.470 --> 06:24:40.770
of the late ex-Senator Bruce, is a member of the council and represents it in all that pertains to

06:24:40.770 --> 06:24:45.530
the life of the girls at the school. In addition to the executive council, there is a financial

06:24:45.530 --> 06:24:49.630
committee of six that meets every week and decides upon the expenditures for the week.

06:24:50.330 --> 06:24:54.190
Once a month, and sometimes oftener, there is a general meeting of all the instructors.

06:24:54.890 --> 06:24:59.190
Aside from these, there are innumerable smaller meetings such as that of the instructors in the

06:24:59.190 --> 06:25:03.490
Phelps Hall Bible Training School or of the instructors in the Agricultural Department.

06:25:04.250 --> 06:25:08.990
In order that I may keep in constant touch with the life of the institution, I have a system of

06:25:08.990 --> 06:25:13.950
reports so arranged that a record of the school's work reaches me every day of the year, no matter

06:25:13.950 --> 06:25:19.370
in what part of the country I am. I know by these reports even what students are excused from school

06:25:19.370 --> 06:25:24.850
and why they are excused, whether for reasons of ill health or otherwise. Through the medium of

06:25:24.850 --> 06:25:29.850
these reports, I know each day what the income of the school in money is, I know how many gallons

06:25:29.850 --> 06:25:34.330
of milk and how many pounds of butter come from the dairy, what the bill of fare for the teachers

06:25:34.330 --> 06:25:39.170
and students is, whether a certain kind of meat was boiled or baked, and whether certain vegetables

06:25:39.170 --> 06:25:44.610
served in the dining room were bought from a store or procured from our own farm. Human nature,

06:25:44.770 --> 06:25:49.510
I find to be very much the same the world over, and it is sometimes not hard to yield to the

06:25:49.510 --> 06:25:54.330
temptation to go to a barrel of rice that has come from the store, with the grain all prepared to go

06:25:54.330 --> 06:25:58.930
in the pot, rather than to take the time and trouble to go to the field and dig and wash one's

06:25:58.930 --> 06:26:03.170
own sweet potatoes, which might be prepared in a manner to take the place of the rice.

06:26:03.590 --> 06:26:08.830
I am often asked how, in the midst of so much work, a large part of which is for the public,

06:26:09.170 --> 06:26:13.850
I can find time for any rest or recreation, and what kind of recreation or sports I am fond of.

06:26:14.310 --> 06:26:18.950
This is rather a difficult question to answer. I have a strong feeling that every individual

06:26:18.950 --> 06:26:23.510
owes it to himself, and to the cause which he is serving, to keep a vigorous healthy body,

06:26:23.870 --> 06:26:28.030
with the nerves steady and strong, prepared for great efforts, and prepared for disappointments

06:26:28.030 --> 06:26:33.690
and trying positions. As far as I can, I make it a rule to plan for each day's work, not merely

06:26:33.690 --> 06:26:38.330
to go through with the same routine of daily duties, but to get rid of some of the routine work as

06:26:38.330 --> 06:26:43.430
early in the day as possible, and then to enter upon some new or advanced work. I make it a rule

06:26:43.430 --> 06:26:48.130
to clear my desk every day before leaving my office, of all correspondence and memoranda,

06:26:48.450 --> 06:26:53.770
so that on the morrow I can begin a new day of work. I make it a rule never to let my work drive

06:26:53.770 --> 06:26:59.490
me, but to so master it and keep it in such complete control, and to keep so far ahead of it

06:26:59.490 --> 06:27:04.470
that I will be the master instead of the servant. There is a physical and mental and spiritual

06:27:04.470 --> 06:27:08.770
enjoyment that comes from a consciousness of being the absolute master of one's work

06:27:08.770 --> 06:27:14.610
in all its details, that is very satisfactory and inspiring. My experience teaches me that,

06:27:14.890 --> 06:27:19.690
if one learns to follow this plan, he gets a freshness of body and vigour of mind out of work

06:27:19.690 --> 06:27:24.410
that goes a long way toward keeping him strong and healthy. I believe that when one can grow

06:27:24.410 --> 06:27:28.670
to the point where he loves his work, this gives him a kind of strength that is most valuable.

06:27:29.570 --> 06:27:33.730
When I begin my work in the morning, I expect to have a successful and pleasant day of it,

06:27:33.810 --> 06:27:37.810
but at the same time I prepare myself for unpleasant and unexpected hard places.

06:27:38.330 --> 06:27:42.550
I prepared myself to hear that one of our school buildings is on fire, or has burned,

06:27:43.030 --> 06:27:47.630
or that some disagreeable accident has occurred, or that someone has abused me in a public address,

06:27:47.630 --> 06:27:51.170
or printed article, for something I have done or omitted to do,

06:27:51.330 --> 06:27:56.010
or for something that he had heard that I had said, probably something that I had never thought

06:27:56.010 --> 06:28:02.570
of saying. In nineteen years of continuous work I have taken but one vacation. That was two years

06:28:02.570 --> 06:28:07.450
ago when some of my friends put the money into my hands and forced Mrs. Washington and myself to

06:28:07.450 --> 06:28:12.090
spend three months in Europe. I have said that I believe it is the duty of everyone to keep his

06:28:12.090 --> 06:28:17.070
body in good condition. I try to look after the little ills with the idea that if I take care of

06:28:17.070 --> 06:28:21.810
little ills the big ones will not come. When I find myself unable to sleep well,

06:28:22.110 --> 06:28:26.030
I know that something is wrong. If I find any part of my system the least weak

06:28:26.030 --> 06:28:31.190
and not performing its duty, I consult a good physician. The ability to sleep well,

06:28:31.250 --> 06:28:36.410
at any time and in any place, I find of great advantage. I have so trained myself that I

06:28:36.410 --> 06:28:40.970
can lie down for a nap of fifteen or twenty minutes and get up refreshed in body and mind.

06:28:41.570 --> 06:28:45.410
I have said that I make it a rule to finish up each day's work before leaving it.

06:28:45.410 --> 06:28:50.430
There is perhaps one exception to this. When I have an unusually difficult question to decide,

06:28:50.830 --> 06:28:55.770
one that appeals strongly to the emotions, I find it a safe rule to sleep over it for a night,

06:28:56.030 --> 06:28:59.970
or to wait until I have had an opportunity to talk over it with my wife and friends.

06:29:00.830 --> 06:29:05.190
As to my reading, the most time I get for solid reading is when I am on the cars.

06:29:05.870 --> 06:29:10.570
Newspapers are to me a constant source of delight in recreation. The only trouble is that I read

06:29:10.570 --> 06:29:15.890
many of them. Fiction I care little for. Frequently I have to almost force myself

06:29:15.890 --> 06:29:20.050
to read a novel that is on everyone's lips. The kind of reading that I have the greatest

06:29:20.050 --> 06:29:25.450
fondness for is biography. I like to be sure that I am reading about a real man or a real thing.

06:29:26.070 --> 06:29:30.470
I think I do not go too far when I say that I have read nearly every book and magazine article

06:29:30.470 --> 06:29:34.890
that has been written about Abraham Lincoln. In literature he is my patron saint.

06:29:34.890 --> 06:29:40.410
Out of the twelve months in a year I suppose that, on average, I spend six months away from

06:29:41.090 --> 06:29:45.590
Tuskegee. While my being absent from the school so much unquestionably has its disadvantages,

06:29:46.130 --> 06:29:51.150
yet there are at the same time some compensations. The change of work brings a certain kind of rest.

06:29:51.490 --> 06:29:55.510
I enjoy a ride of a long distance on the cars when I am permitted to ride where I can be

06:29:55.510 --> 06:30:00.510
comfortable. I get rest on the cars except when the inevitable individual, who seems to be on

06:30:00.510 --> 06:30:03.090
every train, approaches me with the now familiar phrase,

06:30:03.690 --> 06:30:06.970
Isn't this Booker Washington? I want to introduce myself to you.

06:30:07.970 --> 06:30:11.850
Absence from the school enables me to lose sight of the unimportant details of the work

06:30:11.850 --> 06:30:15.790
and study it in a broader and more comprehensive manner than I could do on the grounds.

06:30:16.350 --> 06:30:20.870
This absence also brings me into contact with the best work being done in educational lines

06:30:20.870 --> 06:30:26.290
and into contact with the best educators in the land. But, after all this is said,

06:30:26.290 --> 06:30:31.150
the time when I get the most solid rest in recreation is when I can be at Tuskegee,

06:30:31.290 --> 06:30:35.130
and, after our evening meal is over, can sit down, as is our custom,

06:30:35.550 --> 06:30:40.450
with my wife and Portia and Baker and Davidson, my three children, and read a story,

06:30:40.790 --> 06:30:45.470
or each take turns in telling a story. To me there is nothing on earth equal to that,

06:30:45.730 --> 06:30:49.550
although what is nearly equal to it is to go with them for an hour or more,

06:30:49.770 --> 06:30:54.030
as we like to do on Sunday afternoons, into the woods where we can live for a while near

06:30:54.030 --> 06:30:59.410
the heart of nature, where no one can disturb or vex us, surrounded by pure air, the trees,

06:30:59.530 --> 06:31:03.870
the shrubbery, the flowers, and the sweet fragrance that springs from a hundred plants,

06:31:04.310 --> 06:31:08.570
enjoying the chirp of the crickets and the songs of the birds. This is solid rest.

06:31:09.190 --> 06:31:14.510
My garden, also, what little time I can be at Tuskegee, is another source of rest and enjoyment.

06:31:15.070 --> 06:31:20.410
Somehow I like, as often as possible, to touch nature, not something that is artificial or an

06:31:20.410 --> 06:31:25.430
imitation, but the real thing. When I can leave my office in time so that I can spend 30 or 40

06:31:25.430 --> 06:31:30.750
minutes in spading the ground, in planting seeds, in digging about the plants, I feel that I am

06:31:30.750 --> 06:31:34.990
coming into contact with something that is giving me strength for the many duties and hard places

06:31:34.990 --> 06:31:40.130
that await me out in the big world. I pity the man or woman who has never learned to enjoy nature

06:31:40.130 --> 06:31:45.370
and to get strength and inspiration out of it. Aside from the large number of fowls and animals

06:31:45.370 --> 06:31:50.170
kept by the school, I keep individually a number of pigs and fowls of the best grades,

06:31:50.490 --> 06:31:55.310
and in raising these I take a great deal of pleasure. I think the pig is my favorite animal.

06:31:55.790 --> 06:32:00.730
Few things are more satisfactory to me than a high-grade Berkshire or Poland China pig.

06:32:01.850 --> 06:32:06.990
Games I care little for. I have never seen a game of football. In cards I do not know one

06:32:06.990 --> 06:32:12.050
card from another. A game of old-fashioned marbles with my two boys once in a while is all I care for

06:32:12.050 --> 06:32:17.230
this direction. I suppose I would care for games now if I had any time in my youth to give to them,

06:32:17.390 --> 06:32:18.870
but that was not possible.

06:32:46.230 --> 06:32:49.030
—Europe

06:32:50.510 --> 06:32:58.250
In 1893, I was married to Miss Margaret James Murray, a native of Mississippi and a graduate

06:32:58.250 --> 06:33:04.810
of Fisk University in Nashville, Tennessee, who had come to Tuskegee as a teacher several

06:33:04.810 --> 06:33:09.990
years before, and at the time we were married was filling the position of Lady Principal.

06:33:10.330 --> 06:33:16.190
Not only is Mrs. Washington completely one with me in the work directly connected with

06:33:16.850 --> 06:33:22.490
relieving me of many burdens and perplexities, but aside from her work on the school grounds,

06:33:22.710 --> 06:33:28.010
she carries on a mother's meeting in the town of Tuskegee and the plantation work among

06:33:28.010 --> 06:33:33.770
the women, children, and men who live in a settlement connected with a large plantation

06:33:33.770 --> 06:33:36.530
about eight miles from Tuskegee.

06:33:36.930 --> 06:33:43.670
Both the mother's meeting and the plantation work are carried on not only with a view to

06:33:43.670 --> 06:33:49.630
helping those who are directly reached, but also for the purpose of furnishing object

06:33:49.630 --> 06:33:56.210
lessons in these two kinds of work that may be followed by our students when they go out

06:33:56.210 --> 06:33:59.070
into the world for their own life work.

06:33:59.490 --> 06:34:06.870
Aside from these two enterprises, Mrs. Washington is also largely responsible for a women's

06:34:06.870 --> 06:34:12.890
club at the school, which brings together, twice a month, the women who live on the school

06:34:12.890 --> 06:34:17.970
grounds and those who live near, for the discussion of some important topics.

06:34:18.890 --> 06:34:25.810
She is also the president of what is known as the Federation of Southern Colored Women's

06:34:25.810 --> 06:34:32.990
Clubs and is chairman of the executive committee of the National Federation of Colored Women's

06:34:33.810 --> 06:34:34.570
Clubs.

06:34:35.630 --> 06:34:40.250
Portia, the oldest of my three children, has learned dressmaking.

06:34:40.250 --> 06:34:44.330
She has unusual ability in instrumental music.

06:34:44.770 --> 06:34:50.070
Aside from her studies at Tuskegee, she has already begun to teach there.

06:34:50.370 --> 06:34:53.650
Booker Tolliver is my next oldest child.

06:34:54.450 --> 06:34:59.870
Young as he is, he has already nearly mastered the brick mason's trade.

06:35:00.710 --> 06:35:06.910
He began working at this trade when he was quite small, dividing his time between this

06:35:06.910 --> 06:35:07.910
and classwork.

06:35:08.510 --> 06:35:13.150
And he has developed great skill in the trade and a fondness for it.

06:35:13.910 --> 06:35:17.530
He says that he is going to be an architect and brick mason.

06:35:18.450 --> 06:35:23.830
One of the most satisfactory letters that I have ever received from anyone came to me

06:35:23.830 --> 06:35:25.810
from Booker last summer.

06:35:26.470 --> 06:35:32.230
When I left home for this summer I told him that he must work at his trade half of each

06:35:32.230 --> 06:35:36.910
day and that the other half of the day he could spend as he pleased.

06:35:36.910 --> 06:35:42.050
When I had been away from home two weeks I received the following letter from him.

06:35:42.830 --> 06:35:49.910
Tuskegee, Alabama, my dear Papa, before you left home you told me to work at my trade

06:35:49.910 --> 06:35:51.210
half of each day.

06:35:51.350 --> 06:35:56.330
I like my work so much that I want to work at my trade all day.

06:35:56.870 --> 06:36:02.410
Besides I want to earn all the money I can so that when I go to another school I shall

06:36:02.410 --> 06:36:06.570
have money to pay my expenses, your son, Booker.

06:36:07.070 --> 06:36:13.250
My youngest child, Ernest Davidson Washington, says that he is going to be a physician.

06:36:13.930 --> 06:36:20.050
In addition to going to school where he studies books and has manual training, he regularly

06:36:20.050 --> 06:36:25.310
spends a portion of his time in the office of our resident physician and has already

06:36:25.310 --> 06:36:29.910
learned to do many of the studies which pertain to a doctor's office.

06:36:30.550 --> 06:36:37.510
The thing in my life which brings me the keenest regret is that my work in connection with

06:36:37.510 --> 06:36:45.050
public affairs keeps me for so much of the time away from my family where, of all places

06:36:45.050 --> 06:36:47.690
in the world, I delight to be.

06:36:48.350 --> 06:36:54.030
I always envy the individual whose life work is so laid that he can spend his evenings

06:36:54.030 --> 06:36:54.690
at home.

06:36:55.350 --> 06:37:01.650
I have sometimes thought that people who have this rare privilege do not appreciate it as

06:37:01.650 --> 06:37:02.310
they should.

06:37:03.330 --> 06:37:09.270
It is such a rest and relief to get away from crowds of people and handshaking and traveling,

06:37:09.730 --> 06:37:13.850
to get home even if it be for but a very brief while.

06:37:14.490 --> 06:37:19.970
Another thing at Tuskegee out of which I get a great deal of pleasure and satisfaction

06:37:20.450 --> 06:37:26.550
is in the meeting with our students and teachers and their families in the chapel for devotional

06:37:26.550 --> 06:37:32.990
exercises every evening at half past eight, the last thing before retiring for the night.

06:37:33.570 --> 06:37:39.790
It is an inspiring sight when one stands on the platform there and sees before him eleven

06:37:39.790 --> 06:37:46.230
or twelve hundred earnest young men and women, and one cannot but feel that it is a privilege

06:37:46.230 --> 06:37:51.190
to help to guide them to a higher and more useful life.

06:37:51.710 --> 06:37:58.570
In the spring of 1899 there came to me what I might describe as almost the greatest surprise

06:37:58.570 --> 06:37:59.350
of my life.

06:38:00.370 --> 06:38:06.210
Some good ladies in Boston arranged a public meeting in the interest of Tuskegee to be

06:38:06.210 --> 06:38:08.130
held in the Hollis Street Theater.

06:38:08.850 --> 06:38:14.350
This meeting was attended by large numbers of the best people of Boston of both races.

06:38:14.990 --> 06:38:16.430
Bishop Lawrence presided.

06:38:17.090 --> 06:38:24.330
In addition to an address by myself, Mr. Paul Lawrence Dunbar, read from his poems, and

06:38:24.330 --> 06:38:28.530
Dr. W. E. B. DeBose read an original sketch.

06:38:29.590 --> 06:38:36.210
Some of those who attended the meeting noticed that I seemed unusually tired, and some little

06:38:36.210 --> 06:38:41.450
time after the close of the meeting, one of the ladies who had been interested in it asked

06:38:41.450 --> 06:38:44.650
me, in a casual way, if I had ever been to Europe.

06:38:44.790 --> 06:38:46.770
I replied that I never had.

06:38:47.570 --> 06:38:53.090
She asked me if I had ever thought of going, and I told her no, that it was something entirely

06:38:53.090 --> 06:38:54.030
beyond me.

06:38:54.990 --> 06:39:01.450
This conversation soon passed out of my mind, but a few days afterward I was informed that

06:39:01.450 --> 06:39:08.290
some friends in Boston, including Mr. Francis J. Garrison, had raised a sum of money sufficient

06:39:08.290 --> 06:39:15.890
to pay all the expenses of Mrs. Washington and myself during a three or four month trip

06:39:15.890 --> 06:39:16.510
to Europe.

06:39:17.150 --> 06:39:20.170
It was added with emphasis that we must go.

06:39:20.810 --> 06:39:26.210
A year previous to this, Mr. Garrison had attempted to get me to promise to go to Europe

06:39:26.210 --> 06:39:31.770
for a summer's rest, with the understanding that he would be responsible for raising the

06:39:31.770 --> 06:39:35.210
money among his friends for the expenses of the trip.

06:39:35.210 --> 06:39:41.010
At that time such a journey seemed so entirely foreign to anything that I should ever be

06:39:41.010 --> 06:39:46.890
able to undertake, that I did confess I did not give the matter very serious attention.

06:39:47.670 --> 06:39:52.890
But later Mr. Garrison joined his efforts to those of the ladies whom I have mentioned,

06:39:53.370 --> 06:39:58.610
and when their plans were made known to me, Mr. Garrison not only had the route mapped

06:39:58.610 --> 06:40:04.230
but had, I believe, selected the steamer upon which we were to sail.

06:40:06.350 --> 06:40:12.690
Whole thing was so sudden and so unexpected that I was completely taken off my feet.

06:40:13.690 --> 06:40:19.810
I had been at work steadily for eighteen years in connection with Tuskegee, and I had never

06:40:19.810 --> 06:40:23.190
thought of anything else but ending my life in that way.

06:40:23.910 --> 06:40:30.470
Each day the school seemed to depend upon me more, largely for its daily expenses, and

06:40:30.470 --> 06:40:35.990
I told these Boston friends that, while I thanked them sincerely for their thoughtfulness

06:40:35.990 --> 06:40:42.110
and generosity, I could not go to Europe for the reason that the school could not live

06:40:42.110 --> 06:40:44.130
financially while I was absent.

06:40:44.510 --> 06:40:51.030
They then informed me that Mr. Henry L. Higginson and some other good friends, who I know do

06:40:51.030 --> 06:40:56.670
not want their names made public, were then raising a sum of money which would be sufficient

06:40:56.670 --> 06:40:59.650
to keep the school in operation while I was away.

06:41:00.050 --> 06:41:02.370
At this point I was compelled to surrender.

06:41:02.930 --> 06:41:05.910
Every avenue of escape had been closed.

06:41:06.410 --> 06:41:13.190
Deep down in my heart the whole thing seemed more like a dream than like reality, and for

06:41:13.190 --> 06:41:19.490
a long time it was difficult for me to make myself believe that I was actually going to

06:41:19.490 --> 06:41:19.730
Europe.

06:41:19.730 --> 06:41:26.610
I had been born and largely reared in the lowest depths of slavery, ignorance, and poverty.

06:41:27.510 --> 06:41:35.030
In my childhood I had suffered for want of a place to sleep, for lack of food, clothing,

06:41:35.210 --> 06:41:35.750
and shelter.

06:41:36.890 --> 06:41:43.810
I had not had the privilege of sitting down to a dining table until I was quite well-grown.

06:41:44.970 --> 06:41:51.190
Luxuries had always seemed to me to be something meant for white people, not for my race.

06:41:52.590 --> 06:41:59.810
I had always regarded Europe and London and Paris much as I regarded heaven, and now could

06:41:59.810 --> 06:42:02.730
it be that I was actually going to Europe?

06:42:03.610 --> 06:42:07.190
Such thoughts as these were constantly with me.

06:42:07.530 --> 06:42:10.530
Two other thoughts troubled me a good deal.

06:42:10.530 --> 06:42:17.710
I feared that people who heard that Mrs. Washington and I were going to Europe might not know

06:42:17.710 --> 06:42:24.470
all the circumstances and might get the idea that we had become, as some might say, stuck

06:42:24.470 --> 06:42:27.370
up, and were trying to show off.

06:42:27.870 --> 06:42:34.610
I recalled that from my youth I had heard it said that too often when people of my race

06:42:34.610 --> 06:42:42.730
reached any degree of success they were inclined to unduly exalt themselves, to try and ape

06:42:42.730 --> 06:42:46.250
the wealthy and in so doing to lose their heads.

06:42:46.910 --> 06:42:51.690
The fear that people might think this of us haunted me a good deal.

06:42:52.530 --> 06:42:59.390
Then too I could not see how my conscience would permit me to spare the time from my

06:42:59.390 --> 06:43:00.630
work and be happy.

06:43:01.300 --> 06:43:08.490
It seemed mean and selfish in me to be taking a vacation while others were at work and while

06:43:08.490 --> 06:43:10.970
there was so much that needed to be done.

06:43:11.430 --> 06:43:17.290
From the time I could remember I had always been at work, and I did not see how I could

06:43:17.290 --> 06:43:20.290
spend three or four months in doing nothing.

06:43:21.050 --> 06:43:25.230
The fact was that I did not know how to take a vacation.

06:43:25.850 --> 06:43:32.450
Mrs. Washington had much the same difficulty in getting away, but she was anxious to go

06:43:32.450 --> 06:43:34.890
because she thought that I needed to rest.

06:43:35.770 --> 06:43:41.890
There were many important national questions bearing upon the life of the race which were

06:43:41.890 --> 06:43:47.570
being agitated at that time, and this made it all the harder for us to decide to go.

06:43:47.810 --> 06:43:54.130
We finally gave our Boston friends our promise that we would go, and then they insisted that

06:43:54.130 --> 06:43:57.550
the date of our departure be set as soon as possible.

06:43:58.390 --> 06:44:05.950
So we decided upon May 10, my good friend Mr. Garrison kindly took charge of all the

06:44:05.950 --> 06:44:12.830
details necessary for the success of the trip, and he, as well as other friends, gave us

06:44:12.830 --> 06:44:17.910
a great number of letters of introduction to people in France and England, and made

06:44:17.910 --> 06:44:21.350
other arrangements for our comfort and convenience abroad.

06:44:21.970 --> 06:44:28.050
Goodbyes were said at Tuskegee, and we were in New York May 9, ready to sail the next

06:44:28.050 --> 06:44:28.390
day.

06:44:28.810 --> 06:44:34.930
Our daughter, Portia, who was then studying in South Framington, Massachusetts, came to

06:44:34.930 --> 06:44:36.570
New York to see us off.

06:44:38.050 --> 06:44:44.750
Mr. Scott, my secretary, came with me to New York in order that I might clear up the last

06:44:44.750 --> 06:44:46.810
bit of business before I left.

06:44:46.970 --> 06:44:50.250
Other friends also came to New York to see us off.

06:44:50.830 --> 06:44:56.290
Just before we went on board the steamer, another pleasant surprise came to us in the

06:44:56.290 --> 06:45:02.170
form of a letter from two generous ladies, stating that they had decided to give us the

06:45:02.170 --> 06:45:09.530
money with which to erect a new building to be used in properly housing all our industries

06:45:09.530 --> 06:45:11.770
for girls at Tuskegee.

06:45:12.530 --> 06:45:18.730
We were to sail on the freezeland of the Red Star Line, and the beautiful vessel she

06:45:18.730 --> 06:45:19.170
was.

06:45:19.930 --> 06:45:23.310
We went on board just before noon, the hour of sailing.

06:45:24.070 --> 06:45:30.430
I had never before been on board a large ocean steamer, and the feeling which took possession

06:45:30.430 --> 06:45:34.430
of me when I found myself there is rather hard to describe.

06:45:35.430 --> 06:45:38.730
It was a feeling, I think, of all mingled with delight.

06:45:39.450 --> 06:45:45.590
We were agreeably surprised to find that the captain as well as several of the other officers

06:45:46.110 --> 06:45:52.090
not only knew who we were, but was expecting us and gave us a pleasant greeting.

06:45:53.050 --> 06:45:58.770
There were several passengers whom we knew, including Senator Sewell of New Jersey and

06:45:58.770 --> 06:46:01.610
Edward Marshall, the newspaper correspondent.

06:46:02.730 --> 06:46:08.410
I had just a little fear that we would not be treated civilly by some of the passengers.

06:46:09.390 --> 06:46:14.550
This fear was based upon what I had heard other people of my race, who had crossed the

06:46:14.550 --> 06:46:20.630
ocean, say about unpleasant experiences in crossing the ocean in American vessels.

06:46:21.630 --> 06:46:27.530
But in our case, from the captain down to the most humble servant, we were treated with

06:46:27.530 --> 06:46:28.730
the greatest kindness.

06:46:29.270 --> 06:46:34.210
Nor was this kindness confined to those who were connected with the steamer.

06:46:34.550 --> 06:46:37.570
It was shown by all the passengers also.

06:46:38.160 --> 06:46:44.590
There were not a few southern men and women on board, and they were as cordial as those

06:46:44.590 --> 06:46:46.530
from other parts of the country.

06:46:47.510 --> 06:46:54.510
As soon as the last goodbyes were said, and the steamer had cut loose from the war, the

06:46:54.510 --> 06:47:01.930
load of care, anxiety, and responsibility, which I had carried for eighteen years, began

06:47:01.930 --> 06:47:07.590
to lift itself from my shoulders at the rate, it seemed to me, of a pound a minute.

06:47:08.510 --> 06:47:15.250
It was the first time in all those years that I had felt, even in a measure, free from care,

06:47:15.890 --> 06:47:19.430
and my feeling of relief it is hard to describe on paper.

06:47:20.130 --> 06:47:25.050
Added to this was the delightful anticipation of being in Europe soon.

06:47:25.830 --> 06:47:29.350
It all seemed more like a dream than like a reality.

06:47:29.350 --> 06:47:35.790
Mr. Garrison had thoughtfully arranged to have us have one of the most comfortable rooms

06:47:35.790 --> 06:47:36.530
on the ship.

06:47:37.590 --> 06:47:42.930
The second or third day out I began to sleep, and I think that I slept at the rate of fifteen

06:47:42.930 --> 06:47:46.450
hours a day during the remainder of the ten days passage.

06:47:47.550 --> 06:47:52.230
Then it was that I began to understand how tired I really was.

06:47:53.130 --> 06:47:58.450
These long sleeps I kept up for a month after we landed on the other side.

06:47:58.450 --> 06:48:05.430
It was such an unusual feeling to wake up in the morning and realize that I had no engagements,

06:48:06.090 --> 06:48:11.170
did not have to take a train at a certain hour, did not have an appointment to meet

06:48:11.170 --> 06:48:14.670
someone or to make an address at a certain hour.

06:48:15.230 --> 06:48:22.210
How different all this was from the experiences that I have been through when travelling when

06:48:22.210 --> 06:48:27.030
I have sometimes slept in three different beds in a single night.

06:48:28.910 --> 06:48:35.490
When Sunday came, the captain invited me to conduct the religious services, but, not being

06:48:35.490 --> 06:48:36.930
a minister, I declined.

06:48:37.950 --> 06:48:43.910
The passengers, however, began making requests that I deliver an address to them in the dining

06:48:43.910 --> 06:48:49.070
salon sometime during the voyage, and this I consented to do.

06:48:49.790 --> 06:48:52.390
Senator Sewell presided at this meeting.

06:48:52.770 --> 06:48:58.930
After ten days of delightful weather, during which I was not seasick for a day, we landed

06:48:58.930 --> 06:49:02.530
at the interesting old city of Antwerp in Belgium.

06:49:03.710 --> 06:49:10.150
The next day after we landed happened to be one of those numberless holidays which the

06:49:10.150 --> 06:49:13.410
people of those countries are in the habit of observing.

06:49:13.410 --> 06:49:16.230
It was a bright, beautiful day.

06:49:16.630 --> 06:49:22.650
Our room in the hotel faced the main public square, and the sights there, the people coming

06:49:22.650 --> 06:49:28.390
in from the country with all kinds of beautiful flowers to sell, the women coming in with

06:49:28.390 --> 06:49:34.110
their dogs drawing large, brightly polished cans filled with milk, the people streaming

06:49:34.110 --> 06:49:40.850
into the cathedral, filled me with a sense of newness that I had never before experienced.

06:49:42.810 --> 06:49:49.350
After spending some time in Antwerp, we were invited to go with a party of a half dozen

06:49:49.350 --> 06:49:51.890
persons on a trip through Holland.

06:49:52.990 --> 06:49:58.490
This party included Edward Marshall and some American artists who had come over on the

06:49:58.490 --> 06:49:59.850
same steamer with us.

06:50:00.730 --> 06:50:04.130
We accepted the invitation and enjoyed the trip greatly.

06:50:04.390 --> 06:50:10.110
I think it was all the more interesting and instructive, because we went, for most of

06:50:10.110 --> 06:50:13.870
the way, on one of the slow, old-fashioned canal boats.

06:50:14.530 --> 06:50:20.470
This gave us an opportunity of seeing and studying the real life of the people in the

06:50:20.470 --> 06:50:21.370
country districts.

06:50:22.090 --> 06:50:28.810
We went in this way as far as Rotterdam and later went to The Hague, where the peace conference

06:50:28.810 --> 06:50:35.030
was then in session and where we were kindly received by the American representatives.

06:50:36.150 --> 06:50:43.450
The thing that impressed itself most on me in Holland was the thoroughness of the agriculture

06:50:43.450 --> 06:50:46.210
and the excellence of the Holstein cattle.

06:50:48.160 --> 06:50:54.970
I never knew, before visiting Holland, how much it was possible for people to get out

06:50:54.970 --> 06:50:56.850
of a small plot of ground.

06:50:58.840 --> 06:51:02.750
It seemed to me that absolutely no land was wasted.

06:51:03.510 --> 06:51:09.770
It was worth a trip to Holland, too, just to get a sight of three or four hundred fine

06:51:09.770 --> 06:51:14.790
Holstein cows grazing in one of those intensely green fields.

06:51:16.230 --> 06:51:22.050
From Holland we went to Belgium and made a hasty trip through that country, stopping

06:51:22.050 --> 06:51:26.350
at Brussels, where we visited the battlefield of Waterloo.

06:51:27.050 --> 06:51:34.310
From Belgium we went direct to Paris, where we found that Mr. Theodore Stanton, the son

06:51:34.310 --> 06:51:40.030
of Mrs. Elizabeth Caddy Stanton, had kindly provided accommodations for us.

06:51:40.330 --> 06:51:46.030
We had barely got settled in Paris before an invitation came to me from the University

06:51:46.030 --> 06:51:51.130
Club of Paris to be its guest at a banquet which was soon to be given.

06:51:51.440 --> 06:51:57.790
The other guests were ex-President Benjamin Harrison and Archbishop Ireland, who were

06:51:57.790 --> 06:51:59.330
in Paris at the time.

06:51:59.830 --> 06:52:04.610
The American Ambassador General Horace Porter presided at the banquet.

06:52:04.990 --> 06:52:10.110
My address on this occasion seemed to give satisfaction to those who heard it.

06:52:10.670 --> 06:52:16.910
General Harrison kindly devoted a large portion of his remarks at dinner to myself and to

06:52:16.910 --> 06:52:21.150
influence of the work at Tuskegee on the American Race Question.

06:52:21.790 --> 06:52:27.890
After my address at this banquet other invitations came to me, but I declined the most of them,

06:52:27.890 --> 06:52:32.730
knowing that if I accepted them all, the object of my visit would be defeated.

06:52:33.210 --> 06:52:38.830
I did, however, consent to deliver an address in the American Chapel the following Sunday

06:52:38.830 --> 06:52:45.130
morning, and at this meeting General Harrison, General Porter, and other distinguished Americans

06:52:45.130 --> 06:52:46.050
were present.

06:52:47.030 --> 06:52:54.310
Later we received a formal call from the American Ambassador and were invited to attend a reception

06:52:54.310 --> 06:52:55.490
at his residence.

06:52:56.670 --> 06:53:02.710
At this reception we met many Americans, among them Justice Fuller and Harlan of the United

06:53:02.710 --> 06:53:04.110
States Supreme Court.

06:53:04.670 --> 06:53:11.410
During our entire stay of a month in Paris, both the American Ambassador and his wife,

06:53:11.410 --> 06:53:16.110
as well as several other Americans, were very kind to us.

06:53:17.010 --> 06:53:24.270
While in Paris we saw a good deal of the now famous American Negro painter, Mr. Henry O.

06:53:24.450 --> 06:53:27.550
Tanner, whom we had formerly known in America.

06:53:28.490 --> 06:53:34.830
It was very satisfactory to find how well known Mr. Tanner was in the field of art and

06:53:34.830 --> 06:53:38.590
to note the high standing which all classes accorded to him.

06:53:39.100 --> 06:53:44.070
When we told some Americans that we were going to the Luxembourg Palace to see a painting

06:53:44.070 --> 06:53:49.410
by an American Negro, it was hard to convince them that a Negro had been thus honored.

06:53:50.570 --> 06:53:56.330
I do not believe that they were really convinced of the fact until they saw the picture for

06:53:56.330 --> 06:53:56.970
themselves.

06:53:57.850 --> 06:54:04.230
My acquaintance with Mr. Tanner reinforced in my mind the truth which I am constantly

06:54:04.230 --> 06:54:10.710
trying to impress upon our students at Tuskegee and on our people throughout the country as

06:54:10.710 --> 06:54:16.730
far as I can reach them with my voice, that any man, regardless of color, will be recognized

06:54:16.730 --> 06:54:24.050
and rewarded just in proportion as he learns to do something well, learns to do it better

06:54:24.050 --> 06:54:27.790
than someone else, however humble the thing may be.

06:54:28.370 --> 06:54:34.210
As I have said, I believe that my race will succeed in proportion as it learns to do a

06:54:34.210 --> 06:54:41.150
common thing in an uncommon manner, learns to do a thing so thoroughly that no one can

06:54:41.150 --> 06:54:46.790
improve upon what it has done, learns to make its service of indispensable value.

06:54:47.150 --> 06:54:53.070
This was the spirit that inspired me in my first effort at Hampton when I was given the

06:54:53.070 --> 06:55:00.270
opportunity to sweep and dust that schoolroom, in a degree I felt that my whole future life

06:55:00.270 --> 06:55:05.370
depended upon the thoroughness with which I cleaned that room, and I was determined

06:55:05.370 --> 06:55:10.050
to do it so well that no one could find any fault with the job.

06:55:10.570 --> 06:55:16.870
Few people ever stopped, I found, when looking at this picture to inquire whether Mr. Tanner

06:55:16.870 --> 06:55:21.010
was a Negro painter, a French painter, or a German painter.

06:55:21.370 --> 06:55:26.990
They simply knew that he was able to produce something which the world wanted, a great

06:55:26.990 --> 06:55:31.810
painting, and the matter of his color did not enter into their minds.

06:55:32.850 --> 06:55:39.570
When a Negro girl learns to cook, to wash dishes, to sew, or write a book, or a Negro

06:55:39.570 --> 06:55:45.950
boy learns to groom horses, or to grow sweet potatoes, or to produce butter, or to build

06:55:45.950 --> 06:55:52.310
a house, or to be able to practice medicine as well or better than someone else, they

06:55:52.310 --> 06:55:55.270
will be rewarded regardless of race or color.

06:55:55.270 --> 06:56:01.910
In the long run, the world is going to have the best, and any difference in race, religion,

06:56:02.070 --> 06:56:07.430
or previous history will not long keep the world from what it wants.

06:56:08.210 --> 06:56:14.510
I think the whole future of my race hinges on the question as to whether or not it can

06:56:14.510 --> 06:56:21.230
make itself of such indispensable value that the people in the town and the state where

06:56:21.230 --> 06:56:27.910
reside will feel that our presence is necessary to the happiness and well-being of the community.

06:56:28.650 --> 06:56:34.590
No man who continues to add something to the material, intellectual, and moral well-being

06:56:34.590 --> 06:56:39.770
of the place in which he lives is long left without proper reward.

06:56:40.230 --> 06:56:44.970
This is a great human law which cannot be permanently nullified.

06:56:45.490 --> 06:56:50.910
The love of pleasure and excitement which seems in a large measure to possess the French

06:56:50.910 --> 06:56:53.710
people impressed itself upon me.

06:56:54.450 --> 06:57:00.310
I think they are more noted in this respect than is true of the people of my own race.

06:57:01.150 --> 06:57:06.450
In point of morality and moral earnestness, I do not believe that the French are ahead

06:57:06.450 --> 06:57:08.170
of my own race in America.

06:57:09.070 --> 06:57:14.950
Severe competition and the great stress of life have led them to learn to do things more

06:57:14.950 --> 06:57:21.810
thoroughly and to exercise greater economy, but time, I think, will bring my race to the

06:57:21.810 --> 06:57:22.550
same point.

06:57:23.390 --> 06:57:28.750
In the matter of truth and high honor, I do not believe that the average Frenchman is

06:57:28.750 --> 06:57:34.790
ahead of the American Negro, while so far as mercy and kindness to dumb animals go,

06:57:35.070 --> 06:57:37.730
I believe that my race is far ahead.

06:57:39.430 --> 06:57:45.230
In fact, when I left France, I had more faith in the future of the black man in America

06:57:45.230 --> 06:57:47.130
than I had ever possessed.

06:57:51.010 --> 06:57:57.210
From Paris we went to London and reached there early in July, just about the height of the

06:57:57.210 --> 06:57:58.730
London social season.

06:57:59.370 --> 06:58:03.090
Parliament was in session, there was a great deal of gaiety.

06:58:03.610 --> 06:58:09.170
Mr. Garrison and other friends had provided us with a large number of letters of introduction,

06:58:09.830 --> 06:58:14.930
and they had also sent letters to other persons in different parts of the United Kingdom,

06:58:15.350 --> 06:58:17.330
apprising these people of our coming.

06:58:18.210 --> 06:58:23.730
Very soon, after reaching London, we were flooded with invitations to attend all manner

06:58:23.730 --> 06:58:30.390
of social functions, and a great many invitations came to me, asking that I deliver public addresses.

06:58:31.170 --> 06:58:36.030
The most of these invitations I declined for the reason that I wanted to rest.

06:58:36.970 --> 06:58:41.450
Neither were we able to accept more than a small portion of the other invitations.

06:58:42.310 --> 06:58:48.450
The Reverend Dr. Brooke Hereford and Mrs. Hereford, whom I had known in Boston, consulted

06:58:48.450 --> 06:58:54.030
with the American Ambassador, the Honorable Joseph Cote, and arranged for me to speak

06:58:54.030 --> 06:58:56.770
at a public meeting to be held in Essex Hall.

06:58:56.770 --> 06:58:59.910
Mr. Cote kindly consented to preside.

06:59:00.330 --> 06:59:05.850
The meeting was largely attended, there were many distinguished persons present, among

06:59:05.850 --> 06:59:11.190
them several members of Parliament, including Mr. James Bryce, who spoke at the meeting.

06:59:11.830 --> 06:59:18.050
What the American Ambassador said in introducing me, as well as a synopsis of what I said,

06:59:18.390 --> 06:59:22.530
was widely published in England and in the American papers at the time.

06:59:23.090 --> 06:59:29.210
Dr. and Mrs. Hereford gave Mrs. Washington and myself a reception at which we had the

06:59:29.210 --> 06:59:32.670
privilege of meeting some of the best people in England.

06:59:34.230 --> 06:59:39.830
Throughout our stay in London, Ambassador Cote was most kind and attentive to us.

06:59:40.390 --> 06:59:45.130
At the Ambassador's reception I met, for the first time, Mark Twain.

06:59:45.930 --> 06:59:51.750
We were the guests several times of Mrs. T. Fisher Unwin, the daughter of the English

06:59:51.750 --> 06:59:53.730
statesman Richard Cobden.

06:59:54.270 --> 07:00:00.870
It seems as if both Mr. and Mrs. Unwin could not do enough for our comfort and happiness.

07:00:01.570 --> 07:00:07.830
Later for nearly a week we were the guests of the daughter of John Bright, now Mrs. Clark

07:00:07.830 --> 07:00:08.990
of Street England.

07:00:09.530 --> 07:00:15.490
Both Mr. and Mrs. Clark, with their daughter, visited us at Tuskegee the next year.

07:00:16.070 --> 07:00:22.250
In Birmingham, England, we were the guests for several days of Mr. Joseph Sturge, whose

07:00:22.250 --> 07:00:26.390
father was a great abolitionist and friend of Whittier and Garrison.

07:00:27.050 --> 07:00:32.370
It was a great privilege to meet throughout England those who had known and honored the

07:00:32.370 --> 07:00:38.030
late William Lloyd Garrison, the Honorable Frederick Douglass, and other abolitionists.

07:00:38.370 --> 07:00:44.730
The English abolitionists with whom we came in contact never seemed to tire of talking

07:00:44.730 --> 07:00:46.350
about these two Americans.

07:00:46.970 --> 07:00:54.090
Before going to England, I had no proper conception of the deep interest displayed by the abolitionists

07:00:54.090 --> 07:01:00.710
of England in the cause of freedom, nor did I realize the amount of substantial help given

07:01:00.710 --> 07:01:01.590
by them.

07:01:03.190 --> 07:01:09.130
In Bristol, England, both Mrs. Washington and I spoke at the Women's Liberal Club.

07:01:09.950 --> 07:01:16.210
I was also the principal speaker at the commencement exercises of the Royal College for the Blind.

07:01:17.750 --> 07:01:23.290
These exercises were held in the Crystal Palace, and the presiding officer was the late Duke

07:01:23.290 --> 07:01:28.930
of Westminster, who was said to be, I believe, the richest man in England, if not in the

07:01:28.930 --> 07:01:29.330
world.

07:01:29.870 --> 07:01:35.230
The Duke, as well as his wife and their daughter, seemed to be pleased with what I said and

07:01:35.230 --> 07:01:36.370
thanked me heartily.

07:01:36.750 --> 07:01:41.750
Through the kindness of Lady Aberdeen, my wife and I were enabled to go with a party

07:01:41.750 --> 07:01:48.230
of those who were attending the International Congress of Women, the Innsation in London,

07:01:48.470 --> 07:01:54.950
to see Queen Victoria at Windsor Castle, where afterward we were all the guests of Her Majesty

07:01:54.950 --> 07:01:55.690
at tea.

07:01:56.140 --> 07:02:02.050
In our party was Miss Susan B. Anthony, and I was deeply impressed with the fact that

07:02:02.050 --> 07:02:08.450
one did not often get an opportunity to see during the same hour two women so remarkable

07:02:08.450 --> 07:02:13.030
in different ways as Susan B. Anthony and Queen Victoria.

07:02:14.470 --> 07:02:19.970
In the House of Commons, which we visited several times, we met Sir Henry M. Stanley.

07:02:20.810 --> 07:02:27.410
I talked with him about Africa and its relation to the American Negro, and after my interview

07:02:27.410 --> 07:02:34.530
with him I became more convinced than ever that there was no hope of the American Negroes

07:02:34.530 --> 07:02:37.650
improving his condition by immigrating to Africa.

07:02:38.850 --> 07:02:44.170
On various occasions, Mrs. Washington and I were the guests of Englishmen in their country

07:02:44.170 --> 07:02:48.790
homes, where I think one sees the Englishmen at his best.

07:02:49.190 --> 07:02:54.590
In one thing at least, I feel sure that the English are ahead of Americans, and that is

07:02:54.590 --> 07:02:57.490
that they have learned how to get more out of life.

07:02:58.350 --> 07:03:04.230
The home life of the English seemed to me to be about as perfect as anything can be.

07:03:04.770 --> 07:03:06.610
Everything moves like clockwork.

07:03:06.970 --> 07:03:14.910
I was impressed, too, with the deference that the servants show to their masters and mistresses—terms

07:03:14.910 --> 07:03:17.910
which I suppose would not be tolerated in America.

07:03:19.130 --> 07:03:24.930
The English servant expects as a rule to be nothing but a servant, and so he perfects

07:03:24.930 --> 07:03:30.890
himself in the art to a degree that no class of servants in America has yet reached.

07:03:31.410 --> 07:03:36.750
In our country the servant expects to become, in a few years, a master himself.

07:03:37.450 --> 07:03:39.270
Which system is preferable?

07:03:39.490 --> 07:03:41.350
I will not venture an answer.

07:03:43.390 --> 07:03:49.590
Another thing that impressed itself upon me throughout England was the high regard that

07:03:49.590 --> 07:03:55.070
all classes have for law and order, and the ease and thoroughness with which everything

07:03:55.070 --> 07:03:55.830
is done.

07:03:56.710 --> 07:04:03.010
The Englishmen, I found, took plenty of time for eating, as for everything else.

07:04:03.590 --> 07:04:09.390
I'm not sure if, in the long run, they do not accomplish as much or more than rushing

07:04:09.390 --> 07:04:11.030
nervous Americans do.

07:04:12.030 --> 07:04:17.410
My visit to England gave me a higher regard for the nobility than I had had.

07:04:18.550 --> 07:04:24.970
I had no idea that they were so generally loved and respected by the classes, nor did

07:04:24.970 --> 07:04:30.810
I any correct conception of how much time and money they spent in works of philanthropy,

07:04:31.390 --> 07:04:34.470
and how much real heart they put into this work.

07:04:35.310 --> 07:04:40.570
My impression had been that they merely spent money freely and had a good time.

07:04:41.130 --> 07:04:45.510
It was hard for me to get accustomed to speaking to English audiences.

07:04:46.610 --> 07:04:52.470
The average Englishman is so serious and is so tremendously in earnest about everything

07:04:52.890 --> 07:04:58.590
that when I told a story that would have made an American audience roar with laughter, the

07:04:58.590 --> 07:05:03.110
Englishman simply looked me straight in the face without even cracking a smile.

07:05:05.190 --> 07:05:11.350
When the Englishman takes you into his heart and friendship, he binds you there as with

07:05:11.350 --> 07:05:16.870
cords of steel, and I do not believe that there are many other friendships that are

07:05:16.870 --> 07:05:19.470
so lasting or so satisfactory.

07:05:20.450 --> 07:05:25.470
Perhaps I can illustrate this point in no better way than by relating the following

07:05:25.470 --> 07:05:26.150
incident.

07:05:26.820 --> 07:05:32.850
Mrs. Washington and I were invited to attend a reception given by the Duke and Duchess

07:05:32.850 --> 07:05:37.210
of Sutherland at Stafford House, said to be the finest house in London.

07:05:37.830 --> 07:05:43.430
I may add that I believe the Duchess of Sutherland is said to be the most beautiful woman in

07:05:43.430 --> 07:05:43.910
England.

07:05:44.530 --> 07:05:48.030
There must have been at least three hundred persons at this reception.

07:05:48.650 --> 07:05:54.630
Twice during the evening the Duchess sought us out for a conversation, and she asked me

07:05:54.630 --> 07:05:59.670
to write her when we got home and tell her more about the work at Tuskegee.

07:06:00.190 --> 07:06:01.190
This I did.

07:06:01.710 --> 07:06:07.350
When Christmas came we were surprised and delighted to receive her photograph with her

07:06:07.350 --> 07:06:08.390
autograph on it.

07:06:09.230 --> 07:06:15.310
The correspondence has continued, and we now feel that in the Duchess of Sutherland we

07:06:15.310 --> 07:06:18.090
have one of our warmest friends.

07:06:20.170 --> 07:06:25.790
After three months in Europe we sailed from Southampton in the steamship St. Louis.

07:06:26.790 --> 07:06:33.030
On this steamer there was a fine library that had been presented to the ship by the citizens

07:06:33.030 --> 07:06:34.330
of St. Louis, Missouri.

07:06:34.970 --> 07:06:40.650
In this library I found a life of Frederick Douglass, which I began reading.

07:06:41.130 --> 07:06:47.750
I became especially interested in Mr. Douglass's description of the way he was treated on shipboard

07:06:47.750 --> 07:06:50.410
during his first or second visit to England.

07:06:51.750 --> 07:06:58.290
In this description he told how he was not permitted to enter the cabin, but had to confine

07:06:58.290 --> 07:07:00.190
himself to the deck of the ship.

07:07:00.910 --> 07:07:06.570
A few minutes after I had finished reading this description I was waited on by a committee

07:07:06.570 --> 07:07:13.150
of ladies and gentlemen with requests that I deliver an address at the concert which

07:07:13.150 --> 07:07:20.030
to begin the following evening, and yet there are people who are bold enough to say that

07:07:20.030 --> 07:07:23.670
race feeling in America is not growing less intense.

07:07:24.150 --> 07:07:30.390
At this concert, the Honorable Benjamin B. Odell, Jr., the present Governor of New York

07:07:30.390 --> 07:07:34.990
presided, I was never given a more cordial hearing anywhere.

07:07:35.790 --> 07:07:39.410
A large portion of the passengers were southern people.

07:07:39.990 --> 07:07:45.550
After the concert, some of the passengers proposed that a subscription be raised to

07:07:45.550 --> 07:07:51.450
help to work at Tuskegee and the money to support several scholarships was the result.

07:07:52.090 --> 07:07:57.790
While we were in Paris, I was very pleasantly surprised to receive the following invitation

07:07:57.790 --> 07:08:03.890
from the citizens of West Virginia and of the city near which I had spent my boyhood

07:08:03.890 --> 07:08:04.670
days.

07:08:05.230 --> 07:08:14.990
Charleston, West Virginia, May 16, 1899, Professor Booker T. Washington, Paris, France.

07:08:15.390 --> 07:08:22.630
Dear Sir, Many of the best citizens of West Virginia have united in liberal expressions

07:08:22.630 --> 07:08:28.790
of admiration and praise of your worth and work, and desire that on your return from

07:08:28.790 --> 07:08:35.610
Europe, you should favor them with your presence and with the inspiration of your words.

07:08:36.430 --> 07:08:43.110
We must sincerely endorse this move, and on behalf of the citizens of Charleston, extend

07:08:43.110 --> 07:08:50.590
to you our most cordial invitation to have you come to us, that we may honor you, who

07:08:50.590 --> 07:08:54.730
have done so much by your life and work to honor us.

07:08:54.730 --> 07:09:03.030
We are, very truly yours, the Common Council of the City of Charleston, by W. Herman Smith

07:09:04.610 --> 07:09:05.450
Mayer.

07:09:05.530 --> 07:09:10.730
This invitation from the City Council of Charleston was accompanied by the following.

07:09:12.170 --> 07:09:15.950
Professor Booker T. Washington, Paris, France.

07:09:16.370 --> 07:09:24.390
Dear Sir, We, the citizens of Charleston and West Virginia, desire to express our pride

07:09:24.390 --> 07:09:30.870
in you, and the splendid career that you have thus far accomplished, and ask that we

07:09:30.870 --> 07:09:35.830
be permitted to show our pride and interest in a substantial way.

07:09:36.630 --> 07:09:42.990
Your recent visit to your old home in our midst awoke within us the keenest regret

07:09:42.990 --> 07:09:49.550
that we were not permitted to hear you and render some substantial aid to your work before

07:09:49.550 --> 07:09:50.690
you left for Europe.

07:09:51.340 --> 07:09:58.270
In view of the foregoing, we earnestly invite you to share the hospitality of our city upon

07:09:58.270 --> 07:10:04.690
your return from Europe, and give us the opportunity to hear you and put ourselves in touch with

07:10:04.690 --> 07:10:11.970
your work in a way that will be most gratifying to yourself, and that we may receive the inspiration

07:10:11.970 --> 07:10:13.630
of your words and presence.

07:10:14.090 --> 07:10:19.650
An early reply to this invitation, with an indication of the time you may reach our city,

07:10:19.650 --> 07:10:23.450
will greatly oblige, yours very respectfully,

07:10:24.170 --> 07:10:26.530
The Charleston Daily Gazette

07:10:26.750 --> 07:10:29.730
The Daily Mail Tribune

07:10:29.730 --> 07:10:32.870
G. W. Atkinson, Governor

07:10:32.870 --> 07:10:36.390
E. L. Boggs, Secretary to Governor

07:10:36.390 --> 07:10:40.690
William M. O. Dawson, Secretary of State

07:10:41.210 --> 07:10:44.310
L. M. Lafollette, Auditor

07:10:44.310 --> 07:10:47.690
J. R. Trotter, Superintendent of Schools

07:10:48.050 --> 07:10:51.050
E. W. Wilson, Ex-Governor

07:10:51.050 --> 07:10:54.210
W. A. McCorkle, Ex-Governor

07:10:54.210 --> 07:10:58.730
John Q. Dickinson, President, Kauana Valley Bank

07:10:58.730 --> 07:11:03.030
L. Pritchard, President, Charleston National Bank

07:11:03.030 --> 07:11:07.970
George S. Couch, President, Kauana National Bank

07:11:07.970 --> 07:11:13.050
Edward Reed, Cashier, Kauana National Bank

07:11:13.050 --> 07:11:16.930
George S. Lately, Superintendent, City Schools

07:11:17.690 --> 07:11:21.050
L. E. McWhorter, President, Board of Education

07:11:21.610 --> 07:11:24.570
Charles K. Payne, Hostel Merchant

07:11:24.570 --> 07:11:25.970
and many others

07:11:26.970 --> 07:11:33.730
This invitation, coming as it did from the City Council, the State Officers, and all

07:11:33.730 --> 07:11:39.370
the substantial citizens of both races of the community where I had spent my boyhood,

07:11:40.470 --> 07:11:46.870
and from which I had gone a few years before, unknown, in poverty and ignorance, in quest

07:11:46.870 --> 07:11:54.150
of an education, not only surprised me but almost unmanned me. I could not understand

07:11:54.150 --> 07:12:01.390
what I had done to deserve it all. I accepted the invitation and at the appointed day was

07:12:01.390 --> 07:12:08.010
met at the railway station at Charleston by a committee headed by Ex-Governor W. A. McCorkle

07:12:08.010 --> 07:12:15.510
and composed of men of both races. The public reception was held in the Opera House at Charleston.

07:12:16.070 --> 07:12:22.910
The Governor of the State, the Honorable George W. Atkinson, presided, and an address of welcome

07:12:22.910 --> 07:12:29.270
was made by Ex-Governor McCorkle. A prominent part of the reception was taken by the colored

07:12:29.270 --> 07:12:35.490
citizens. The Opera House was filled with citizens of both races, and among the white

07:12:35.490 --> 07:12:41.530
people were many for whom I had worked when I was a boy. The next day Governor and Mrs.

07:12:41.530 --> 07:12:48.030
Atkinson gave me a public reception at the State House which was attended by all classes.

07:12:48.810 --> 07:12:54.310
Not long after this the colored people in Atlanta, Georgia gave me a reception at which

07:12:54.310 --> 07:13:01.910
the Governor of the State presided and a similar reception was given me in New Orleans, which

07:13:01.910 --> 07:13:09.770
was presided over by the Mayor of the City. Invitations came from many other places which

07:13:09.770 --> 07:13:11.330
I was not able to accept.

07:13:41.930 --> 07:13:46.370
LAST WORDS of Booker T. Washington's Up from Slavery

07:13:47.950 --> 07:13:53.770
Before going to Europe some events came into my life which were of great surprises to me.

07:13:54.430 --> 07:13:57.850
In fact my whole life has largely been one of surprises.

07:13:58.670 --> 07:14:03.990
I believe that any man's life will be filled with constant unexpected encouragements of

07:14:03.990 --> 07:14:10.470
this kind if he makes up his mind to do his level best each day of his life, that is,

07:14:10.470 --> 07:14:17.910
tries to make each day reach as nearly as possible the high water mark of pure unselfish useful living.

07:14:19.110 --> 07:14:24.590
I pity the man, black or white, who has never experienced the joy and satisfaction

07:14:24.590 --> 07:14:32.370
that come to one by reason of an effort to assist in making someone else more useful and more happy.

07:14:34.050 --> 07:14:39.330
Six months before he died, and nearly a year after he had been stricken with paralysis,

07:14:39.330 --> 07:14:44.850
General Armstrong expressed a wish to visit Tuskegee again before he passed away.

07:14:46.130 --> 07:14:50.790
Notwithstanding the fact that he had lost the use of his limbs to such an extent that he was

07:14:50.790 --> 07:14:56.110
practically helpless, his wish was gratified and he was brought to Tuskegee.

07:14:57.250 --> 07:15:00.590
The owners of the Tuskegee Railroad, white men living in the town,

07:15:00.850 --> 07:15:04.650
offered to run a special train, without cost, out of the main station,

07:15:04.650 --> 07:15:11.730
Chihaw, five miles away, to meet him. He arrived on the school grounds about nine o'clock in the

07:15:11.730 --> 07:15:16.910
evening. Someone had suggested that we give the general a pine-knot torchlight reception.

07:15:17.810 --> 07:15:22.590
This plan was carried out, and the moment that his carriage entered the school grounds,

07:15:23.210 --> 07:15:26.450
he began passing between two lines of lighted and waving,

07:15:26.650 --> 07:15:31.170
fat pinewood knots held by over a thousand students and teachers.

07:15:31.170 --> 07:15:36.270
The whole thing was so novel and surprising that the general was completely overcome

07:15:36.270 --> 07:15:40.930
with happiness. He remained a guest in my home for nearly two months,

07:15:41.730 --> 07:15:45.050
and although almost wholly without the use of voice or limb,

07:15:45.570 --> 07:15:50.170
he spent nearly every hour in devising ways and means to help the South.

07:15:51.570 --> 07:15:57.550
Time and time again he said to me during this visit that it was not only the duty of the country

07:15:57.550 --> 07:16:02.930
to assist in elevating the negro of the South, but the poor white man as well.

07:16:03.630 --> 07:16:09.150
At the end of his visit I resolved anew to devote myself more earnestly than ever

07:16:09.150 --> 07:16:16.370
to the cause which was so near his heart. I said that if a man in his condition was willing to

07:16:16.370 --> 07:16:23.510
think, work, and act, I should not be wanting, in furthering in every possible way, the wish of his

07:16:23.510 --> 07:16:30.810
heart. The death of General Armstrong a few weeks later gave me the privilege of getting acquainted

07:16:30.810 --> 07:16:37.990
with one of the finest, most unselfish, and most attractive men that I have ever come in contact

07:16:37.990 --> 07:16:45.290
with. I refer to the Reverend Dr. Hollis B. Frizzle, now the principal of the Hampton Institute,

07:16:46.250 --> 07:16:52.410
and General Armstrong's successor. Under the clear, strong, and almost perfect leadership of

07:16:52.410 --> 07:17:00.330
Dr. Frizzle, Hampton has had a career of prosperity and usefulness that is all that the General could

07:17:00.330 --> 07:17:07.550
have wished for. It seems to be the constant effort of Dr. Frizzle to hide his own great

07:17:07.550 --> 07:17:14.670
personality behind that of General Armstrong, to make himself of no reputation for the sake of the

07:17:14.670 --> 07:17:21.350
cause. More than once I have been asked what was the greatest surprise that ever came to me.

07:17:21.350 --> 07:17:26.690
I have little hesitation in answering that question. It was the following letter,

07:17:26.870 --> 07:17:32.490
which came to me one Sunday morning when I was sitting on the veranda of my home at Tuskegee,

07:17:32.970 --> 07:17:40.950
surrounded by my wife and three children. Harvard University, Cambridge, May 28, 1896

07:17:42.170 --> 07:17:49.370
President Booker T. Washington, My dear sir, Harvard University desired to confer on you

07:17:49.370 --> 07:17:55.690
at the approaching commencement an honorary degree, but it is our custom to confer degrees

07:17:55.690 --> 07:18:01.730
only on gentlemen who are present. Our commencement occurs this year on June 24,

07:18:02.570 --> 07:18:08.170
and your presence would be desirable from about noon till about five o'clock in the afternoon.

07:18:08.910 --> 07:18:12.150
Would it be possible for you to be in Cambridge on that day?

07:18:12.150 --> 07:18:18.370
Believe me with great regard, very truly yours, Charles W. Eliot.

07:18:21.250 --> 07:18:26.190
This was a recognition that had never in the slightest manner entered into my mind,

07:18:26.530 --> 07:18:30.990
and it was hard for me to realize that I was to be honored by a degree

07:18:30.990 --> 07:18:34.870
from the oldest and most renowned university in America.

07:18:35.530 --> 07:18:41.810
As I sat upon my veranda with this letter in hand, tears came into my eyes.

07:18:42.150 --> 07:18:48.710
My whole former life, my life as a slave on the plantation, my work in the coal mine,

07:18:49.270 --> 07:18:54.730
the times when I was without food and clothing, when I made my bed under a sidewalk,

07:18:55.370 --> 07:19:00.790
my struggles for an education, the trying days I had had at Tuskegee,

07:19:01.130 --> 07:19:05.710
days when I did not know where to turn for a dollar to continue the work there,

07:19:05.710 --> 07:19:14.330
the ostracism and sometimes oppression of my race, all this passed before me and nearly overcame me.

07:19:15.570 --> 07:19:19.390
I had never sought or cared for what the world calls fame.

07:19:20.030 --> 07:19:24.370
I have always looked upon fame as something to be used in accomplishing good.

07:19:25.370 --> 07:19:30.710
I have often said to my friends that if I can use whatever prominence may have come to me

07:19:30.710 --> 07:19:34.870
as an instrument with which to do good, I am content to have it.

07:19:35.630 --> 07:19:41.250
I care for it only as a means to be used for doing good, just as wealth may be used.

07:19:41.930 --> 07:19:46.650
The more I come into contact with wealthy people, the more I believe that they are

07:19:46.650 --> 07:19:51.970
growing in the direction of looking upon their money simply as an instrument which

07:19:51.970 --> 07:19:55.230
God has placed in their hand for doing good with.

07:19:55.590 --> 07:19:58.890
I never go to the office of Mr. John D. Rockefeller,

07:19:58.890 --> 07:20:04.990
who more than once has been generous to Tuskegee without being reminded of this.

07:20:05.670 --> 07:20:11.210
The close, careful, and minute investigation that he always makes in order to be sure that

07:20:11.210 --> 07:20:18.010
every dollar that he gives will do the most good, an investigation that is just as searching as if

07:20:18.010 --> 07:20:24.270
he were investing money in a business enterprise, convinces me that the growth in this direction

07:20:24.270 --> 07:20:25.950
is most encouraging.

07:20:26.930 --> 07:20:32.990
At nine o'clock on the morning of June 24th, I met President Elliott, the Board of Overseers

07:20:32.990 --> 07:20:38.810
of Harvard University, and the other guests at the designated place on the university grounds

07:20:38.810 --> 07:20:44.630
for the purpose of being escorted to Sanders Theater, where the commencement exercises were

07:20:44.630 --> 07:20:51.870
to be held and degrees conferred. Among others invited to be present for the purpose of receiving

07:20:51.870 --> 07:20:58.610
a degree at this time were General Nelson A. Miles, Dr. Bell, the inventor of the Bell telephone,

07:20:59.550 --> 07:21:05.770
Bishop Vincent, and the Reverend Minot J. Savage. We were placed in line immediately behind the

07:21:05.770 --> 07:21:11.110
President and the Board of Overseers, and directly afterward the Governor of Massachusetts,

07:21:11.570 --> 07:21:16.930
escorted by the Lancers, arrived and took his place in the line of march by the side of President

07:21:16.930 --> 07:21:23.270
Elliott. In the line there were also various other officers and professors, plaid in cap and gown.

07:21:23.870 --> 07:21:29.470
In this order we marched to Sanders Theater, where after the usual commencement exercises

07:21:29.470 --> 07:21:35.890
came the conferring of the honorary degrees. This, it seems, is always considered the most

07:21:35.890 --> 07:21:42.030
interesting feature at Harvard. It is not known until the individuals appear, upon whom the

07:21:42.030 --> 07:21:48.710
degrees are to be conferred, and those receiving these honors are cheered by the students and

07:21:48.710 --> 07:21:55.050
others in proportion to their popularity. During the conferring of the degrees, excitement and

07:21:55.050 --> 07:22:02.170
enthusiasm are at the highest pitch. When my name was called, I rose, and President Elliott,

07:22:02.570 --> 07:22:07.930
in beautiful and strong English, conferred upon me the degree of Master of Arts.

07:22:08.770 --> 07:22:14.710
After these exercises were over, those who had received honorary degrees were invited to lunch

07:22:14.710 --> 07:22:21.370
with the President. After the lunch, we were formed in line again, and were escorted by the

07:22:21.370 --> 07:22:26.070
Marshal of the day, who that year happened to be Bishop William Lawrence, through the grounds,

07:22:26.510 --> 07:22:31.650
where, at different points, those who had been honored were called by name and received the

07:22:31.650 --> 07:22:37.490
Harvard Yale. This march ended at Memorial Hall, where the alumni dinner was served.

07:22:37.930 --> 07:22:43.310
To see over a thousand strong men representing all that is best in state, church, business,

07:22:43.410 --> 07:22:49.890
and education, with the glow and enthusiasm of college loyalty and college pride, which has,

07:22:49.890 --> 07:22:55.210
I think, a peculiar Harvard flavor, is a sight that does not easily fade from memory.

07:22:55.970 --> 07:23:02.490
Among the speakers after dinner were President Elliott, Governor Roger Wolcott, General Miles,

07:23:02.490 --> 07:23:10.110
Dr. Minot J. Savage, the Honorable Henry Cabot Lodge, and myself. When I was called upon,

07:23:10.350 --> 07:23:16.970
I said, among other things, it would in some measure relieve my embarrassment if I could,

07:23:17.010 --> 07:23:22.430
even in a slight degree, feel myself worthy of the great honor which you do me today.

07:23:22.990 --> 07:23:28.230
Why you have called me from the black belt of the South, from among my humble people,

07:23:28.230 --> 07:23:34.970
to share in the honors of this occasion is not for me to explain, and yet it may not be

07:23:34.970 --> 07:23:41.170
inappropriate for me to suggest that it seems to me that one of the most vital questions that touch

07:23:41.170 --> 07:23:47.890
our American life is how to bring the strong, wealthy, and learned into helpful touch with

07:23:47.890 --> 07:23:54.570
the poorest, most ignorant, and humblest, and at the same time make one appreciate the vitalizing,

07:23:54.570 --> 07:24:02.510
strengthening influence of the other. How shall we make the mansion on Yon Beacon Street feel and

07:24:02.510 --> 07:24:09.710
see the need of the spirits in the lowliest cabin in Alabama cotton fields or Louisiana sugar bottoms?

07:24:10.750 --> 07:24:16.250
This problem Harvard University is solving, not by bringing itself down,

07:24:16.670 --> 07:24:23.290
but by bringing the masses up. If my life in the past has meant anything in the lifting up

07:24:23.290 --> 07:24:28.150
my people and the bringing about of better relations between your race and mine,

07:24:28.610 --> 07:24:35.230
I assure you from this day it will mean doubly more. In the economy of God there is but one

07:24:35.230 --> 07:24:43.570
standard by which an individual can succeed. There is but one for a race. This country demands that

07:24:43.570 --> 07:24:51.190
every race shall measure itself by the American standard. By it a race must rise or fall, succeed

07:24:51.190 --> 07:24:58.750
or fail, and in the last analysis mere sentiment counts for little. During the next half century

07:24:58.750 --> 07:25:05.810
and more my race must continue passing through the severe American crucible. We ought to be

07:25:05.810 --> 07:25:12.610
tested in our patience, our forbearance, our perseverance, our power to endure wrong,

07:25:13.110 --> 07:25:20.190
to withstand temptations, to economize, to acquire a new skill, in our ability to compete,

07:25:20.190 --> 07:25:27.290
to succeed in commerce, to disregard the superficial for the real, the appearance for the substance,

07:25:27.830 --> 07:25:34.250
to be great and yet small, learned and yet simple, high and yet the servant of all.

07:25:35.730 --> 07:25:40.790
As this was the first time that a New England University had conferred an honorary degree

07:25:40.790 --> 07:25:46.490
upon a Negro, it was the occasion of much newspaper comment throughout the country.

07:25:47.290 --> 07:25:53.550
A correspondent of a New York paper said, When the name of Booker T. Washington was called,

07:25:54.170 --> 07:26:00.270
and he arose to acknowledge and accept, there was such an outburst of applause as greeted no

07:26:00.270 --> 07:26:06.590
other name except that of the popular soldier patriot General Miles. The applause was not

07:26:06.590 --> 07:26:14.870
studied in stiff, sympathetic and condoling, it was enthusiasm and admiration. Every part of the

07:26:14.870 --> 07:26:20.890
audience from pit to gallery joined in, and a glow covered the cheeks of those around me,

07:26:21.110 --> 07:26:27.050
proving sincere appreciation of the rising struggle of an ex-slave and the work he has

07:26:27.050 --> 07:26:35.370
accomplished for his race. A Boston paper said, editorially, In conferring the honorary degree of

07:26:35.370 --> 07:26:41.730
Master of Arts upon the principle of Tuskegee Institute, Harvard University has honored itself

07:26:41.730 --> 07:26:47.430
as well as the object of this distinction. The work which Professor Booker T. Washington

07:26:47.430 --> 07:26:53.530
has accomplished for the education, good citizenship and popular enlightenment in his

07:26:53.530 --> 07:26:59.370
chosen field of labor in the South entitles him to rank with our national benefactors.

07:27:00.030 --> 07:27:05.890
The university which can claim him on its list of sons, whether in regular course or

07:27:05.890 --> 07:27:12.630
honoree scouser, may be proud. It has been mentioned that Mr. Washington is the first

07:27:12.630 --> 07:27:19.470
of his race to receive an honorary degree from a New England university. This in itself is a

07:27:19.470 --> 07:27:24.690
distinction, but the degree was not conferred because Mr. Washington is a colored man,

07:27:25.230 --> 07:27:31.650
or because he was born in slavery, but because he has shown by his work for the elevation of

07:27:31.970 --> 07:27:39.570
the Black Belt of the South a genius and a broad humanity which count for greatness in any man,

07:27:39.870 --> 07:27:44.750
whether his skin be white or black. Another Boston paper said,

07:27:46.090 --> 07:27:53.350
It is Harvard which, first among New England colleges, confers an honorary degree upon a

07:27:53.350 --> 07:28:00.070
black man. No one who has followed the history of Tuskegee and its work can fail to admire the

07:28:00.790 --> 07:28:09.090
persistence and splendid common sense of Booker T. Washington. Well may Harvard honor the ex-slave,

07:28:09.470 --> 07:28:15.850
the value of whose services, alike to his race and country, only the future can estimate.

07:28:17.250 --> 07:28:19.890
The correspondent of the New York Times wrote,

07:28:20.570 --> 07:28:26.790
All the speeches were enthusiastically received, but the colored man carried off the oratorical

07:28:26.790 --> 07:28:33.030
honors, and the applause which broke out when he had finished was vociferous and long continued.

07:28:33.850 --> 07:28:40.770
After I began work at Tuskegee, I formed a resolution in the secret of my heart that I

07:28:40.770 --> 07:28:46.750
would try to build up a school that would be of so much service to the country that the President

07:28:46.750 --> 07:28:53.610
of the United States would one day come to see it. This was, I confess, rather a bold resolution,

07:28:54.170 --> 07:29:00.290
and for a number of years I kept it hidden in my own thoughts, not daring to share it with anyone.

07:29:01.970 --> 07:29:09.710
In November 1897, I made the first move in this direction, and that was in securing a visit from a

07:29:09.710 --> 07:29:15.470
member of President McKinley's cabinet, the Honorable James Wilson, Secretary of Agriculture.

07:29:16.310 --> 07:29:21.550
He came to deliver an address at the formal opening of the Slater-Armstrong Agricultural

07:29:21.550 --> 07:29:27.490
Building, our first large building to be used for the purpose of giving training to our students

07:29:27.490 --> 07:29:35.170
in agriculture and kindred branches. In the fall of 1898 I heard that President McKinley was likely

07:29:35.170 --> 07:29:40.810
to visit Atlanta, Georgia, for the purpose of taking part in the Peace Jubilee exercises

07:29:40.810 --> 07:29:47.770
to be held there to commemorate the successful close of the Spanish-American War. At this time

07:29:47.770 --> 07:29:53.390
I had been hard at work, together with our teachers, for 18 years trying to build up a

07:29:53.390 --> 07:29:58.890
school that we thought would be of service to the nation, and I determined to make a direct effort

07:29:58.890 --> 07:30:05.150
to secure a visit from the President and his cabinet. I went to Washington, and I was not long

07:30:05.150 --> 07:30:10.690
in the city before I found my way to the White House. When I got there I found the waiting rooms

07:30:10.690 --> 07:30:17.330
full of people, and my heart began to sink, for I feared there would not be much chance

07:30:17.330 --> 07:30:24.670
of my seeing the President that day if at all. But at any rate I got an opportunity to see Mr.

07:30:24.670 --> 07:30:29.970
J. Addison Porter, the Secretary to the President, and explained to him my mission.

07:30:30.890 --> 07:30:36.290
Mr. Porter kindly sent my card directly to the President, and in a few minutes word came from

07:30:36.290 --> 07:30:43.930
Mr. McKinley that he would see me. How any man can see so many people of all kinds, with all kinds

07:30:43.930 --> 07:30:50.710
of errands, and to do so much hard work, and still keep himself calm, patient, and fresh for each

07:30:50.710 --> 07:30:57.810
visitor in the way that President McKinley does, I cannot understand. When I saw the President he

07:30:57.810 --> 07:31:02.890
kindly thanked me for the work which we were doing at Tuskegee, for the interests of the country.

07:31:03.530 --> 07:31:10.130
I then told him briefly the object of my visit. I impressed upon him the fact that a visit from

07:31:10.130 --> 07:31:15.170
the Chief Executive of the Nation would not only encourage our students and teachers,

07:31:15.670 --> 07:31:21.830
but would help the entire race. He seemed interested, but did not make a promise to go

07:31:21.830 --> 07:31:27.270
to Tuskegee, for the reason that his plans about going to Atlanta were not then fully made,

07:31:27.670 --> 07:31:31.330
but he asked me to call the matter to his attention a few weeks later.

07:31:32.890 --> 07:31:38.370
By the middle of the following month the President had definitely decided to attend the Peace Jubilee

07:31:38.370 --> 07:31:45.030
at Atlanta. I went to Washington again and saw him with a view of getting him to extend his trip

07:31:45.030 --> 07:31:52.290
to Tuskegee. On this second visit Mr. Charles W. Hare, a prominent white citizen of Tuskegee,

07:31:52.370 --> 07:31:57.870
kindly volunteered to accompany me to reinforce my invitation with one from the white people

07:31:57.870 --> 07:32:04.490
Tuskegee and the vicinity. Just previous to my going to Washington the second time,

07:32:04.890 --> 07:32:10.370
the country had been excited and the colored people greatly depressed because of several

07:32:10.370 --> 07:32:17.170
severe race riots which had occurred at different points in the south. As soon as I saw the President

07:32:17.170 --> 07:32:23.270
I perceived that his heart was greatly burdened by reason of these race disturbances. Although

07:32:23.270 --> 07:32:29.070
there were many people waiting to see him, he detained me for some time discussing the condition

07:32:29.070 --> 07:32:35.710
and prospects of the race. He remarked several times that he was determined to show his interest

07:32:35.710 --> 07:32:43.730
and faith in the race not merely in words but by acts. When I told him that I thought that at that

07:32:43.730 --> 07:32:50.010
time scarcely anything would go farther in giving hope and encouragement to the race than the fact

07:32:50.010 --> 07:32:55.570
that the President of the nation would be willing to travel 140 miles out of his way

07:32:55.570 --> 07:33:03.530
to spend a day at a Negro institution he seemed deeply impressed. While I was with the President

07:33:03.530 --> 07:33:09.410
a white citizen of Atlanta, a Democrat and an ex-slave holder came into the room and the

07:33:09.410 --> 07:33:15.650
President asked his opinion as to the wisdom of his going to Tuskegee. Without hesitation

07:33:15.650 --> 07:33:20.130
the Atlanta man replied that it was the proper thing for him to do.

07:33:20.790 --> 07:33:27.490
This opinion was reinforced by that friend of the race Dr. J. L. M. Curry. The President promised

07:33:27.490 --> 07:33:33.750
that he would visit our school on the 16th of December. When it became known that the

07:33:33.750 --> 07:33:39.910
President was going to visit our school the white citizens of the town of Tuskegee, a mile distant

07:33:39.910 --> 07:33:46.310
from the school, were as much pleased as were our students and teachers. The white people of this

07:33:46.310 --> 07:33:52.310
town including both men and women began arranging to decorate the town and to form themselves into

07:33:52.310 --> 07:33:57.450
committees for the purpose of cooperating with the officers of our school in order that the

07:33:57.450 --> 07:34:03.910
distinguished visitor might have a fitting reception. I think I never realized before this

07:34:03.910 --> 07:34:08.730
how much the white people of Tuskegee and vicinity thought of our institution.

07:34:09.810 --> 07:34:13.430
During the days when we were preparing for the President's reception

07:34:13.430 --> 07:34:19.650
dozens of these people came to me and said that while they did not want to push themselves into

07:34:19.650 --> 07:34:26.470
prominence if there was anything they could do to help or to relieve me personally I had but to

07:34:26.470 --> 07:34:33.210
intimate it and they would be only too glad to assist. In fact the thing that touched me almost

07:34:33.210 --> 07:34:40.550
as deeply as the visit of the President itself was the deep pride which all classes of citizens in

07:34:40.550 --> 07:34:48.330
Alabama seem to take in our work. The morning of December 16th brought to the little city of

07:34:48.330 --> 07:34:55.570
Tuskegee such a crowd as it had never seen before. With the President came Mrs. McKinley and all of

07:34:55.570 --> 07:35:01.590
cabinet officers but one and most of them brought their wives or some members of their families.

07:35:02.470 --> 07:35:08.530
Several prominent generals came including General Shafter and General Joseph Wheeler who were

07:35:08.530 --> 07:35:15.850
recently returned from the Spanish-American War. There was also a host of newspaper correspondents.

07:35:16.510 --> 07:35:21.990
The Alabama legislature was in session in Montgomery at this time. This body passed a

07:35:21.990 --> 07:35:28.190
resolution to adjourn for the purpose of visiting Tuskegee just before the arrival of the President's

07:35:28.190 --> 07:35:33.410
party the legislature arrived headed by the governor and other state officials.

07:35:35.290 --> 07:35:40.990
The citizens of Tuskegee had decorated the town from the station to the school in a generous manner.

07:35:41.910 --> 07:35:47.550
In order to economize in the matter of time we arranged to have the whole school pass in review

07:35:47.550 --> 07:35:53.270
before the President. Each student carried a stalk of sugar cane with some open balls

07:35:53.270 --> 07:35:59.610
of cotton fastened to the end of it. Following the students the work of all departments of the

07:35:59.610 --> 07:36:07.770
school passed in review displayed on floats drawn by horses mules and oxen. On these floats we tried

07:36:07.770 --> 07:36:14.070
to exhibit not only the present work of the school but to show the contrasts between the old methods

07:36:14.070 --> 07:36:20.790
of doing things and the new. As an example we showed the old method of dairying in contrast

07:36:20.790 --> 07:36:26.630
with the improved methods, the old methods of tilling the soil in contrast with the new,

07:36:27.090 --> 07:36:33.690
the old methods of cooking and housekeeping in contrast with the new. These floats consumed an

07:36:33.690 --> 07:36:39.910
hour and a half of time in passing. In his address in our large new chapel which the

07:36:39.910 --> 07:36:44.090
had recently completed the President said, among other things,

07:36:44.870 --> 07:36:50.790
to meet you under such pleasant auspices and to have the opportunity of a personal observation

07:36:50.790 --> 07:36:58.470
of your work is indeed most gratifying. The Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute is ideal

07:36:58.470 --> 07:37:05.030
in its conception and has already a large and growing reputation in the country and is not

07:37:05.030 --> 07:37:12.990
known abroad. I congratulate all who are associated in this undertaking for the good work which it is

07:37:12.990 --> 07:37:19.270
doing in the education of its students to lead lives of honor and usefulness, thus exalting the

07:37:19.270 --> 07:37:25.950
race for which it was established. Nowhere, I think, could a more delightful location have been

07:37:25.950 --> 07:37:32.590
chosen for this unique educational experiment which has attracted the attention and won the

07:37:32.590 --> 07:37:37.310
even of conservative philanthropists in all sections of the country.

07:37:38.410 --> 07:37:43.810
To speak of Tuskegee without paying special tribute to Booker T. Washington's genius

07:37:43.810 --> 07:37:50.390
and perseverance would be impossible. The inception of this noble enterprise was his

07:37:50.390 --> 07:37:57.850
and he deserves high credit for it. His was the enthusiasm and enterprise which made its

07:37:57.850 --> 07:38:04.950
progress possible and established in the institution its present high standard of

07:38:04.950 --> 07:38:11.430
accomplishment. He has won a worthy reputation as one of the great leaders of his race,

07:38:11.950 --> 07:38:17.250
widely known and much respected at home and abroad as an accomplished educator,

07:38:17.750 --> 07:38:25.710
a great orator, and a true philanthropist. The Honorable John D. Long, the Secretary of the

07:38:25.710 --> 07:38:33.590
Society, said in part, I cannot make a speech today. My heart is too full, full of hope,

07:38:34.250 --> 07:38:40.650
admiration and pride for my countrymen of both sections and both colors. I am filled with

07:38:40.650 --> 07:38:47.570
gratitude and admiration for your work, and from this time forward I shall have absolute confidence

07:38:47.570 --> 07:38:53.930
in your progress and in the solution of the problem in which you are engaged. The problem,

07:38:54.530 --> 07:39:01.830
has been solved. A picture has been presented today which should be put upon canvas with the

07:39:01.830 --> 07:39:08.630
pictures of Washington and Lincoln and transmitted to future time and generations, a picture which

07:39:08.630 --> 07:39:15.590
the press of the country should spread broadcast over the land, a most dramatic picture, and that

07:39:15.590 --> 07:39:22.370
picture is this. The President of the United States standing on this platform, on one side

07:39:22.370 --> 07:39:29.130
the governor of Alabama, on the other completing the trinity, a representative of a race only a

07:39:29.130 --> 07:39:35.770
few years ago in bondage, the colored president of the Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute.

07:39:36.790 --> 07:39:43.010
God bless the president under whose majesty such a scene as that is presented to the American

07:39:43.010 --> 07:39:49.270
people. God bless the state of Alabama which is showing that it can deal with this problem

07:39:49.270 --> 07:39:57.430
for itself. God bless the orator, philanthropist, and disciple of the great master who, if he were

07:39:57.430 --> 07:40:02.470
on earth, would be doing the same work. Booker T. Washington.

07:40:04.390 --> 07:40:11.230
Postmaster General Smith closed the address which he made with these words. We have witnessed many

07:40:11.230 --> 07:40:17.310
spectacles within the last few days. We have seen the magnificent grandeur and the magnificent

07:40:17.310 --> 07:40:23.550
achievements of one of the great metropolitan cities of the south. We have seen heroes of the

07:40:23.550 --> 07:40:30.290
war pass by in procession. We have seen floral parades, but I am sure my colleagues will agree

07:40:30.290 --> 07:40:37.010
with me in saying that we have witnessed no spectacle more impressive and more encouraging,

07:40:37.670 --> 07:40:42.790
more inspiring for our future than that which we have witnessed here this morning.

07:40:43.710 --> 07:40:49.510
Some days after the president returned to Washington, I received the letter which follows.

07:40:50.970 --> 07:41:02.030
Executive Mansion, Washington, December 23, 1899. Dear sir, by this mail I take pleasure in sending

07:41:02.030 --> 07:41:09.410
you engrossed copies of the souvenir of the visit of the president to your institution. These sheets

07:41:09.410 --> 07:41:14.830
bear the autographs of the president and members of the cabinet who accompanied him on the trip.

07:41:15.970 --> 07:41:21.970
Let me take this opportunity of congratulating you most heartily and sincerely upon the great

07:41:21.970 --> 07:41:28.330
success of the exercises provided for and entertainment furnished us under your auspices

07:41:28.330 --> 07:41:35.790
during our visit to Tuskegee. Every feature of the program was perfectly executed and was viewed or

07:41:35.790 --> 07:41:42.570
participated in with the heartiest satisfaction by every visitor present. The unique exhibition

07:41:42.570 --> 07:41:48.670
which you gave of your pupils engaged in their industrial vocations was not only artistic but

07:41:48.670 --> 07:41:54.490
thoroughly impressive. The tribute paid by the president and his cabinet to your work

07:41:54.490 --> 07:42:02.490
was none too high and forms a most encouraging augury, I think, for the future prosperity of your

07:42:02.490 --> 07:42:10.350
institution. I cannot close without assuring you that the modesty shown by yourself in the exercises

07:42:10.350 --> 07:42:17.090
was most favorably commented upon by all the members of our party. With best wishes for the

07:42:17.090 --> 07:42:23.190
continued advance of your most useful and patriotic undertaking, kind personal regards,

07:42:24.010 --> 07:42:29.690
and the compliments of the season, believe me always with very sincerely yours,

07:42:29.690 --> 07:42:36.450
John Addison Porter, Secretary to the President, to President Booker T. Washington,

07:42:37.050 --> 07:42:41.410
Tuskegee Normal and Industrial Institute, Tuskegee, Alabama.

07:42:42.910 --> 07:42:48.790
Twenty years have now passed since I made the first humble effort at Tuskegee in a broken down

07:42:48.790 --> 07:42:55.370
shanty and an old hen house without owning a dollar's worth of property and with but one

07:42:55.370 --> 07:43:02.190
teacher and thirty students. At the present time, the institution owns twenty-three hundred acres

07:43:02.190 --> 07:43:10.970
of land, one thousand of which are under cultivation each year entirely by student labor. There are now

07:43:10.970 --> 07:43:18.530
upon the grounds, counting large and small, sixty-six buildings, and all except four of these,

07:43:19.310 --> 07:43:22.690
have been almost wholly erected by the labor of our students.

07:43:23.370 --> 07:43:28.870
While the students are at work upon the land and in erecting buildings, they are taught

07:43:28.870 --> 07:43:35.270
by competent instructors the latest methods of agriculture and the trades connected with building.

07:43:36.370 --> 07:43:42.470
There are in constant operation at the school, in connection with thorough academic and religious

07:43:42.470 --> 07:43:49.770
training, thirty industrial departments. All of these teach industries at which our men and women

07:43:49.770 --> 07:43:56.710
can find immediate employment as soon as they leave the institution. The only difficulty now

07:43:56.710 --> 07:44:02.850
is that the demand for our graduates from both white and black people in the South is so great

07:44:02.850 --> 07:44:08.590
that we cannot supply more than one-half the persons for whom applications come to us.

07:44:08.990 --> 07:44:19.750
Neither have we the buildings nor the money for current expenses to enable us to admit to the

07:44:19.750 --> 07:44:26.610
In our industrial teaching, we keep three things in mind. First, that the student shall be

07:44:26.610 --> 07:44:32.990
so educated that he shall be enabled to meet conditions as they exist now in the part of

07:44:32.990 --> 07:44:39.150
the South where he lives, in a word, to be able to do the thing which the world wants done.

07:44:40.110 --> 07:44:45.230
Second, that every student who graduates from the school shall have enough skill, coupled with

07:44:45.750 --> 07:44:51.250
and moral character, to enable him to make a living for himself and others.

07:44:52.170 --> 07:44:59.030
Third, to send every graduate out feeling and knowing that labor is dignified and beautiful.

07:44:59.750 --> 07:45:06.390
To make each one love labor instead of trying to escape it. In addition to the agricultural

07:45:06.390 --> 07:45:11.090
training which we give to young men and the training given to our girls in all the usual

07:45:11.090 --> 07:45:17.690
employments, we now train a number of girls in agriculture each year. These girls are taught

07:45:17.690 --> 07:45:25.370
gardening, fruit growing, dairying, bee culture, and poultry raising. While the institution is

07:45:25.370 --> 07:45:32.030
in no sense denominational, we have a department known as the Phelps Hall Bible Training School,

07:45:32.430 --> 07:45:37.630
in which a number of students are prepared for the ministry and other forms of Christian work,

07:45:37.630 --> 07:45:44.190
especially work in the country districts. What is equally important, each one of the students

07:45:44.190 --> 07:45:50.810
works half of each day at some industry in order to get skill and the love of work, so that when

07:45:50.810 --> 07:45:57.770
he goes out from the institution, he is prepared to set the people with whom he goes to labor

07:45:57.770 --> 07:46:05.830
a proper example in the matter of industry. The value of our property is now over seven

07:46:05.830 --> 07:46:11.050
hundred thousand dollars. If we add to this our endowment fund, which at present is one million

07:46:11.050 --> 07:46:16.030
dollars, the value of the total property is now one million seven hundred thousand dollars.

07:46:16.730 --> 07:46:20.890
Aside from the need for more buildings and for money for current expenses,

07:46:21.510 --> 07:46:25.390
the endowment fund should be increased to at least three million dollars.

07:46:25.890 --> 07:46:35.070
The annual current expenses are now about one hundred and fifty thousand dollars. The greater

07:46:35.430 --> 07:46:42.030
and from house to house, all of our property is free from mortgage and it is deeded to an

07:46:42.030 --> 07:46:46.510
undenominational board of trustees who have the control of the institution.

07:46:47.970 --> 07:46:53.330
From thirty students the number has grown to fourteen hundred, coming from twenty-seven

07:46:53.330 --> 07:47:00.530
states and territories, from Africa, Cuba, Puerto Rico, Jamaica and other foreign countries.

07:47:01.290 --> 07:47:07.570
In our departments there are one hundred and ten officers and instructors, and if we add the

07:47:07.570 --> 07:47:13.910
families of our instructors, we have a constant population upon our grounds of not far from

07:47:13.910 --> 07:47:20.110
seventeen hundred people. I have often been asked how we keep so large a body of people together

07:47:20.110 --> 07:47:26.870
and at the same time keep them out of mischief. There are two answers, that the men and women

07:47:26.870 --> 07:47:31.590
who come to us for an education are in earnest and that everybody is kept busy.

07:47:32.210 --> 07:47:36.070
The following outline of our daily work will testify to this.

07:47:36.750 --> 07:47:43.830
Five a.m. rising bell, five fifty a.m. morning breakfast bell, six a.m. breakfast bell,

07:47:44.490 --> 07:47:53.830
six twenty a.m. breakfast over, six twenty to six fifty a.m. rooms are clean, six fifty work bell,

07:47:53.830 --> 07:48:02.830
seven thirty morning study hours, eight twenty morning school bell, eight twenty five inspection

07:48:02.830 --> 07:48:10.800
of young men's toilet in ranks, eight forty devotional exercises in chapel, eight fifty five,

07:48:11.190 --> 07:48:19.850
five minutes with the daily news, nine a.m. class work begins, twelve class work closes,

07:48:20.410 --> 07:48:30.870
twelve fifteen p.m. dinner, one p.m. work bell, one thirty p.m. class work begins, three thirty p.m.

07:48:31.110 --> 07:48:41.270
class work ends, five thirty p.m. bell to knock off work, six p.m. supper, seven ten p.m. evening

07:48:41.270 --> 07:48:49.630
prayers, seven thirty p.m. evening study hours, eight forty five p.m. evening study hour closes,

07:48:50.670 --> 07:48:56.970
nine twenty p.m. warning retiring bell, nine thirty p.m. retiring bell.

07:48:58.670 --> 07:49:04.650
We try to keep constantly in mind the fact that the worth of the school is to be judged by its

07:49:04.650 --> 07:49:10.250
graduates, counting those who have finished the full course together with those who have

07:49:10.250 --> 07:49:14.970
taken enough training to enable them to do reasonably good work. We can safely say that

07:49:14.970 --> 07:49:20.470
at least six thousand men and women from Tuskegee are now at work in different parts of the South.

07:49:21.190 --> 07:49:26.630
Men and women who, by their own example or by direct efforts, are showing the masses of our race

07:49:26.630 --> 07:49:34.610
how to improve their material, educational, and moral and religious life. What is equally important,

07:49:34.610 --> 07:49:40.290
they are exhibiting a degree of common sense and self-control which is causing better relations

07:49:40.290 --> 07:49:46.230
to exist between the races and is causing the southern white man to learn to believe in the

07:49:46.230 --> 07:49:53.010
value of educating the men and women of my race. Aside from this, there is the influence that is

07:49:53.010 --> 07:49:57.950
constantly being exerted through the mothers meeting and the plantation work conducted by

07:49:57.950 --> 07:50:04.770
Mrs. Washington. Wherever our graduates go, the changes which soon begin to appear in the buying

07:50:04.770 --> 07:50:11.030
of land, improving homes, saving money, in education, and in high moral characters are

07:50:11.030 --> 07:50:17.050
remarkable. Whole communities are fast being revolutionized through the instrumentality of

07:50:17.050 --> 07:50:25.430
these men and women. Ten years ago, I organized at Tuskegee the first Negro Conference. This is an

07:50:25.430 --> 07:50:30.250
annual gathering which now brings to the school eight or nine hundred representative men and women

07:50:30.250 --> 07:50:36.770
of the race who come to spend a day in finding out what the actual industrial, mental, and moral

07:50:36.770 --> 07:50:43.970
conditions of the people are and informing plans for improvement. Out from this Central Negro

07:50:43.970 --> 07:50:50.190
Conference at Tuskegee have grown numerous state and local conferences which are doing the same

07:50:50.190 --> 07:50:57.510
work. As a result of the influence of these gatherings, one delegate reported at the last

07:50:57.510 --> 07:51:03.170
annual meeting that ten families in his community had bought and paid for homes.

07:51:04.610 --> 07:51:09.070
On the day following the annual Negro Conference, there is the Workers Conference.

07:51:09.570 --> 07:51:16.130
This is composed of officers and teachers who are engaged in educational work in the larger

07:51:16.130 --> 07:51:22.410
institutions in the South. The Negro Conference furnishes a rare opportunity for these workers

07:51:22.410 --> 07:51:26.390
to study the real condition of the rank and file of the people.

07:51:28.350 --> 07:51:35.010
In the summer of 1900, with the assistance of such prominent colored men as Mr. T. Thomas Fortune,

07:51:35.610 --> 07:51:41.890
who has always upheld my hands in every effort, I organized the National Negro Business League

07:51:41.890 --> 07:51:47.130
which held its first meeting in Boston and brought together for the first time a large

07:51:47.130 --> 07:51:53.090
number of colored men who are engaged in various lines of trade or business in different parts of

07:51:53.090 --> 07:51:59.810
the United States. Thirty states were represented at our first meeting. Out of this national meeting

07:51:59.810 --> 07:52:07.110
grew state and local business leagues. In addition to looking after the executive side of the work at

07:52:07.920 --> 07:52:11.710
and raising the greater part of the money for the support of the school,

07:52:12.490 --> 07:52:18.050
I cannot seem to escape the duty of answering at least a part of the calls which come to me

07:52:18.050 --> 07:52:24.990
unsought to address southern white audiences and audiences of my own race, as well as frequent

07:52:24.990 --> 07:52:31.250
gatherings in the North. As to how much of my time is spent in this way, the following clipping from

07:52:31.250 --> 07:52:37.250
Buffalo New York paper will tell. This has reference to an occasion when I spoke before

07:52:37.250 --> 07:52:40.690
the National Educational Association in that city.

07:52:42.930 --> 07:52:47.370
Booker T. Washington, the foremost educator among the colored people of the world,

07:52:47.710 --> 07:52:52.630
was a very busy man from the time he arrived in the city the other night from the West

07:52:52.630 --> 07:52:59.270
and registered at the Iroquois. He had hardly removed the stains of travel when it was time

07:52:59.270 --> 07:53:06.050
to partake of supper. Then he held a public levy in the parlors of the Iroquois until eight o'clock.

07:53:06.690 --> 07:53:12.050
During that time he was greeted by over 200 eminent teachers and educators from all parts

07:53:12.050 --> 07:53:17.390
of the United States. Shortly after eight o'clock he was driven in a carriage to Music Hall,

07:53:17.950 --> 07:53:23.890
and in one hour and a half he made two ringing addresses to as many as five thousand people

07:53:23.890 --> 07:53:28.870
on Negro education. Then Mr. Washington was taken in charge

07:53:28.870 --> 07:53:33.090
by a delegation of colored citizens, headed by the Reverend Mr. Watkins,

07:53:33.550 --> 07:53:39.370
and hustled off to a small informal reception arranged in honor of the visitor by the people

07:53:39.370 --> 07:53:46.650
of his race. Nor can I, in addition to making these addresses, escape the duty of calling

07:53:46.650 --> 07:53:51.810
the attention of the South and of the country in general, through the medium of the press,

07:53:51.810 --> 07:53:58.650
to matters that pertain to the interests of both races. This, for example, I have done in regard

07:53:58.650 --> 07:54:04.750
to the evil habit of lynching. When the Louisiana State Constitutional Convention was in session,

07:54:05.270 --> 07:54:11.710
I wrote an open letter to that body pleading for justice for the race. In all such efforts I have

07:54:11.710 --> 07:54:17.670
received warm and hearty support from the southern newspapers as well as from those in all other

07:54:17.670 --> 07:54:24.150
parts of the country. Despite superficial and temporary signs which might lead one to

07:54:24.150 --> 07:54:29.850
entertain a contrary opinion, there was never a time when I felt more hopeful for the race

07:54:29.850 --> 07:54:36.650
than I do at the present. The great human law that in the end recognizes and rewards merit

07:54:36.650 --> 07:54:43.570
is everlasting and universal. The outside world does not know, neither can it appreciate the

07:54:43.570 --> 07:54:49.890
that is constantly going on in the hearts of both the southern white people and their former slaves

07:54:49.890 --> 07:54:55.190
to free themselves from racial prejudice. And while both races are thus struggling,

07:54:55.730 --> 07:55:00.870
they should have the sympathy, the support, and the forbearance of the rest of the world.

07:55:01.370 --> 07:55:07.890
As I write the closing words of this autobiography, I find myself, not by design,

07:55:08.530 --> 07:55:15.090
in the city of Richmond, Virginia, the city which only a few decades ago was the capital of the

07:55:15.090 --> 07:55:21.110
Southern Confederacy, and where, about twenty-five years ago, because of my poverty,

07:55:21.670 --> 07:55:29.070
I slept night after night under a sidewalk. This time I am in Richmond as the guest of the

07:55:29.070 --> 07:55:34.350
colored people of the city, and came at their request to deliver an address last night to both

07:55:34.350 --> 07:55:39.710
races in the Academy of Music, the largest and finest audience room in the city.

07:55:40.470 --> 07:55:45.170
This was the first time that the colored people had ever been permitted to use this hall.

07:55:45.690 --> 07:55:51.670
The day before I came, the City Council passed a vote to attend the meeting in a body to hear me

07:55:51.670 --> 07:55:58.830
speak. The State Legislature, including the House of Delegates and the Senate, also passed a unanimous

07:55:58.830 --> 07:56:05.470
vote to attend in a body. In the presence of hundreds of colored people, many distinguished

07:56:05.470 --> 07:56:12.310
white citizens, the City Council, the State Legislature, and State officials, I delivered

07:56:12.310 --> 07:56:19.790
my message, which was one of hope and cheer, and from the bottom of my heart I thanked both

07:56:19.790 --> 07:56:24.030
races for this welcome back to the State that gave me birth.

07:56:29.810 --> 07:56:36.910
End of Up From Slavery and Autobiography by Booker T. Washington
